window.QUESTION_BANK = [{"id":1,"question":"Which network topology connects all devices to a single central device such as a switch or hub?","options":["Star topology","Bus topology","Ring topology","Mesh topology"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A star topology uses a central device (switch/hub) that all nodes connect to individually.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["A star topology uses a central device (switch/hub) that all nodes connect to individually.","Bus topology uses a shared backbone cable, not a central connecting device.","Ring topology connects each device to two neighbors in a loop, not through a central device.","Mesh topology links devices directly to each other, not through one central point."]},{"id":2,"question":"In which topology do all devices share a single backbone cable, and a break in that cable can take down the entire network segment?","options":["Bus topology","Star topology","Mesh topology","Hybrid topology"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A bus topology uses one main cable, or backbone. A break disrupts the entire segment.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["A bus topology uses one main cable, or backbone. A break disrupts the entire segment.","Star topology uses a central device, so one connection failing doesn't take down the whole segment.","Mesh topology has multiple redundant paths, so a single cable break wouldn't disrupt the whole network.","Hybrid topology combines multiple topology types, not a single shared backbone cable."]},{"id":3,"question":"Which topology offers the highest redundancy by providing multiple paths between nodes?","options":["Full mesh topology","Bus topology","Star topology","Ring topology"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A full mesh topology provides direct links between all nodes, maximizing redundancy.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["A full mesh topology provides direct links between all nodes, maximizing redundancy.","Bus topology relies on a single shared cable, offering little redundancy.","Star topology depends entirely on the central device, limiting redundancy.","Ring topology only provides one path around the loop unless dual-ring redundancy is added."]},{"id":4,"question":"A network uses a physical star layout, but logically all devices share the same collision domain because a hub is used. What is this?","options":["Physical star, logical bus","Physical bus, logical star","Physical mesh, logical ring","Physical ring, logical mesh"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A hub creates a shared medium like a bus, even though the wiring is a star.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["A hub creates a shared medium like a bus, even though the wiring is a star.","This reverses the actual layout described; the wiring here is physically a star, not a bus.","The scenario describes a hub-based star wiring, not a mesh or ring arrangement.","The scenario describes a hub-based star wiring, not a ring or mesh arrangement."]},{"id":5,"question":"Which WAN topology connects each site to a central site, similar to a hub-and-spoke model?","options":["Star topology","Full mesh topology","Bus topology","Ring topology"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Hub-and-spoke WANs are essentially star topologies.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Hub-and-spoke WANs are essentially star topologies.","Full mesh connects every site to every other site directly, not just to one central site.","Bus topology relies on a single shared cable, not a central hub site.","Ring topology connects sites in a loop, not through one central hub."]},{"id":6,"question":"In a ring topology, how does data typically travel between devices?","options":["From node to node in a circular path","Directly from each device to every other device","All devices share a single coaxial cable","Using a dedicated link to a central switch"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Ring topology passes frames around the circle until they reach the destination.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Ring topology passes frames around the circle until they reach the destination.","Direct device-to-device links describe mesh, not how a ring forwards data around the loop.","A single shared coax cable describes bus topology, not how a ring physically forwards data.","A dedicated link to a central switch describes star topology, not the ring's circular path."]},{"id":7,"question":"Which topology is most commonly used in modern Ethernet LANs?","options":["Star topology using switches","Bus topology using coaxial cable","Logical ring using token passing","Full mesh topology between all workstations"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Modern Ethernet LANs use a physical star with switches.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Modern Ethernet LANs use a physical star with switches.","Coaxial bus wiring was used in legacy Ethernet, not modern LANs.","Token passing rings were used in older Token Ring networks, not typical modern Ethernet.","Full mesh between every workstation isn't practical or standard for typical LAN wiring."]},{"id":8,"question":"A company combines a star topology in its access layer with a partial mesh between distribution switches. What is this?","options":["Hybrid topology","Bus topology","Logical ring topology","Point-to-point topology"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Combining multiple topology types creates a hybrid topology.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Combining multiple topology types creates a hybrid topology.","Bus topology describes a single shared cable, not combining star and partial mesh elements.","A logical ring describes token-passing behavior, not combining star and mesh layouts.","Point-to-point describes one dedicated link between two devices, not this combined layout."]},{"id":9,"question":"Which topology is most sensitive to a single device failure in classic implementations?","options":["Ring topology","Full mesh topology","Star topology","Bus topology"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A break in a ring disrupts the entire loop unless redundancy is added.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["A break in a ring disrupts the entire loop unless redundancy is added.","Full mesh has multiple redundant paths, making it resilient to a single device failure.","Star topology isolates device failures since each connects independently to the center.","Bus topology can survive a single device failure since the shared cable itself isn't a single device."]},{"id":10,"question":"Which topology describes a direct link between exactly two network devices?","options":["Point-to-point topology","Star topology","Point-to-multipoint topology","Bus topology"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Point-to-point is a single dedicated connection between two endpoints.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Point-to-point is a single dedicated connection between two endpoints.","Star topology involves a central device connecting to multiple devices, not just two.","Point-to-multipoint involves one device connecting to several others, not just two.","Bus topology involves multiple devices sharing one cable, not a single dedicated link."]},{"id":11,"question":"Which topology is commonly used in wireless networks where one AP serves multiple clients?","options":["Point-to-multipoint topology","Bus topology","Ring topology","Full mesh topology"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Wi-Fi uses a point-to-multipoint structure with an AP at the center.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Wi-Fi uses a point-to-multipoint structure with an AP at the center.","Bus topology describes a shared cable, not one AP serving multiple wireless clients.","Ring topology describes a circular wired loop, not a wireless AP-to-clients structure.","Full mesh connects every device to every other device directly, not through one central AP."]},{"id":12,"question":"In a partial mesh topology, what is the main trade-off compared to full mesh?","options":["Less redundancy but lower cost and complexity","More redundancy but lower cost","Higher redundancy and higher cost","No redundancy but highest performance"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Partial mesh reduces cost while still offering some redundancy.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Partial mesh reduces cost while still offering some redundancy.","Partial mesh actually has less redundancy than full mesh, not more.","Higher redundancy and higher cost describes full mesh itself, not the partial-mesh trade-off.","Partial mesh still retains some redundancy; it isn't a no-redundancy design."]},{"id":13,"question":"At which OSI layer does a switch primarily operate when making forwarding decisions?","options":["Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 1 – Physical","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 4 – Transport"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Switches forward frames using MAC addresses at Layer 2.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Switches forward frames using MAC addresses at Layer 2.","Layer 1 handles physical signaling, not MAC-based forwarding decisions.","Layer 3 handles IP-based routing, which is a router's job, not a switch's basic forwarding.","Layer 4 handles end-to-end transport, unrelated to a switch's frame-forwarding function."]},{"id":14,"question":"At which OSI layer would you associate IP addressing and routing?","options":["Layer 3 – Network","Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 4 – Transport","Layer 7 – Application"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Routing and IP addressing occur at Layer 3.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Routing and IP addressing occur at Layer 3.","Layer 2 handles MAC addressing and frame forwarding, not IP addressing and routing.","Layer 4 handles segmentation and transport, not IP addressing decisions.","Layer 7 handles application-level protocols, not IP routing."]},{"id":15,"question":"Which OSI layer is responsible for segmentation and end-to-end transport?","options":["Layer 4 – Transport","Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 5 – Session"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Layer 4 handles segmentation, flow control, and reliability.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Layer 4 handles segmentation, flow control, and reliability.","Layer 2 handles frames and MAC addressing, not end-to-end segmentation.","Layer 3 handles routing between networks, not transport-level segmentation.","Layer 5 manages sessions, not the segmentation function itself."]},{"id":16,"question":"Which OSI layer would you troubleshoot if you suspect a bad cable or NIC port?","options":["Layer 1 – Physical","Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 4 – Transport"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Physical connectivity issues occur at Layer 1.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Physical connectivity issues occur at Layer 1.","Layer 2 handles frame forwarding, which assumes physical connectivity is already working.","Layer 3 handles routing, a layer above where a bad cable or NIC port issue would occur.","Layer 4 handles transport-level function, unrelated to a physical cable or port fault."]},{"id":17,"question":"Frame checksums and MAC address-based forwarding are associated with which OSI layer?","options":["Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 1 – Physical","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 7 – Application"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Layer 2 handles frames, MAC addresses, and link-level error detection.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Layer 2 handles frames, MAC addresses, and link-level error detection.","Layer 1 handles raw signal transmission, not checksums or MAC-based forwarding.","Layer 3 handles IP-based routing, not frame checksums or MAC forwarding.","Layer 7 handles application protocols, unrelated to frame-level checksums."]},{"id":18,"question":"Which OSI layer manages the setup, maintenance, and teardown of communication sessions?","options":["Layer 5 – Session","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 4 – Transport","Layer 6 – Presentation"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The Session layer manages dialogs between applications.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["The Session layer manages dialogs between applications.","Layer 3 handles routing, not session setup and teardown.","Layer 4 handles transport/segmentation, not session management.","Layer 6 handles data formatting/presentation, not session dialogs."]},{"id":19,"question":"Encryption and decryption are most commonly associated with which OSI layer?","options":["Layer 6 – Presentation","Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 7 – Application"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Layer 6 handles data formatting, compression, and encryption.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Layer 6 handles data formatting, compression, and encryption.","Layer 2 handles frames and MAC forwarding, not data formatting or encryption.","Layer 3 handles routing, not encryption/presentation formatting.","Layer 7 handles application protocols themselves, though encryption specifically is a Presentation-layer function."]},{"id":20,"question":"HTTP, FTP, and SMTP operate at which OSI layer?","options":["Layer 7 – Application","Layer 4 – Transport","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 2 – Data Link"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Application protocols operate at Layer 7.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Application protocols operate at Layer 7.","Layer 4 handles transport, not application protocols like HTTP/FTP/SMTP themselves.","Layer 3 handles routing, not application-level protocols.","Layer 2 handles frames, not application-level protocols."]},{"id":21,"question":"A router dropping packets due to an invalid IP address is a problem at which OSI layer?","options":["Layer 3 – Network","Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 4 – Transport","Layer 7 – Application"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Routers operate at Layer 3.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Routers operate at Layer 3.","Layer 2 handles MAC-based frame forwarding, not IP address validity.","Layer 4 handles transport, not the IP address validation performed by routers.","Layer 7 handles application protocols, not IP-level packet routing."]},{"id":22,"question":"TCP and UDP operate at which OSI layer?","options":["Layer 4 – Transport","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 1 – Physical"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"TCP and UDP are Transport layer protocols.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["TCP and UDP are Transport layer protocols.","Layer 3 handles IP addressing/routing, not TCP/UDP transport functions themselves.","Layer 2 handles frames, not transport protocols like TCP/UDP.","Layer 1 handles physical signaling, unrelated to TCP/UDP."]},{"id":23,"question":"Which OSI layer adds port numbers to direct traffic to the correct application?","options":["Layer 4 – Transport","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 5 – Session"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Port numbers are part of Layer 4.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Port numbers are part of Layer 4.","Layer 3 handles IP addressing, not port numbers.","Layer 2 handles MAC addressing, not port numbers.","Layer 5 manages sessions, not port-based application addressing."]},{"id":24,"question":"A user can ping a server but cannot load its webpage. Which OSI layer is likely at fault?","options":["Layer 7 – Application","Layer 1 – Physical","Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 3 – Network"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"If ping works but HTTP fails, the issue is at the Application layer.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["If ping works but HTTP fails, the issue is at the Application layer.","Layer 1 handles physical connectivity, which ping already confirms is working.","Layer 2 handles frame forwarding, which is already functioning since ping succeeds.","Layer 3 handles routing, which is already functioning since ping succeeds."]},{"id":25,"question":"Users on different switches in a star topology report slow file transfers. Which OSI layer should you check first?","options":["Layer 2 switches and VLAN configuration","Layer 1 cabling","Layer 7 application settings","Layer 5 session timers"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Inter-switch performance issues often relate to Layer 2.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Inter-switch performance issues often relate to Layer 2.","Cabling issues would typically show connectivity failures, not just slow transfers across switches.","Application settings wouldn't typically explain slow transfers specifically tied to switch-to-switch communication.","Session timers relate to session-layer behavior, not inter-switch transfer speed."]},{"id":26,"question":"In a bus topology, the shared coax cable primarily operates at which OSI layer?","options":["Layer 1 – Physical","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 4 – Transport","Layer 7 – Application"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The shared medium itself is a Layer 1 component.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["The shared medium itself is a Layer 1 component.","Layer 3 handles routing, not the physical shared cable medium itself.","Layer 4 handles transport, unrelated to the physical bus cable.","Layer 7 handles applications, unrelated to the physical medium."]},{"id":27,"question":"Redesigning a full mesh WAN into a partial mesh affects which OSI layer most directly?","options":["Layer 3 – Network","Layer 1 – Physical","Layer 4 – Transport","Layer 6 – Presentation"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"WAN topology changes affect routing paths at Layer 3.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["WAN topology changes affect routing paths at Layer 3.","Layer 1 handles physical links, not the routing-path changes from a topology redesign.","Layer 4 handles transport, not the routing paths affected by a WAN topology change.","Layer 6 handles presentation, unrelated to WAN routing topology."]},{"id":28,"question":"Frames are not circulating correctly between two adjacent nodes in a ring topology. Which OSI layers should you check first?","options":["Layer 1 (Physical) and Layer 2 (Data Link)","Layer 3 (Network) and Layer 4 (Transport)","Layer 5 (Session) and Layer 7 (Application)","Layer 2 (Data Link) and Layer 6 (Presentation)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Ring issues usually involve physical links or frame forwarding.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Ring issues usually involve physical links or frame forwarding.","Layer 3/4 handle routing and transport, not frame circulation between adjacent physical nodes.","Layer 5/7 handle sessions and applications, unrelated to frames not circulating in a ring.","Layer 6 handles presentation, not frame circulation issues in a ring."]},{"id":29,"question":"Which OSI layer is responsible for how data is formatted and presented to the user?","options":["Layer 6 – Presentation","Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 4 – Transport"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Layer 6 handles data format, character sets, and presentation.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["Layer 6 handles data format, character sets, and presentation.","Layer 2 handles frames/MAC addressing, not data formatting for the user.","Layer 3 handles routing, not data presentation.","Layer 4 handles transport, not data formatting/presentation."]},{"id":30,"question":"In a star topology, users can communicate locally but cannot reach external networks. Which device is most likely at fault?","options":["Layer 3 router or default gateway","Layer 1 patch panel","Layer 2 switch port","Layer 7 application proxy"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"If local traffic works but external traffic fails, the router/default gateway is the issue.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Day 1.html","optionExplanations":["If local traffic works but external traffic fails, the router/default gateway is the issue.","A patch panel is a passive Layer 1 component and wouldn't selectively block only external traffic.","A switch port issue would typically affect local connectivity too, not just external reachability.","An application proxy issue would show different symptoms than a general inability to reach external networks."]},{"id":31,"question":"An attacker forges the source Internet Protocol (IP) address of packets so traffic appears to come from a trusted host. Which attack type BEST matches this behavior?","options":["IP spoofing.","MAC spoofing.","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) poisoning.","Domain Name System (DNS) poisoning."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"IP spoofing falsifies the source Internet Protocol (IP) address so packets appear to originate from another system.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["IP spoofing falsifies the source Internet Protocol (IP) address so packets appear to originate from another system.","MAC spoofing falsifies a MAC address, not the IP address used to impersonate a trusted host.","ARP poisoning corrupts local ARP mappings; it doesn't itself forge the source IP address of packets.","DNS poisoning corrupts name resolution; it doesn't forge a packet's source IP address."]},{"id":32,"question":"A threat actor overwhelms a web server with excessive Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) synchronization packets but never completes the handshake, exhausting resources. Which attack is being performed?","options":["SYN flood.","Distributed denial-of-service (DDoS).","Smurf attack.","Replay attack."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A SYN flood sends many TCP SYN packets without completing the three-way handshake, consuming server state and resources.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A SYN flood sends many TCP SYN packets without completing the three-way handshake, consuming server state and resources.","A DDoS is a broader category of distributed attacks, not the specific incomplete-handshake technique described.","A Smurf attack uses spoofed ICMP broadcasts, not incomplete TCP handshakes.","A replay attack resends captured legitimate traffic, not incomplete SYN packets."]},{"id":33,"question":"A malicious user intercepts traffic between two hosts and secretly alters the data before forwarding it. Which attack type is occurring?","options":["Man-in-the-middle (MITM).","Replay attack.","Session hijacking.","IP spoofing."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A man-in-the-middle attack places the attacker between two communicating parties so traffic can be intercepted and manipulated.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A man-in-the-middle attack places the attacker between two communicating parties so traffic can be intercepted and manipulated.","A replay attack resends previously captured traffic; it doesn't actively alter data in real time between two hosts.","Session hijacking takes over an existing authenticated session, rather than altering traffic between two parties generally.","IP spoofing forges a source address; it doesn't describe intercepting and altering traffic in transit."]},{"id":34,"question":"A user receives an email that appears to come from corporate Information Technology (IT) and asks them to verify their password on a fake website. What attack is this?","options":["Phishing.","Smishing.","Vishing.","Spear phishing."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Phishing uses fraudulent email messages and links to trick users into revealing credentials or other sensitive data.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["Phishing uses fraudulent email messages and links to trick users into revealing credentials or other sensitive data.","Smishing is phishing conducted via SMS text message, not email.","Vishing is phishing conducted via a phone call, not email.","Spear phishing is a more specifically targeted version of this attack, not the general email-based technique described."]},{"id":35,"question":"An attacker sends gratuitous Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) replies that map the default gateway Internet Protocol (IP) address to the attacker's media access control (MAC) address. Which attack is being executed?","options":["ARP poisoning.","MAC spoofing.","Internet Protocol (IP) spoofing.","Domain Name System (DNS) hijacking."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"ARP poisoning corrupts local ARP caches so traffic intended for another device is redirected through the attacker.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["ARP poisoning corrupts local ARP caches so traffic intended for another device is redirected through the attacker.","MAC spoofing falsifies a device's own MAC address; it doesn't send gratuitous ARP replies mapping the gateway to the attacker.","IP spoofing forges a packet's source IP address, not ARP cache mappings.","DNS hijacking redirects name resolution, not local ARP cache entries."]},{"id":36,"question":"A wireless attacker captures authentication handshakes and then tries a huge number of possible passwords offline until one works. Which attack type is this?","options":["Brute-force attack.","Dictionary attack.","Deauthentication attack.","Evil twin attack."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A brute-force attack systematically tries all possible values or a very large keyspace until the correct credential is found.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A brute-force attack systematically tries all possible values or a very large keyspace until the correct credential is found.","A dictionary attack tries a curated list of likely passwords, not an exhaustive systematic search of the whole keyspace.","A deauthentication attack disconnects clients from the network; it doesn't crack captured handshakes offline.","An evil twin impersonates a legitimate access point; it doesn't describe offline password guessing."]},{"id":37,"question":"A malicious actor sets up a wireless access point that copies the service set identifier (SSID) of a legitimate network to lure users into connecting. What attack is this?","options":["Evil twin.","Rogue access point.","Deauthentication attack.","Captive portal spoofing."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An evil twin impersonates a legitimate wireless network so victims associate with the attacker's access point.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["An evil twin impersonates a legitimate wireless network so victims associate with the attacker's access point.","A generic rogue access point may not specifically copy the legitimate network's SSID to lure victims.","A deauthentication attack disconnects clients; it doesn't itself involve setting up a copycat access point.","Captive portal spoofing involves a fake login page, not the act of copying the SSID itself."]},{"id":38,"question":"A threat actor floods a switch with thousands of fake media access control (MAC) addresses so the switch begins forwarding frames out many ports. Which attack is being used?","options":["MAC flooding.","MAC spoofing.","ARP poisoning.","Broadcast storming."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"MAC flooding overwhelms the switch content-addressable memory table so the switch may start flooding traffic like a hub.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["MAC flooding overwhelms the switch content-addressable memory table so the switch may start flooding traffic like a hub.","MAC spoofing falsifies one device's MAC address; it doesn't flood the switch with thousands of fake entries.","ARP poisoning targets ARP cache mappings, not the switch's MAC address table capacity.","\"Broadcast storming\" isn't the standard term for this specific CAM-table-overflow technique."]},{"id":39,"question":"A malicious user repeatedly sends spoofed deauthentication frames to disconnect wireless clients from their access point. Which attack is this?","options":["Deauthentication attack.","Jamming.","Evil twin.","Disassociation monitoring."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A deauthentication attack forces clients off the network by sending forged management frames that tell them to disconnect.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A deauthentication attack forces clients off the network by sending forged management frames that tell them to disconnect.","Jamming disrupts the wireless signal itself, rather than sending forged disconnect frames.","An evil twin impersonates a legitimate access point; it doesn't itself send deauth frames to disconnect clients.","\"Disassociation monitoring\" isn't a recognized attack technique matching this forged-frame behavior."]},{"id":40,"question":"An attacker corrupts name-resolution data so users trying to reach a legitimate website are redirected to a malicious Internet Protocol (IP) address. Which attack is being performed?","options":["Domain Name System (DNS) poisoning.","Domain Name System (DNS) amplification.","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) poisoning.","IP spoofing."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"DNS poisoning tampers with cached or authoritative name-resolution data so victims are sent to attacker-controlled destinations.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["DNS poisoning tampers with cached or authoritative name-resolution data so victims are sent to attacker-controlled destinations.","DNS amplification abuses DNS servers to flood a victim with traffic, not to redirect users to a malicious site.","ARP poisoning corrupts local ARP mappings, not DNS name-resolution data.","IP spoofing forges a packet's source address; it doesn't corrupt name-resolution data."]},{"id":41,"question":"A threat actor captures legitimate authentication traffic and later retransmits it to gain unauthorized access. Which attack type is this?","options":["Replay attack.","Man-in-the-middle (MITM).","Session fixation.","Brute-force attack."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A replay attack reuses previously captured valid traffic, such as authentication exchanges, to impersonate an authorized user or device.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A replay attack reuses previously captured valid traffic, such as authentication exchanges, to impersonate an authorized user or device.","MITM actively intercepts and alters live traffic, rather than capturing and resending it later.","Session fixation forces a known session ID on a victim, not replaying previously captured traffic.","Brute-force systematically guesses credentials, not reusing captured legitimate traffic."]},{"id":42,"question":"A malicious user drives around neighborhoods searching for open or weak wireless networks. Which technique is this?","options":["War driving.","War chalking.","Site surveying.","Bluejacking."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"War driving is the act of moving through an area while detecting and mapping wireless networks.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["War driving is the act of moving through an area while detecting and mapping wireless networks.","War chalking marks physical locations with symbols; it doesn't involve actively driving around searching.","Site surveying assesses signal coverage for legitimate design purposes, not searching for exploitable networks.","Bluejacking sends unsolicited Bluetooth messages, unrelated to scanning for Wi-Fi networks while driving."]},{"id":43,"question":"An attacker sends Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) echo requests to a broadcast address while spoofing the victim's Internet Protocol (IP) address as the source. Which attack is this?","options":["Smurf attack.","SYN flood.","Ping flood.","Reflection attack."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A Smurf attack amplifies ICMP traffic by sending spoofed requests to broadcast-capable networks so many hosts reply to the victim.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A Smurf attack amplifies ICMP traffic by sending spoofed requests to broadcast-capable networks so many hosts reply to the victim.","A SYN flood exploits the TCP handshake, not ICMP broadcast amplification.","A ping flood sends many pings directly, without the broadcast amplification and spoofing described.","\"Reflection attack\" is a broader general term, while this specific ICMP-broadcast technique is a Smurf attack."]},{"id":44,"question":"A malicious actor sends unsolicited Bluetooth messages to nearby devices but does not steal data. Which attack is this?","options":["Bluejacking.","Bluesnarfing.","Bluebugging.","Near-field communication skimming."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Bluejacking pushes unsolicited Bluetooth messages or business cards to nearby devices without necessarily accessing stored data.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["Bluejacking pushes unsolicited Bluetooth messages or business cards to nearby devices without necessarily accessing stored data.","Bluesnarfing steals data from a device, unlike sending unsolicited messages without data theft.","Bluebugging takes remote control of a device's functions, beyond just sending messages.","NFC skimming captures contactless payment data, unrelated to Bluetooth messaging."]},{"id":45,"question":"A Bluetooth attacker connects to a nearby device and steals contacts or messages without authorization. Which attack is this?","options":["Bluesnarfing.","Bluejacking.","Bluebugging.","Evil twin."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Bluesnarfing is unauthorized access to information stored on a Bluetooth-enabled device.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["Bluesnarfing is unauthorized access to information stored on a Bluetooth-enabled device.","Bluejacking sends unsolicited messages without accessing stored data.","Bluebugging takes control of device functions like calls, beyond just stealing stored data.","An evil twin impersonates a Wi-Fi network, unrelated to Bluetooth data theft."]},{"id":46,"question":"A threat actor disrupts a wireless network by transmitting continuous radio frequency interference across the channel. Which attack is being executed?","options":["Jamming.","Deauthentication attack.","Evil twin.","War driving."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Jamming interferes with wireless communications by overwhelming the radio frequency spectrum used by legitimate devices.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["Jamming interferes with wireless communications by overwhelming the radio frequency spectrum used by legitimate devices.","A deauthentication attack sends forged disconnect frames, not continuous RF interference.","An evil twin impersonates a legitimate access point, not blanket RF interference.","War driving involves searching for networks, not disrupting them with interference."]},{"id":47,"question":"An attacker follows an authorized employee through a secured door without using a badge or authentication. Which attack is this?","options":["Tailgating.","Shoulder surfing.","Phishing.","Impersonation."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Tailgating is a physical security attack in which an unauthorized person follows an authorized user into a restricted area.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["Tailgating is a physical security attack in which an unauthorized person follows an authorized user into a restricted area.","Shoulder surfing involves visually observing someone's screen or input, not physically following through a door.","Phishing is an electronic message-based attack, not physical building access.","Impersonation involves posing as someone else, a related but distinct technique from simply following someone through a door."]},{"id":48,"question":"A malicious user marks sidewalks or buildings with symbols that describe nearby wireless network characteristics for other attackers. Which technique is this?","options":["War chalking.","War driving.","Bluejacking.","Site surveying."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"War chalking uses physical symbols to advertise wireless network details such as openness or security level.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["War chalking uses physical symbols to advertise wireless network details such as openness or security level.","War driving is the act of searching for networks while moving around, not marking physical locations.","Bluejacking sends unsolicited Bluetooth messages, unrelated to marking locations with symbols.","Site surveying assesses signal coverage for legitimate design, not marking locations for other attackers."]},{"id":49,"question":"A threat actor changes their network interface so it uses another device's media access control (MAC) address. Which attack type is this?","options":["MAC spoofing.","MAC flooding.","ARP poisoning.","IP spoofing."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"MAC spoofing alters the hardware address presented by a device so it appears to be another endpoint on the local network.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["MAC spoofing alters the hardware address presented by a device so it appears to be another endpoint on the local network.","MAC flooding overwhelms a switch's address table, rather than impersonating one specific device's address.","ARP poisoning corrupts ARP cache mappings, not changing one's own presented MAC address.","IP spoofing forges the IP address, not the MAC address."]},{"id":50,"question":"A malicious user sends fraudulent Short Message Service (SMS) messages to convince victims to reveal credentials or financial data. Which attack is this?","options":["Smishing.","Phishing.","Vishing.","Pretexting."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Smishing is phishing conducted through text messages rather than email.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["Smishing is phishing conducted through text messages rather than email.","Phishing is typically associated with email, not text messages specifically.","Vishing is voice-call-based, not text-message-based.","Pretexting relies on a fabricated scenario/story, not specifically SMS-delivered fraud."]},{"id":51,"question":"A threat actor places voice calls that appear to come from a trusted organization and pressures the victim to disclose sensitive information. Which attack is this?","options":["Vishing.","Phishing.","Smishing.","Whaling."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Vishing is voice-based social engineering, usually delivered through phone or Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) calls.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["Vishing is voice-based social engineering, usually delivered through phone or VoIP calls.","Phishing is typically email-based, not phone-call-based.","Smishing is text-message-based, not phone-call-based.","Whaling specifically targets high-profile executives, not phone calls in general."]},{"id":52,"question":"An attacker injects malicious script into a trusted website so the code runs in visitors' browsers. Which attack is this?","options":["Cross-site scripting (XSS).","Structured Query Language (SQL) injection.","Command injection.","Cross-site request forgery (CSRF)."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Cross-site scripting injects client-side code into a web page so the victim's browser executes it.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["Cross-site scripting injects client-side code into a web page so the victim's browser executes it.","SQL injection targets backend database queries, not client-side browser code execution.","Command injection executes OS-level commands on a server, not client-side scripts in a browser.","CSRF tricks a user's browser into making unwanted requests, rather than injecting scripts into the site itself."]},{"id":53,"question":"A threat actor manipulates backend database queries by placing crafted input into a web form. Which attack is this?","options":["Structured Query Language (SQL) injection.","Cross-site scripting (XSS).","Command injection.","Buffer overflow."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"SQL injection inserts malicious input into application fields so the backend database executes unintended queries.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["SQL injection inserts malicious input into application fields so the backend database executes unintended queries.","XSS injects client-side script into a browser, not backend database queries.","Command injection executes OS commands, not database queries specifically.","A buffer overflow exploits memory handling, not manipulating database queries through a web form."]},{"id":54,"question":"A malicious user installs unauthorized hardware on the network to capture or redirect traffic. Which attack is this?","options":["Rogue device.","Rogue access point.","Man-in-the-middle (MITM).","Port mirroring abuse."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A rogue device is unauthorized hardware placed on the network, often to observe, manipulate, or pivot through traffic.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A rogue device is unauthorized hardware placed on the network, often to observe, manipulate, or pivot through traffic.","A rogue access point is a specific type of rogue device focused on wireless access, narrower than general unauthorized hardware.","MITM describes intercepting traffic between parties, which could result from a rogue device but isn't the device itself.","\"Port mirroring abuse\" describes misusing a legitimate monitoring feature, not installing new unauthorized hardware."]},{"id":55,"question":"A threat actor uses a single compromised host under remote control to launch attacks while concealing the real source. Which term describes that compromised system?","options":["Zombie.","Botnet.","Agentless node.","Rogue host."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A zombie is one compromised system under attacker control that can be directed to participate in malicious activity.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A zombie is one compromised system under attacker control that can be directed to participate in malicious activity.","A botnet is the larger group of many zombie systems, not a single compromised host.","\"Agentless node\" isn't a security term describing a compromised, remotely controlled system.","\"Rogue host\" is a more general term, not the specific term for a bot-controlled compromised system."]},{"id":56,"question":"A large group of compromised hosts is centrally controlled and used to launch coordinated attacks. What is this called?","options":["Botnet.","Zombie.","Peer group.","Server farm."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A botnet is a collection of compromised systems that an attacker controls as a group.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A botnet is a collection of compromised systems that an attacker controls as a group.","A zombie is a single compromised host, not the entire coordinated group.","A peer group describes a general networking arrangement, not centrally controlled compromised systems.","A server farm is a legitimate cluster of servers, not compromised attacker-controlled hosts."]},{"id":57,"question":"A threat actor attempts to guess an account password by trying every possible combination until one succeeds. Which attack is this?","options":["Brute-force attack.","Dictionary attack.","Password spraying.","Replay attack."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A brute-force attack exhaustively tries combinations until the correct password is found.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A brute-force attack exhaustively tries combinations until the correct password is found.","A dictionary attack uses a curated wordlist, not every possible combination.","Password spraying tries a few common passwords across many accounts, not every combination against one account.","A replay attack resends captured traffic, not guessing password combinations."]},{"id":58,"question":"An attacker attempts unauthorized access by testing a list of common words and known weak passwords rather than every possible combination. Which attack is this?","options":["Dictionary attack.","Brute-force attack.","Password spraying.","Credential stuffing."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A dictionary attack uses a predefined wordlist of likely passwords instead of testing the full keyspace.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A dictionary attack uses a predefined wordlist of likely passwords instead of testing the full keyspace.","Brute-force tests every possible combination, not a predefined wordlist.","Password spraying tries common passwords across many different accounts, not one account with a wordlist.","Credential stuffing reuses previously breached username/password pairs, not a generic wordlist."]},{"id":59,"question":"A malicious user sends crafted traffic to exploit a service and make it unavailable to legitimate users. Which attack type is this?","options":["Denial-of-service (DoS).","Distributed denial-of-service (DDoS).","SYN flood.","Resource exhaustion."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A denial-of-service attack is any attack intended to disrupt availability for legitimate users, whether by crashing or exhausting the target.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A denial-of-service attack is any attack intended to disrupt availability for legitimate users, whether by crashing or exhausting the target.","DDoS specifically uses multiple distributed sources, a more specific case than general DoS.","A SYN flood is one specific technique used to carry out a DoS, not the general category itself.","\"Resource exhaustion\" describes one mechanism of causing a DoS, not the overall attack category name."]},{"id":60,"question":"A coordinated collection of compromised systems simultaneously overwhelms a target with traffic from many sources. Which attack is this?","options":["Distributed denial-of-service (DDoS).","Denial-of-service (DoS).","Smurf attack.","SYN flood."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A distributed denial-of-service attack uses many systems at once, making the attack harder to block and amplifying its impact.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 10_hardened_instant_feedback.html","optionExplanations":["A distributed denial-of-service attack uses many systems at once, making the attack harder to block and amplifying its impact.","DoS describes disruption generally and can come from a single source, not specifically many coordinated systems.","A Smurf attack is one specific amplification technique, not the general coordinated multi-source category.","A SYN flood is one specific technique, not necessarily involving many distributed compromised systems."]},{"id":61,"question":"A network administrator needs to track long-term performance trends, identify anomalies, and compare current behavior against historical norms. Which monitoring concept is being used?","options":["Baseline","Threshold alerting","system logging (Syslog) correlation","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) trap analysis"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Baselines establish normal performance levels for comparison.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Baselines establish normal performance levels for comparison.","Threshold alerting triggers on crossing a defined limit, not establishing the historical norm itself.","Syslog correlation cross-references log messages, not tracking long-term performance trends specifically.","SNMP trap analysis reviews unsolicited alerts, not building historical performance baselines."]},{"id":62,"question":"A monitoring system must notify administrators immediately when central processing unit (CPU) utilization exceeds 90% for more than 5 minutes. Which feature provides this functionality?","options":["Threshold alerting","Baseline reporting","Packet capture","system logging (Syslog) archiving"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Threshold alerts trigger notifications when metrics exceed defined limits.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Threshold alerts trigger notifications when metrics exceed defined limits.","Baseline reporting documents normal performance, not the alerting trigger itself.","Packet capture records raw traffic, unrelated to triggering a CPU-usage alert.","Syslog archiving stores log history, not real-time threshold-based alerting."]},{"id":63,"question":"A technician needs to collect interface statistics, bandwidth usage, and error counters from switches and routers. Which protocol is MOST appropriate?","options":["Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)","system logging (Syslog)","NetFlow","Network Time Protocol (NTP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) retrieves device metrics and performance counters.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) retrieves device metrics and performance counters.","Syslog centralizes log messages, not the interface counters and statistics themselves.","NetFlow provides traffic flow data, but SNMP is the standard protocol for polling interface statistics and error counters directly.","NTP synchronizes time, unrelated to collecting interface statistics."]},{"id":64,"question":"A network engineer wants to analyze traffic flows, including source/destination pairs and byte counts, to identify unusual patterns. Which technology provides this?","options":["NetFlow/Internet Protocol Flow Information Export (IPFIX)","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) polling of device counters","system logging (Syslog) message collection from devices","Traceroute path discovery between source and destination"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"NetFlow and Internet Protocol Flow Information Export (IPFIX) provide flow-level traffic analytics.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["NetFlow and Internet Protocol Flow Information Export (IPFIX) provide flow-level traffic analytics.","SNMP polling retrieves device counters and status, not detailed source/destination flow records.","Syslog collects log messages, not flow-level traffic statistics.","Traceroute shows the path to a destination, not aggregated flow traffic analytics."]},{"id":65,"question":"A centralized system collects log messages from routers, switches, firewalls, and servers for correlation and analysis. Which service is being used?","options":["system logging (Syslog)","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)","Network Time Protocol (NTP)","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"system logging (Syslog) centralizes log messages from network devices.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["system logging (Syslog) centralizes log messages from network devices.","SNMP polls device metrics/counters, rather than centralizing log messages for correlation.","NTP synchronizes time, unrelated to centralized log collection.","DHCP assigns IP addresses, unrelated to centralized logging."]},{"id":66,"question":"A technician needs to determine whether a network outage occurred at a specific time by reviewing historical logs. Which tool is MOST appropriate?","options":["system logging (Syslog) server","Packet sniffer","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) manager","NetFlow collector"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"system logging (Syslog) servers store historical logs for review.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["system logging (Syslog) servers store historical logs for review.","A packet sniffer captures live traffic, not historical logs of past events.","An SNMP manager polls current device metrics, not stored historical event logs.","A NetFlow collector stores traffic flow data, not general historical event logs."]},{"id":67,"question":"A network administrator wants to ensure accurate timestamps across all logs for correlation. Which protocol provides this?","options":["Network Time Protocol (NTP)","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)","system logging (Syslog)","Domain Name System (DNS)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Network Time Protocol (NTP) synchronizes time across devices.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Network Time Protocol (NTP) synchronizes time across devices.","SNMP polls device metrics, unrelated to synchronizing clocks.","Syslog centralizes log messages, but relies on accurate time from elsewhere rather than providing synchronization itself.","DNS resolves names to addresses, unrelated to time synchronization."]},{"id":68,"question":"A monitoring system receives unsolicited notifications from devices when critical events occur. What are these notifications called?","options":["Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) traps","system logging (Syslog) alerts written to a central log server","Threshold breach notifications configured within monitoring software","Flow records exported for later traffic analysis"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) traps are unsolicited alerts sent by agents.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) traps are unsolicited alerts sent by agents.","Syslog alerts are log-based messages written to a server, a different mechanism than SNMP's unsolicited trap notifications.","Threshold breaches are the triggering condition, not the specific unsolicited notification mechanism itself.","Flow records describe traffic patterns, not unsolicited event notifications from devices."]},{"id":69,"question":"A technician needs to capture packets to troubleshoot intermittent connectivity issues. Which tool is MOST appropriate?","options":["Protocol analyzer","system logging (Syslog) server","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) manager","NetFlow collector"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Protocol analyzers capture and decode packets.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Protocol analyzers capture and decode packets.","A syslog server stores log messages, not raw packet captures.","An SNMP manager polls device metrics, not packet-level captures.","A NetFlow collector records flow summaries, not full packet captures for detailed troubleshooting."]},{"id":70,"question":"A network engineer wants to identify the root cause of a performance issue by analyzing error counters and interface statistics. Which monitoring method is used?","options":["Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) polling","system logging (Syslog) parsing of collected device log messages","Packet capture and manual inspection of individual frames","Flow analysis of aggregated traffic source/destination pairs"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) polling retrieves interface statistics and counters.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.1","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) polling retrieves interface statistics and counters.","Syslog parsing reviews log messages, not the interface error counters and statistics themselves.","Packet capture inspects individual frames, a more granular and manual approach than polling counters.","Flow analysis reviews traffic patterns, not interface-level error counters and statistics directly."]},{"id":71,"question":"A company needs to ensure that critical services remain available even if a primary server fails. Which concept addresses this requirement?","options":["Redundancy","Baseline","system logging (Syslog) retention","Traffic shaping"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Redundancy ensures continued operation during failures.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Redundancy ensures continued operation during failures.","A baseline documents normal performance, not availability during a failure.","Syslog retention preserves log history, unrelated to service availability during failure.","Traffic shaping manages bandwidth prioritization, not availability during a server failure."]},{"id":72,"question":"A technician configures a secondary router to automatically take over if the primary router fails. Which disaster recovery concept is being implemented?","options":["Failover","Load balancing","Clustering","Snapshotting"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Failover automatically switches to a backup device.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Failover automatically switches to a backup device.","Load balancing distributes traffic across active devices, not switching to a backup after failure.","Clustering groups devices for availability generally, while the specific automatic switchover is failover.","Snapshotting captures system state, unrelated to automatically switching to a backup router."]},{"id":73,"question":"A company wants to minimize the amount of data lost during a disaster. Which metric measures acceptable data loss?","options":["recovery point objective (RPO)","recovery time objective (RTO)","mean time between failures (MTBF)","mean time to repair (MTTR)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"recovery point objective (RPO) defines how much data loss is acceptable.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["recovery point objective (RPO) defines how much data loss is acceptable.","RTO measures acceptable downtime duration, not acceptable data loss.","MTBF measures average time between failures, not acceptable data loss.","MTTR measures repair duration, not acceptable data loss."]},{"id":74,"question":"A business needs to restore critical services within 2 hours after a disaster. Which metric defines this requirement?","options":["recovery time objective (RTO)","recovery point objective (RPO)","mean time between failures (MTBF)","mean time to repair (MTTR)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"recovery time objective (RTO) defines how quickly services must be restored.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["recovery time objective (RTO) defines how quickly services must be restored.","RPO measures acceptable data loss, not restoration time.","MTBF measures average time between failures, not a target restoration time.","MTTR measures actual repair time, not a target restoration objective."]},{"id":75,"question":"A technician performs nightly backups and stores them offsite to protect against catastrophic loss. Which strategy is being used?","options":["Disaster recovery planning","Load balancing","Baseline creation","Traffic shaping"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Offsite backups are part of disaster recovery planning.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.1","objective":"Network Monitoring","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Offsite backups are part of disaster recovery planning.","Load balancing distributes active traffic, unrelated to offsite backup strategy.","Baseline creation establishes normal performance metrics, unrelated to disaster recovery backups.","Traffic shaping manages bandwidth, unrelated to offsite backup strategy."]},{"id":76,"question":"A company uses a combination of full backups on weekends and incremental backups on weekdays. Which backup strategy is this?","options":["Hybrid backup","Differential-only","Snapshot-only","Continuous replication"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Hybrid strategies combine full and incremental backups.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Hybrid strategies combine full and incremental backups.","\"Differential-only\" would mean only differential backups, not combining full and incremental.","\"Snapshot-only\" would mean only point-in-time snapshots, not full plus incremental backups.","Continuous replication mirrors data in real time, not scheduled full/incremental backup cycles."]},{"id":77,"question":"A technician needs to restore a system to the exact state it was in at a specific point in time. Which backup type is MOST appropriate?","options":["Snapshot","Incremental","Differential","Bare-metal"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Snapshots capture the system state at a moment in time.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Snapshots capture the system state at a moment in time.","Incremental backups capture only changes since the last backup, not necessarily a full exact point-in-time system state.","Differential backups capture changes since the last full backup, not necessarily a complete exact-state restore point.","Bare-metal backups restore an entire system to new hardware, a broader process than a specific point-in-time snapshot."]},{"id":78,"question":"A company replicates data in real time to a secondary data center. Which disaster recovery method is being used?","options":["Hot site","Warm site","Cold site","Incremental backup"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Hot sites maintain real-time replication and immediate failover capability.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Hot sites maintain real-time replication and immediate failover capability.","A warm site has hardware ready but needs data restoration, lacking real-time replication.","A cold site has minimal readiness and requires significant setup, not real-time replication.","Incremental backup is a data backup method, not a disaster recovery site type."]},{"id":79,"question":"A disaster recovery site has hardware installed but requires data restoration before becoming operational. Which type of site is this?","options":["Warm site","Hot site","Cold site","Hybrid site"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Warm sites have hardware ready but require data restoration.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Warm sites have hardware ready but require data restoration.","A hot site has real-time replication and immediate failover, more ready than requiring data restoration.","A cold site lacks installed hardware entirely, less ready than one with hardware already in place.","\"Hybrid site\" isn't one of the standard DR site tiers (hot/warm/cold)."]},{"id":80,"question":"A company maintains an empty facility with power and cooling but no hardware installed. Which type of disaster recovery (DR) site is this?","options":["Cold site","Warm site","Hot site","Hybrid site"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Cold sites have infrastructure but no equipment.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Cold sites have infrastructure but no equipment.","A warm site has hardware installed already, unlike an empty facility with no equipment.","A hot site has real-time replication and ready hardware, unlike an empty facility.","\"Hybrid site\" isn't one of the standard DR site tiers (hot/warm/cold)."]},{"id":81,"question":"A technician needs to verify that backup files can be restored successfully. Which process is being performed?","options":["Backup testing","Baseline validation","Failover simulation","Log correlation"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Backup testing ensures restorability.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.1","objective":"Network Monitoring","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Backup testing ensures restorability.","Baseline validation compares current performance to an established norm, not verifying restore success.","Failover simulation tests switching to a standby system, not restoring backup files specifically.","Log correlation cross-references log entries, unrelated to verifying backup restorability."]},{"id":82,"question":"A company wants to ensure that critical applications remain available even during maintenance windows. Which concept supports this?","options":["High availability","Cold site","Baseline reporting","Traffic policing"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"High availability ensures continuous uptime.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.1","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["High availability ensures continuous uptime.","A cold site is a backup facility that takes time to activate, not a way to keep current systems available during maintenance.","Baseline reporting documents normal performance levels, not availability during maintenance.","Traffic policing enforces bandwidth limits, unrelated to maintaining availability during maintenance."]},{"id":83,"question":"A network engineer configures multiple servers to share workload and improve performance. Which concept is being used?","options":["Load balancing","Failover","Clustering","Snapshotting"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Load balancing distributes traffic across multiple servers.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Load balancing distributes traffic across multiple servers.","Failover switches to a standby system after a failure, rather than actively sharing workload.","Clustering groups servers together for availability, but the specific act of distributing load is load balancing.","Snapshotting captures a point-in-time system state, unrelated to distributing workload."]},{"id":84,"question":"A technician needs to identify unusual spikes in bandwidth usage. Which monitoring tool is MOST appropriate?","options":["NetFlow analyzer","system logging (Syslog) server","Network Time Protocol (NTP) server","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) logs"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"NetFlow provides traffic flow visibility.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["NetFlow provides traffic flow visibility.","A syslog server collects event logs, not traffic flow/bandwidth statistics.","An NTP server synchronizes time, unrelated to bandwidth monitoring.","DHCP logs record address leases, not bandwidth usage patterns."]},{"id":85,"question":"A company wants to ensure that logs are retained for compliance and forensic analysis. Which concept applies?","options":["Log retention policy","Baseline creation","Failover planning","Snapshot rotation"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Log retention policies define how long logs must be stored.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.1","objective":"Network Monitoring","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Log retention policies define how long logs must be stored.","Baseline creation establishes normal performance metrics, not log storage duration.","Failover planning prepares for switching to backup systems, unrelated to log retention.","Snapshot rotation manages point-in-time system captures, not log storage duration."]},{"id":86,"question":"A technician needs to identify the root cause of a network outage by reviewing event messages from multiple devices. Which tool is MOST appropriate?","options":["security information and event management (SIEM)","A packet sniffer captures individual packets on one segment, not correlated event logs from multiple devices","A NetFlow collector tracks traffic flow statistics, not general event log correlation across devices","A Network Time Protocol (NTP) server synchronizes clocks; it doesn't collect or correlate event logs"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"security information and event management (SIEM) systems correlate logs from multiple sources.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["security information and event management (SIEM) systems correlate logs from multiple sources.","A packet sniffer captures individual packets on one segment, not correlated event logs from multiple devices.","A NetFlow collector tracks traffic flow statistics, not general event log correlation across devices.","A Network Time Protocol (NTP) server synchronizes clocks; it doesn't collect or correlate event logs."]},{"id":87,"question":"A company wants to reduce downtime by having a secondary system ready to take over instantly. Which concept supports this?","options":["Hot standby","Cold site","Incremental backup","Baseline monitoring"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Hot standby systems are ready for immediate failover.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.1","objective":"Network Monitoring","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["Hot standby systems are ready for immediate failover.","A cold site requires time to activate and provision, not an instantly ready standby system.","Incremental backup saves changed data over time, unrelated to instant failover readiness.","Baseline monitoring tracks normal performance, not standby system readiness."]},{"id":88,"question":"A technician needs to determine how long a device typically operates before failing. Which metric is used?","options":["mean time between failures (MTBF)","mean time to repair (MTTR)","recovery time objective (RTO)","recovery point objective (RPO)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"mean time between failures (MTBF) measures average time between failures.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["mean time between failures (MTBF) measures average time between failures.","MTTR measures how long repairs take, not the time between failures.","RTO defines the target time to restore a system after an outage, not average operating time before failure.","RPO defines acceptable data loss in time, not average operating time before failure."]},{"id":89,"question":"A network engineer wants to measure how long it takes to repair a failed device. Which metric applies?","options":["mean time to repair (MTTR)","mean time between failures (MTBF)","recovery time objective (RTO)","recovery point objective (RPO)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"mean time to repair (MTTR) measures repair time.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["mean time to repair (MTTR) measures repair time.","MTBF measures average time between failures, not repair duration.","RTO defines the target restoration time as a goal, not a measured repair duration metric.","RPO defines acceptable data loss, unrelated to repair time."]},{"id":90,"question":"A company performs a simulated disaster scenario to test its recovery procedures. Which process is this?","options":["disaster recovery (DR) drill","Baseline validation","Failover rotation","Log correlation"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"disaster recovery (DR) drills test disaster recovery readiness.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.1","objective":"Network Monitoring","source":"Net + Day 11.html","optionExplanations":["disaster recovery (DR) drills test disaster recovery readiness.","Baseline validation checks normal performance metrics, not simulated disaster response.","Failover rotation cycles through standby systems, not a simulated disaster test itself.","Log correlation cross-references log data, unrelated to disaster recovery testing."]},{"id":91,"question":"A technician is staging six laptops in a temporary classroom. The laptops need to exchange files directly with one another, and there is no access point (AP) available. Which wireless mode should be used?","options":["Ad hoc mode.","Bridge mode.","Mesh mode.","Repeater mode."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Ad hoc mode allows wireless clients to communicate directly without an access point (AP). Bridge mode links network segments, mesh provides resilient access point (AP)-to-access point (AP) paths, and repeater mode extends existing coverage.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["Ad hoc mode allows wireless clients to communicate directly without an access point (AP). Bridge mode links network segments, mesh provides resilient AP-to-AP paths, and repeater mode extends existing coverage.","Bridge mode links two separate network segments together, not direct client-to-client file exchange.","Mesh mode provides resilient AP-to-AP paths, not direct client-to-client connections without any AP.","Repeater mode extends existing AP coverage, rather than enabling direct client-to-client communication."]},{"id":92,"question":"A network engineer must connect two buildings across a parking lot with a focused point-to-point wireless link. Which antenna type is the best fit?","options":["Yagi antenna.","Dipole antenna.","Omnidirectional antenna.","Rubber duck antenna."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A Yagi antenna is directional and suited for longer point-to-point links. Dipole, omnidirectional, and rubber duck antennas radiate more broadly and are not the best choice for a focused building-to-building path.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["A Yagi antenna is directional and suited for longer point-to-point links. Dipole, omnidirectional, and rubber duck antennas radiate more broadly and are not the best choice for a focused building-to-building path.","A dipole antenna radiates broadly in a donut pattern, not a focused point-to-point beam.","An omnidirectional antenna spreads signal in all directions, unsuitable for a focused long link.","A rubber duck antenna is a compact omnidirectional design, not suited for focused long-distance links."]},{"id":93,"question":"A wireless admin is deploying three nearby 2.4 gigahertz (GHz) access points in a busy office. Which channel plan best reduces overlap?","options":["Channels 1, 6, and 11.","Channels 2, 6, and 10.","Channels 3, 7, and 11.","Channels 4, 8, and 12."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"In the 2.4 gigahertz (GHz) band, 1, 6, and 11 are the standard non-overlapping channels. The other sets still overlap and create interference.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["In the 2.4 gigahertz (GHz) band, 1, 6, and 11 are the standard non-overlapping channels. The other sets still overlap and create interference.","Channels 2, 6, and 10 still overlap with each other in the 2.4 GHz band.","Channels 3, 7, and 11 still overlap with each other in the 2.4 GHz band.","Channels 4, 8, and 12 still overlap with each other in the 2.4 GHz band."]},{"id":94,"question":"A security team is replacing an old wireless deployment and wants the strongest modern protection for a new employee service set identifier (SSID). Which option should be selected?","options":["Wi‑Fi Protected Access 3 (WPA3) with Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE).","Wi‑Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) with Temporal Key Integrity Protocol (TKIP).","Wi‑Fi Protected Access (WPA) with Temporal Key Integrity Protocol (TKIP).","Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) with Rivest Cipher 4 (RC4)."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Wi‑Fi Protected Access 3 (WPA3) with Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) is the strongest current choice among these options. Wi‑Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) with Temporal Key Integrity Protocol (TKIP), Wi‑Fi Protected Access (WPA), and Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) are weaker or outdated.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.1","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["Wi‑Fi Protected Access 3 (WPA3) with Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) is the strongest current choice among these options. WPA2 with TKIP, WPA, and WEP are weaker or outdated.","WPA2 with TKIP uses an outdated, weaker cipher than current best practice.","WPA with TKIP is an older, weaker standard than WPA3.","WEP with RC4 is obsolete and easily broken, far weaker than modern options."]},{"id":95,"question":"Users in a warehouse report poor Wi-Fi reception after new storage walls were installed. Which condition is the most likely cause of signal loss?","options":["Concrete barriers.","Long Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) leases.","Disabled service set identifier (SSID) broadcast.","Misnumbered virtual local area networks (VLANs)."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Dense materials such as concrete attenuate radio frequency (RF) signals. Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) leases, service set identifier (SSID) broadcast settings, and virtual local area network (VLAN) numbering do not directly cause radio frequency (RF) absorption.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["Dense materials such as concrete attenuate radio frequency (RF) signals. DHCP leases, SSID broadcast settings, and VLAN numbering do not directly cause RF absorption.","DHCP lease length affects address renewal timing, not radio signal strength.","Disabled SSID broadcast hides the network name, but doesn't affect signal penetration through walls.","VLAN numbering affects logical network segmentation, not physical RF signal attenuation."]},{"id":96,"question":"A small office needs better Wi-Fi coverage in a conference room, but running new Ethernet is not currently possible. Which device is the best choice?","options":["Wireless range extender.","Load balancer appliance.","Forward proxy server.","Network intrusion detection system (IDS) sensor."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A wireless range extender retransmits an existing signal into the weak area. The other options do not extend Wi-Fi coverage.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["A wireless range extender retransmits an existing signal into the weak area. The other options do not extend Wi-Fi coverage.","A load balancer distributes traffic across servers, unrelated to extending Wi-Fi coverage.","A forward proxy manages outbound web requests, not wireless signal coverage.","An IDS sensor monitors for intrusions, unrelated to extending wireless coverage."]},{"id":97,"question":"A company wants new access points (APs) to support 5 gigahertz (GHz) operation and multi-user, multiple input, multiple output (MU‑MIMO) for higher throughput. Which standard meets that requirement best?","options":["802.11ac standard.","802.11g standard.","802.11b standard.","802.11a bridge mode."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"802.11ac operates on 5 gigahertz (GHz) and supports multi-user, multiple input, multiple output (MU‑MIMO). 802.11g and 802.11b are older, slower standards, and 802.11a bridge mode is not the correct standard reference here.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["802.11ac operates on 5 GHz and supports MU-MIMO. 802.11g and 802.11b are older, slower standards, and 802.11a bridge mode is not the correct standard reference here.","802.11g operates only on 2.4 GHz and doesn't support MU-MIMO.","802.11b is an older, slower 2.4 GHz-only standard without MU-MIMO support.","\"802.11a bridge mode\" isn't a standard matching the 5 GHz/MU-MIMO requirement described."]},{"id":98,"question":"A technician is terminating copper cabling onto a patch panel in a new main distribution frame (MDF). Which tool is required for the job?","options":["Punchdown tool.","Crimping tool.","Optical power meter.","Loopback adapter."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A punchdown tool seats copper pairs into insulation displacement connector (IDC) terminals on a patch panel. Crimpers are used for modular connectors, while the other tools serve different purposes.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["A punchdown tool seats copper pairs into IDC terminals on a patch panel. Crimpers are used for modular connectors, while the other tools serve different purposes.","A crimping tool attaches modular connectors like RJ45 plugs, not IDC terminals on a patch panel.","An optical power meter measures fiber signal strength, unrelated to copper patch panel termination.","A loopback adapter tests port function, not for terminating cabling onto a patch panel."]},{"id":99,"question":"A company is configuring enterprise wireless authentication with a Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) server for employee logins. Which method should be used?","options":["802.1X authentication.","Wi‑Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) personal mode.","Wi‑Fi Protected Setup (WPS).","Open authentication."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"802.1X is the enterprise authentication framework used with Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS). Wi‑Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) personal uses a shared passphrase, Wi‑Fi Protected Setup (WPS) is for simplified setup, and open authentication provides no real access control.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["802.1X is the enterprise authentication framework used with RADIUS. WPA2 personal uses a shared passphrase, WPS is for simplified setup, and open authentication provides no real access control.","WPA2 Personal uses a shared passphrase, not RADIUS-based individual authentication.","WPS is a simplified setup method, not an enterprise RADIUS authentication framework.","Open authentication provides no real access control at all."]},{"id":100,"question":"An access point is being mounted in the center of a large open workspace. Which antenna pattern is best for even horizontal coverage?","options":["Omnidirectional pattern.","Yagi directional pattern.","Parabolic dish pattern.","Laser line pattern."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An omnidirectional antenna radiates in all horizontal directions, making it ideal for broad room coverage. Yagi and parabolic designs are directional.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["An omnidirectional antenna radiates in all horizontal directions, making it ideal for broad room coverage. Yagi and parabolic designs are directional.","A Yagi antenna is directional, focusing signal in one direction rather than evenly around a room.","A parabolic dish is highly directional, suited for long point-to-point links, not broad room coverage.","A \"laser line pattern\" isn't a real RF antenna pattern relevant to Wi-Fi coverage."]},{"id":101,"question":"A cable run must pass near industrial motors and electrical lines. Which medium is most resistant to electromagnetic interference (EMI) and radio frequency interference (RFI)?","options":["Fiber optic cable.","Unshielded twisted pair.","Shielded twisted pair.","Thick coaxial cable."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Fiber optic cable uses light instead of electrical signaling, so it is immune to electromagnetic interference (EMI) and radio frequency interference (RFI). Copper media can still be affected to some degree.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["Fiber optic cable uses light instead of electrical signaling, so it is immune to EMI and RFI. Copper media can still be affected to some degree.","Unshielded twisted pair has no shielding and is vulnerable to EMI/RFI near industrial equipment.","Shielded twisted pair reduces some interference but is still more susceptible than fiber, which uses light instead of electricity.","Thick coaxial cable is still a copper conductor and remains susceptible to EMI/RFI, unlike fiber."]},{"id":102,"question":"A company wants the highest throughput and better efficiency for dense wireless client environments. Which wireless local area network (WLAN) standard is the best choice?","options":["802.11ax standard.","802.11ac standard.","802.11n standard.","802.11g standard."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"802.11ax, also known as Wi-Fi 6, improves efficiency and throughput in dense deployments. The other standards are older and less capable.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["802.11ax, also known as Wi-Fi 6, improves efficiency and throughput in dense deployments. The other standards are older and less capable.","802.11ac is capable but less efficient in dense client environments than 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6).","802.11n is an older standard with lower throughput and less efficient dense-client handling.","802.11g is an older, slower 2.4 GHz-only standard, not suited for dense high-throughput needs."]},{"id":103,"question":"A rack installer wants to keep patch cables neat and maintain airflow inside a network cabinet. Which component should be added?","options":["Cable management panel.","Keystone wall plate.","registered jack 45 (RJ45) strain boot.","Media converter tray."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A cable management panel organizes patch cables in a rack and helps preserve airflow. The other items do not provide the same rack-level cable organization.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["A cable management panel organizes patch cables in a rack and helps preserve airflow. The other items do not provide the same rack-level cable organization.","A keystone wall plate terminates cabling at a wall outlet, not rack-level cable organization.","An RJ45 strain boot protects an individual cable's connector, not overall rack cable management.","A media converter tray houses media converters, not general cable organization."]},{"id":104,"question":"Coverage at the far end of a conference room is weak. Which access point setting most directly affects how far the signal reaches?","options":["Transmit power level.","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) lease period.","Native virtual local area network (VLAN) value.","service set identifier (SSID) visibility state."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Transmit power has a direct effect on radio frequency (RF) range. Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) leases, virtual local area network (VLAN) values, and service set identifier (SSID) visibility do not change the physical reach of the signal.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["Transmit power has a direct effect on RF range. DHCP leases, VLAN values, and SSID visibility do not change the physical reach of the signal.","DHCP lease period affects address renewal timing, not radio signal range.","Native VLAN value affects logical network segmentation, not physical signal reach.","SSID visibility affects whether the network name is broadcast, not signal range."]},{"id":105,"question":"Two wired local area networks (LANs) on opposite sides of a courtyard need to be connected over Wi-Fi without laying fiber. Which device role should be used?","options":["Wireless bridge role.","Wireless repeater role.","Wireless client role.","Wireless scanner role."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A wireless bridge connects separate wired local area network (LAN) segments over a wireless link. A repeater extends coverage, while a client role joins an existing wireless local area network (WLAN).","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["A wireless bridge connects separate wired LAN segments over a wireless link. A repeater extends coverage, while a client role joins an existing WLAN.","A wireless repeater extends coverage of an existing network, not linking two separate wired LANs.","A wireless client role joins an existing WLAN as an endpoint, not connecting two LAN segments.","A \"wireless scanner\" role isn't a standard device role for linking wired networks."]},{"id":106,"question":"A wireless admin is assigning 5 gigahertz (GHz) channels and wants to identify the range that requires Dynamic Frequency Selection (DFS) checks for radar. Which range is correct?","options":["Channels 52 through 144.","Channels 1 through 11.","Channels 36 through 48.","Channels 149 through 165."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Dynamic Frequency Selection (DFS) applies to much of the mid-5 gigahertz (GHz) spectrum, including channels 52 through 144. The 2.4 gigahertz (GHz) channels and the lower and upper non-Dynamic Frequency Selection (DFS) 5 gigahertz (GHz) groups do not match that range.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["DFS applies to much of the mid-5 GHz spectrum, including channels 52 through 144. The 2.4 GHz channels and the lower and upper non-DFS 5 GHz groups do not match that range.","Channels 1-11 are in the 2.4 GHz band, unrelated to 5 GHz DFS requirements.","Channels 36-48 are the lower 5 GHz UNII-1 band, which doesn't require DFS.","Channels 149-165 are the upper 5 GHz UNII-3 band, which also doesn't require DFS."]},{"id":107,"question":"A technician needs to confirm a new Ethernet drop has proper continuity and pin mapping before it is handed off. Which tool should be used first?","options":["Cable tester.","Tone generator.","Protocol analyzer.","Optical loss meter."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A cable tester verifies continuity and pinout on Ethernet cable. A tone generator traces cable paths, while the other tools are for different tasks.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["A cable tester verifies continuity and pinout on Ethernet cable. A tone generator traces cable paths, while the other tools are for different tasks.","A tone generator traces cable paths, not verify pin mapping/continuity directly.","A protocol analyzer inspects network traffic, unrelated to physical cable continuity.","An optical loss meter tests fiber signal loss, not copper Ethernet continuity."]},{"id":108,"question":"Users need to walk between floors and remain connected to the same wireless network without manually reconnecting. Which feature enables this behavior?","options":["Client roaming.","Port bonding.","Packet shaping.","service set identifier (SSID) cloaking."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Roaming allows a client to move from one access point (AP) to another while maintaining connectivity. The other features do not describe handoff between access points (APs).","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["Roaming allows a client to move from one AP to another while maintaining connectivity. The other features do not describe handoff between access points.","Port bonding combines multiple physical links for bandwidth/redundancy, unrelated to wireless handoff.","Packet shaping controls traffic flow prioritization, unrelated to maintaining connection while moving between APs.","SSID cloaking hides the network name, unrelated to handoff between access points."]},{"id":109,"question":"A Wi‑Fi 6 deployment is being optimized for many simultaneous users in a lecture hall. Which feature most directly improves efficient shared access?","options":["orthogonal frequency-division multiple access (OFDMA) scheduling.","Wi-Fi Protected Setup (WPS) enrollment simplifies connecting new devices; it doesn't improve shared-access efficiency for many simultaneous users","Captive portal mode handles a login/splash page for guest access; it doesn't address efficient spectrum sharing","Frequency hopping is a legacy spread-spectrum technique, not a Wi-Fi 6 efficiency feature for many simultaneous users"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"orthogonal frequency-division multiple access (OFDMA) is a key Wi‑Fi 6 feature that improves spectrum efficiency by dividing channels into smaller resource units for multiple clients.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["orthogonal frequency-division multiple access (OFDMA) is a key Wi‑Fi 6 feature that improves spectrum efficiency by dividing channels into smaller resource units for multiple clients.","Wi-Fi Protected Setup (WPS) enrollment simplifies connecting new devices; it doesn't improve shared-access efficiency for many simultaneous users.","Captive portal mode handles a login/splash page for guest access; it doesn't address efficient spectrum sharing.","Frequency hopping is a legacy spread-spectrum technique, not a Wi-Fi 6 efficiency feature for many simultaneous users."]},{"id":110,"question":"An installer must attach access points securely to the suspended ceiling grid in an office renovation. Which component is intended for that job?","options":["access point (AP) mounting bracket.","Surface raceway cover.","Rack cable lacer.","Patch panel insert."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An access point (AP) mounting bracket is designed to secure the access point to the ceiling structure. The other items are used for different installation tasks.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["An access point mounting bracket is designed to secure the access point to the ceiling structure. The other items are used for different installation tasks.","A surface raceway cover protects wall-routed cabling, not mounting hardware for ceiling-installed APs.","A rack cable lacer organizes cables within a rack, unrelated to ceiling-mounted AP installation.","A patch panel insert is part of rack-mounted cable termination, not AP ceiling mounting."]},{"id":111,"question":"A legacy guest wireless local area network (WLAN) still uses a weak encryption method that can be cracked quickly and should be removed. Which method is it?","options":["Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) security.","Wi‑Fi Protected Access 3 (WPA3) security.","Wi‑Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) with Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) security.","Wi‑Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) Enterprise security."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) is obsolete and insecure. Wi‑Fi Protected Access 3 (WPA3), Wi‑Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) with Advanced Encryption Standard (AES), and Wi‑Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) Enterprise are stronger options than Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP).","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["WEP is obsolete and insecure. WPA3, WPA2 with AES, and WPA2 Enterprise are stronger options than WEP.","WPA3 is the current strongest standard, not a weak legacy method needing removal.","WPA2 with AES is a strong, modern option, not the weak legacy method described.","WPA2 Enterprise is a strong, modern authentication option, not the weak legacy method described."]},{"id":112,"question":"A warehouse with tall metal shelving has unstable signal quality because radio waves are bouncing off surfaces. What is the most likely radio frequency (RF) issue?","options":["Multipath interference.","Address exhaustion.","Subnet overlap.","Route summarization."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Reflective surfaces can create multipath interference by causing radio frequency (RF) signals to arrive along multiple paths. The other answers are unrelated to radio frequency (RF) reflection.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["Reflective surfaces can create multipath interference by causing RF signals to arrive along multiple paths. The other answers are unrelated to RF reflection.","Address exhaustion relates to running out of IP addresses, unrelated to RF signal reflection.","Subnet overlap is an IP addressing conflict, unrelated to RF signal bouncing off surfaces.","Route summarization is a routing efficiency technique, unrelated to RF reflection issues."]},{"id":113,"question":"A long-distance directional wireless connection is being built between two buildings to link their wired networks. Which wireless mode best fits the design?","options":["Bridge mode.","Ad hoc mode.","Hotspot mode.","Monitor mode."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Bridge mode is used to connect separate wired networks over a wireless link. Ad hoc mode is client-to-client, hotspot mode provides access service, and monitor mode is for capture and analysis.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["Bridge mode is used to connect separate wired networks over a wireless link. Ad hoc mode is client-to-client, hotspot mode provides access service, and monitor mode is for capture and analysis.","Ad hoc mode connects clients directly to each other, not linking two separate wired networks.","Hotspot mode provides internet access service to clients, not a point-to-point building link.","Monitor mode captures wireless traffic for analysis, not for linking networks."]},{"id":114,"question":"A company needs an outdoor backbone run between buildings for a wireless backhaul project. Which cable type is most appropriate for the long distance?","options":["Fiber optic cable.","Category 3 cable.","Category 5e cable.","RG-59 coax cable."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Fiber is the best choice for long outdoor interbuilding runs because of distance capability and electromagnetic interference (EMI) immunity. The copper options are less suitable for this backbone use.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["Fiber is the best choice for long outdoor interbuilding runs because of distance capability and EMI immunity. The copper options are less suitable for this backbone use.","Category 3 cable is an outdated, low-bandwidth copper cable unsuited for a long backbone run.","Category 5e cable has significant distance limitations compared to fiber for a long outdoor backbone.","RG-59 coax is intended for video/CATV runs, not a modern outdoor network backbone."]},{"id":115,"question":"An administrator wants to increase throughput on a 5 gigahertz (GHz) access point (AP) by combining adjacent channels into a wider channel. Which feature is being configured?","options":["Channel bonding.","Band steering.","Airtime fairness.","Client isolation."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Channel bonding combines adjacent channels to create greater bandwidth. Band steering nudges clients between bands, airtime fairness adjusts usage, and client isolation separates endpoints.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["Channel bonding combines adjacent channels to create greater bandwidth. Band steering nudges clients between bands, airtime fairness adjusts usage, and client isolation separates endpoints.","Band steering nudges dual-band clients toward one band or another, not combining channels.","Airtime fairness balances how much time each client gets on the air, not channel width.","Client isolation prevents wireless clients from communicating with each other, unrelated to channel width."]},{"id":116,"question":"A technician is routing data cabling along an office wall and wants both protection and a clean appearance. Which item should be installed?","options":["Surface raceway.","Cable certifier.","Patch panel shelf.","Modular coupler."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A surface raceway protects and conceals cabling routed along a wall. The other items do not provide wall-mounted cable protection.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["A surface raceway protects and conceals cabling routed along a wall. The other items do not provide wall-mounted cable protection.","A cable certifier tests cable performance, not physical wall-mounted protection.","A patch panel shelf supports rack-mounted patch panels, not wall-routed cabling.","A modular coupler joins two cable segments, not wall-mounted cable protection/concealment."]},{"id":117,"question":"A wireless engineer wants the access point (AP) to focus radio frequency (RF) energy toward associated clients to improve signal quality and throughput. Which feature should be enabled?","options":["Beamforming feature.","Channel hopping feature.","service set identifier (SSID) hiding feature.","Port mirroring feature."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Beamforming directs radio frequency (RF) energy toward clients to improve signal quality. The other options do not perform directional radio frequency (RF) optimization.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["Beamforming directs RF energy toward clients to improve signal quality. The other options do not perform directional RF optimization.","Channel hopping changes operating channels over time, unrelated to focusing signal toward clients.","SSID hiding conceals the network name, unrelated to directional signal focusing.","Port mirroring copies traffic for monitoring on a switch, unrelated to wireless signal direction."]},{"id":118,"question":"During a cabling project, a technician must identify the matching far-end cable hidden inside a wall cavity. Which tool pair is best for the task?","options":["Tone generator and probe.","Crimper and die set.","Cable tester and loopback.","Protocol sniffer and tap."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A tone generator and probe help trace and identify cable runs through walls or ceilings. The other tool pairs do not provide the same tracing function.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["A tone generator and probe help trace and identify cable runs through walls or ceilings. The other tool pairs do not provide the same tracing function.","A crimper and die set attaches connectors to cable ends, not tracing hidden cable runs.","A cable tester and loopback verify continuity/wiring, not tracing which physical cable is which inside a wall.","A protocol sniffer and tap capture network traffic, unrelated to physically tracing cable runs."]},{"id":119,"question":"A large facility wants wireless coverage that can automatically reroute traffic if one access point (AP) fails. Which topology best provides self-healing behavior?","options":["Mesh topology.","Star topology.","Bus topology.","Ring topology."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A mesh topology can reroute traffic dynamically when a node becomes unavailable. Star, bus, and ring do not describe the same wireless self-healing design.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 12 .html","optionExplanations":["A mesh topology can reroute traffic dynamically when a node becomes unavailable. Star, bus, and ring do not describe the same wireless self-healing design.","Star topology depends on one central device, without the dynamic self-healing rerouting of mesh.","Bus topology relies on a shared cable without dynamic rerouting capability.","Ring topology is vulnerable to a single break unless special redundancy is added, unlike self-healing mesh."]},{"id":120,"question":"A network administrator is deploying a new cloud-based file storage system that users can access from any device without installing additional software. Which cloud service model does this represent?","options":["Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Software as a Service (SaaS)","Security as a Service (SECaaS)"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Software as a Service (SaaS) provides fully managed applications accessible through a browser or app without requiring local installation.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["IaaS provides virtualized infrastructure like servers and storage, not a ready-to-use application.","PaaS provides a platform for developers to build applications, not an end-user-ready application.","Software as a Service (SaaS) provides fully managed applications accessible through a browser or app without requiring local installation.","\"Security as a Service\" delivers security tools/services, not general file storage software."]},{"id":121,"question":"A company wants full control over the operating system and installed applications but does not want to maintain physical servers. Which cloud model best fits this requirement?","options":["Software as a Service (SaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Function as a Service (FaaS)"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) provides virtual machines and storage while the customer manages the operating system (OS) and applications.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) provides virtual machines and storage while the customer manages the operating system (OS) and applications.","SaaS provides fully managed applications, not OS/application control.","PaaS manages the OS and runtime, leaving less control than IaaS provides.","FaaS runs individual functions without managing servers or the OS at all."]},{"id":122,"question":"Which cloud characteristic allows multiple customers to share the same physical hardware while keeping their environments logically isolated?","options":["Elasticity","Multitenancy","Measured service","Orchestration"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Multitenancy enables shared infrastructure while maintaining tenant isolation.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Multitenancy enables shared infrastructure while maintaining tenant isolation.","Elasticity refers to scaling resources up or down, not shared hardware with isolated tenants.","Measured service refers to usage-based billing, not shared-hardware isolation.","Orchestration automates deployment workflows, not tenant isolation on shared hardware."]},{"id":123,"question":"A company uses its private data center for sensitive workloads but bursts into a public cloud during peak usage. What deployment model is this?","options":["Public cloud","Hybrid cloud","Community cloud","Distributed cloud"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Hybrid cloud blends private and public cloud resources.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Hybrid cloud blends private and public cloud resources.","Public cloud alone wouldn't include a private data center component.","Community cloud is shared among organizations with similar needs, not a private+public burst arrangement.","Distributed cloud spreads resources across locations, not specifically blending private and public infrastructure."]},{"id":124,"question":"Which cloud concept describes the ability to automatically scale resources up or down based on workload?","options":["Elasticity","Portability","Abstraction","Metering"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Elasticity allows cloud resources to expand or contract dynamically.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Elasticity allows cloud resources to expand or contract dynamically.","Portability refers to moving workloads between environments, not scaling resource capacity.","Abstraction hides underlying hardware complexity, not automatic scaling.","Metering tracks resource usage, not the scaling capability itself."]},{"id":125,"question":"A developer wants a cloud environment that includes runtime, database engines, and development tools without managing the underlying operating system (OS). Which model applies?","options":["Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Software as a Service (SaaS)","Security as a Service (SECaaS)"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Platform as a Service (PaaS) provides managed development environments and tools.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Platform as a Service (PaaS) provides managed development environments and tools.","IaaS requires managing the OS yourself, unlike the managed runtime/tools described.","SaaS delivers a complete end-user application, not a development platform with runtime and tools.","SECaaS delivers security services, not general development runtime and tools."]},{"id":126,"question":"Which cloud characteristic ensures customers pay only for the resources they consume?","options":["Measured service","Elasticity","Resource pooling","Abstraction"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Measured service tracks usage so customers are billed based on consumption.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Measured service tracks usage so customers are billed based on consumption.","Elasticity refers to scaling capacity, not usage-based billing.","Resource pooling refers to sharing infrastructure among customers, not billing based on consumption.","Abstraction hides hardware complexity, unrelated to usage-based billing."]},{"id":127,"question":"A company wants to migrate a legacy application to the cloud without rewriting it. Which approach is most appropriate?","options":["Platform as a Service (PaaS) refactor","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) lift-and-shift","Software as a Service (SaaS) subscription","Function as a Service (FaaS) event-driven"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) supports lift-and-shift migrations with minimal modification.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) supports lift-and-shift migrations with minimal modification.","A PaaS refactor requires rewriting the app for the platform, not a direct move without changes.","A SaaS subscription replaces the app entirely with a vendor's product, not migrating the existing legacy app.","FaaS requires restructuring the app into individual event-driven functions, not a direct lift-and-shift."]},{"id":128,"question":"Which cloud concept hides the complexity of underlying hardware from the user?","options":["Elasticity","Abstraction","Replication","Metering"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Abstraction masks hardware details and presents virtualized resources.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Abstraction masks hardware details and presents virtualized resources.","Elasticity refers to scaling capacity, not hiding hardware complexity.","Replication maintains data copies for availability, not hiding hardware details.","Metering tracks usage, unrelated to hiding hardware complexity."]},{"id":129,"question":"A cloud provider offers identity management, malware scanning, and intrusion detection as a subscription. What service model is this?","options":["Software as a Service (SaaS)","Security as a Service (SECaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Security as a Service (SECaaS) delivers cloud-based security services.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Security as a Service (SECaaS) delivers cloud-based security services.","SaaS delivers general applications, not specifically security-focused services like this.","IaaS provides virtualized infrastructure, not managed security services like malware scanning.","PaaS provides a development platform, not managed security services."]},{"id":130,"question":"Which deployment model is owned and operated exclusively for a single organization?","options":["Public cloud","Private cloud","Community cloud","Hybrid cloud"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Private clouds are dedicated to one organization.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Private clouds are dedicated to one organization.","Public cloud serves multiple customers on shared infrastructure, not one dedicated organization.","Community cloud is shared among multiple similar organizations, not exclusive to one.","Hybrid cloud combines private and public resources, not exclusively private for one organization."]},{"id":131,"question":"Which cloud characteristic allows users to provision resources without human interaction?","options":["On-demand self-service","Multitenancy","Measured service","Elasticity"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"On-demand self-service allows users to deploy resources instantly.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["On-demand self-service allows users to deploy resources instantly.","Multitenancy refers to shared hardware with isolated tenants, not self-provisioning without human interaction.","Measured service refers to usage-based billing, not the self-provisioning capability itself.","Elasticity refers to scaling capacity, not the human-interaction-free provisioning process."]},{"id":132,"question":"A company uses multiple public cloud providers to avoid vendor lock-in. What strategy is this?","options":["Hybrid cloud","Multicloud","Distributed cloud","Community cloud"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Multicloud uses multiple public cloud vendors simultaneously.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Multicloud uses multiple public cloud vendors simultaneously.","Hybrid cloud combines private and public resources, not multiple public cloud vendors specifically.","Distributed cloud spreads resources geographically, not necessarily across multiple different vendors.","Community cloud is shared among similar organizations, not a multi-vendor avoidance strategy."]},{"id":133,"question":"Which cloud concept ensures workloads can move between environments with minimal reconfiguration?","options":["Portability","Elasticity","Abstraction","Metering"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Portability allows workloads to run across different environments with few changes.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Portability allows workloads to run across different environments with few changes.","Elasticity refers to scaling capacity, not moving workloads between environments.","Abstraction hides hardware complexity, not workload portability specifically.","Metering tracks usage, unrelated to moving workloads between environments."]},{"id":134,"question":"A cloud provider automatically deploys additional compute nodes when central processing unit (CPU) usage exceeds 80%. What is this an example of?","options":["Elastic scaling","Resource pooling","Abstraction","Orchestration"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Elastic scaling adjusts resources based on demand.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Elastic scaling adjusts resources based on demand.","Resource pooling refers to sharing infrastructure among customers, not automatically adding nodes based on demand.","Abstraction hides hardware complexity, unrelated to automatically adding compute nodes.","Orchestration automates broader workflows, while this specific demand-based node addition is elastic scaling."]},{"id":135,"question":"Which cloud deployment model is shared by organizations with similar compliance or security needs?","options":["Community cloud","Public cloud","Hybrid cloud","Private cloud"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Community clouds serve groups with shared requirements.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Community clouds serve groups with shared requirements.","Public cloud serves the general public broadly, not a specific group with shared requirements.","Hybrid cloud blends private and public resources, not a shared model among similar organizations.","Private cloud is dedicated to a single organization, not shared among several with similar needs."]},{"id":136,"question":"A company wants to run serverless functions that execute only when triggered by events. Which cloud model supports this?","options":["Function as a Service (FaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Software as a Service (SaaS)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Function as a Service (FaaS) executes code in response to events without managing servers.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Function as a Service (FaaS) executes code in response to events without managing servers.","PaaS provides an ongoing managed platform, not code that runs only on individual triggered events.","IaaS requires managing virtual servers, not serverless event-triggered execution.","SaaS delivers a complete application, not individual event-triggered functions."]},{"id":137,"question":"Which cloud concept refers to pooling computing resources to serve multiple customers efficiently?","options":["Resource pooling","Elasticity","Metering","Abstraction"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Resource pooling allows providers to dynamically allocate resources to customers.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Resource pooling allows providers to dynamically allocate resources to customers.","Elasticity refers to scaling capacity up or down, not pooling resources among customers.","Metering tracks usage, unrelated to pooling infrastructure among customers.","Abstraction hides hardware complexity, not the pooling of resources itself."]},{"id":138,"question":"A company wants to deploy a cloud environment across multiple geographic regions to reduce latency. Which concept applies?","options":["Distributed cloud","Hybrid cloud","Multicloud","Community cloud"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Distributed cloud places cloud resources in multiple physical locations.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Distributed cloud places cloud resources in multiple physical locations.","Hybrid cloud blends private and public resources, not specifically spreading resources across regions for latency.","Multicloud uses multiple providers, not necessarily multiple geographic regions for latency reduction.","Community cloud is shared among similar organizations, not about geographic distribution for latency."]},{"id":139,"question":"Which cloud model provides the highest level of customer control?","options":["Software as a Service (SaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Security as a Service (SECaaS)"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) gives customers control over operating system (OS), applications, and configurations.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) gives customers control over operating system (OS), applications, and configurations.","SaaS gives the least control since the provider manages everything except data.","PaaS gives more control than SaaS but less than IaaS, since the OS itself is managed by the provider.","SECaaS delivers security services, not general infrastructure control."]},{"id":140,"question":"A company wants to automate provisioning, configuration, and deployment of cloud resources. Which concept is this?","options":["Orchestration","Elasticity","Multitenancy","Metering"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Orchestration automates complex cloud workflows.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Orchestration automates complex cloud workflows.","Elasticity refers to scaling capacity, not automating provisioning workflows.","Multitenancy refers to shared-hardware isolation, not automated deployment processes.","Metering tracks usage, unrelated to automating provisioning and deployment."]},{"id":141,"question":"Which cloud concept ensures that data and applications remain available even if a server fails?","options":["Replication","Elasticity","Abstraction","Metering"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Replication maintains copies of data across systems for availability.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.1","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Replication maintains copies of data across systems for availability.","Elasticity refers to scaling capacity, not maintaining data copies for availability.","Abstraction hides hardware complexity, unrelated to keeping data available during failures.","Metering tracks usage, unrelated to maintaining availability through data copies."]},{"id":142,"question":"A company wants to use cloud services but must comply with strict data sovereignty laws. Which deployment model is most appropriate?","options":["Public cloud","Private cloud","Community cloud","Hybrid cloud"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Private cloud offers full control over data location and compliance.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Private cloud offers full control over data location and compliance.","Public cloud offers less control over exact data location, a concern for strict sovereignty laws.","Community cloud is shared among multiple organizations, offering less exclusive control than a private cloud.","Hybrid cloud still involves public cloud components, which may not fully satisfy strict data sovereignty needs."]},{"id":143,"question":"Which cloud service model provides the least customer responsibility?","options":["Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Software as a Service (SaaS)","Function as a Service (FaaS)"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Software as a Service (SaaS) handles everything except user data.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Software as a Service (SaaS) handles everything except user data.","IaaS requires the customer to manage the OS and applications, the most responsibility among these options.","PaaS requires the customer to manage application code and data, more responsibility than SaaS.","FaaS requires the customer to write and manage functions, more responsibility than fully managed SaaS."]},{"id":144,"question":"A company wants to deploy containers in the cloud without managing the underlying container hosts. Which model supports this?","options":["Container-as-a-Service","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Software as a Service (SaaS)","Security as a Service (SECaaS)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Container as a Service (CaaS) provides managed container orchestration environments.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Container as a Service (CaaS) provides managed container orchestration environments.","IaaS would require managing the underlying servers/hosts yourself, unlike a managed container service.","SaaS delivers a complete end-user application, not a container deployment platform.","SECaaS delivers security services, not container hosting and orchestration."]},{"id":145,"question":"Which cloud concept allows customers to quickly deploy additional instances of an application to handle increased demand?","options":["Horizontal scaling","Vertical scaling","Abstraction","Metering"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Horizontal scaling adds more instances to distribute load.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Horizontal scaling adds more instances to distribute load.","Vertical scaling adds resources to an existing instance, rather than deploying additional instances.","Abstraction hides hardware complexity, unrelated to adding more application instances.","Metering tracks usage, unrelated to deploying additional instances for demand."]},{"id":146,"question":"Which cloud model allows customers to run applications without provisioning or managing servers?","options":["Function as a Service (FaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Software as a Service (SaaS)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Function as a Service (FaaS) executes code without server management.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Function as a Service (FaaS) executes code without server management.","IaaS still requires provisioning and managing virtual servers yourself.","PaaS still involves managing an ongoing platform, not purely event-triggered code with zero server management.","SaaS delivers a complete application, not a way to run custom code without managing servers."]},{"id":147,"question":"A company wants to centralize logging, monitoring, and alerting across multiple cloud environments. Which concept supports this?","options":["Cloud management platform","Elasticity","Multitenancy","Replication"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Cloud management platforms unify monitoring and control across environments.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Cloud management platforms unify monitoring and control across environments.","Elasticity refers to scaling capacity, not centralizing monitoring across environments.","Multitenancy refers to shared-hardware isolation, not centralized cross-cloud monitoring.","Replication maintains data copies, unrelated to centralizing logging and alerting."]},{"id":148,"question":"Which cloud characteristic ensures that resources can be provisioned and released rapidly?","options":["Rapid elasticity","Measured service","Resource pooling","Abstraction"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Rapid elasticity enables quick scaling of resources.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Rapid elasticity enables quick scaling of resources.","Measured service refers to usage-based billing, not the speed of provisioning/releasing resources.","Resource pooling refers to shared infrastructure, not the speed of scaling resources.","Abstraction hides hardware complexity, unrelated to rapid provisioning speed."]},{"id":149,"question":"A company wants to run workloads in the cloud but maintain sensitive data on-premises. Which model supports this?","options":["Hybrid cloud","Public cloud","Community cloud","Distributed cloud"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Hybrid cloud allows workloads to span cloud and on-premises environments.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 13.html","optionExplanations":["Hybrid cloud allows workloads to span cloud and on-premises environments.","Public cloud alone wouldn't keep sensitive data on-premises.","Community cloud is shared among similar organizations, not a mix of cloud and on-prem for one company.","Distributed cloud spreads cloud resources geographically, not specifically splitting between cloud and on-prem."]},{"id":150,"question":"Which cloud service model provides virtual machines, storage, and networking while leaving the operating system (OS) and applications under customer control?","options":["Software as a Service (SaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Function as a Service (FaaS)"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"IaaS provides virtualized compute, storage, and networking; the customer manages the operating system (OS), apps, and data.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["IaaS provides virtualized compute, storage, and networking; the customer manages the operating system (OS), apps, and data.","SaaS manages the OS and applications for the customer, the opposite of leaving them under customer control.","PaaS manages the OS itself, leaving less under customer control than IaaS.","FaaS abstracts away servers entirely, leaving even less infrastructure under direct customer control."]},{"id":151,"question":"In which cloud service model does the provider manage the operating system (OS), runtime, and platform, while the customer focuses on deploying code and managing data?","options":["Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Software as a Service (SaaS)","Bare-metal hosting"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"PaaS abstracts the operating system (OS) and runtime so developers can focus on code and data, not server management.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["PaaS abstracts the operating system (OS) and runtime so developers can focus on code and data, not server management.","IaaS leaves the OS and runtime management to the customer, unlike the scenario described.","SaaS manages the application itself entirely, leaving the customer with no code deployment role at all.","\"Bare-metal hosting\" gives full hardware control without any managed OS/platform layer."]},{"id":152,"question":"Which cloud service model typically delivers a fully managed application, such as email or customer relationship management (CRM), accessible via a web browser?","options":["Software as a Service (SaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Network as a Service (NaaS)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"SaaS delivers complete applications over the internet; the provider manages everything behind the scenes.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["SaaS delivers complete applications over the internet; the provider manages everything behind the scenes.","PaaS provides a development platform, not a fully finished end-user application like email or CRM.","IaaS provides raw infrastructure, not a ready-to-use managed application.","NaaS delivers networking capabilities, not a complete end-user application."]},{"id":153,"question":"A company wants to keep sensitive workloads on-premises while bursting to the public cloud during peak demand. Which deployment model best fits this requirement?","options":["Public cloud","Private cloud","Hybrid cloud","Community cloud"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Hybrid cloud combines private and public resources, allowing cloud bursting and flexible workload placement.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Hybrid cloud combines private and public resources, allowing cloud bursting and flexible workload placement.","Public cloud alone doesn't keep sensitive workloads on-premises.","Private cloud alone doesn't include bursting to public cloud resources.","Community cloud is shared among similar organizations, not a private-plus-public burst arrangement for one company."]},{"id":154,"question":"Which cloud deployment model is shared by several organizations with similar regulatory or business requirements, such as healthcare groups?","options":["Public cloud","Private cloud","Hybrid cloud","Community cloud"],"correctIndex":3,"explanation":"Community cloud is shared by organizations with common concerns, such as compliance or mission.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Community cloud is shared by organizations with common concerns, such as compliance or mission.","Public cloud serves the general public broadly, not a specific group with shared regulatory needs.","Private cloud is dedicated to one organization, not shared among several similar ones.","Hybrid cloud blends private and public resources, not a shared model among similar organizations."]},{"id":155,"question":"Which term describes running multiple virtual machines on a single physical host using a hypervisor?","options":["Containerization","Virtualization","Orchestration","Segmentation"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Virtualization allows multiple virtual machines to share a single physical host via a hypervisor.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Virtualization allows multiple virtual machines to share a single physical host via a hypervisor.","Containerization isolates apps at the OS level without full separate virtual machines.","Orchestration automates deployment workflows, not the hypervisor-based VM technology itself.","Segmentation divides networks logically, unrelated to running VMs on a hypervisor."]},{"id":156,"question":"Which type of hypervisor runs directly on the host's hardware without a traditional underlying operating system (OS)?","options":["Type 1 hypervisor","Type 2 hypervisor","Container engine","Bare-metal OS"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Type 1 hypervisors run directly on hardware and are often used in enterprise and cloud environments.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Type 1 hypervisors run directly on hardware and are often used in enterprise and cloud environments.","A Type 2 hypervisor runs on top of a host operating system, not directly on hardware.","A container engine shares the host OS kernel rather than running directly on bare hardware as a hypervisor.","\"Bare-metal OS\" isn't the standard term for a hypervisor running directly on hardware."]},{"id":157,"question":"Which technology isolates applications using shared OS resources rather than full virtual machines, often used in microservices architectures?","options":["Full virtualization","Containerization","Bare-metal hosting","Thick clients"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Containerization isolates applications at the operating system (OS) level, sharing the kernel while keeping workloads separate.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Containerization isolates applications at the operating system (OS) level, sharing the kernel while keeping workloads separate.","Full virtualization uses complete separate virtual machines, not shared-kernel isolation.","Bare-metal hosting runs directly on physical hardware, not app-level OS-shared isolation.","\"Thick clients\" refers to full-featured local client software, unrelated to container-based app isolation."]},{"id":158,"question":"Which option best describes a dedicated, private connection between an on-premises network and a cloud provider, bypassing the public internet?","options":["Site-to-site Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) virtual private network (VPN) over the internet","Client-based SSL virtual private network (VPN)","Direct connect / express route","Remote desktop gateway"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Services like AWS Direct Connect or Azure ExpressRoute provide private, dedicated connectivity to the cloud.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Services like AWS Direct Connect or Azure ExpressRoute provide private, dedicated connectivity to the cloud.","A site-to-site IPsec VPN still traverses the public internet, unlike a dedicated private connection.","A client-based SSL VPN is for individual remote users, not a dedicated site-to-cloud connection.","A remote desktop gateway provides remote desktop access, not a dedicated network connection to a cloud provider."]},{"id":159,"question":"A company connects its on-premises network to a cloud virtual private cloud (VPC) using an encrypted tunnel over the internet. Which technology is most commonly used?","options":["GRE tunnel without encryption","Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) site-to-site virtual private network (VPN)","Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) label-switched path","Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) over Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 3389"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) site-to-site virtual private networks (VPNs) are commonly used to securely connect on-prem networks to cloud environments.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) site-to-site virtual private networks (VPNs) are commonly used to securely connect on-prem networks to cloud environments.","A GRE tunnel without encryption doesn't provide the encrypted protection described.","An MPLS label-switched path is a private carrier circuit technology, not an encrypted tunnel over the public internet.","RDP over port 3389 is a remote desktop protocol, not a site-to-site encrypted network tunnel."]},{"id":160,"question":"In a cloud environment, what is a virtual private cloud (VPC)?","options":["A physical private data center owned by the customer","A logically isolated virtual network within a public cloud","A dedicated Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) circuit between sites","A virtual private network (VPN) client installed on user devices"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A virtual private cloud (VPC) is a logically isolated virtual network in a public cloud, where you define subnets, routing, and security.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["A virtual private cloud (VPC) is a logically isolated virtual network in a public cloud, where you define subnets, routing, and security.","A VPC is a virtual network within a cloud provider, not a physical private data center.","A dedicated MPLS circuit is a private carrier connection technology, not the isolated virtual network itself.","A VPN client installed on devices is a remote-access tool, not the isolated cloud network construct itself."]},{"id":161,"question":"Which cloud networking component acts like a traditional firewall, controlling inbound and outbound traffic at the instance or subnet level?","options":["Object storage","Security group / network security group","Content delivery network","Domain Name System (DNS) zone"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Security groups and network security groups (NSGs) control traffic to instances or subnets, similar to virtual firewalls.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Security groups and network security groups (NSGs) control traffic to instances or subnets, similar to virtual firewalls.","Object storage stores unstructured data/files, not traffic filtering rules.","A CDN caches content at edge locations, unrelated to instance-level traffic filtering.","A DNS zone manages name resolution records, not inbound/outbound traffic control."]},{"id":162,"question":"Which cloud feature distributes incoming traffic across multiple servers or instances to improve availability and performance?","options":["Auto-scaling group","Load balancer","Object storage","Message queue"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Load balancers distribute traffic across multiple targets, improving availability and responsiveness.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Load balancers distribute traffic across multiple targets, improving availability and responsiveness.","An auto-scaling group adds/removes capacity based on demand, not distributing live traffic itself.","Object storage stores data files, unrelated to distributing incoming traffic.","A message queue holds messages for asynchronous processing, not distributing live user traffic."]},{"id":163,"question":"Which term describes deploying resources across multiple geographic regions or availability zones to minimize downtime from localized failures?","options":["Vertical scaling","Single-homing","Geographic redundancy","Over-subscription"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Geographic redundancy spreads resources across regions or zones to survive localized outages.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Geographic redundancy spreads resources across regions or zones to survive localized outages.","Vertical scaling adds resources to one instance, unrelated to spreading across regions.","Single-homing means relying on one connection/location, the opposite of redundancy across regions.","Over-subscription refers to allocating more capacity than physically available, unrelated to geographic spread."]},{"id":164,"question":"Which cloud capability automatically adds or removes instances based on demand, such as CPU utilization or request rate?","options":["Static provisioning","Auto-scaling","Cold standby","Manual failover"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Auto-scaling dynamically adjusts capacity based on demand, helping maintain performance and control costs.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.2","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Auto-scaling dynamically adjusts capacity based on demand, helping maintain performance and control costs.","Static provisioning sets fixed capacity that doesn't adjust automatically.","Cold standby is an inactive backup system, not automatic demand-based scaling.","Manual failover requires human action, not automatic demand-based adjustment."]},{"id":165,"question":"Which type of cloud storage is optimized for storing large amounts of unstructured data such as backups, media, and logs?","options":["Block storage","Object storage","File storage","Tape library"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Object storage is ideal for large, unstructured data and is commonly used for backups and archives.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Object storage is ideal for large, unstructured data and is commonly used for backups and archives.","Block storage presents raw volumes like disks, less suited to large unstructured file storage.","File storage organizes data in a directory/file hierarchy, less optimized for massive unstructured data.","A tape library is a legacy physical backup medium, not typical modern cloud storage."]},{"id":166,"question":"Which storage type is typically used as a virtual hard disk for cloud virtual machines?","options":["Object storage","Block storage","File sync service","Optical storage"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Block storage presents volumes to virtual machines (VMs) like traditional disks and is used for operating system (OS) and application data.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Block storage presents volumes to virtual machines (VMs) like traditional disks and is used for operating system (OS) and application data.","Object storage is for unstructured files/data, not presenting a disk volume to a VM.","A file sync service shares files across devices, not a raw disk volume for a VM's OS.","Optical storage uses discs, not a modern cloud VM disk solution."]},{"id":167,"question":"Which concept describes the shared responsibilities between a cloud provider and a customer for securing cloud resources?","options":["Zero trust model","Shared responsibility model","Defense in depth","Least privilege"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"The shared responsibility model defines which security tasks are handled by the provider and which by the customer.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["The shared responsibility model defines which security tasks are handled by the provider and which by the customer.","Zero trust assumes no implicit trust and verifies every request, a different security philosophy than dividing tasks between provider/customer.","Defense in depth layers multiple security controls, not specifically dividing responsibility between provider and customer.","Least privilege limits permissions to the minimum needed, unrelated to dividing security duties between parties."]},{"id":168,"question":"In most public cloud environments, who is primarily responsible for securing the guest operating system (OS) and applications running on a virtual machine?","options":["The cloud provider only","The customer","The internet service provider (ISP)","The domain registrar"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Under the shared responsibility model, the customer secures the operating system (OS), applications, and data on their virtual machines (VMs).","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Under the shared responsibility model, the customer secures the operating system (OS), applications, and data on their virtual machines (VMs).","The provider alone doesn't secure the guest OS/apps; that responsibility falls to the customer under the shared model.","An ISP provides internet connectivity, unrelated to securing a VM's guest OS.","A domain registrar manages domain name registration, unrelated to securing a VM's OS."]},{"id":169,"question":"Which security control is commonly used to restrict which IP addresses or networks can reach a cloud-based management interface or service?","options":["Access control list (ACL)","Any/any firewall rule that permits all traffic without restriction","DHCP relay forwarding requests between subnets","NAT overload (PAT) address translation configuration"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"ACLs are used to permit or deny traffic based on IP addresses, protocols, and ports.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["ACLs are used to permit or deny traffic based on IP addresses, protocols, and ports.","An any/any rule permits everything and provides no restriction at all, the opposite of a targeted access control list.","DHCP relay forwards address requests across subnets; it doesn't restrict which networks reach a management interface.","NAT overload translates addresses for outbound connections; it isn't the mechanism for restricting inbound access by source."]},{"id":170,"question":"Which cloud characteristic allows customers to provision resources on demand and release them when no longer needed?","options":["Measured service","On-demand self-service","Resource pooling","Broad network access"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"On-demand self-service lets customers provision and deprovision resources without human interaction from the provider.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["On-demand self-service lets customers provision and deprovision resources without human interaction from the provider.","Measured service tracks usage for billing, not the self-provisioning capability itself.","Resource pooling refers to shared infrastructure, not the ability to self-provision on demand.","Broad network access refers to availability over standard network connections, not self-service provisioning."]},{"id":171,"question":"Which cloud characteristic describes the provider’s ability to serve multiple customers using shared infrastructure while keeping their data logically separate?","options":["Elasticity","Multitenancy","High availability","Fault tolerance"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Multitenancy allows multiple customers to share infrastructure while maintaining logical isolation.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Multitenancy allows multiple customers to share infrastructure while maintaining logical isolation.","Elasticity refers to scaling capacity, not shared infrastructure with logical isolation.","High availability refers to uptime, not shared-tenant infrastructure isolation.","Fault tolerance refers to surviving failures, not multi-customer shared-hardware isolation."]},{"id":172,"question":"Which term describes the ability of a cloud environment to automatically allocate more resources when demand increases and reduce them when demand drops?","options":["Elasticity","Multihoming","Overprovisioning","Static allocation"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Elasticity is the automatic scaling of resources up or down based on demand.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Elasticity is the automatic scaling of resources up or down based on demand.","Multihoming refers to multiple network connections, not automatic resource scaling.","Overprovisioning means allocating more than needed upfront, not dynamically adjusting to demand.","Static allocation is fixed and doesn't adjust automatically to demand."]},{"id":173,"question":"Which Domain Name System (DNS)-related feature is often used with cloud services to direct users to the closest or healthiest endpoint?","options":["Geo-Domain Name System (DNS) / latency-based routing","Round-robin only rotation without geographic or latency awareness","Static host file entries manually mapped on each client device","DHCP reservations tied to specific device MAC addresses"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Geo-Domain Name System (DNS) and latency-based routing direct clients to the nearest or best-performing endpoint.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Geo-Domain Name System (DNS) and latency-based routing direct clients to the nearest or best-performing endpoint.","Round-robin rotation alone cycles through endpoints without considering geography or latency.","Static host file entries are manually set per device and don't dynamically route to the best endpoint.","DHCP reservations assign fixed addresses by MAC address; they don't direct traffic to the nearest endpoint."]},{"id":174,"question":"Which cloud feature caches content at edge locations around the world to reduce latency for users?","options":["Content Delivery Network (CDN)","Object storage designed for storing large unstructured data files","Block storage presented as virtual hard disks to servers","Message queue service for asynchronous application communication"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"content delivery network (CDN)s cache content closer to users at edge locations, improving performance and reducing latency.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["CDNs cache content closer to users at edge locations, improving performance and reducing latency.","Object storage stores large unstructured data; it doesn't specifically cache content at edge locations for latency reduction.","Block storage presents virtual disks to servers, unrelated to edge caching for end users.","A message queue handles asynchronous messaging between application components, unrelated to edge content caching."]},{"id":175,"question":"Which interface is commonly used to automate cloud resource provisioning and management programmatically?","options":["Cloud provider representational state transfer application programming interface (REST API)","keyboard, video, and mouse (KVM) console used for direct virtual machine display access","physical keyboard, video, and mouse (KVM) switch used to control multiple physical servers","Serial console cable connected directly to a device's console port"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Cloud provider APIs allow programmatic control of resources for automation and integration.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Cloud provider APIs allow programmatic control of resources for automation and integration.","A KVM console gives direct display access to one virtual machine, not general programmatic automation.","A physical KVM switch lets an admin control multiple physical servers manually, not programmatic automation.","A serial console cable provides direct low-level device access, not scalable programmatic resource management."]},{"id":176,"question":"Which tool or concept describes using templates or code files to define and deploy cloud infrastructure consistently?","options":["Manual configuration","Infrastructure as Code (IaC)","Ad-hoc scripting only","Physical runbooks"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Infrastructure as Code uses templates or code to define and deploy infrastructure in a repeatable way.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Infrastructure as Code uses templates or code to define and deploy infrastructure in a repeatable way.","Manual configuration is done by hand each time, the opposite of consistent code-defined deployment.","Ad-hoc scripting without structure lacks the consistency and repeatability of formal IaC templates.","Physical runbooks are paper/document-based instructions, not executable code-defined infrastructure."]},{"id":177,"question":"Which pricing model charges customers based on actual resource usage, such as compute hours or storage consumed?","options":["Flat monthly fee regardless of usage","Usage-based / pay-as-you-go","Lifetime license","Perpetual hardware purchase"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Usage-based or pay-as-you-go pricing charges based on actual consumption of resources.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Usage-based or pay-as-you-go pricing charges based on actual consumption of resources.","A flat monthly fee doesn't vary with actual resource consumption.","A lifetime license is a one-time purchase model, not usage-based billing.","A perpetual hardware purchase is a one-time capital cost, not ongoing usage-based billing."]},{"id":178,"question":"Which migration approach moves an existing application to the cloud with minimal changes, often called “lift and shift”?","options":["Re-architecting","Re-platforming","Re-hosting","Retiring"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Re-hosting, or lift and shift, moves workloads to the cloud with minimal architectural changes.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Re-hosting, or lift and shift, moves workloads to the cloud with minimal architectural changes.","Re-architecting involves redesigning the application significantly, not a minimal-change lift and shift.","Re-platforming involves some optimization changes, more than the minimal-change approach described.","Retiring means decommissioning an application, not moving it to the cloud."]},{"id":179,"question":"Which protocol is commonly used to provide secure remote command-line access to cloud-based Linux servers?","options":["Telnet","Secure Shell (SSH)","FTP","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Secure Shell (SSH) provides encrypted remote command-line access and is standard for managing Linux servers in the cloud.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Day 14.html","optionExplanations":["Secure Shell (SSH) provides encrypted remote command-line access and is standard for managing Linux servers in the cloud.","Telnet transmits data unencrypted, unlike SSH's encrypted access.","FTP is for file transfer, not interactive command-line access.","SNMP is used for monitoring and management data, not interactive remote command-line sessions."]},{"id":180,"question":"Which cable type is most appropriate for a 10 Gbps connection over 55 meters in an office environment?","options":["Cat6","Cat5e","RG-6","Cat3"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Cat6 supports 10GBASE-T up to 55 meters, making it suitable for short-range 10 Gbps links.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Cat6 supports 10GBASE-T up to 55 meters, making it suitable for short-range 10 Gbps links.","Cat5e doesn't reliably support 10 Gbps at that distance.","RG-6 is a coaxial cable type, not typically used for 10 Gbps Ethernet networking.","Cat3 is a legacy low-bandwidth cable, far short of 10 Gbps capability."]},{"id":181,"question":"A technician needs to run cable through an area with high EMI. Which cable type is the best choice?","options":["Fiber optic","Cat5e UTP","Cat6 UTP","RG-59"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Fiber is immune to electromagnetic interference, making it ideal for high-EMI environments.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Fiber is immune to electromagnetic interference, making it ideal for high-EMI environments.","Cat5e UTP has no shielding and remains susceptible to EMI.","Cat6 UTP also lacks shielding and remains susceptible to EMI near industrial sources.","RG-59 is a coaxial cable still using electrical signaling, susceptible to EMI."]},{"id":182,"question":"Which connector is used with multimode fiber?","options":["LC","RJ45","BNC","F-type"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"LC is a common connector for multimode fiber installations.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["LC is a common connector for multimode fiber installations.","RJ45 is used for copper Ethernet connections, not fiber.","BNC is used for older coaxial connections, not modern fiber.","F-type is used for coaxial cable (like cable TV), not fiber optic connections."]},{"id":183,"question":"A run between two wiring closets is 120 meters. Which cable type is appropriate?","options":["Single-mode fiber","Cat6","Cat5e","RG-6"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Single-mode fiber supports long-distance runs well beyond 120 meters.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Single-mode fiber supports long-distance runs well beyond 120 meters.","Cat6 copper is limited to 100 meters, far short of 120 meters.","Cat5e copper is also limited to 100 meters, insufficient for this distance.","RG-6 coax isn't a standard choice for long structured network backbone runs like this."]},{"id":184,"question":"Which tool is used to terminate wires into a patch panel?","options":["Punchdown tool","Crimper","OTDR","Tone generator"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Punchdown tools are used to seat wires into patch panel IDC terminals.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Punchdown tools are used to seat wires into patch panel IDC terminals.","A crimper attaches modular plug connectors, not terminating wires into a patch panel's IDC terminals.","An OTDR tests fiber optic cable, not copper patch panel termination.","A tone generator traces cable paths; it doesn't terminate wires into a panel."]},{"id":185,"question":"A technician needs to verify the length and quality of a fiber run. Which tool should be used?","options":["OTDR","Multimeter","Loopback plug","Punchdown tool"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An OTDR measures fiber length, signal loss, and faults.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["An OTDR measures fiber length, signal loss, and faults.","A multimeter measures electrical properties, not fiber optic signal loss or length.","A loopback plug tests port connectivity, not fiber length or quality.","A punchdown tool terminates copper wiring, unrelated to testing fiber runs."]},{"id":186,"question":"Which wiring standard is most commonly used in the United States for Ethernet cabling?","options":["T568B","T568A","RJ11","SC"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"T568B is the most widely used Ethernet wiring standard in the U.S.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["T568B is the most widely used Ethernet wiring standard in the U.S.","T568A is a valid wiring standard but is less commonly used in the U.S. than T568B.","RJ11 is a phone-line connector standard, not the dominant Ethernet wiring standard.","SC is a fiber optic connector type, not a copper wiring standard."]},{"id":187,"question":"What is the maximum recommended length for a copper Ethernet horizontal run?","options":["100 meters","50 meters","150 meters","300 meters"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Ethernet copper runs are limited to 100 meters end-to-end.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Ethernet copper runs are limited to 100 meters end-to-end.","50 meters is shorter than the actual standard maximum for copper Ethernet.","150 meters exceeds the standard copper Ethernet distance limitation.","300 meters greatly exceeds the standard copper Ethernet distance limitation."]},{"id":188,"question":"Which device is used to locate the opposite end of a cable in a building?","options":["Tone generator and probe","OTDR","Crimper","Loopback adapter"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A tone generator and probe help trace cable paths through walls and ceilings.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["A tone generator and probe help trace cable paths through walls and ceilings.","An OTDR tests fiber optic cables, not tracing copper cable ends in a building.","A crimper attaches connectors to cable ends, not for tracing which cable is which.","A loopback adapter tests port function, not tracing a cable's physical path."]},{"id":189,"question":"A technician needs to test for split pairs in a copper cable. Which tool is required?","options":["Cable certifier","Punchdown tool","Fiber light meter","RJ45 coupler"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Cable certifiers detect wiring faults including split pairs.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Cable certifiers detect wiring faults including split pairs.","A punchdown tool terminates wires; it doesn't test for wiring faults like split pairs.","A fiber light meter tests optical signal strength, not copper wiring faults.","An RJ45 coupler joins two cable segments; it doesn't test for wiring faults."]},{"id":190,"question":"Which type of ladder rack is used to support horizontal cable runs above ceiling tiles?","options":["Cable tray","Patch panel","Riser","Raceway"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Cable trays support horizontal cable bundles above ceilings.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Cable trays support horizontal cable bundles above ceilings.","A patch panel terminates cabling in a rack, not supporting horizontal runs above ceilings.","A riser is a vertical cabling pathway between floors, not horizontal ceiling support.","A raceway is typically wall-mounted for surface cable routing, not overhead ceiling support structure."]},{"id":191,"question":"What is the purpose of a plenum-rated cable?","options":["To reduce toxic smoke in air-handling spaces","To support higher bandwidth","To prevent water intrusion","To reduce crosstalk"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Plenum cable uses low-smoke materials for HVAC air-handling spaces.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Plenum cable uses low-smoke materials for HVAC air-handling spaces.","Plenum rating concerns fire/smoke safety materials, not a bandwidth improvement.","Plenum cable's rating addresses fire safety, not water resistance.","Reducing crosstalk relates to cable pair twisting/shielding, not the plenum fire-safety rating itself."]},{"id":192,"question":"Which component organizes and terminates horizontal cabling in a wiring closet?","options":["Patch panel","Repeater","UPS","Firewall"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Patch panels provide structured termination points for horizontal cabling.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Patch panels provide structured termination points for horizontal cabling.","A repeater regenerates signals to extend distance, not organizing/terminating cabling.","A UPS provides backup power, unrelated to cable termination and organization.","A firewall filters network traffic, unrelated to physical cable termination."]},{"id":193,"question":"Which device is used to protect network equipment from power fluctuations?","options":["UPS","Patch panel","Repeater","Load balancer"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A UPS provides clean, stable power and battery backup.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["A UPS provides clean, stable power and battery backup.","A patch panel organizes cabling, unrelated to power protection.","A repeater regenerates signals, unrelated to power fluctuation protection.","A load balancer distributes traffic, unrelated to protecting equipment from power issues."]},{"id":194,"question":"Which type of cable is required for in-wall residential or commercial installations?","options":["Riser or plenum-rated","Patch cable","RG-59","Direct burial"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"In-wall installations require riser or plenum-rated cable depending on the environment.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["In-wall installations require riser or plenum-rated cable depending on the environment.","A patch cable is a short connector cable, not the fire-rated cable type required for in-wall runs.","RG-59 is a coaxial cable type for video, not the standard fire-rated choice for in-wall network runs.","Direct burial cable is rated for underground use, not typical in-wall installation."]},{"id":195,"question":"A technician needs to route cables along a wall surface. Which product should be used?","options":["Raceway","Patch panel","Cable tray","Riser"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Raceways protect and conceal cables along walls.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Raceways protect and conceal cables along walls.","A patch panel terminates cabling in a rack, not routing cable along a wall surface.","A cable tray supports bundled cables typically above ceilings, not wall-surface routing.","A riser is a vertical pathway between floors, not wall-surface cable routing."]},{"id":196,"question":"Which device regenerates signals to extend cable distance?","options":["Repeater","Switch","Firewall","Load balancer"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Repeaters regenerate signals to extend cable runs.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Repeaters regenerate signals to extend cable runs.","A switch forwards frames between devices; it doesn't regenerate signal strength over distance.","A firewall filters traffic, unrelated to signal regeneration.","A load balancer distributes traffic, unrelated to extending cable distance via signal regeneration."]},{"id":197,"question":"Which standard defines telecommunications room cabling and pathways?","options":["TIA-568","IEEE 802.3","ISO 9001","RFC 1918"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"TIA-568 defines structured cabling standards.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["TIA-568 defines structured cabling standards.","IEEE 802.3 defines Ethernet protocol standards, not telecom room cabling/pathway standards.","ISO 9001 is a quality management standard, unrelated to cabling pathways.","RFC 1918 defines private IP address ranges, unrelated to physical cabling standards."]},{"id":198,"question":"Which device distributes incoming internet traffic across multiple servers?","options":["Load balancer","Firewall","Switch","Repeater"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Load balancers distribute traffic to improve performance and redundancy.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Load balancers distribute traffic to improve performance and redundancy.","A firewall filters/inspects traffic for security, not distributing it across servers.","A switch forwards frames within a LAN, not distributing internet traffic across multiple servers.","A repeater regenerates signal strength, unrelated to distributing traffic across servers."]},{"id":199,"question":"Which appliance inspects traffic and blocks malicious activity?","options":["Firewall","Switch","Patch panel","Repeater"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Firewalls filter and inspect traffic for security.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Firewalls filter and inspect traffic for security.","A switch forwards frames between devices; it doesn't inspect for malicious activity.","A patch panel organizes physical cabling, unrelated to traffic inspection.","A repeater regenerates signal strength, unrelated to security inspection."]},{"id":200,"question":"Which device caches frequently accessed web content to reduce bandwidth usage?","options":["Proxy server","Load balancer","Repeater","UPS"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Proxy servers can cache web content to improve performance.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Proxy servers can cache web content to improve performance.","A load balancer distributes traffic across servers, not caching content to reduce bandwidth.","A repeater regenerates signal strength, unrelated to caching web content.","A UPS provides backup power, unrelated to caching content."]},{"id":201,"question":"Which device aggregates multiple WAN connections for redundancy?","options":["Router","Switch","Patch panel","Repeater"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Routers manage WAN connections and routing decisions.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Routers manage WAN connections and routing decisions.","A switch forwards frames within a LAN, not aggregating WAN links.","A patch panel organizes cabling, unrelated to WAN redundancy.","A repeater regenerates signals, unrelated to WAN link aggregation."]},{"id":202,"question":"Which appliance is used to detect and alert on suspicious network activity?","options":["IDS","Load balancer","Repeater","Patch panel"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"IDS systems monitor traffic and alert on suspicious behavior.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["IDS systems monitor traffic and alert on suspicious behavior.","A load balancer distributes traffic, not detecting suspicious activity.","A repeater regenerates signals, unrelated to security monitoring.","A patch panel organizes cabling, unrelated to traffic inspection."]},{"id":203,"question":"Which device both detects and blocks malicious traffic automatically?","options":["IPS","IDS","Proxy","Repeater"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"IPS systems actively block malicious traffic.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["IPS systems actively block malicious traffic.","An IDS only detects and alerts; it doesn't actively block traffic.","A proxy handles client requests on behalf of users, not primarily blocking malicious traffic.","A repeater regenerates signals, unrelated to blocking malicious traffic."]},{"id":204,"question":"Which device provides secure remote access using encrypted tunnels?","options":["VPN concentrator","Switch","Repeater","Patch panel"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"VPN concentrators manage encrypted remote access tunnels.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["VPN concentrators manage encrypted remote access tunnels.","A switch forwards frames within a LAN, unrelated to encrypted remote tunnels.","A repeater regenerates signals, unrelated to secure remote access.","A patch panel organizes cabling, unrelated to VPN tunnels."]},{"id":205,"question":"Which device is used to connect multiple network segments and forward frames based on MAC addresses?","options":["Switch","Router","Firewall","Proxy"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Switches forward frames using MAC address tables.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Switches forward frames using MAC address tables.","A router forwards based on IP addresses between networks, not MAC-based frame forwarding within a segment.","A firewall filters traffic based on rules, not MAC-based frame forwarding.","A proxy handles requests on behalf of clients, unrelated to MAC-based frame switching."]},{"id":206,"question":"Which appliance filters traffic based on Layer 7 application data?","options":["Next-generation firewall","Repeater","Patch panel","Hub"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"NGFWs inspect traffic at the application layer.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["NGFWs inspect traffic at the application layer.","A repeater regenerates signals, unrelated to application-layer inspection.","A patch panel organizes cabling, unrelated to traffic filtering.","A hub blindly repeats traffic to all ports with no inspection at all."]},{"id":207,"question":"Which device is used to connect legacy coaxial Ethernet segments?","options":["Media converter","Switch","Firewall","Load balancer"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Media converters allow different media types to interoperate.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Media converters allow different media types to interoperate.","A switch forwards frames but doesn't convert between different physical media types like coax and modern Ethernet.","A firewall filters traffic, unrelated to converting between physical media types.","A load balancer distributes traffic, unrelated to media type conversion."]},{"id":208,"question":"Which device isolates broadcast domains?","options":["Router","Switch","Hub","Repeater"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Routers separate broadcast domains.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["Routers separate broadcast domains.","A switch typically forwards within one broadcast domain rather than separating them.","A hub extends one shared collision/broadcast domain further, the opposite of isolating it.","A repeater regenerates signals within the same segment, not separating broadcast domains."]},{"id":209,"question":"Which appliance is used to optimize WAN traffic by compressing and caching data?","options":["WAN optimizer","Proxy server","Firewall","Repeater"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"WAN optimizers improve WAN performance using compression and caching.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 2.html","optionExplanations":["WAN optimizers improve WAN performance using compression and caching.","A proxy server caches web content generally, but a WAN optimizer specifically targets WAN link compression/optimization.","A firewall filters traffic for security, unrelated to WAN performance optimization.","A repeater regenerates signals, unrelated to compressing/caching WAN traffic."]},{"id":210,"question":"A user on a small office LAN can reach the local printer but cannot reach a device on another floor. Which device is most likely forwarding traffic between those IP networks?","options":["Router.","Switch.","Hub.","Patch panel."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Routers make forwarding decisions with IP addressing and move traffic between different networks or subnets.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["Routers make forwarding decisions with IP addressing and move traffic between different networks or subnets.","A switch forwards within a single network/broadcast domain, not between separate IP networks.","A hub simply repeats signals to all ports, without any IP-based forwarding decisions.","A patch panel organizes cabling, unrelated to forwarding traffic between networks."]},{"id":211,"question":"A technician replaces an unmanaged device with one that separates collision domains and forwards frames based on MAC addresses. Which appliance was installed?","options":["Switch.","Router.","Firewall.","Load balancer."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A switch is the Layer 2 device that forwards traffic by MAC address and gives each port its own collision domain.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A switch is the Layer 2 device that forwards traffic by MAC address and gives each port its own collision domain.","A router forwards based on IP addresses between networks, not MAC-based frame forwarding within a segment.","A firewall filters traffic by rule sets, not separating collision domains by port.","A load balancer distributes traffic across servers, unrelated to collision domain separation."]},{"id":212,"question":"A company wants to inspect traffic by application, user, and content instead of relying only on ports and IP addresses. Which appliance best fits that need?","options":["Next-generation firewall.","Layer 2 switch.","Repeater.","Media converter."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A next-generation firewall can inspect traffic at higher layers and apply application-aware security policies.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A next-generation firewall can inspect traffic at higher layers and apply application-aware security policies.","A Layer 2 switch forwards frames by MAC address, without inspecting application-layer content.","A repeater regenerates signals, unrelated to application-aware inspection.","A media converter changes physical media types, unrelated to content inspection."]},{"id":213,"question":"Users say the customer portal slows down whenever one web server gets overloaded. Which appliance is designed to spread requests across multiple servers?","options":["Load balancer.","Proxy server.","IDS sensor.","RADIUS server."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A load balancer distributes client connections across backend servers to improve performance and availability.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A load balancer distributes client connections across backend servers to improve performance and availability.","A proxy server handles requests on behalf of clients, not primarily distributing load across multiple servers.","An IDS sensor detects suspicious activity, unrelated to distributing server load.","A RADIUS server handles authentication, unrelated to distributing web traffic."]},{"id":214,"question":"A school wants to reduce repeated internet downloads of the same web content and speed up browsing for students. Which appliance would help most?","options":["Proxy server.","Patch panel.","Wireless bridge.","PoE injector."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A proxy server can cache web content so repeated requests do not always have to go back out to the internet.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A proxy server can cache web content so repeated requests do not always have to go back out to the internet.","A patch panel organizes cabling, unrelated to caching web content.","A wireless bridge links wired networks over Wi-Fi, unrelated to caching internet content.","A PoE injector adds power to Ethernet cabling, unrelated to caching web content."]},{"id":215,"question":"Remote VPN users must log in with centralized credentials before they are allowed onto the network. Which server role is commonly used for that authentication?","options":["RADIUS server.","DHCP server.","Syslog server.","File server."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"RADIUS is commonly used to centralize authentication and authorization for VPN and network access.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["RADIUS is commonly used to centralize authentication and authorization for VPN and network access.","A DHCP server assigns IP addresses, not centralized authentication credentials.","A syslog server collects log messages, unrelated to authenticating VPN logins.","A file server stores shared files, unrelated to centralized authentication."]},{"id":216,"question":"A warehouse Wi‑Fi signal is weak in one corner, and the business wants to extend coverage without running new cable. Which device is the best fit?","options":["Wireless extender.","Load balancer.","Spam filter.","VPN concentrator."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A wireless extender repeats or retransmits the existing wireless signal to expand coverage.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A wireless extender repeats or retransmits the existing wireless signal to expand coverage.","A load balancer distributes traffic across servers, unrelated to extending Wi-Fi coverage.","A spam filter blocks unwanted email, unrelated to wireless coverage.","A VPN concentrator manages encrypted tunnels, unrelated to extending local Wi-Fi coverage."]},{"id":217,"question":"An office router is providing internet access for many internal hosts that all use private IPv4 addresses. Which function is letting those hosts share a public address?","options":["NAT.","QoS.","PoE.","TFTP."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Network Address Translation lets private internal addresses be translated to a public address for outbound internet access.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["Network Address Translation lets private internal addresses be translated to a public address for outbound internet access.","QoS prioritizes certain traffic types, unrelated to address translation/sharing.","PoE delivers power over Ethernet cabling, unrelated to address sharing.","TFTP is a simple file transfer protocol, unrelated to address translation."]},{"id":218,"question":"A technician is trying to extend a copper Ethernet run beyond its normal distance by regenerating the electrical signal. Which device performs that function?","options":["Repeater.","Firewall.","Proxy.","Content filter."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A repeater regenerates a weakened signal so it can travel farther on the medium.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A repeater regenerates a weakened signal so it can travel farther on the medium.","A firewall filters traffic by rules, unrelated to regenerating a weakened electrical signal.","A proxy handles requests on behalf of clients, unrelated to signal regeneration.","A content filter blocks traffic by policy, unrelated to extending cable distance."]},{"id":219,"question":"A security policy says certain inbound traffic must be allowed while other traffic must be blocked based on rule sets. Which appliance primarily handles that job?","options":["Firewall.","Switch.","Hub.","Punchdown block."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A firewall enforces permit and deny rules on network traffic.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A firewall enforces permit and deny rules on network traffic.","A switch forwards frames within a LAN, not enforcing permit/deny rule sets.","A hub simply repeats traffic without any rule-based filtering at all.","A punchdown block is passive cable termination hardware, unrelated to traffic rules."]},{"id":220,"question":"A junior tech plugs several hosts into an old device and notices that every frame is sent out every port. Which device is the tech most likely using?","options":["Hub.","Switch.","Router.","Bridge."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A hub is a basic Layer 1 device that repeats traffic to all ports instead of forwarding selectively.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A hub is a basic Layer 1 device that repeats traffic to all ports instead of forwarding selectively.","A switch forwards frames selectively to the correct port, not out every port.","A router makes forwarding decisions based on IP addresses, not blind repetition to every port.","A bridge selectively forwards between two segments, not blindly repeating to every port."]},{"id":221,"question":"A company wants to terminate many encrypted remote-access tunnels on a dedicated platform rather than on a standard router. Which appliance is designed for that?","options":["VPN concentrator.","Load balancer.","Proxy server.","Wireless controller."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A VPN concentrator is built to terminate and manage many VPN tunnels efficiently.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A VPN concentrator is built to terminate and manage many VPN tunnels efficiently.","A load balancer distributes traffic across servers, unrelated to terminating VPN tunnels.","A proxy server handles requests on behalf of clients, unrelated to VPN tunnel termination.","A wireless controller manages access points, unrelated to terminating wired VPN tunnels."]},{"id":222,"question":"Employees can connect to Wi‑Fi, but they have to type IP settings manually because nothing is assigning them automatically. Which server role is missing?","options":["DHCP server.","DNS server.","NTP server.","AAA server."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"DHCP automatically assigns IP addresses and related settings like the subnet mask, gateway, and often DNS servers.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["DHCP automatically assigns IP addresses and related settings like the subnet mask, gateway, and often DNS servers.","A DNS server resolves names to addresses, not assigning IP configuration itself.","An NTP server synchronizes time, unrelated to assigning IP settings.","An AAA server handles authentication/authorization, unrelated to automatic IP address assignment."]},{"id":223,"question":"Users can reach internal resources by IP address but not by hostname. Which network service should be checked first?","options":["DNS server.","DHCP server.","Proxy server.","RADIUS server."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"DNS resolves hostnames to IP addresses, so hostname failures point there first.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["DNS resolves hostnames to IP addresses, so hostname failures point there first.","A DHCP server assigns IP addresses, and IP-based access already works, pointing elsewhere.","A proxy server handles requests on behalf of clients, unrelated to hostname resolution failures.","A RADIUS server handles authentication, unrelated to hostname resolution."]},{"id":224,"question":"A security analyst wants a tool that watches traffic and generates alerts when suspicious patterns are detected, but does not block packets automatically. Which appliance fits?","options":["IDS.","IPS.","Web filter.","Load balancer."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An IDS detects suspicious traffic and alerts on it, while an IPS goes a step further and actively blocks.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["An IDS detects suspicious traffic and alerts on it, while an IPS goes a step further and actively blocks.","An IPS actively blocks traffic, beyond just detecting and alerting.","A web filter blocks specific web content/categories, not general traffic pattern alerting.","A load balancer distributes traffic across servers, unrelated to detecting suspicious patterns."]},{"id":225,"question":"A company wants malicious traffic stopped in real time instead of just logged for later review. Which security appliance is the better choice?","options":["IPS.","IDS.","Proxy server.","DHCP server."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An IPS is designed to detect and actively prevent or block malicious traffic.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["An IPS is designed to detect and actively prevent or block malicious traffic.","An IDS only detects and alerts, without actively blocking traffic in real time.","A proxy server handles requests on behalf of clients, not actively blocking malicious traffic.","A DHCP server assigns IP addresses, unrelated to blocking malicious traffic."]},{"id":226,"question":"A branch office uses two ISP circuits and wants one appliance to combine them for resiliency and better use of bandwidth. Which appliance best matches that goal?","options":["WAN aggregator.","Content filter.","Loopback adapter.","Mail gateway."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A WAN aggregator combines multiple WAN links for redundancy, performance, or load-sharing.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A WAN aggregator combines multiple WAN links for redundancy, performance, or load-sharing.","A content filter blocks traffic by policy category, unrelated to combining multiple WAN circuits.","A loopback adapter tests port function, unrelated to combining WAN links.","A mail gateway manages email flow, unrelated to combining ISP circuits."]},{"id":227,"question":"Management wants to block categories like gambling and malware sites before users ever reach them. Which appliance is best suited for that policy?","options":["Web security gateway.","Patch management server.","VPN concentrator.","Media converter."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A web security gateway can enforce browsing policies and filter traffic by category or reputation.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A web security gateway can enforce browsing policies and filter traffic by category or reputation.","A patch management server distributes software updates, unrelated to blocking website categories.","A VPN concentrator manages encrypted tunnels, unrelated to web content filtering policy.","A media converter changes physical media types, unrelated to website category blocking."]},{"id":228,"question":"A department needs a central place where shared documents can be stored and accessed by many users. Which server role is the most direct fit?","options":["File server.","DNS server.","Load balancer.","IDS sensor."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A file server is used to store and share files over the network.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A file server is used to store and share files over the network.","A DNS server resolves names to addresses, unrelated to storing shared documents.","A load balancer distributes traffic across servers, unrelated to file storage.","An IDS sensor detects suspicious activity, unrelated to file storage."]},{"id":229,"question":"An IT team wants endpoints to receive operating system and software updates from a centralized internal system. Which appliance supports that process?","options":["Patch management server.","Wireless extender.","Router.","Protocol analyzer."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A patch management server helps distribute approved updates to managed devices.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A patch management server helps distribute approved updates to managed devices.","A wireless extender extends Wi-Fi coverage, unrelated to distributing software updates.","A router forwards traffic between networks, unrelated to centralized update distribution.","A protocol analyzer captures/inspects traffic, unrelated to distributing patches."]},{"id":230,"question":"A company wants one back-end service to handle authentication, authorization, and accounting for network access. Which role does that describe?","options":["AAA server.","Proxy server.","DHCP relay.","File share."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"AAA stands for authentication, authorization, and accounting.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["AAA stands for authentication, authorization, and accounting.","A proxy server handles requests on behalf of clients, not authentication/authorization/accounting.","DHCP relay forwards address requests across subnets, unrelated to AAA functions.","A file share stores shared files, unrelated to authentication/authorization/accounting."]},{"id":231,"question":"A parent organization wants branch offices to block websites based on categories such as social media or adult content. Which appliance most directly fits?","options":["Content filter.","Switch.","Cable tester.","VPN tunnel."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A content filter blocks or allows traffic based on policy categories or specific web content rules.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A content filter blocks or allows traffic based on policy categories or specific web content rules.","A switch forwards frames within a LAN, unrelated to blocking website categories.","A cable tester verifies physical cabling, unrelated to web content policy.","A VPN tunnel provides secure remote connectivity, unrelated to category-based web blocking."]},{"id":232,"question":"A technician needs to capture packets during a slow application complaint and inspect the headers in detail. Which tool should be used?","options":["Protocol analyzer.","Patch panel.","Repeater.","Load balancer."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A protocol analyzer captures and decodes packets so a technician can troubleshoot network behavior.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A protocol analyzer captures and decodes packets so a technician can troubleshoot network behavior.","A patch panel organizes cabling, unrelated to capturing/inspecting packet headers.","A repeater regenerates signals, unrelated to packet-level inspection.","A load balancer distributes traffic, unrelated to detailed packet capture."]},{"id":233,"question":"A security team wants logs from many devices collected in one place and correlated for suspicious patterns. Which platform best fits?","options":["SIEM.","DHCP server.","Content filter.","Wireless bridge."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A SIEM centralizes log collection and correlation so analysts can investigate events across many systems.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A SIEM centralizes log collection and correlation so analysts can investigate events across many systems.","A DHCP server assigns addresses, unrelated to centralized log correlation.","A content filter blocks web traffic by policy, unrelated to log correlation across devices.","A wireless bridge links wired networks over Wi-Fi, unrelated to centralized security log analysis."]},{"id":234,"question":"A malware analyst wants to open a suspicious file in an isolated environment where it cannot affect production systems. What should be used?","options":["Sandbox.","Load balancer.","Proxy cache.","DHCP scope."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A sandbox isolates code or files for safe analysis and testing.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.2","objective":"Common Attacks & Threats","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A sandbox isolates code or files for safe analysis and testing.","A load balancer distributes traffic across servers, unrelated to isolated file analysis.","A proxy cache stores web content for reuse, unrelated to isolating suspicious files for analysis.","A DHCP scope defines an address range, unrelated to isolated malware analysis."]},{"id":235,"question":"A company with slow branch links wants to compress and optimize repetitive traffic between sites to improve perceived performance. Which appliance is designed for that?","options":["WAN accelerator.","Hub.","NGFW.","PoE injector."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A WAN accelerator improves application performance across slower WAN links by using techniques like caching and optimization.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A WAN accelerator improves application performance across slower WAN links by using techniques like caching and optimization.","A hub blindly repeats traffic, unrelated to compressing or optimizing WAN traffic.","An NGFW inspects traffic for security policy, not primarily optimizing WAN performance.","A PoE injector adds power over Ethernet, unrelated to WAN traffic optimization."]},{"id":236,"question":"A network team needs an appliance that stores and forwards email messages for users in the organization. Which role is being described?","options":["Mail server.","DNS server.","IDS.","VPN concentrator."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A mail server handles email delivery, storage, and forwarding.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A mail server handles email delivery, storage, and forwarding.","A DNS server resolves names to addresses, unrelated to storing/forwarding email.","An IDS detects suspicious traffic, unrelated to email delivery.","A VPN concentrator manages encrypted tunnels, unrelated to email storage/forwarding."]},{"id":237,"question":"A technician is documenting a network closet and wants to identify the device that simply organizes cable terminations without processing traffic. Which item is that?","options":["Patch panel.","Router.","Firewall.","Proxy server."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A patch panel is passive hardware for cable organization and termination. It does not forward traffic.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.2","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A patch panel is passive hardware for cable organization and termination. It does not forward traffic.","A router makes IP-based forwarding decisions, unlike a passive cable-organizing panel.","A firewall actively filters traffic, unlike a passive cable-organizing panel.","A proxy server actively handles client requests, unlike a passive cable-organizing panel."]},{"id":238,"question":"A network engineer needs to connect two different network segments and also break up broadcast domains. Which appliance is the usual answer?","options":["Router.","Hub.","Repeater.","Punchdown tool."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Routers separate broadcast domains and connect different IP networks.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["Routers separate broadcast domains and connect different IP networks.","A hub extends one shared broadcast domain, the opposite of breaking it up.","A repeater regenerates signal within the same segment, not separating broadcast domains.","A punchdown tool terminates copper wiring, unrelated to broadcast domain separation."]},{"id":239,"question":"A technician wants a device that can place multiple backend servers behind one public-facing service while checking which servers are healthy. Which appliance best fits?","options":["Load balancer.","Protocol analyzer.","DHCP server.","Repeater."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A load balancer can monitor server health and direct client requests only to available backend systems.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 3 .html","optionExplanations":["A load balancer can monitor server health and direct client requests only to available backend systems.","A protocol analyzer captures/inspects traffic, unrelated to distributing requests across healthy servers.","A DHCP server assigns IP addresses, unrelated to distributing traffic across backend servers.","A repeater regenerates signals, unrelated to backend server health checking."]},{"id":240,"question":"A help desk technician sees a PC with 169.254.22.14 and notices the user cannot reach network resources. What is the most likely issue?","options":["The PC did not receive a DHCP lease.","The PC has a valid public address.","The PC is using the loopback range.","The PC is connected to the wrong DNS zone."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An address in the 169.254.0.0/16 range is APIPA. That usually means the device could not contact DHCP and self-assigned an address.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.3","objective":"Network Service Issues","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["An address in the 169.254.0.0/16 range is APIPA. That usually means the device could not contact DHCP and self-assigned an address.","169.254.x.x is a private APIPA address, not a valid public address.","The loopback range is 127.0.0.0/8, a different reserved range than APIPA's 169.254.0.0/16.","DNS zone assignment is unrelated to why a device would self-assign a 169.254.x.x address."]},{"id":241,"question":"A workstation can reach devices on its own subnet but cannot reach a file server on another subnet. Which setting should be checked first?","options":["Default gateway.","Screen resolution.","Hostname length.","MAC vendor."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Traffic to a different subnet must be sent to a default gateway. If local access works but remote access fails, the gateway is a smart first check.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["Traffic to a different subnet must be sent to a default gateway. If local access works but remote access fails, the gateway is a smart first check.","Screen resolution has no connection to network subnet reachability.","Hostname length doesn't affect IP routing between subnets.","MAC vendor identifies hardware manufacturer, unrelated to cross-subnet routing."]},{"id":242,"question":"A junior technician asks what a subnet mask is mainly used for. Which answer is best?","options":["To identify which part of an IPv4 address is network and which part is host.","To translate domain names or hostnames directly into their corresponding IP addresses","To encrypt packets before they are transmitted across the network","To automatically assign VLAN numbers to devices on the network"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A subnet mask tells a device which bits belong to the network portion and which bits belong to the host portion of an IP address.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["A subnet mask tells a device which bits belong to the network portion and which bits belong to the host portion of an IP address.","DNS handles translating names to IP addresses, not a subnet mask's purpose.","Encryption is handled by protocols like IPsec/TLS, not a subnet mask.","VLAN numbering is a switch configuration task, unrelated to subnet mask function."]},{"id":243,"question":"A laptop is configured with 192.168.1.25/24. Which address is in the same subnet?","options":["192.168.1.200.","192.168.2.25.","192.168.10.25.","192.168.0.25."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A /24 means the first three octets must match for devices to be in the same subnet.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["A /24 means the first three octets must match for devices to be in the same subnet.","192.168.2.25 is in a different third octet, a different /24 subnet.","192.168.10.25 is in a different third octet, a different /24 subnet.","192.168.0.25 is in a different third octet, a different /24 subnet."]},{"id":244,"question":"A technician wants to test the local TCP/IP stack without sending traffic onto the network. Which address should be used?","options":["127.0.0.1.","169.254.1.1.","255.255.255.255.","224.0.0.1."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"127.0.0.1 is the loopback address. It is used to test the local TCP/IP stack on the device itself.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["127.0.0.1 is the loopback address. It is used to test the local TCP/IP stack on the device itself.","169.254.1.1 is an APIPA address used when DHCP fails, not the loopback address.","255.255.255.255 is the limited broadcast address, not a loopback test address.","224.0.0.1 is a multicast address, not the loopback address."]},{"id":245,"question":"A network admin is reviewing logs and needs to quickly identify a private IPv4 address. Which one is private?","options":["10.24.8.15.","11.24.8.15.","172.40.8.15.","193.168.8.15."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"10.0.0.0/8 is a private IPv4 range. The others are not in the standard private ranges.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["10.0.0.0/8 is a private IPv4 range. The others are not in the standard private ranges.","11.24.8.15 falls outside the 10.0.0.0/8 private range.","172.40.8.15 falls outside the 172.16.0.0-172.31.255.255 private range.","193.168.8.15 is not within any of the standard private IPv4 ranges."]},{"id":246,"question":"A branch office uses 192.168.50.0/24. Which address would most likely be assigned to the router interface for users on that subnet?","options":["192.168.50.1.","192.168.51.1.","192.168.50.0.","255.255.255.0."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The router interface serving a subnet is often assigned the first usable host address, such as .1.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["The router interface serving a subnet is often assigned the first usable host address, such as .1.","192.168.51.1 is in a different subnet than 192.168.50.0/24.","192.168.50.0 is the network address itself, not assignable to a host interface.","255.255.255.0 is a subnet mask, not a valid host address."]},{"id":247,"question":"A user reports that a PC has the address 255.255.255.0 entered in the IP address field. What is the problem?","options":["That value is a subnet mask, not a host IP address.","That value is a valid default gateway.","That value is a loopback address.","That value is a valid APIPA address."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"255.255.255.0 is a subnet mask. It is not a valid host IP address for a workstation.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.3","objective":"Network Service Issues","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["255.255.255.0 is a subnet mask. It is not a valid host IP address for a workstation.","255.255.255.0 is not a typical default gateway address format used for hosts.","The loopback address is 127.0.0.1, not 255.255.255.0.","A valid APIPA address falls in 169.254.0.0/16, not 255.255.255.0."]},{"id":248,"question":"A technician reads that a network uses a /24 prefix. Which dotted-decimal mask matches that prefix?","options":["255.255.255.0.","255.255.0.0.","255.255.255.128.","255.255.254.0."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A /24 prefix equals 255.255.255.0. This is one of the most common mask conversions to know.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["A /24 prefix equals 255.255.255.0. This is one of the most common mask conversions to know.","255.255.0.0 corresponds to a /16 prefix, not /24.","255.255.255.128 corresponds to a /25 prefix, not /24.","255.255.254.0 corresponds to a /23 prefix, not /24."]},{"id":249,"question":"A small office wants two PCs to talk directly over IP on the same LAN without routing. What must be true?","options":["They must be in the same subnet.","They must use different DNS servers.","They must have different MAC vendors.","They must use public addresses."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Devices communicate directly at Layer 2 when they are in the same IP subnet. Traffic between different subnets requires routing.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["Devices communicate directly at Layer 2 when they are in the same IP subnet. Traffic between different subnets requires routing.","DNS server assignment doesn't determine whether two devices can communicate directly at Layer 2.","MAC vendor (manufacturer) has no bearing on whether two devices can talk directly on a LAN.","Public vs. private addressing doesn't determine whether two devices are on the same local subnet."]},{"id":250,"question":"A support analyst sees 172.20.12.55 on a company laptop. How should that address be classified?","options":["Private IPv4 address.","Public IPv4 address.","Loopback address.","APIPA address."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"172.16.0.0 through 172.31.255.255 is private IPv4 space. 172.20.12.55 falls inside that range.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.3","objective":"Network Service Issues","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["172.16.0.0 through 172.31.255.255 is private IPv4 space. 172.20.12.55 falls inside that range.","A public address would need to be outside reserved private ranges; 172.20.12.55 falls inside the private 172.16/12 range.","The loopback address is 127.0.0.1, not addresses in the 172.16-172.31 range.","APIPA addresses fall in 169.254.0.0/16, not the 172.16-172.31 range."]},{"id":251,"question":"A technician is asked what a default gateway actually does for a host. Which answer is best?","options":["It forwards traffic to remote networks.","It assigns IP addresses to clients.","It resolves MAC addresses to hostnames.","It replaces the subnet mask."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A default gateway is the router a host uses when it needs to reach a different IP network.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["A default gateway is the router a host uses when it needs to reach a different IP network.","Assigning IP addresses is a DHCP server function, not the gateway's role.","Resolving MAC addresses to hostnames isn't a standard networking function performed by a gateway.","A gateway address is separate from and doesn't replace the subnet mask."]},{"id":252,"question":"A device with address 192.168.10.44/24 needs to reach 192.168.10.99. How will the host treat that destination?","options":["As local traffic on the same subnet.","As remote traffic that must go to the gateway.","As multicast traffic.","As loopback traffic."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"With a /24 mask, both addresses are in the 192.168.10.0 network, so the host treats the destination as local.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["With a /24 mask, both addresses are in the 192.168.10.0 network, so the host treats the destination as local.","Since both addresses share the same /24 network, the host treats this as local, not requiring the gateway.","Multicast traffic targets a specific reserved address range, not a regular host-to-host address like this.","Loopback traffic targets 127.0.0.1, not another device's regular IP address."]},{"id":253,"question":"A user can browse websites by IP address but not by hostname. Which service should be checked first?","options":["DNS.","NTP.","DHCP reservation.","Loopback adapter."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"If IP-based access works but hostname-based access fails, DNS is the most likely issue.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["If IP-based access works but hostname-based access fails, DNS is the most likely issue.","NTP synchronizes time, unrelated to hostname resolution.","A DHCP reservation assigns a specific address to a device, unrelated to resolving hostnames to IPs.","A loopback adapter tests local network stack function, unrelated to hostname resolution."]},{"id":254,"question":"A network administrator wants a quick example of a public IPv4 address. Which address fits best?","options":["8.8.8.8.","10.10.10.10.","172.16.10.10.","192.168.10.10."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"8.8.8.8 is a public IPv4 address. The other options are private address ranges.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["8.8.8.8 is a public IPv4 address. The other options are private address ranges.","10.10.10.10 falls within the private 10.0.0.0/8 range.","172.16.10.10 falls within the private 172.16.0.0/12 range.","192.168.10.10 falls within the private 192.168.0.0/16 range."]},{"id":255,"question":"A desktop is manually configured with 192.168.5.25 and mask 255.255.255.0. Which prefix length matches that mask?","options":["/24.","/16.","/25.","/23."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The mask 255.255.255.0 corresponds to a /24 prefix.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["The mask 255.255.255.0 corresponds to a /24 prefix.","/16 corresponds to mask 255.255.0.0, not 255.255.255.0.","/25 corresponds to mask 255.255.255.128, not 255.255.255.0.","/23 corresponds to mask 255.255.254.0, not 255.255.255.0."]},{"id":256,"question":"A junior admin asks what DHCP does on a typical network. Which answer is correct?","options":["It automatically assigns IP configuration to clients.","It filters unwanted websites.","It translates hostnames to IP addresses.","It encrypts traffic between subnets."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"DHCP automatically assigns IP settings such as the IP address, subnet mask, gateway, and often DNS servers.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["DHCP automatically assigns IP settings such as the IP address, subnet mask, gateway, and often DNS servers.","Filtering websites is a content filter's job, not DHCP's function.","Translating hostnames to IPs is DNS's job, not DHCP's function.","Encrypting traffic is a VPN/encryption function, not something DHCP does."]},{"id":257,"question":"A technician needs to recognize a Class C network in an old document. Which default mask belongs to that classful range?","options":["255.255.255.0.","255.255.0.0.","255.0.0.0.","255.255.255.192."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"In classful addressing, a Class C network used the default mask 255.255.255.0, or /24.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["In classful addressing, a Class C network used the default mask 255.255.255.0, or /24.","255.255.0.0 is the default mask for Class B, not Class C.","255.0.0.0 is the default mask for Class A, not Class C.","255.255.255.192 is a subnetted /26 mask, not the classful Class C default."]},{"id":258,"question":"A PC with 10.1.5.10/8 sends traffic to 10.99.44.2. How will the PC view that destination?","options":["As part of the same IP network.","As a remote host that needs routing.","As a broadcast destination.","As an APIPA address."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"With a /8 mask, any address beginning with 10 is in the same IP network from the host's perspective.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.3","objective":"Network Service Issues","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["With a /8 mask, any address beginning with 10 is in the same IP network from the host's perspective.","With a /8 mask, addresses sharing the first octet (10.x.x.x) are in the same network, not requiring routing.","A broadcast destination would use a specific reserved address, not this particular host address.","An APIPA address specifically falls in the 169.254.0.0/16 range, not 10.x.x.x addresses."]},{"id":259,"question":"A company wants to avoid public addressing internally. Which range is designed for private LAN use?","options":["192.168.0.0/16.","127.0.0.0/8.","224.0.0.0/4.","169.254.0.0/16."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"192.168.0.0/16 is one of the standard private IPv4 ranges used on internal networks.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["192.168.0.0/16 is one of the standard private IPv4 ranges used on internal networks.","127.0.0.0/8 is the loopback range, not a private LAN addressing range for regular hosts.","224.0.0.0/4 is the multicast address range, not private LAN addressing.","169.254.0.0/16 is the APIPA range used for self-assignment, not standard private LAN addressing."]},{"id":260,"question":"A tech is documenting a subnet and asks which address is reserved as the network identifier in 192.168.30.0/24. Which address should be listed?","options":["192.168.30.0.","192.168.30.1.","192.168.30.254.","192.168.30.255."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"In a /24 subnet, the .0 address identifies the network itself and is not assigned to a host.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["In a /24 subnet, the .0 address identifies the network itself and is not assigned to a host.","192.168.30.1 is typically the first usable host address, not the network identifier itself.","192.168.30.254 is typically a usable host address, not the network identifier.","192.168.30.255 is the broadcast address for this /24, not the network identifier."]},{"id":261,"question":"An intern asks which address in 192.168.30.0/24 is reserved for broadcast traffic to all hosts on that subnet. Which answer is correct?","options":["192.168.30.255.","192.168.30.0.","192.168.30.1.","192.168.31.255."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"In a /24 subnet, the final address in the range is the broadcast address, which is .255.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["In a /24 subnet, the final address in the range is the broadcast address, which is .255.","192.168.30.0 is the network address, not the broadcast address.","192.168.30.1 is a usable host address, not the broadcast address.","192.168.31.255 belongs to a different /24 subnet entirely."]},{"id":262,"question":"A user enters 192.168.1.0 as the IP address of a printer on a /24 network. Why is that a problem?","options":["That is the network address and cannot be used by a host.","That is only ever used as a default gateway address, never as a host address","That address falls specifically within the reserved APIPA addressing range","That address is reserved specifically for multicast group traffic delivery"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"On a /24 network, the .0 address identifies the network itself. Host devices must use usable host addresses instead.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.3","objective":"Network Service Issues","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["On a /24 network, the .0 address identifies the network itself. Host devices must use usable host addresses instead.","255.255.255.0-style addresses are used for masks, not gateway addresses; the actual issue is that .0 is the network address.","The APIPA range is 169.254.0.0/16, not 192.168.1.0.","The multicast range is 224.0.0.0/4, not 192.168.1.0."]},{"id":263,"question":"A help desk ticket says a workstation has the wrong mask and now thinks remote hosts are local. What problem can that create?","options":["The PC may ARP for devices that actually require routing.","The PC will stop using MAC addresses completely.","The PC will automatically become a DHCP server.","The PC will convert IPv4 traffic to IPv6 traffic."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A bad subnet mask can make a host misjudge whether a destination is local or remote. That often leads to ARP attempts instead of sending traffic to the gateway.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["A bad subnet mask can make a host misjudge whether a destination is local or remote. That often leads to ARP attempts instead of sending traffic to the gateway.","A bad subnet mask doesn't stop a PC from using MAC addresses at all; it can cause it to misjudge whether ARP is needed.","A misconfigured mask doesn't turn a client into a DHCP server.","A subnet mask issue doesn't cause IPv4-to-IPv6 protocol conversion."]},{"id":264,"question":"A network diagram shows the mask 255.255.0.0 on an old internal network. Which prefix length is this?","options":["/16.","/8.","/24.","/17."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"255.255.0.0 equals a /16 prefix.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["255.255.0.0 equals a /16 prefix.","/8 corresponds to mask 255.0.0.0, not 255.255.0.0.","/24 corresponds to mask 255.255.255.0, not 255.255.0.0.","/17 corresponds to mask 255.255.128.0, not 255.255.0.0."]},{"id":265,"question":"A branch router is being configured to support about 250 devices on one subnet. Which choice is the most common fit?","options":["/24.","/30.","/29.","/28."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A /24 supports 254 usable host addresses, making it a common fit for around 250 devices.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["A /24 supports 254 usable host addresses, making it a common fit for around 250 devices.","/30 supports only 2 usable hosts, far too few for 250 devices.","/29 supports only 6 usable hosts, far too few for 250 devices.","/28 supports only 14 usable hosts, far too few for 250 devices."]},{"id":266,"question":"A support tech sees that a user can ping 127.0.0.1 but cannot ping the default gateway. What does that prove?","options":["The local TCP/IP stack is functioning.","The switch port is definitely correct.","DNS is working normally.","The remote server is online."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A successful ping to 127.0.0.1 shows the local TCP/IP stack is working. It does not prove broader network connectivity.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["A successful ping to 127.0.0.1 shows the local TCP/IP stack is working. It does not prove broader network connectivity.","A successful loopback ping says nothing about whether the specific switch port is correctly configured.","Loopback connectivity doesn't confirm DNS resolution is functioning at all.","A local loopback ping doesn't reach or confirm anything about a remote server's status."]},{"id":267,"question":"A training handout says an interface uses 255.255.255.128. Which prefix is that?","options":["/25.","/24.","/26.","/23."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"255.255.255.128 corresponds to /25. This splits a /24 into two equal halves.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["255.255.255.128 corresponds to /25. This splits a /24 into two equal halves.","/24 corresponds to mask 255.255.255.0, not 255.255.255.128.","/26 corresponds to mask 255.255.255.192, not 255.255.255.128.","/23 corresponds to mask 255.255.254.0, not 255.255.255.128."]},{"id":268,"question":"A PC is configured with 192.168.10.25/24 and gateway 192.168.20.1. Why is that likely a problem?","options":["The gateway should normally be in the same subnet as the host.","The gateway must always use a public IP address.","The gateway must match the host IP exactly.","The gateway should be the broadcast address."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A host typically uses a default gateway that is on the same local subnet so it can reach the router directly.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["A host typically uses a default gateway that is on the same local subnet so it can reach the router directly.","A gateway can be a private address; it doesn't have to be public.","The gateway address is a separate device from the host and doesn't need to match the host's IP exactly.","The gateway is a specific router interface address, not the subnet's broadcast address."]},{"id":269,"question":"A junior technician asks for the main reason subnetting is used in business networks. Which answer is best?","options":["To divide networks into smaller, more manageable segments.","To replace all existing network switches with simpler hub devices","To completely eliminate the need for any routing between networks","To make every single device's IP address publicly routable"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Subnetting helps segment networks, reduce broadcast domains, and organize addressing more efficiently.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 4 .html","optionExplanations":["Subnetting helps segment networks, reduce broadcast domains, and organize addressing more efficiently.","Subnetting doesn't replace switches with hubs; those are separate hardware choices.","Subnetting organizes IP addressing; it doesn't eliminate the need for routing between subnets.","Subnetting is about internal address organization, not making every address publicly routable."]},{"id":270,"question":"A branch office adds a new remote subnet, and the network team wants routers to learn the path automatically instead of updating each route by hand. Which approach best fits that goal?","options":["Dynamic routing.","Static routing.","Port mirroring.","NAT overload."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Dynamic routing protocols learn and adjust routes automatically as the network changes.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Dynamic routing protocols learn and adjust routes automatically as the network changes.","Static routing requires manually configuring and updating each route by hand, the opposite of automatic learning.","Port mirroring copies traffic for monitoring, unrelated to learning routing paths.","NAT overload translates addresses for outbound traffic, unrelated to learning network routes."]},{"id":271,"question":"A small network uses a simple routing protocol that chooses paths by counting how many routers a packet crosses. Which protocol fits that description best?","options":["RIP.","OSPF.","BGP.","802.1Q."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Routing Information Protocol (RIP) is a distance-vector routing protocol that uses hop count as its metric.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Routing Information Protocol (RIP) is a distance-vector routing protocol that uses hop count as its metric.","OSPF is a link-state protocol using cost/bandwidth metrics, not simple hop counting.","BGP is a path-vector protocol for exchanging routes between autonomous systems, not simple hop-count routing.","802.1Q is a VLAN tagging standard, not a routing protocol at all."]},{"id":272,"question":"A technician is reviewing a router that has an interface directly connected to 192.168.10.0/24. Which route source is normally most preferred for that network?","options":["Directly connected route.","Static default route.","RIP-learned route.","BGP-learned route."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A directly connected network has the best administrative distance and is preferred over learned alternatives.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["A directly connected network has the best administrative distance and is preferred over learned alternatives.","A static default route has a higher administrative distance than a directly connected network.","A RIP-learned route has a much higher administrative distance than a directly connected network.","A BGP-learned route also has a much higher administrative distance than a directly connected network."]},{"id":273,"question":"An enterprise wants an interior routing protocol that builds a topology map and supports areas for large internal networks. Which protocol is the best match?","options":["OSPF.","RIP.","ARP.","SMTP."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) is a link-state routing protocol that supports hierarchical design with areas.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) is a link-state routing protocol that supports hierarchical design with areas.","RIP is a simple distance-vector protocol using hop count, without OSPF's topology map and areas.","ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses; it isn't a routing protocol at all.","SMTP is an email transport protocol, unrelated to interior routing."]},{"id":274,"question":"A service provider router exchanges routes with other autonomous systems on the internet. Which routing protocol is designed for that role?","options":["BGP.","OSPF.","EIGRP.","RSTP."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) is the path-vector protocol used to exchange routes between autonomous systems.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) is the path-vector protocol used to exchange routes between autonomous systems.","OSPF is an interior routing protocol for a single organization's network, not exchanging routes between autonomous systems.","EIGRP is also an interior routing protocol, not designed for inter-AS route exchange on the internet.","RSTP is a Layer 2 loop-prevention protocol, not a routing protocol for exchanging routes between networks."]},{"id":275,"question":"A host needs to send traffic to a destination that is not listed in the router table as a specific match. Which route does the router use as the gateway of last resort?","options":["Default route.","Host route.","Connected route.","Floating route."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A default route is used when no more specific route matches the destination network.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["A default route is used when no more specific route matches the destination network.","A host route is a very specific /32 route, not the general fallback for unmatched destinations.","A connected route applies to directly attached networks, not unmatched remote destinations.","A floating route is a backup route with a higher administrative distance, not specifically the gateway-of-last-resort concept itself."]},{"id":276,"question":"A switch begins forwarding a frame as soon as it reads the destination MAC address, without waiting for the full frame. Which switching method is being used?","options":["Cut-through switching.","Store-and-forward switching.","Circuit switching.","Packet shaping."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Cut-through switching forwards early after reading the destination Media Access Control (MAC) field.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Cut-through switching forwards early after reading the destination Media Access Control (MAC) field.","Store-and-forward waits for the entire frame before forwarding, the opposite of forwarding immediately after the destination MAC.","Circuit switching establishes a dedicated path for a whole session, unrelated to frame-by-frame Ethernet switching.","Packet shaping manages traffic flow/prioritization, not how quickly a switch begins forwarding a frame."]},{"id":277,"question":"A switch in a noisy environment must verify the FCS before sending frames onward. Which switching method best fits this requirement?","options":["Store-and-forward switching.","Cut-through switching.","Fast reroute.","Source routing."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Store-and-forward switching buffers the full frame and checks for errors before forwarding.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Store-and-forward switching buffers the full frame and checks for errors before forwarding.","Cut-through switching forwards before the full frame (and its FCS) is received, the opposite of checking for errors first.","\"Fast reroute\" refers to rerouting around failures, not a frame-forwarding method.","Source routing lets the sender specify a path, unrelated to a switch checking the FCS before forwarding."]},{"id":278,"question":"A campus network has redundant switch links, and users start seeing broadcast storms after a misconfiguration. Which protocol is meant to prevent this Layer 2 problem?","options":["STP.","HSRP.","RIP.","NTP."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Spanning Tree Protocol blocks redundant Layer 2 paths to prevent switching loops.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Spanning Tree Protocol blocks redundant Layer 2 paths to prevent switching loops.","HSRP provides gateway redundancy, not Layer 2 loop prevention.","RIP is a routing protocol, unrelated to preventing Layer 2 switching loops.","NTP synchronizes time, unrelated to preventing broadcast storms from switching loops."]},{"id":279,"question":"A network engineer wants faster recovery from a failed switch link than legacy STP typically provides. Which standard should be used?","options":["RSTP.","VTP.","LACP.","PAT."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (RSTP) converges faster than traditional Spanning Tree Protocol (STP).","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (RSTP) converges faster than traditional Spanning Tree Protocol (STP).","VTP synchronizes VLAN database information, not link failure recovery speed.","LACP bundles multiple physical links into one logical link, not specifically faster STP-style convergence.","PAT translates addresses/ports for outbound traffic, unrelated to switch link failure recovery."]},{"id":280,"question":"Two switches must carry traffic for several VLANs across one physical uplink. Which feature should be configured on that link?","options":["802.1Q trunking.","Port security.","Loopback mode.","APIPA."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An IEEE 802.1Q trunk tags frames so multiple Virtual Local Area Networks (VLANs) can share the same physical link.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.3","objective":"Network Service Issues","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["An IEEE 802.1Q trunk tags frames so multiple Virtual Local Area Networks (VLANs) can share the same physical link.","Port security restricts which MAC addresses can use a port, unrelated to carrying multiple VLANs.","Loopback mode is a diagnostic testing mode, not a way to carry multiple VLANs across a link.","APIPA is a self-assigned IP addressing fallback, unrelated to VLAN trunking."]},{"id":281,"question":"A user device is connected to a normal office switchport and should belong to only one VLAN with untagged traffic. What kind of switchport is that?","options":["Access port.","Trunk port.","Routed port.","Mirror port."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An access port carries untagged traffic for a single Virtual Local Area Network (VLAN).","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["An access port carries untagged traffic for a single Virtual Local Area Network (VLAN).","A trunk port carries multiple VLANs tagged, not a single untagged VLAN.","A routed port operates at Layer 3 without VLAN switching behavior, not a single-VLAN access port.","A mirror port copies traffic for monitoring, unrelated to normal single-VLAN device connectivity."]},{"id":282,"question":"Finance users in VLAN 20 need to reach servers in VLAN 30. Which device or function is required for that communication?","options":["Inter-VLAN routing on a router or Layer 3 switch.","A Layer 1 hub between the VLANs.","A longer trunk cable.","A different STP priority only."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Traffic between Virtual Local Area Networks (VLANs) requires Layer 3 routing, either on a router or a multilayer switch.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Traffic between Virtual Local Area Networks (VLANs) requires Layer 3 routing, either on a router or a multilayer switch.","A hub operates at Layer 1 and doesn't provide the Layer 3 routing needed between VLANs.","A longer trunk cable doesn't add routing capability between VLANs.","Changing STP priority affects Layer 2 loop prevention, not inter-VLAN Layer 3 routing."]},{"id":283,"question":"A technician asks what a routing table actually tells a router. Which answer is best?","options":["Which next hop or exit interface to use for a destination network.","Which specific MAC addresses are allowed to be learned on each individual switch port","Which VLAN name has been assigned to each switch in the network","Which specific DNS server is used to resolve local hostnames"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A routing table lists destination networks and the next hop or exit interface used to reach them.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["A routing table lists destination networks and the next hop or exit interface used to reach them.","Learning which MAC addresses are allowed per port describes port security, not routing table content.","VLAN naming is a switch configuration detail, not something stored in a router's routing table.","DNS server assignment is a separate network service, not information found in a routing table."]},{"id":284,"question":"A network team wants routes to remain fixed until an administrator changes them manually. Which type of route should they use?","options":["Static route.","Dynamic route.","Connected route.","Default learned route."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A static route is manually configured and stays in place until it is changed or removed.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["A static route is manually configured and stays in place until it is changed or removed.","A dynamic route updates automatically as the network changes, not staying fixed until manually changed.","A connected route is automatically created for directly attached networks, not manually entered like a static route.","\"Default learned route\" implies a dynamically learned route, not one fixed until manual administrator changes."]},{"id":285,"question":"Why do many organizations choose dynamic routing instead of building large networks entirely with static routes?","options":["It adapts automatically when topology changes occur.","It eliminates the need for IP addressing.","It prevents every routing loop by default.","It turns Layer 2 switches into routers."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Dynamic routing protocols can learn and update paths automatically when the network changes.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Dynamic routing protocols can learn and update paths automatically when the network changes.","Dynamic routing doesn't eliminate IP addressing; addressing is still required regardless of routing method.","Dynamic routing protocols can still experience loops without proper design; it doesn't prevent all loops by default.","Dynamic routing runs on routers (or Layer 3 switches); it doesn't turn basic Layer 2 switches into routers."]},{"id":286,"question":"An engineer mentions a routing protocol that uses TCP port 179. Which protocol is being discussed?","options":["BGP.","RIP.","OSPF.","ICMP."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 179 for peer sessions.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 179 for peer sessions.","RIP uses UDP, not TCP port 179.","OSPF runs directly over IP (protocol 89), not TCP port 179.","ICMP is a network diagnostic protocol, not a TCP-based routing protocol using port 179."]},{"id":287,"question":"A company creates separate logical networks for voice devices, printers, and employee PCs on the same physical switch infrastructure. What technology is being used?","options":["VLANs.","NAT pools.","Loopback interfaces.","Port channels."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Virtual Local Area Networks (VLANs) logically segment a Layer 2 network into separate broadcast domains.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Virtual Local Area Networks (VLANs) logically segment a Layer 2 network into separate broadcast domains.","NAT pools translate addresses for outbound traffic, unrelated to segmenting devices by function.","Loopback interfaces are virtual interfaces on a device, unrelated to segmenting a physical switch into logical networks.","Port channels bundle physical links together, unrelated to creating separate logical broadcast domains."]},{"id":288,"question":"A switch forwards Ethernet frames by learning which hardware addresses live on which ports. Which table stores that information?","options":["MAC address table.","Routing table.","ARP cache.","DNS zone file."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A switch Media Access Control (MAC) address table maps learned MAC addresses to specific switch ports.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["A switch Media Access Control (MAC) address table maps learned MAC addresses to specific switch ports.","A routing table stores IP network paths, not MAC-to-port mappings.","An ARP cache maps IP addresses to MAC addresses, not MAC addresses to switch ports.","A DNS zone file stores name-to-IP mappings, unrelated to switch port learning."]},{"id":289,"question":"A security policy says a public lobby switchport should learn only one approved device MAC address. Which switch feature supports that requirement?","options":["Port security.","Trunking.","Spanning tree.","CDP."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Port security can restrict how many Media Access Control (MAC) addresses are allowed on a port and which ones are accepted.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Port security can restrict how many Media Access Control (MAC) addresses are allowed on a port and which ones are accepted.","Trunking carries multiple VLANs across a link, unrelated to restricting learned MAC addresses.","Spanning tree prevents Layer 2 loops, unrelated to limiting which MAC addresses a port learns.","CDP shares device information between neighboring Cisco devices, unrelated to restricting MAC addresses on a port."]},{"id":290,"question":"A user can reach local devices on the same subnet but cannot reach any remote network. Which host setting should be checked first?","options":["Default gateway.","Subnet mask classful default.","VLAN name.","Switch port speed only."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The default gateway is what a host uses to send traffic to remote networks.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["The default gateway is what a host uses to send traffic to remote networks.","A classful subnet mask default doesn't determine whether remote traffic can be reached at all.","VLAN name is a label for administrative reference, unrelated to reaching remote networks.","Switch port speed affects link performance, not whether remote networks are reachable at all."]},{"id":291,"question":"An engineer wants to bundle several physical switch links into one logical connection for higher throughput and redundancy. Which technology should be configured?","options":["Link aggregation with LACP.","Port mirroring.","Private VLANs.","Split horizon."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Link Aggregation Control Protocol (LACP) and similar link aggregation methods combine multiple physical links into one logical port channel for resiliency and bandwidth.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Link Aggregation Control Protocol (LACP) and similar link aggregation methods combine multiple physical links into one logical port channel for resiliency and bandwidth.","Port mirroring copies traffic for monitoring, unrelated to combining multiple links into one logical connection.","Private VLANs restrict communication within a VLAN, unrelated to bundling physical links.","Split horizon is a routing loop-prevention technique, unrelated to combining switch links."]},{"id":292,"question":"Several Cisco switches need to share VLAN information automatically across their switching domain. Which protocol is associated with that task?","options":["VTP.","LLDP.","SNMP.","HSRP."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"VLAN Trunking Protocol (VTP) is a Cisco protocol used to distribute Virtual Local Area Network (VLAN) information among switches.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["VLAN Trunking Protocol (VTP) is a Cisco protocol used to distribute Virtual Local Area Network (VLAN) information among switches.","LLDP shares device/neighbor information generically, not specifically VLAN database synchronization.","SNMP is used for general device monitoring/management, not specifically distributing VLAN configuration.","HSRP provides gateway redundancy, unrelated to VLAN information sharing between switches."]},{"id":293,"question":"A protocol builds a full view of the network and calculates best paths from that topology map instead of relying only on periodic neighbor updates. What type of routing protocol is this?","options":["Link-state.","Distance-vector.","Path-vector.","Static-only."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Link-state protocols build a topology map and then calculate optimal paths.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Link-state protocols build a topology map and then calculate optimal paths.","Distance-vector protocols rely on periodic neighbor updates rather than a full topology map.","Path-vector protocols track path information for route selection between autonomous systems, not detailed topology mapping within one network.","\"Static-only\" refers to manually configured routes, not a protocol that calculates paths dynamically at all."]},{"id":294,"question":"A technician wants to describe what makes a router different from a Layer 2 switch. Which statement is most accurate?","options":["A router forwards traffic between IP networks using Layer 3 addressing.","A router forwards frames using MAC addresses inside one VLAN only.","A router repeats electrical signals to extend cable length.","A router tags multiple VLANs on a trunk by itself without routing."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Routers operate at Layer 3 and forward packets between different IP networks.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Routers operate at Layer 3 and forward packets between different IP networks.","This describes switch behavior (MAC-based forwarding within one VLAN), not what makes a router distinct.","Repeating electrical signals describes a physical-layer repeater, not routing behavior.","Tagging VLANs on a trunk without routing describes switch trunking behavior, not what a router specifically does."]},{"id":295,"question":"A switchport is connected to another switch and must carry voice, data, and management VLANs at the same time. Which port type should be used?","options":["Trunk port.","Access port.","Disabled port.","Console port."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A trunk port is used when multiple VLANs must cross the same physical connection.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["A trunk port is used when multiple VLANs must cross the same physical connection.","An access port only carries a single untagged VLAN, not multiple VLANs simultaneously.","A disabled port passes no traffic at all, the opposite of carrying multiple VLANs.","A console port provides local management access, unrelated to carrying VLAN traffic between switches."]},{"id":296,"question":"A network admin is comparing OSPF and RIP. Which statement best describes OSPF in that comparison?","options":["It is a link-state protocol that scales better in larger internal networks.","It is a distance-vector protocol limited mainly by hop count.","It is the main protocol used between internet autonomous systems.","It is a switching protocol that prevents loops on trunks."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) is a link-state Interior Gateway Protocol (IGP) that generally scales better than Routing Information Protocol (RIP) in larger enterprise environments.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) is a link-state Interior Gateway Protocol (IGP) that generally scales better than Routing Information Protocol (RIP) in larger enterprise environments.","This describes RIP itself (distance-vector, hop-count limited), the opposite comparison point being asked about OSPF.","BGP, not OSPF, is the protocol used between internet autonomous systems.","OSPF is a routing protocol, not a Layer 2 switching loop-prevention protocol."]},{"id":297,"question":"A user plugs into a switch and causes a loop by connecting two wall jacks together in the same VLAN. What symptom is most likely to appear first?","options":["Broadcast storm and unstable switching.","Immediate DNS zone corruption.","Loss of NAT translations on the firewall.","A BGP peer reset on the edge router."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Layer 2 loops commonly lead to broadcast storms, MAC table instability, and network slowdown.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Layer 2 loops commonly lead to broadcast storms, MAC table instability, and network slowdown.","DNS zone data isn't affected by a Layer 2 switching loop.","NAT translations on a firewall aren't directly disrupted by a local switching loop.","A BGP peer reset on an edge router is unrelated to a local Layer 2 loop within one VLAN."]},{"id":298,"question":"An engineer says EIGRP is often described as an advanced distance-vector or hybrid routing protocol. What family of protocol is being referenced?","options":["Dynamic routing protocol.","VLAN trunking protocol.","Wireless roaming protocol.","Time synchronization protocol."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP) is a dynamic routing protocol and is often described as an advanced distance-vector or hybrid approach.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP) is a dynamic routing protocol and is often described as an advanced distance-vector or hybrid approach.","VLAN trunking protocol is a different Cisco protocol (VTP) for VLAN sync, not what EIGRP is classified as.","Wireless roaming protocols manage Wi-Fi client handoff, unrelated to EIGRP's routing function.","Time synchronization protocols (like NTP) synchronize clocks, unrelated to EIGRP's routing function."]},{"id":299,"question":"A network design calls for logical separation of departments at Layer 2 and controlled communication between them at Layer 3. Which combination best matches that design?","options":["VLANs with inter-VLAN routing.","Hubs with repeaters.","Proxies with DHCP relays.","NAT with port mirroring."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Virtual Local Area Networks (VLANs) create Layer 2 separation, and inter-VLAN routing enables controlled traffic flow between those VLANs.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 5 .html","optionExplanations":["Virtual Local Area Networks (VLANs) create Layer 2 separation, and inter-VLAN routing enables controlled traffic flow between those VLANs.","Hubs and repeaters operate at Layer 1 without any VLAN segmentation or routing capability.","Proxies and DHCP relays serve different functions (web proxying, DHCP forwarding), not Layer 2/3 department segmentation.","NAT and port mirroring serve address translation and traffic monitoring, not department-level segmentation and controlled routing."]},{"id":300,"question":"A help desk technician notices several new workstations received IP addresses automatically after being connected to the office network. Which service most likely provided those addresses?","options":["Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP).","Domain Name System (DNS).","Network Time Protocol (NTP).","Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP)."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) automatically assigns IP addresses and other network settings such as subnet mask, default gateway, and DNS server information.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) automatically assigns IP addresses and other network settings such as subnet mask, default gateway, and DNS server information.","DNS resolves names to addresses, not assigning IP configuration automatically.","NTP synchronizes time, unrelated to automatic IP address assignment.","TFTP transfers files, unrelated to automatic IP address assignment."]},{"id":301,"question":"A user types a website name into a browser, and the system needs to find the matching IPv4 address. Which record type is most directly used for that lookup?","options":["A record.","AAAA record.","Pointer (PTR) record.","Canonical Name (CNAME) record."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An A record maps a hostname to an Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) address. An AAAA record is used for Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) addresses.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["An A record maps a hostname to an Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) address. An AAAA record is used for Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) addresses.","An AAAA record maps a hostname to an IPv6 address, not IPv4.","A PTR record performs reverse lookup (IP to name), not forward lookup (name to IPv4 address).","A CNAME record is an alias pointing to another hostname, not directly to an IPv4 address."]},{"id":302,"question":"A laptop knows the IPv4 address of a printer on the same subnet but still needs the hardware address before sending the frame. Which protocol handles that step?","options":["Address Resolution Protocol (ARP).","Domain Name System (DNS).","Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP).","Network Address Translation (NAT)."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) resolves an IPv4 address to a Media Access Control (MAC) address on the local network segment.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) resolves an IPv4 address to a Media Access Control (MAC) address on the local network segment.","DNS resolves hostnames to IP addresses, not IP addresses to MAC addresses.","ICMP handles diagnostic messaging like ping, not address-to-MAC resolution.","NAT translates addresses for routing between networks, not resolving MAC addresses locally."]},{"id":303,"question":"Several switches and routers show mismatched timestamps in the logs, making troubleshooting difficult. Which service should be checked first?","options":["Network Time Protocol (NTP).","Domain Name System (DNS).","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP).","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Network Time Protocol (NTP) synchronizes device clocks so logs and alerts line up correctly across the network.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Network Time Protocol (NTP) synchronizes device clocks so logs and alerts line up correctly across the network.","DNS resolves names to addresses, unrelated to synchronizing device clocks.","DHCP assigns IP configuration, unrelated to clock synchronization.","SNMP is used for monitoring/management data, not specifically synchronizing time across devices."]},{"id":304,"question":"A small office uses private IPv4 addressing internally but still reaches the internet through one public address on the edge device. Which service makes that possible?","options":["Network Address Translation (NAT).","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP).","Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP).","Domain Name System (DNS)."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Network Address Translation (NAT) translates private addresses to a public address so internal hosts can communicate externally.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Network Address Translation (NAT) translates private addresses to a public address so internal hosts can communicate externally.","ARP resolves IP to MAC addresses locally, unrelated to translating private addresses for internet access.","ICMP handles diagnostic messaging, unrelated to address translation.","DNS resolves names to addresses, unrelated to translating private to public addresses."]},{"id":305,"question":"A technician runs ping to verify whether a remote device responds across the network. Which protocol is ping using?","options":["Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP).","Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).","User Datagram Protocol (UDP).","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Ping uses Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) Echo Request and Echo Reply messages to test reachability.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Ping uses Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) Echo Request and Echo Reply messages to test reachability.","TCP is a connection-oriented transport protocol, not what ping specifically uses for its echo messages.","UDP is a connectionless transport protocol, not what ping specifically uses for its echo messages.","SNMP is used for device monitoring/management, not connectivity testing via ping."]},{"id":306,"question":"A client has just joined a network and is trying to locate a server that can lease it an address. Which Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol message is sent first?","options":["DHCPDISCOVER.","DHCPOFFER.","DHCPREQUEST.","DHCPACK."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The first message is DHCPDISCOVER, which is usually broadcast so the client can find available Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol servers.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["The first message is DHCPDISCOVER, which is usually broadcast so the client can find available Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol servers.","DHCPOFFER is the server's response after receiving a DISCOVER, not the client's first message.","DHCPREQUEST comes after the client receives an offer, not as the very first message.","DHCPACK is the server's final acknowledgment, occurring last in the exchange, not first."]},{"id":307,"question":"An administrator is performing a reverse lookup to identify the hostname associated with an IP address. Which Domain Name System record is used?","options":["Pointer (PTR) record.","A record.","Mail Exchange (MX) record.","Canonical Name (CNAME) record."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A Pointer (PTR) record maps an IP address back to a hostname for reverse Domain Name System lookups.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["A Pointer (PTR) record maps an IP address back to a hostname for reverse Domain Name System lookups.","An A record maps a hostname to an IPv4 address (forward lookup), not IP-to-hostname reverse lookup.","An MX record identifies mail servers for a domain, unrelated to reverse IP lookups.","A CNAME record is an alias to another hostname, not a reverse-lookup record type."]},{"id":308,"question":"A network engineer needs a lightweight method to transfer a boot image to a device during startup, without the overhead of a full-featured file transfer service. Which protocol is the best fit?","options":["Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP).","File Transfer Protocol (FTP).","SSH File Transfer Protocol (SFTP).","Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure (HTTPS)."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) is a simple User Datagram Protocol (UDP)-based transfer service often used for boot files and device configurations.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) is a simple User Datagram Protocol (UDP)-based transfer service often used for boot files and device configurations.","FTP is a more full-featured file transfer protocol with more overhead than the lightweight TFTP.","SFTP adds encryption and more overhead, not the lightweight simplicity described.","HTTPS is a general secure web protocol, not the lightweight boot-file transfer method traditionally used here."]},{"id":309,"question":"A network operations team wants to poll routers and switches and read management data from their Management Information Bases. Which protocol should be used?","options":["Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).","Domain Name System (DNS).","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP).","Network Time Protocol (NTP)."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) is used to monitor and manage devices, often by reading values from a Management Information Base (MIB).","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) is used to monitor and manage devices, often by reading values from a Management Information Base (MIB).","DNS resolves names to addresses, unrelated to polling device management data.","DHCP assigns IP configuration, unrelated to polling MIB data.","NTP synchronizes time, unrelated to polling device management information."]},{"id":310,"question":"A security analyst sees encrypted web sessions leaving the network and wants to verify the standard destination port. Which port is normally used by Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure?","options":["443.","80.","21.","110."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure (HTTPS) normally uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 443.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure (HTTPS) normally uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 443.","Port 80 is used by regular unencrypted HTTP, not HTTPS.","Port 21 is used by FTP's control channel, not HTTPS.","Port 110 is used by POP3 for email retrieval, not HTTPS."]},{"id":311,"question":"A web server is intentionally configured to accept standard unencrypted browser traffic. Which port should the firewall allow for Hypertext Transfer Protocol?","options":["80.","443.","8080.","20."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 80 by default.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 80 by default.","Port 443 is used by encrypted HTTPS, not unencrypted HTTP.","Port 8080 is a common alternate web port, not the standard default HTTP port.","Port 20 is used by FTP's data channel, not HTTP."]},{"id":312,"question":"A workstation can reach sites by IP address but not by name. A technician suspects the port for name resolution queries is blocked. Which port should be checked first?","options":["53.","25.","110.","143."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Domain Name System (DNS) commonly uses port 53 for queries, using User Datagram Protocol (UDP) in many cases and Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) when needed.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Domain Name System (DNS) commonly uses port 53 for queries, using User Datagram Protocol (UDP) in many cases and Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) when needed.","Port 25 is used by SMTP for email, not DNS queries.","Port 110 is used by POP3 for email retrieval, not DNS queries.","Port 143 is used by IMAP for email access, not DNS queries."]},{"id":313,"question":"An administrator wants encrypted command-line remote access to a Linux server instead of using Telnet. Which port should be allowed for Secure Shell?","options":["22.","23.","161.","3389."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Secure Shell (SSH) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 22 and provides encrypted remote administration.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Secure Shell (SSH) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 22 and provides encrypted remote administration.","Port 23 is used by unencrypted Telnet, the insecure alternative SSH replaces.","Port 161 is used by SNMP, not SSH.","Port 3389 is used by RDP for graphical remote desktop, not SSH command-line access."]},{"id":314,"question":"A legacy device still requires plaintext terminal access over the network. Which port is associated with Telnet?","options":["23.","22.","80.","110."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Telnet uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 23, but it is considered insecure because it does not encrypt traffic.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Telnet uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 23, but it is considered insecure because it does not encrypt traffic.","Port 22 is used by encrypted SSH, not plaintext Telnet.","Port 80 is used by HTTP web traffic, not Telnet.","Port 110 is used by POP3 email retrieval, not Telnet."]},{"id":315,"question":"A mail relay is forwarding outbound email between servers. Which standard port is most closely associated with Simple Mail Transfer Protocol?","options":["25.","110.","143.","587."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) commonly uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 25 for server-to-server email transfer.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) commonly uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 25 for server-to-server email transfer.","Port 110 is used by POP3 for retrieving mail, not SMTP for sending it.","Port 143 is used by IMAP for mailbox access, not SMTP relay.","Port 587 is commonly used for authenticated mail submission from clients, not traditional server-to-server SMTP relay described here."]},{"id":316,"question":"A user downloads messages from a mailbox to a local client and often removes them from the server afterward. Which protocol and port best match that behavior?","options":["Post Office Protocol version 3 (POP3) on port 110.","Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP) on port 143.","Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) on port 25.","Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) on port 389."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Post Office Protocol version 3 (POP3) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 110 and is associated with downloading mail to a local client.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Post Office Protocol version 3 (POP3) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 110 and is associated with downloading mail to a local client.","IMAP on port 143 typically leaves messages on the server rather than removing them after download.","SMTP on port 25 is used for sending mail between servers, not downloading messages to a client.","LDAP on port 389 is a directory access protocol, unrelated to retrieving email messages."]},{"id":317,"question":"A user needs to keep email synchronized across a laptop and phone while leaving messages stored on the server. Which protocol and port best fit that need?","options":["Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP) on port 143.","Post Office Protocol version 3 (POP3) on port 110.","Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) on port 25.","Secure Shell (SSH) on port 22."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 143 and is designed for server-based mail access across multiple devices.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 143 and is designed for server-based mail access across multiple devices.","POP3 on port 110 typically downloads and removes messages from the server, not keeping them synced across devices.","SMTP on port 25 is used for sending mail between servers, not client-side synchronized access.","SSH on port 22 provides remote command-line access, unrelated to email synchronization."]},{"id":318,"question":"A support tech must remotely control a Windows workstation through the graphical desktop interface. Which port is usually involved for Remote Desktop Protocol?","options":["3389.","5900.","22.","443."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 3389 by default.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 3389 by default.","Port 5900 is associated with VNC, a different remote-desktop technology than RDP.","Port 22 is used by SSH for command-line access, not RDP's graphical desktop.","Port 443 is used by HTTPS, not RDP."]},{"id":319,"question":"A firewall rule must allow the control channel for File Transfer Protocol sessions. Which port is the standard match?","options":["21.","20.","69.","22."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"File Transfer Protocol (FTP) traditionally uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 21 for the control channel.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["File Transfer Protocol (FTP) traditionally uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 21 for the control channel.","Port 20 is FTP's data channel, not the control channel being asked about.","Port 69 is used by TFTP, a different, simpler file transfer protocol.","Port 22 is used by SSH, not FTP's control channel."]},{"id":320,"question":"An engineer is reviewing an older File Transfer Protocol deployment and needs to identify the traditional data channel port. Which port is correct?","options":["20.","21.","69.","110."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"In traditional active File Transfer Protocol (FTP), port 20 is used for the data channel and port 21 is used for the control channel.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["In traditional active File Transfer Protocol (FTP), port 20 is used for the data channel and port 21 is used for the control channel.","Port 21 is FTP's control channel, not the data channel being asked about.","Port 69 is used by TFTP, a different, simpler file transfer protocol.","Port 110 is used by POP3 for email, unrelated to FTP's data channel."]},{"id":321,"question":"A technician is imaging a device that boots from the network using a very small file transfer service. Which port is associated with Trivial File Transfer Protocol?","options":["69.","20.","21.","161."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) uses User Datagram Protocol (UDP) port 69.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Correct — TFTP uses UDP port 69 for its small, connectionless file transfers, which is why it is used for network device booting.","Wrong — port 20 is used for FTP data transfer, not TFTP.","Wrong — port 21 is the FTP control port, not TFTP.","Wrong — port 161 is used by SNMP for management queries, not TFTP."]},{"id":322,"question":"A monitoring platform is polling a managed switch for counters and interface statistics. Which port is typically used by Simple Network Management Protocol queries?","options":["161.","162.","23.","514."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) usually uses User Datagram Protocol (UDP) port 161 for queries and management requests.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Correct — SNMP queries and management requests are sent to UDP port 161 on the managed device.","Wrong — port 162 is used for SNMP traps sent from the device, not for queries sent to it.","Wrong — port 23 is used by Telnet, an unrelated remote-access protocol.","Wrong — port 514 is used by Syslog, not SNMP."]},{"id":323,"question":"A managed device sends an unsolicited alert to the monitoring server after an interface fails. Which port is associated with a Simple Network Management Protocol trap?","options":["162.","161.","443.","514."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) trap messages are commonly sent to User Datagram Protocol (UDP) port 162.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Correct — SNMP trap messages, which are unsolicited alerts, are sent to UDP port 162 on the management station.","Wrong — port 161 is used for SNMP queries sent to the device, not traps sent from it.","Wrong — port 443 is used for HTTPS, unrelated to SNMP traps.","Wrong — port 514 is used by Syslog, a separate logging protocol."]},{"id":324,"question":"An administrator needs to query a directory service for users and groups using the standard unencrypted port. Which port aligns with Lightweight Directory Access Protocol?","options":["389.","636.","88.","53."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) commonly uses port 389. Secure LDAP traffic typically uses a different port.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Correct — LDAP uses TCP port 389 for standard, unencrypted directory queries.","Wrong — port 636 is used by LDAPS, the encrypted version of LDAP.","Wrong — port 88 is used by Kerberos for authentication, not LDAP.","Wrong — port 53 is used by DNS, not directory services."]},{"id":325,"question":"A security policy requires encrypted directory lookups to Active Directory. Which port should be opened for Lightweight Directory Access Protocol Secure?","options":["636.","389.","443.","22."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Lightweight Directory Access Protocol Secure (LDAPS) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 636 for encrypted directory communication.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Correct — LDAPS uses TCP port 636 to provide encrypted directory lookups.","Wrong — port 389 is the standard, unencrypted LDAP port.","Wrong — port 443 is used for general HTTPS traffic, not specifically LDAPS.","Wrong — port 22 is used by SSH, unrelated to directory services."]},{"id":326,"question":"A Windows domain environment is failing authentication because a required ticket-based service is blocked at the firewall. Which port should be verified for Kerberos?","options":["88.","389.","110.","514."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Kerberos commonly uses port 88 over Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or User Datagram Protocol (UDP) for authentication.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Correct — Kerberos uses port 88 for its ticket-based authentication exchanges.","Wrong — port 389 is used by LDAP for directory queries, not Kerberos tickets.","Wrong — port 110 is used by POP3 for retrieving email, unrelated to authentication tickets.","Wrong — port 514 is used by Syslog, not Kerberos."]},{"id":327,"question":"A log server is receiving event messages from routers, switches, and firewalls. Which port is traditionally used by Syslog?","options":["514.","161.","69.","23."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Syslog traditionally uses User Datagram Protocol (UDP) port 514 for centralized logging.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Correct — Syslog traditionally uses UDP port 514 to send log messages to a central collector.","Wrong — port 161 is used by SNMP for management queries, not Syslog.","Wrong — port 69 is used by TFTP for file transfers, not logging.","Wrong — port 23 is used by Telnet, an unrelated remote-access protocol."]},{"id":328,"question":"A database administrator is troubleshooting connectivity to a MySQL server. Which port is the default one to check?","options":["3306.","1433.","1521.","8080."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"MySQL commonly uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 3306 by default.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Correct — MySQL listens on TCP port 3306 by default.","Wrong — port 1433 is the default port for Microsoft SQL Server, not MySQL.","Wrong — port 1521 is the default port for Oracle databases, not MySQL.","Wrong — port 8080 is a common alternate web/proxy port, not a database port."]},{"id":329,"question":"A line-of-business application cannot reach its Microsoft database backend after a firewall change. Which destination port is the usual default for Microsoft SQL Server?","options":["1433.","3306.","1521.","3389."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Microsoft SQL Server commonly uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 1433 by default.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 6 .html","optionExplanations":["Correct — Microsoft SQL Server listens on TCP port 1433 by default.","Wrong — port 3306 is the default port for MySQL, not SQL Server.","Wrong — port 1521 is the default port for Oracle databases, not SQL Server.","Wrong — port 3389 is used by RDP for remote desktop sessions, not database connections."]},{"id":330,"question":"Which protocol is primarily responsible for translating human-readable hostnames into IP addresses on a TCP/IP network?","options":["DHCP.","DNS.","NTP.","SNMP."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Domain Name System (DNS) resolves hostnames such as www.example.com into Internet Protocol (IP) addresses so devices can find each other on a network.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) automatically assigns IP settings to clients; it does not resolve names to addresses.","Domain Name System (DNS) is correct because it translates hostnames into IP addresses.","Network Time Protocol (NTP) synchronizes time on network devices; it does not perform name resolution.","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) is used for monitoring and management, not hostname resolution."]},{"id":331,"question":"A network administrator wants clients to automatically receive IP addresses, subnet masks, default gateways, and DNS server information. Which service should be configured?","options":["DNS.","RADIUS.","DHCP.","LDAP."],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) automatically leases IP configuration details such as IP address, subnet mask, default gateway, and Domain Name System (DNS) server information.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Domain Name System (DNS) resolves names to IP addresses, but it does not hand out client IP configuration.","Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) handles centralized authentication, authorization, and accounting, not address assignment.","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) is correct because it automatically provides client network settings.","Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) provides directory services and authentication lookups, not IP addressing."]},{"id":332,"question":"Which application service is most associated with providing centralized authentication, authorization, and accounting for remote access or wireless clients?","options":["RADIUS.","DNS.","NTP.","TFTP."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) is commonly used for centralized authentication, authorization, and accounting (AAA) for virtual private network (VPN), wireless, and other remote access solutions.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) is correct because it provides centralized AAA for remote and wireless access.","Domain Name System (DNS) resolves names, not user access decisions.","Network Time Protocol (NTP) keeps clocks synchronized, which helps logs and authentication systems, but it is not the AAA service itself.","Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) transfers files and configurations without authentication features."]},{"id":333,"question":"A company wants to distribute software images to many network devices using a simple, lightweight protocol that does not require authentication. Which protocol is best suited?","options":["FTP.","TFTP.","SFTP.","HTTPS."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) is a lightweight User Datagram Protocol (UDP)-based file transfer protocol commonly used for boot images and configuration files. It is simple, but it does not provide authentication or encryption.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["File Transfer Protocol (FTP) can transfer files, but it is heavier and not the classic lightweight choice for device boot images.","Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) is correct because it is simple, lightweight, and commonly used for network device image or configuration transfers.","SSH File Transfer Protocol (SFTP) is secure and encrypted, but it is not the lightweight no-authentication protocol described here.","Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure (HTTPS) is encrypted web transport, not the typical lightweight device imaging protocol in this context."]},{"id":334,"question":"Which service is used to synchronize the clocks of devices across a network to a common time source?","options":["NTP.","DNS.","DHCP.","SMTP."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Network Time Protocol (NTP) synchronizes time across network devices so logs, certificates, authentication, and scheduled tasks stay consistent.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Network Time Protocol (NTP) is correct because it synchronizes system clocks across devices.","Domain Name System (DNS) resolves names, not time.","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) assigns IP settings, not clock settings.","Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) sends email and does not synchronize device time."]},{"id":335,"question":"A security engineer wants to prevent internal users from directly accessing websites and instead have a server fetch web content on their behalf. Which service provides this functionality?","options":["Load balancer.","Proxy server.","RADIUS server.","NTP server."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A proxy server acts as an intermediary between clients and web servers. It can fetch content on behalf of users and is often used for filtering, logging, and caching.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["A load balancer distributes traffic across backend servers; it is not primarily used to fetch web content on behalf of internal users.","A proxy server is correct because it intermediates client web requests and can apply filtering or caching.","A Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) server handles authentication and accounting, not web content retrieval.","A Network Time Protocol (NTP) server provides time synchronization, not web proxy services."]},{"id":336,"question":"Which type of proxy is specifically designed to handle HTTP and HTTPS traffic for web browsing?","options":["Reverse proxy.","Transparent proxy.","Web proxy.","SOCKS proxy."],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"A web proxy is designed specifically for Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) and Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure (HTTPS) traffic and is commonly used for browsing control, caching, and content inspection.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.2","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["A reverse proxy protects or fronts servers, not end-user browsing traffic.","A transparent proxy intercepts traffic without client configuration, but it describes deployment style rather than the specific web-browsing role asked here.","A web proxy is correct because it is built to handle HTTP and HTTPS web traffic.","A SOCKS proxy can relay multiple traffic types, but it is broader and not specifically the web-focused proxy named here."]},{"id":337,"question":"Which application service is commonly used to distribute incoming client requests across multiple servers to improve availability and performance?","options":["Proxy server.","Load balancer.","DHCP relay.","NTP server."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A load balancer distributes incoming client requests across multiple backend servers to improve scalability, responsiveness, and fault tolerance.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.1","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["A proxy server intermediates requests, but balancing traffic across multiple backend servers is the core role of a load balancer.","A load balancer is correct because it spreads traffic across multiple servers.","A Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) relay forwards address-assignment requests between subnets and does not distribute application traffic.","A Network Time Protocol (NTP) server synchronizes time and is unrelated to server traffic distribution."]},{"id":338,"question":"A network team deploys a device that terminates client connections and then establishes new connections to backend servers, hiding the servers from direct client access. What is this an example of?","options":["Forward proxy.","DNS server.","Reverse proxy.","DHCP server."],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"A reverse proxy sits in front of servers, accepts client requests, and forwards them to internal backend servers while hiding those servers from direct public access.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["A forward proxy sits in front of clients, not servers.","A Domain Name System (DNS) server resolves names to addresses and does not terminate application sessions in this way.","A reverse proxy is correct because it fronts backend servers and hides them from clients.","A Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) server assigns IP settings and does not broker application sessions."]},{"id":339,"question":"Which protocol is typically used by VoIP phones to discover call managers and obtain configuration details automatically?","options":["SIP.","TFTP.","NTP.","SNMP."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Many Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) phones use Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) to download configuration files or firmware during startup.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) handles call signaling, but many phones still use a separate service such as TFTP to pull configuration files.","Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) is correct because many VoIP phones download configuration details from it during boot.","Network Time Protocol (NTP) synchronizes the phone clock but does not usually deliver the configuration files themselves.","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) monitors and manages devices rather than serving boot-time configuration in this scenario."]},{"id":340,"question":"Which protocol is most associated with setting up, modifying, and tearing down VoIP sessions between endpoints?","options":["RTP.","SIP.","NTP.","DNS."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) handles Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) signaling, including establishing, modifying, and terminating sessions. Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) carries the actual voice data.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) carries the voice media, but it does not set up or tear down the call.","Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) is correct because it manages call signaling and session control.","Network Time Protocol (NTP) handles clock synchronization, not call signaling.","Domain Name System (DNS) may help locate services, but it does not control the VoIP session lifecycle."]},{"id":341,"question":"In a VoIP deployment, which protocol is primarily responsible for carrying the actual voice payload between endpoints?","options":["SIP.","RTP.","NTP.","SNMP."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) carries the audio stream for Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) communications. Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) is used for signaling, not the media payload itself.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) sets up the call, but it does not carry the live voice stream.","Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) is correct because it transports the actual voice media.","Network Time Protocol (NTP) synchronizes time, not voice payloads.","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) monitors devices and is unrelated to carrying call audio."]},{"id":342,"question":"Which service allows a DHCP server to provide IP configuration to clients located on a different subnet?","options":["DHCP relay.","DNS forwarder.","Proxy ARP.","NAT gateway."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) relay forwards DHCP requests from one subnet to a DHCP server on another subnet so clients can still receive automatic IP configuration without a local DHCP server on every network.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) relay is correct because it forwards DHCP messages across subnet boundaries.","A Domain Name System (DNS) forwarder relays name-resolution queries, not address-assignment traffic.","Proxy Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) answers ARP requests on behalf of another host and does not relay DHCP traffic.","A Network Address Translation (NAT) gateway translates addresses for routed traffic, not DHCP discovery and lease traffic."]},{"id":343,"question":"A network administrator configures a device to translate private IP addresses to a single public IP address when accessing the internet. Which service is being used?","options":["PAT.","Proxy.","NTP.","RADIUS."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Port Address Translation (PAT), a form of Network Address Translation (NAT), maps many private IP addresses to one public IP address by using different source port numbers.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Port Address Translation (PAT) is correct because it lets many internal hosts share one public IP by tracking port numbers.","A proxy can intermediate traffic at the application layer, but it is not the standard address-translation mechanism described here.","Network Time Protocol (NTP) handles time synchronization, not address translation.","Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) handles centralized authentication and accounting, not IP translation."]},{"id":344,"question":"Which application service is commonly used to centralize user authentication for network devices such as switches, routers, and VPN concentrators?","options":["DNS.","RADIUS or TACACS+.","NTP.","TFTP."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) and Terminal Access Controller Access-Control System Plus (TACACS+) are centralized authentication, authorization, and accounting (AAA) protocols commonly used for network infrastructure administration.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Domain Name System (DNS) resolves names and is not a centralized login service for infrastructure devices.","Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) or Terminal Access Controller Access-Control System Plus (TACACS+) is correct because these are the common centralized AAA choices for device administration.","Network Time Protocol (NTP) synchronizes clocks and does not authenticate administrators.","Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) transfers files and configurations, not user logins."]},{"id":345,"question":"A company wants to ensure that internal hostnames (such as fileserver.corp.local) are resolved only inside the organization. Which service should be configured for this?","options":["Public DNS hosting.","Internal DNS server.","DHCP relay.","Reverse proxy."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"An internal Domain Name System (DNS) server can host private zones and records that are only available within the organization’s network.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Public Domain Name System (DNS) hosting would expose records externally and is not the best fit for internal-only name resolution.","An internal Domain Name System (DNS) server is correct because it keeps private records available only inside the organization.","A Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) relay forwards DHCP requests and does not resolve hostnames.","A reverse proxy fronts application servers and is unrelated to internal-only name resolution."]},{"id":346,"question":"Which DNS record type is used to map a hostname to an IPv4 address?","options":["AAAA record.","MX record.","CNAME record.","A record."],"correctIndex":3,"explanation":"An A record maps a hostname to an Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) address. An AAAA record maps to Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6), a Mail Exchanger (MX) record identifies mail servers, and a Canonical Name (CNAME) record creates an alias.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["An AAAA record maps a hostname to an Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) address, not IPv4.","A Mail Exchanger (MX) record identifies the mail server for a domain, not a host's IPv4 address.","A Canonical Name (CNAME) record aliases one name to another name rather than directly storing the IPv4 address asked for here.","An A record is correct because it maps a hostname directly to an Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) address."]},{"id":347,"question":"Which DNS record type is used to map a hostname to an IPv6 address?","options":["A record.","AAAA record.","PTR record.","TXT record."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"An AAAA record maps a hostname to an Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) address. An A record is for Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4), a Pointer (PTR) record is for reverse lookups, and a Text (TXT) record stores arbitrary text.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["An A record maps to Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4), not IPv6.","An AAAA record is correct because it maps a hostname to an Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) address.","A Pointer (PTR) record is used for reverse lookups from address to name, not forward mapping to IPv6.","A Text (TXT) record stores text data such as verification strings or policy information, not host address mappings."]},{"id":348,"question":"Which DNS record type is used to specify the mail server responsible for accepting email on behalf of a domain?","options":["MX record.","NS record.","SRV record.","CNAME record."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A Mail Exchanger (MX) record specifies which mail servers accept email for a domain.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["A Mail Exchanger (MX) record is correct because it identifies the mail server for the domain.","A Name Server (NS) record identifies authoritative DNS servers for a zone, not the mail server used to accept email.","A Service (SRV) record advertises the location of specific services, but standard email routing for domains uses MX records.","A Canonical Name (CNAME) record creates an alias and does not define the domain’s mail exchanger."]},{"id":349,"question":"Which DNS record type is commonly used to specify the location of services such as SIP servers or LDAP servers?","options":["SRV record.","TXT record.","PTR record.","SOA record."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A Service (SRV) record specifies the hostname and port information for a service such as Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) or Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP).","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["A Service (SRV) record is correct because it advertises the target host and port for a service.","A Text (TXT) record stores text-based information such as verification or policy data, not structured service location details.","A Pointer (PTR) record is used for reverse lookups, not advertising service endpoints.","A Start of Authority (SOA) record describes authoritative zone information, not individual service locations."]},{"id":350,"question":"A network engineer wants to offload SSL/TLS encryption from backend web servers to a dedicated device. Which application service is most relevant?","options":["DHCP relay.","SSL offloading on a load balancer.","NTP server.","TFTP server."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Many load balancers can perform Secure Sockets Layer / Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS) offloading by terminating encrypted sessions and passing traffic to backend servers, reducing server processing overhead.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["A Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) relay forwards DHCP traffic and has nothing to do with web encryption termination.","Secure Sockets Layer / Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS) offloading on a load balancer is correct because it lets a dedicated device handle encryption and decryption.","A Network Time Protocol (NTP) server synchronizes time and is unrelated to TLS termination.","A Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) server serves files and configurations, not encrypted web sessions."]},{"id":351,"question":"Which service can cache frequently requested web content to reduce bandwidth usage and improve response times for users?","options":["DNS server.","Caching proxy.","NTP server.","RADIUS server."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A caching proxy stores copies of frequently requested web content locally so repeated requests can be served faster and with less bandwidth use.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["A Domain Name System (DNS) server caches name-resolution data, but it does not typically cache full web content for users.","A caching proxy is correct because it stores and reuses previously fetched web content.","A Network Time Protocol (NTP) server handles time synchronization, not web-object caching.","A Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) server handles authentication and accounting, not content caching."]},{"id":352,"question":"Which protocol is commonly used by network devices to send alerts and performance data to a centralized monitoring system?","options":["SNMP.","SIP.","RTP.","TFTP."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) is used to monitor and manage network devices. It can collect statistics and send traps or alerts to centralized monitoring systems.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) is correct because it is used for monitoring, statistics, and alerting from network devices.","Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) is a signaling protocol for Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP), not a device monitoring protocol.","Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) carries audio or video streams and is not used for infrastructure monitoring alerts.","Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) transfers files but does not provide centralized performance monitoring."]},{"id":353,"question":"A network administrator wants to allow external users to access a web application hosted on internal servers while hiding the internal server IP addresses. Which service is best suited?","options":["Forward proxy, which represents outbound requests from internal clients rather than publishing an internal server.","Reverse proxy or application load balancer.","DHCP relay, which forwards DHCP broadcast traffic between subnets and has no role in publishing web applications.","NTP server, which synchronizes clocks across devices and has no role in proxying or publishing a web application."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A reverse proxy or application load balancer presents a single public-facing endpoint while forwarding requests to internal servers and hiding their private addresses.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a forward proxy represents outbound requests from internal clients, not external users reaching an internal server.","Correct — a reverse proxy or application load balancer fronts internal servers, presenting a single public endpoint and hiding their direct addresses.","Wrong — DHCP relay forwards DHCP broadcast traffic between subnets and is unrelated to publishing web applications.","Wrong — an NTP server synchronizes clocks and has no role in proxying or publishing a web application."]},{"id":354,"question":"Which application service is most associated with providing directory-based authentication and authorization, often used by Windows domains?","options":["DNS.","LDAP/Active Directory.","NTP.","TFTP."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) directory services, such as Microsoft Active Directory, provide centralized identity, authentication, and authorization information for domain resources.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Domain Name System (DNS) is important in Windows domains, but the directory-based authentication and authorization service itself is LDAP / Active Directory.","Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) / Active Directory is correct because it provides centralized directory-based identity and access services.","Network Time Protocol (NTP) helps keep authentication timestamps accurate, but it is not the directory service.","Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) transfers files and is unrelated to directory-based sign-in services."]},{"id":355,"question":"A network engineer configures a device to inspect HTTP and HTTPS traffic, apply URL filtering, and block malicious sites. Which type of service is this?","options":["NTP server.","Web security gateway.","DHCP server.","RADIUS server."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A web security gateway inspects Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) and Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure (HTTPS) traffic, applies URL filtering policies, and helps block malicious or inappropriate web content.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["A Network Time Protocol (NTP) server synchronizes time and does not inspect web traffic.","A web security gateway is correct because it filters and inspects web traffic for policy enforcement and threat protection.","A Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) server assigns IP settings and does not perform URL filtering.","A Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) server authenticates users, but it is not a web content filtering gateway."]},{"id":356,"question":"Which protocol is typically used by email clients to retrieve messages from a mail server while leaving a copy on the server?","options":["SMTP.","IMAP.","SNMP.","RTP."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP) allows an email client to access and manage messages stored on the mail server so they remain available across multiple devices.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) sends email; it is not the primary protocol for retrieving stored messages.","Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP) is correct because it retrieves and manages mail while keeping messages on the server.","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) monitors devices and is unrelated to email retrieval.","Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) carries media streams and has nothing to do with mail access."]},{"id":357,"question":"Which protocol is primarily used to send email from a client to a mail server or between mail servers?","options":["IMAP.","POP3.","SMTP.","FTP."],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) is the standard protocol for sending email from a client to a mail server and between mail servers.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP) retrieves and manages existing mail; it is not the primary send protocol.","Post Office Protocol version 3 (POP3) retrieves mail from a server and is not primarily used to send it.","Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) is correct because it sends email between clients and servers or between mail servers.","File Transfer Protocol (FTP) transfers files and is unrelated to standard email transport."]},{"id":358,"question":"A network administrator wants to ensure that DNS queries from internal clients are forwarded to external DNS servers while still allowing internal caching. Which feature should be configured?","options":["DNS forwarding.","DHCP relay.","NTP peering.","RADIUS proxy."],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Domain Name System (DNS) forwarding sends queries that cannot be resolved locally to upstream DNS servers while still allowing the internal DNS server to cache the responses.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Domain Name System (DNS) forwarding is correct because it passes unresolved queries upstream while preserving local caching.","A Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) relay handles DHCP traffic between subnets, not DNS query forwarding.","Network Time Protocol (NTP) peering exchanges time information, not name-resolution traffic.","A Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) proxy relays AAA traffic, not DNS lookups."]},{"id":359,"question":"Which application service is responsible for mapping a domain name to the IP address of a content delivery network (CDN) edge node closest to the user?","options":["DHCP.","DNS.","NTP.","SNMP."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Domain Name System (DNS) can return different Internet Protocol (IP) addresses based on user location or policy, which allows a content delivery network (CDN) to direct users to an appropriate edge node.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 7 .html","optionExplanations":["Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) assigns client addressing information and does not select a CDN edge node.","Domain Name System (DNS) is correct because it maps the domain name to an IP address, including CDN-aware responses.","Network Time Protocol (NTP) synchronizes time and is unrelated to selecting content-delivery endpoints.","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) monitors devices and is not part of CDN name-to-address mapping."]},{"id":360,"question":"When a network infrastructure device needs to transmit operational event notifications, anomaly indicators, and system-state messages to a centralized log-aggregation endpoint for long-term retention and correlation, which protocol is MOST commonly used?","options":["SNMP","Syslog","NetFlow","RADIUS"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Syslog is the standard protocol for sending event and status messages from routers, switches, firewalls, and servers to a centralized logging system.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — SNMP is used to poll and manage devices, not to centrally collect free-form log messages.","Correct — Syslog is the standard protocol devices use to forward event, error, and status messages to a central log server.","Wrong — NetFlow exports traffic flow statistics, not general event messages.","Wrong — RADIUS handles authentication, authorization, and accounting, not log forwarding."]},{"id":361,"question":"A network operations center is implementing a standards-based monitoring framework where a centralized management station polls distributed agents for performance counters and device-health metrics stored in structured object hierarchies. Which component is responsible for initiating these polling operations?","options":["SNMP Agent","SNMP Manager","MIB Browser","Trap Receiver"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"The SNMP manager initiates polling requests to SNMP agents and collects the returned management data.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — the SNMP agent responds to requests and generates traps; it does not initiate the polling itself.","Correct — the SNMP manager is the management station that initiates polling requests to agents and collects the returned data.","Wrong — a MIB browser is a tool for viewing MIB structure, not a component that performs polling.","Wrong — a trap receiver passively listens for unsolicited traps; it does not initiate polling."]},{"id":362,"question":"An organization requires a device-management protocol that supports message integrity, authentication, and optional encryption to prevent unauthorized disclosure of management data in transit. Which version BEST satisfies this requirement?","options":["SNMPv1","SNMPv2c","SNMPv3","SNMPv2u"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"SNMPv3 adds authentication, integrity checking, and optional encryption, making it the secure choice for management traffic.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.1","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — SNMPv1 has no real authentication or encryption and sends community strings in plaintext.","Wrong — SNMPv2c still relies on plaintext community strings and offers no encryption.","Correct — SNMPv3 adds user-based authentication, message integrity, and optional encryption for secure management traffic.","Wrong — SNMPv2u is not a standard, widely deployed SNMP version with these security features."]},{"id":363,"question":"A technician is reviewing a hierarchical database that defines object identifiers used for querying device performance, interface counters, and configuration parameters within a network-management ecosystem. What is this database called?","options":["Syslog catalog","Management Information Base (MIB)","Routing table","Access control list"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A MIB defines the managed objects and OIDs that SNMP tools use to read or write information on devices.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a Syslog catalog is not a defined term for a structured database of manageable objects.","Correct — the Management Information Base (MIB) defines the object identifiers (OIDs) that SNMP uses to read or set device data.","Wrong — a routing table stores next-hop information for forwarding packets, not object identifiers for management.","Wrong — an access control list defines permit/deny rules, not a hierarchy of manageable objects."]},{"id":364,"question":"A workstation must automatically receive its IPv4 address, subnet mask, gateway, and DNS information during the boot process without manual configuration. Which IP service provides this functionality?","options":["DNS","DHCP","NTP","TFTP"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"DHCP dynamically assigns IP configuration settings such as address, mask, gateway, and DNS servers.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — DNS resolves names to addresses; it does not assign IP configuration.","Correct — DHCP automatically assigns IP address, subnet mask, gateway, and DNS settings to clients during boot.","Wrong — NTP synchronizes time between devices, unrelated to IP configuration.","Wrong — TFTP transfers small files such as boot images; it does not assign IP settings."]},{"id":365,"question":"A user reports that internal IP-based communication works normally, but any attempt to access external resources using domain names fails. Which IP service is MOST likely misconfigured or unavailable?","options":["DHCP","DNS","NTP","FTP"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"If a device can reach resources by IP address but not by hostname, DNS resolution is the most likely issue.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a DHCP failure would typically prevent the device from getting any IP configuration at all, not just name resolution.","Correct — when IP-based communication works but hostname-based access fails, DNS resolution is the most likely culprit.","Wrong — an NTP problem affects time synchronization, not the ability to resolve domain names.","Wrong — FTP is a file transfer protocol and unrelated to name resolution."]},{"id":366,"question":"A network administrator is creating a forward-lookup zone entry that maps a human-readable hostname to a corresponding IPv4 address. Which DNS record type should be created?","options":["AAAA record","CNAME record","A record","PTR record"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"An A record maps a hostname to an IPv4 address.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — an AAAA record maps a hostname to an IPv6 address, not IPv4.","Wrong — a CNAME record is an alias pointing to another hostname, not directly to an IP address.","Correct — an A record maps a hostname directly to an IPv4 address.","Wrong — a PTR record performs a reverse lookup from IP address to hostname."]},{"id":367,"question":"A mail-routing architecture requires DNS entries that specify which hosts are authorized to receive inbound email for a domain. Which record type fulfills this requirement?","options":["MX record","PTR record","NS record","TXT record"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An MX record identifies the mail server that accepts email for a domain.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — an MX record specifies which mail servers are authorized to accept inbound email for a domain.","Wrong — a PTR record supports reverse DNS lookups, not mail routing.","Wrong — an NS record identifies authoritative name servers for a zone, not mail servers.","Wrong — a TXT record stores arbitrary text data and is not itself the mail-routing record."]},{"id":368,"question":"A technician is troubleshooting a reverse-lookup failure where an IP address cannot be resolved back to its associated hostname. Which DNS record type is required for this operation?","options":["A record","MX record","PTR record","CNAME record"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"A PTR record is used for reverse DNS lookups, mapping an IP address back to a hostname.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — an A record maps a hostname to an IPv4 address, the opposite direction of a reverse lookup.","Wrong — an MX record identifies mail servers, unrelated to reverse lookups.","Correct — a PTR record maps an IP address back to its associated hostname for reverse DNS lookups.","Wrong — a CNAME record is an alias to another hostname, not a reverse-lookup record."]},{"id":369,"question":"A distributed network environment requires synchronized timestamps across routers, switches, servers, and security appliances to ensure accurate log correlation and event sequencing. Which protocol provides this capability?","options":["NTP","SNMP","DNS","DHCP"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"NTP keeps clocks synchronized across networked devices so logs and events line up correctly.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — NTP synchronizes clocks across devices so that logs and events can be correlated accurately.","Wrong — SNMP is used for device monitoring and management, not time synchronization.","Wrong — DNS resolves names to addresses and has no role in clock synchronization.","Wrong — DHCP assigns IP configuration and does not synchronize time."]},{"id":370,"question":"A network engineer needs visibility into traffic patterns, including source and destination pairs, byte counts, and flow durations, to support capacity planning and anomaly detection. Which technology provides this level of flow-based analytics?","options":["Port mirroring","NetFlow or IPFIX","Syslog","SNMP traps"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"NetFlow and IPFIX export flow-level metadata that helps analyze traffic behavior and utilization.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — port mirroring copies raw traffic for inspection but does not itself provide flow analytics like byte counts and durations.","Correct — NetFlow and IPFIX export flow-level metadata, including source/destination pairs, byte counts, and durations, for traffic analysis.","Wrong — Syslog transports log and event messages, not flow-based traffic statistics.","Wrong — SNMP traps report specific events or thresholds, not detailed flow analytics."]},{"id":371,"question":"A security analyst needs to capture a real-time copy of ingress and egress traffic from a specific switch interface for packet-level inspection without disrupting production flows. Which switch feature should be used?","options":["VLAN tagging","Port mirroring (SPAN)","QoS classification","Link aggregation"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Port mirroring, often called SPAN, copies traffic from selected interfaces to a monitoring port for inspection.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — VLAN tagging segments traffic logically; it does not copy traffic to a monitoring port.","Correct — port mirroring, or SPAN, copies traffic from a source interface to a monitoring port for real-time inspection.","Wrong — QoS classification prioritizes traffic; it does not duplicate traffic for capture.","Wrong — link aggregation combines multiple links for bandwidth and redundancy, not traffic capture."]},{"id":372,"question":"A centralized monitoring platform continuously polls network devices, evaluates threshold conditions, and generates alerts when performance metrics exceed acceptable baselines. What type of system is being used?","options":["Packet sniffer","Configuration management system","Network monitoring system (NMS)","TFTP server"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"An NMS monitors device health, gathers metrics, and alerts administrators when thresholds are crossed.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a packet sniffer captures raw packets but does not typically manage baselines and alerting on its own.","Wrong — a configuration management system tracks device configurations, not performance thresholds and alerts.","Correct — a network monitoring system (NMS) continuously polls devices, evaluates thresholds, and generates alerts.","Wrong — a TFTP server transfers files such as firmware images; it does not monitor performance."]},{"id":373,"question":"A network architect must ensure that latency-sensitive applications such as VoIP receive prioritized handling over best-effort traffic during periods of congestion. Which network feature accomplishes this?","options":["Encryption","Quality of Service (QoS)","DHCP relay","NAT"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"QoS classifies and prioritizes time-sensitive traffic so it is handled before lower-priority traffic during congestion.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — encryption protects data confidentiality; it has no role in prioritizing traffic.","Correct — Quality of Service (QoS) classifies and prioritizes latency-sensitive traffic such as VoIP over best-effort traffic.","Wrong — DHCP relay forwards DHCP requests across subnets; it does not prioritize traffic.","Wrong — NAT translates addresses; it has no role in traffic prioritization."]},{"id":374,"question":"A host must automatically discover the presence of local routers and obtain default-gateway information using ICMP-based mechanisms rather than DHCP. Which feature provides this capability?","options":["DHCP relay","Proxy ARP","ICMP Router Discovery","NTP"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"ICMP Router Discovery lets hosts learn about available routers and default-gateway information through ICMP messages.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — DHCP relay forwards DHCP requests across subnets; it does not use ICMP for router discovery.","Wrong — proxy ARP allows a device to answer ARP requests on behalf of another host, unrelated to gateway discovery.","Correct — ICMP Router Discovery lets hosts learn about available routers and default gateways via ICMP messages.","Wrong — NTP synchronizes time and has no role in discovering routers."]},{"id":375,"question":"A DHCP administrator is defining the range of IPv4 addresses that may be dynamically assigned to clients within a specific broadcast domain. What is this range called?","options":["Lease pool","DHCP scope","Reservation table","Address exclusion list"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A DHCP scope defines the assignable address range and related settings for a subnet.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a lease pool is not the standard term for this configured address range.","Correct — a DHCP scope defines the range of addresses that can be dynamically assigned within a subnet.","Wrong — a reservation table lists specific addresses tied to specific hosts, not the general assignable range.","Wrong — an address exclusion list removes addresses from assignment; it is not the range itself."]},{"id":376,"question":"A DHCP server must provide clients with the IP addresses of DNS resolvers during the lease process. Which DHCP option is used for this purpose?","options":["Option 3","Option 6","Option 15","Option 51"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"DHCP Option 6 provides the addresses of DNS servers to clients.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — Option 3 provides the default gateway address, not DNS servers.","Correct — DHCP Option 6 supplies the addresses of DNS servers to the client.","Wrong — Option 15 provides the DNS domain name, not the server addresses.","Wrong — Option 51 specifies the lease time, not DNS server addresses."]},{"id":377,"question":"A multi-subnet environment requires DHCP clients on remote VLANs to obtain addressing information from a centralized DHCP server. Which mechanism enables this communication?","options":["DHCP snooping","DHCP relay","DHCP failover","DHCPv6 prefix delegation"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"DHCP relay forwards DHCP traffic between clients and servers that are on different subnets.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — DHCP snooping is a switch security feature that filters untrusted DHCP messages; it does not forward requests between subnets.","Correct — DHCP relay forwards DHCP broadcasts from clients on one subnet to a DHCP server on another subnet.","Wrong — DHCP failover synchronizes state between redundant DHCP servers, not cross-subnet forwarding.","Wrong — DHCPv6 prefix delegation assigns address prefixes to routers in IPv6, a different mechanism."]},{"id":378,"question":"An enterprise needs a centralized platform to track IP address allocations, subnet utilization, and address-space planning across multiple sites. Which system provides this functionality?","options":["DNS server","IP Address Management (IPAM)","RADIUS server","Proxy server"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"IPAM software tracks address usage, subnets, and allocation planning across the network.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a DNS server resolves names to addresses; it does not track allocation and utilization across sites.","Correct — IP Address Management (IPAM) software tracks IP allocations, subnet utilization, and address-space planning.","Wrong — a RADIUS server handles authentication and accounting, not address-space tracking.","Wrong — a proxy server forwards client requests; it does not manage IP address allocation."]},{"id":379,"question":"A network team wants to ensure that router and switch configurations are automatically backed up, versioned, and retrievable for rollback after changes. Which type of system should be deployed?","options":["Network monitoring system","Configuration management system","Syslog server","Authentication server"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A configuration management system stores versions, automates backups, and supports rollback of device configurations.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a network monitoring system tracks performance and alerts, not configuration versioning and rollback.","Correct — a configuration management system automates backup, versioning, and rollback of device configurations.","Wrong — a Syslog server collects log messages; it does not manage configuration backups.","Wrong — an authentication server verifies credentials; it has no role in configuration backup."]},{"id":380,"question":"A technician must remotely administer a network device using a secure, encrypted management session that protects credentials and configuration data. Which protocol should be used?","options":["Telnet","SSH","FTP","TFTP"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"SSH provides secure, encrypted remote administration. Telnet does not encrypt session data.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — Telnet transmits session data, including credentials, in plaintext.","Correct — SSH provides an encrypted management session that protects credentials and configuration data in transit.","Wrong — FTP transfers files and does not encrypt credentials by default.","Wrong — TFTP is unauthenticated and unencrypted, and is not used for interactive administration."]},{"id":381,"question":"A network engineer needs to validate DNS resolution behavior and view authoritative and non-authoritative responses for troubleshooting. Which tool is MOST appropriate?","options":["ping","tracert","nslookup or dig","ipconfig"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"nslookup and dig query DNS servers directly and show detailed resolution data.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — ping tests basic reachability using ICMP; it does not query DNS records.","Wrong — tracert maps the path packets take to a destination; it does not show DNS resolution details.","Correct — nslookup and dig query DNS servers directly and display authoritative and non-authoritative responses.","Wrong — ipconfig displays local IP configuration; it does not query remote DNS servers."]},{"id":382,"question":"A security team wants to consolidate logs from firewalls, servers, and network devices into a single location for correlation and incident analysis. What is the PRIMARY benefit of this approach?","options":["It automatically assigns IP addresses to new devices as they join the network.","It keeps clock settings synchronized across all connected network devices.","It consolidates event logs in one place, making correlation and incident analysis far easier.","It enforces bandwidth limits and shapes traffic during periods of peak congestion."],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Centralized logging makes it much easier to correlate events across many systems during troubleshooting or incident response.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.1","objective":"Network Monitoring","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — centralized logging does not perform IP address assignment; that is a DHCP function.","Wrong — centralized logging does not synchronize clocks; that is the role of NTP.","Correct — consolidating logs into one location makes it far easier to correlate events and investigate incidents across many systems.","Wrong — centralized logging does not shape or limit bandwidth; that is a QoS function."]},{"id":383,"question":"A workstation has the correct IP address and gateway but an incorrect subnet mask. Which symptom is MOST likely to occur?","options":["It cannot communicate with any host on the network, local or remote, until corrected.","It communicates only with hosts it mistakenly perceives as local, and fails to reach hosts that require routing.","It communicates normally with every host on the network, with no adverse effect.","It loses the ability to resolve DNS names, but IP-based connectivity is unaffected."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A bad subnet mask causes a host to misjudge which destinations are local and which require routing.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — an incorrect subnet mask does not prevent all communication; local reachability is often preserved for hosts perceived as local.","Correct — with a wrong mask, the host miscalculates which addresses are local, so it can reach hosts it wrongly treats as local but fails to reach ones requiring routing.","Wrong — normal communication with all hosts would only occur if the mask happened to be correct for every destination, which is not the case here.","Wrong — a subnet mask issue is a Layer 3 addressing problem, not a DNS resolution problem."]},{"id":384,"question":"An IPv6-enabled network requires hosts to automatically configure their own addresses and default gateways without relying on a DHCPv6 server. Which mechanism provides this?","options":["SLAAC","NAT64","DNSSEC","IPAM"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"SLAAC uses router advertisements to let IPv6 hosts self-configure addressing information.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — SLAAC lets IPv6 hosts self-configure addresses and default gateways using router advertisements, without DHCPv6.","Wrong — NAT64 translates between IPv6 and IPv4 addressing; it does not perform host autoconfiguration.","Wrong — DNSSEC adds cryptographic validation to DNS responses; it is unrelated to address autoconfiguration.","Wrong — IPAM is a management system for tracking address space, not a host autoconfiguration mechanism."]},{"id":385,"question":"A network administrator must ensure that real-time voice traffic receives higher priority than general web browsing during congestion. Which configuration accomplishes this?","options":["Mirroring all switch port traffic to a monitoring interface for analysis.","Configuring QoS to classify voice traffic and place it in a priority queue.","Deploying a DHCP relay agent to forward requests across subnet boundaries.","Enabling NTP authentication to secure time synchronization messages."],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Traffic classification and queuing within QoS policies allow voice traffic to be prioritized over best-effort traffic such as web browsing.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — mirroring traffic to a monitoring port supports analysis and captures but does not prioritize voice traffic.","Correct — configuring QoS to classify voice traffic and queue it with priority ensures it is handled ahead of best-effort traffic during congestion.","Wrong — a DHCP relay agent forwards address requests across subnets; it has no role in traffic prioritization.","Wrong — NTP authentication secures time-sync messages; it does not prioritize voice traffic."]},{"id":386,"question":"A service provider contract specifies guaranteed uptime, latency thresholds, and response times for network services. What type of document defines these expectations?","options":["Security policy","Service Level Agreement (SLA)","Change management plan","Disaster recovery plan"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"An SLA defines the agreed service levels, such as uptime, latency, and support response targets.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a security policy defines security rules and controls, not uptime and latency commitments.","Correct — a Service Level Agreement (SLA) defines guaranteed uptime, latency thresholds, and response-time commitments.","Wrong — a change management plan governs how changes are proposed and approved, not service guarantees.","Wrong — a disaster recovery plan defines recovery procedures after an outage, not ongoing service-level commitments."]},{"id":387,"question":"A monitoring system must receive unsolicited notifications from network devices when critical events occur, such as link failures or threshold violations. What are these notifications called?","options":["Syslog messages","SNMP traps","NetFlow records","ICMP redirects"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"SNMP traps are unsolicited alerts sent by devices to notify a manager about specific events.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — Syslog messages are general event and status logs, not specifically SNMP-triggered alerts.","Correct — SNMP traps are unsolicited notifications a device sends to a manager when specific events, such as link failures, occur.","Wrong — NetFlow records describe traffic flow statistics, not discrete unsolicited event alerts.","Wrong — ICMP redirects tell a host to use a better route; they are not SNMP-based event notifications."]},{"id":388,"question":"A technician needs to verify basic IP-layer reachability to a remote host. Which tool should be used?","options":["ping","tracert","arp","netstat"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"ping uses ICMP echo requests and replies to verify Layer 3 reachability.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — ping uses ICMP echo requests and replies to verify basic Layer 3 reachability to a host.","Wrong — tracert shows the path and hops to a destination, which is more detail than basic reachability requires.","Wrong — arp shows or manipulates the local IP-to-MAC address table, not remote reachability.","Wrong — netstat displays local connection and socket information, not remote host reachability."]},{"id":389,"question":"A user can successfully reach a remote server using its IP address but cannot resolve its hostname. What is the BEST first troubleshooting step?","options":["Check the default gateway","Check DNS server settings on the client","Replace the network cable","Change the subnet mask"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"When connectivity by IP works but name resolution fails, DNS client settings are the best first place to check.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Day 8.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a default gateway problem would typically prevent reaching remote hosts by IP as well, not just by name.","Correct — since IP connectivity works but name resolution fails, checking the client's DNS server settings is the best first step.","Wrong — a bad cable would typically cause a broader connectivity failure, not an isolated name-resolution problem.","Wrong — changing the subnet mask addresses local addressing, not hostname resolution."]},{"id":390,"question":"A technician needs to verify end-to-end Internet Protocol-layer reachability between two hosts while also observing latency variations that may indicate congestion or path instability. Which troubleshooting tool is MOST appropriate?","options":["ping","traceroute","pathping","netstat"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"ping uses Internet Control Message Protocol echo requests to confirm reachability and measure round-trip time. traceroute maps hops, pathping combines path and loss analysis, and netstat focuses on local sessions.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — ping uses ICMP echo requests to confirm reachability and reports round-trip time, revealing latency variation.","Wrong — traceroute focuses on mapping the hop-by-hop path rather than simple reachability and latency at the destination.","Wrong — pathping combines path tracing with packet loss statistics gathered over time, which is more than what is asked for here.","Wrong — netstat reports local connection state, not end-to-end reachability or latency to a remote host."]},{"id":391,"question":"A network engineer suspects that a routing loop or asymmetric path is causing intermittent packet loss. Which tool provides hop-by-hop visibility into the forwarding path taken by packets?","options":["traceroute","pathping","route print","netstat -r"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"traceroute reveals each hop along the packet path, making it the best first tool for locating where routing behavior changes.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — traceroute shows every hop along the forwarding path, revealing where a routing loop or asymmetric route develops.","Wrong — pathping combines path tracing with loss statistics but is less commonly the first tool cited for basic hop-by-hop visibility.","Wrong — route print shows the local routing table, not the actual hops packets take across the network.","Wrong — netstat -r shows the local route table, not the live path taken by packets end to end."]},{"id":392,"question":"A user reports that a workstation cannot communicate with nearby devices on the same subnet, but the default gateway responds normally. Which command can reveal incorrect Address Resolution Protocol cache entries contributing to the issue?","options":["arp -a","route print","ipconfig /all","nslookup"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"arp -a displays Internet Protocol-to-Media Access Control mappings in the local Address Resolution Protocol cache, which helps diagnose local-segment resolution problems.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — arp -a lists the local ARP cache, exposing stale or incorrect IP-to-MAC mappings that cause local-segment failures.","Wrong — route print shows the routing table, not local ARP cache entries.","Wrong — ipconfig /all shows the host's own configuration, not its ARP cache toward other local hosts.","Wrong — nslookup queries DNS servers and has no connection to ARP cache entries."]},{"id":393,"question":"A technician needs to determine which active Transmission Control Protocol and User Datagram Protocol sessions exist on a workstation and identify the associated processes. Which tool should be used?","options":["netstat","ipconfig","tracert","arp -a"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"netstat shows active connections, listening ports, and, with the right switches, associated processes. The other commands focus on addressing, path tracing, or Address Resolution Protocol entries.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — netstat displays active TCP/UDP sessions and, with appropriate switches, the owning process.","Wrong — ipconfig displays IP configuration details, not active connections or processes.","Wrong — tracert maps the hop path to a destination, not active local sessions.","Wrong — arp -a shows local ARP cache entries, not TCP/UDP session information."]},{"id":394,"question":"A network administrator must verify that a Domain Name System server is returning authoritative responses for a specific domain. Which tool provides detailed query and response information?","options":["dig","nslookup","host","ping"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"dig is the most detailed query tool for reviewing Domain Name System responses, flags, and authority information. nslookup can help too, but dig is more precise for this objective.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — dig provides the most detailed DNS query and response output, including flags and authority information.","Wrong — nslookup can query DNS but shows less detailed flag and authority data than dig.","Wrong — host provides a quick lookup but with far less detail than dig.","Wrong — ping only tests reachability; it does not report DNS response details."]},{"id":395,"question":"A technician suspects that a workstation is receiving an incorrect Internet Protocol configuration from Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol. Which command displays the current address, default gateway, and Domain Name System settings?","options":["ipconfig /all","netstat -an","route print","arp -a"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"ipconfig /all shows the full local Transmission Control Protocol or Internet Protocol configuration, including Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol details, gateway, and Domain Name System servers.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — ipconfig /all displays the full IP configuration, including DHCP-assigned address, gateway, and DNS servers.","Wrong — netstat -an shows connections and listening ports, not DHCP or DNS configuration.","Wrong — route print shows the routing table, not the client's assigned IP settings.","Wrong — arp -a shows the local ARP cache, not DHCP-assigned configuration."]},{"id":396,"question":"A network engineer needs to test whether a remote server is reachable on Transmission Control Protocol port 443 and determine whether a firewall is blocking the connection. Which tool is MOST appropriate?","options":["telnet","curl","Test-NetConnection","ping"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"telnet is the classic exam answer for testing whether a specific Transmission Control Protocol port accepts a connection. ping does not test ports, and the other tools are platform-specific alternatives.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — telnet is the classic tool for testing whether a specific TCP port, such as 443, accepts a connection.","Wrong — curl can test HTTP(S) endpoints but is a less universal, platform-specific choice for raw port testing.","Wrong — Test-NetConnection is a Windows-specific PowerShell alternative, not the traditional cross-platform answer.","Wrong — ping only verifies ICMP reachability and cannot test whether a specific TCP port is open."]},{"id":397,"question":"A technician needs to capture and analyze packet-level traffic to identify malformed frames or retransmissions. Which tool should be used?","options":["Protocol analyzer","Interface monitor","Port scanner","Loopback plug"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A protocol analyzer such as Wireshark captures and decodes frames and packets for deep traffic inspection. The other options do not provide full packet payload analysis.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — a protocol analyzer such as Wireshark captures and decodes packets to reveal malformed frames or retransmissions.","Wrong — an interface monitor reports link-level statistics but does not decode packet contents.","Wrong — a port scanner checks which ports are open, not packet-level frame content.","Wrong — a loopback plug tests a NIC's transmit/receive path, not traffic content."]},{"id":398,"question":"A network team wants to verify that a switch port is negotiating the correct speed and duplex settings. Which tool provides real-time interface statistics?","options":["Interface monitoring tool","Protocol analyzer","Cable certifier","Tone generator"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An interface monitoring tool shows link speed, duplex, errors, and utilization in real time. The other tools are for packet capture, cable certification, or cable tracing.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — an interface monitoring tool reports real-time speed, duplex, and utilization statistics for a switch port.","Wrong — a protocol analyzer captures packet content, not negotiated speed and duplex settings.","Wrong — a cable certifier validates cable performance against a standard, not live port negotiation.","Wrong — a tone generator traces a cable run; it provides no interface statistics."]},{"id":399,"question":"A technician needs to determine whether a cable fault exists between a workstation and a switch. Which tool can detect opens, shorts, and wire-pair misalignments?","options":["Cable tester","Cable certifier","Tone generator and probe","Loopback plug"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A cable tester checks basic copper continuity and pinout faults such as opens, shorts, and crossed pairs. A cable certifier is more advanced and validates standards compliance.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — a cable tester detects opens, shorts, and wire-pair miswiring on a copper run.","Wrong — a cable certifier performs more advanced standards-compliance testing, beyond basic fault detection.","Wrong — a tone generator and probe trace a cable's physical path; they don't detect opens or shorts.","Wrong — a loopback plug tests NIC transmit/receive function, not cable continuity faults."]},{"id":400,"question":"A fiber-optic link is experiencing intermittent signal loss. Which tool measures light loss and identifies breaks or bends along the cable?","options":["Optical time-domain reflectometer","Light meter","Cable certifier","Tone generator"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An optical time-domain reflectometer identifies distance to faults and measures attenuation events along a fiber run. A light meter measures loss but does not locate faults along the path the same way.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — an optical time-domain reflectometer (OTDR) measures light loss and pinpoints breaks or bends along a fiber run.","Wrong — a light meter measures signal loss but does not locate the distance to a fault along the cable.","Wrong — a cable certifier is designed for copper standards compliance, not fiber fault location.","Wrong — a tone generator is a copper cable tracing tool and has no function on fiber."]},{"id":401,"question":"A technician needs to trace an unknown copper cable run through a wiring closet. Which tool pair is MOST appropriate?","options":["Tone generator and probe","Cable tester and certifier","Punchdown tool and crimper","Loopback plug and multimeter"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A tone generator and probe are used to identify and trace cable runs through bundles and patch panels. The other tools are for termination, testing, or network interface card checks.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — a tone generator and probe let a technician trace an unidentified cable through bundles and patch panels.","Wrong — a cable tester and certifier verify electrical performance, not physical identification of a specific run.","Wrong — a punchdown tool and crimper are used to terminate cables, not trace them.","Wrong — a loopback plug and multimeter test NIC function and voltage, not cable identity."]},{"id":402,"question":"A network engineer wants to validate that a newly installed copper cable meets performance standards for Category 6. Which tool should be used?","options":["Cable certifier","Cable tester","Tone generator","Multimeter"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A cable certifier validates that the installed link meets the electrical and performance requirements for the specified cable category.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — a cable certifier validates that an installed link meets the performance standard for its category, such as Cat 6.","Wrong — a cable tester checks basic continuity and pinout, not full standards compliance.","Wrong — a tone generator traces cable paths; it does not certify performance.","Wrong — a multimeter measures voltage and continuity but not category performance compliance."]},{"id":403,"question":"A technician suspects a workstation network interface card is malfunctioning. Which tool can simulate a network connection and verify transmit and receive functionality on the adapter?","options":["Loopback plug","Protocol analyzer","Tone generator","Cable tester"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A loopback plug returns the transmitted signal back to the network interface card so the technician can verify local send and receive behavior.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — a loopback plug returns transmitted signal back to the NIC, verifying its transmit and receive paths.","Wrong — a protocol analyzer inspects traffic content; it does not test NIC hardware function directly.","Wrong — a tone generator traces cable runs and has no role in testing a NIC.","Wrong — a cable tester checks the cable itself, not the network interface card."]},{"id":404,"question":"A network administrator needs to determine whether a firewall is blocking outbound traffic to a specific destination service. Which tool can test connectivity to a specific Transmission Control Protocol port?","options":["telnet","tracert","arp -a","route print"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"telnet can attempt a session to a specific Transmission Control Protocol port, which helps confirm whether outbound access is allowed.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — telnet can attempt a session to a specific TCP port, confirming whether outbound access is permitted.","Wrong — tracert shows the hop path to a destination but does not test whether a specific port is reachable.","Wrong — arp -a shows local ARP cache entries, unrelated to firewall port testing.","Wrong — route print shows the local routing table, not port-level connectivity."]},{"id":405,"question":"A technician needs to identify excessive broadcast traffic on a network segment. Which tool provides packet-level visibility into traffic types?","options":["Protocol analyzer","NetFlow collector","Interface monitor","ipconfig /all"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A protocol analyzer shows the actual frames and packets on the segment, making it the best way to confirm broadcast volume and sources.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — a protocol analyzer shows actual frame types and sources, confirming broadcast volume directly.","Wrong — a NetFlow collector summarizes flow statistics but doesn't show individual frame types the way packet capture does.","Wrong — an interface monitor shows aggregate traffic counters, not the packet-level detail needed to identify broadcast sources.","Wrong — ipconfig /all shows local configuration, not traffic on the segment."]},{"id":406,"question":"A user reports slow network performance. The technician wants to determine whether the issue is due to high utilization on a switch port. Which tool is MOST appropriate?","options":["Interface statistics monitor","Protocol analyzer","traceroute","nslookup"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An interface statistics monitor shows bandwidth use, discards, and errors on the switch port. That is the most direct way to confirm high utilization.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — an interface statistics monitor directly reports bandwidth utilization, discards, and errors on a switch port.","Wrong — a protocol analyzer decodes packet contents, which is more detail than needed to confirm utilization.","Wrong — traceroute reveals the path to a destination, not port utilization on a local switch.","Wrong — nslookup tests DNS resolution, unrelated to switch port utilization."]},{"id":407,"question":"A technician needs to verify that a workstation is receiving Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol information from the correct server. Which command can release and renew the Internet Protocol address lease?","options":["ipconfig /release and ipconfig /renew","arp -d * to clear all address resolution protocol cache entries on the host","route print to display the local routing table and next-hop information","netstat -an to list all active and listening network connections"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"ipconfig /release drops the current lease and ipconfig /renew requests a new one from Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol. The other commands do not request a new lease.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — ipconfig /release drops the current DHCP lease and ipconfig /renew requests a new one from the DHCP server.","Wrong — arp -d * clears the ARP cache; it does not release or renew a DHCP lease.","Wrong — route print displays the routing table; it has no effect on DHCP leases.","Wrong — netstat -an lists active connections; it does not manage IP address leases."]},{"id":408,"question":"A network engineer suspects that a misconfigured static route is causing traffic to take an unexpected path. Which command displays the local routing table?","options":["route print","netstat -an","arp -a","ipconfig /displaydns"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"route print displays the host routing table and next-hop information, which is what the engineer needs to inspect.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — route print displays the local routing table, including static and learned routes, letting the engineer verify the expected path.","Wrong — netstat -an shows active connections and listening ports, not the routing table.","Wrong — arp -a shows local IP-to-MAC mappings, not route entries.","Wrong — ipconfig /displaydns shows the local DNS resolver cache, unrelated to routing."]},{"id":409,"question":"A technician needs to verify that a Domain Name System server is reachable and responding to name queries. Which tool provides name-resolution testing against a specific server?","options":["nslookup","ping","arp -a","netstat"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"nslookup is designed to query Domain Name System servers directly for name-resolution testing. ping only tests basic reachability by address or resolved name.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — nslookup is built specifically to query DNS servers directly and test name-resolution responses.","Wrong — ping only confirms basic reachability; it doesn't test DNS query/response behavior directly against a chosen server.","Wrong — arp -a shows local ARP entries, unrelated to DNS testing.","Wrong — netstat shows local connections and ports, not DNS query results."]},{"id":410,"question":"A network administrator wants to determine whether a workstation is using the correct default gateway. Which command displays the gateway currently assigned to the host?","options":["ipconfig","route add","netstat -r","arp -d"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"ipconfig shows the assigned default gateway directly. netstat -r and route print can also expose routes, but ipconfig is the direct configuration-view command.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — ipconfig directly displays the default gateway currently assigned to the host.","Wrong — route add creates a new route entry; it does not display the current gateway.","Wrong — netstat -r can show route information but is a less direct way to view the assigned gateway than ipconfig.","Wrong — arp -d deletes ARP cache entries; it does not display gateway configuration."]},{"id":411,"question":"A technician needs to identify which device on the local network is responding to Address Resolution Protocol requests incorrectly and causing intermittent connectivity issues. Which tool helps identify Internet Protocol-to-Media Access Control mappings?","options":["arp -a","ping","nslookup","tracert"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"arp -a displays local Address Resolution Protocol cache entries, which map Internet Protocol addresses to Media Access Control addresses on the local segment.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — arp -a displays the local ARP cache, revealing incorrect IP-to-MAC mappings on the segment.","Wrong — ping only tests reachability; it does not display ARP mapping details.","Wrong — nslookup queries DNS servers, unrelated to local ARP mappings.","Wrong — tracert maps the hop path to a remote destination, not local ARP entries."]},{"id":412,"question":"A network engineer wants to determine whether packet fragmentation is occurring along a path because of a Maximum Transmission Unit mismatch. Which tool can test that condition most directly?","options":["ping with the Don't Fragment flag","traceroute","arp -a","netstat -s"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Using ping with the Don't Fragment flag helps determine whether a packet of a given size can traverse the path without fragmentation.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — using ping with the Don't Fragment flag tests whether a packet of a given size can cross the path without fragmenting, revealing MTU mismatches.","Wrong — traceroute maps the hop path but does not directly test for fragmentation caused by an MTU mismatch.","Wrong — arp -a shows local address mappings, unrelated to MTU or fragmentation.","Wrong — netstat -s shows protocol statistics but does not directly test a specific packet size against the path MTU."]},{"id":413,"question":"A technician needs to verify that a switch port is not experiencing excessive cyclic redundancy check errors. Which tool provides this information most directly?","options":["Interface statistics monitor","Protocol analyzer","Cable tester","ping"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Interface statistics show cyclic redundancy check errors, runts, giants, and other port-level counters that indicate physical or duplex problems.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — interface statistics directly report CRC errors along with other port-level counters like runts and giants.","Wrong — a protocol analyzer inspects packet contents but is not the most direct source of CRC error counts.","Wrong — a cable tester checks the physical cable, not live switch port error counters.","Wrong — ping tests reachability and does not report interface-level CRC error counts."]},{"id":414,"question":"A network engineer suspects that a Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol server is issuing duplicate Internet Protocol addresses. Which command on an affected client is the BEST first step to confirm the address currently assigned?","options":["ipconfig /all","arp -a","netstat -r","nslookup"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"ipconfig /all confirms the client address, lease details, and Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol server information. That makes it the best first client-side verification step.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — ipconfig /all on the client confirms the currently assigned address, lease details, and DHCP server, making it the best first check.","Wrong — arp -a shows local ARP mappings, not DHCP lease and server information.","Wrong — netstat -r shows the routing table, not DHCP-assigned addressing details.","Wrong — nslookup tests DNS resolution, unrelated to confirming a DHCP-assigned address."]},{"id":415,"question":"A technician needs to determine whether a remote host is reachable on a specific User Datagram Protocol port. Which tool is MOST appropriate?","options":["nc (netcat)","telnet","ping","arp -a"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Netcat can test both Transmission Control Protocol and User Datagram Protocol connectivity. telnet is typically used for Transmission Control Protocol only.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — netcat (nc) can test connectivity over both TCP and UDP, making it suitable for checking a specific UDP port.","Wrong — telnet is generally limited to TCP connections and does not reliably test UDP ports.","Wrong — ping tests basic ICMP reachability, not connectivity to a specific UDP port.","Wrong — arp -a shows local ARP entries, unrelated to testing UDP port reachability."]},{"id":416,"question":"A network administrator wants to verify that a firewall is blocking inbound traffic on a specific port. Which tool can simulate a connection attempt from an external host to that service?","options":["telnet","dig","route print","ipconfig"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"telnet can attempt a basic session to a specific Transmission Control Protocol port from outside the network, helping validate whether the firewall is allowing or blocking access.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — telnet can attempt a basic connection to a specific port from outside the network, validating whether the firewall allows or blocks it.","Wrong — dig queries DNS records; it does not test firewall port behavior.","Wrong — route print shows the local routing table, unrelated to firewall port testing.","Wrong — ipconfig shows local IP configuration, not remote firewall behavior."]},{"id":417,"question":"A technician needs to determine whether a workstation is using Internet Protocol version 6 or Internet Protocol version 4 for outbound connections. Which tool displays active connections and protocol families?","options":["netstat","ping","arp","dig"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"netstat shows active sessions and listening sockets, including whether those entries use Internet Protocol version 4 or Internet Protocol version 6.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — netstat lists active connections and listening sockets, showing whether entries use IPv4 or IPv6.","Wrong — ping tests reachability for a single address but doesn't summarize all active connections and their protocol family.","Wrong — arp shows IP-to-MAC mappings for IPv4 neighbors, not a summary of active connection protocol versions.","Wrong — dig queries DNS records, unrelated to viewing active connections."]},{"id":418,"question":"A network engineer wants to identify the Media Access Control address of a device on the same local subnet. Which tool should be used FIRST to help populate the Address Resolution Protocol cache before viewing it?","options":["ping","arp","traceroute","nslookup"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"On a local subnet, pinging the target first can trigger Address Resolution Protocol resolution. After that, arp can display the resulting Internet Protocol-to-Media Access Control mapping.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — pinging the target first triggers ARP resolution on the local subnet, after which arp can display the resulting mapping.","Wrong — arp alone only shows existing cache entries; if the entry isn't cached yet, it won't reveal the mapping without a prior ping.","Wrong — traceroute maps a path to a destination and does not populate the local ARP cache the same way.","Wrong — nslookup resolves hostnames via DNS, unrelated to populating the local ARP cache."]},{"id":419,"question":"A technician needs to verify that a workstation can reach a remote server but suspects a routing issue somewhere between them. Which tool shows each hop along the path?","options":["traceroute","ping","arp -a","netstat"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"traceroute lists each router hop between the source and destination, which makes it the standard tool for isolating routing-path problems.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Day 9_hardened_distractors.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — traceroute lists each router hop between source and destination, isolating where a routing-path problem occurs.","Wrong — ping confirms basic reachability but does not show the hops along the way.","Wrong — arp -a shows local ARP entries, not the path to a remote server.","Wrong — netstat shows local connection state, not the hop-by-hop path to a destination."]},{"id":420,"question":"A network technician is investigating intermittent connectivity drops on a wireless network where multiple Internet of Things (IoT) sensors report fluctuating received signal strength indicator (RSSI) values. Which issue is the MOST likely cause?","options":["radio frequency (RF) interference","Incorrect service set identifier (SSID) broadcast","Improper virtual local area network (VLAN) tagging","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) scope exhaustion"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Internet of Things (IoT) devices are highly sensitive to radio frequency (RF) noise, causing fluctuating signal strength.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — IoT sensors are especially sensitive to RF interference, which produces fluctuating RSSI and intermittent drops.","Wrong — an incorrect SSID would prevent association entirely rather than cause fluctuating signal strength on connected devices.","Wrong — improper VLAN tagging affects Layer 2 segmentation, not wireless signal strength readings.","Wrong — DHCP scope exhaustion would prevent address assignment, not cause RSSI fluctuation on already-connected sensors."]},{"id":421,"question":"A user reports that their workstation receives an Automatic Private IP Addressing (APIPA) address after rebooting. Which device is MOST likely failing to respond?","options":["Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) server","Domain Name System (DNS) server, which affects name resolution, not addressing","Default gateway, which affects routing to other subnets, not address assignment","Proxy server, which affects application traffic, not IP address assignment"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Automatic Private IP Addressing (APIPA) indicates the client could not obtain a Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) lease.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.3","objective":"Network Service Issues","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — an APIPA address appears specifically when a client cannot reach a DHCP server to obtain a lease.","Wrong — a DNS server failure affects name resolution, not the ability to obtain an IP address via DHCP.","Wrong — a default gateway failure would affect routing to remote networks, not cause an APIPA address to be assigned.","Wrong — a proxy server failure affects application-layer access, not DHCP address assignment."]},{"id":422,"question":"A technician needs to ensure that a router dynamically learns the best path to remote networks using hop count as its primary metric. Which protocol should be enabled?","options":["Routing Information Protocol (RIP)","Open Shortest Path First (OSPF)","Border Gateway Protocol (BGP)","Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Routing Information Protocol (RIP) uses hop count as its sole routing metric.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — RIP uses hop count as its sole metric to choose the best path to remote networks.","Wrong — OSPF uses cost, based on interface bandwidth, rather than hop count as its metric.","Wrong — BGP uses path attributes such as AS-path, not hop count, for path selection.","Wrong — EIGRP uses a composite metric of bandwidth and delay by default, not simple hop count."]},{"id":423,"question":"A network engineer is deploying a high-availability pair of firewalls that share a virtual IP for seamless failover. Which protocol supports this design?","options":["Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol (VRRP)","Hot Standby Router Protocol (HSRP)","Gateway Load Balancing Protocol (GLBP)","Common Address Redundancy Protocol (CARP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol (VRRP) provides router redundancy using a shared virtual IP.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.1","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — VRRP is the open standard protocol that provides router redundancy using a shared virtual IP address.","Wrong — HSRP is Cisco's proprietary equivalent to VRRP, not the vendor-neutral standard.","Wrong — GLBP adds load balancing across multiple routers, going beyond simple shared virtual IP failover.","Wrong — CARP is a BSD-based redundancy protocol, less commonly the standards-based answer expected here."]},{"id":424,"question":"A help desk technician observes that a user cannot resolve hostnames but can reach websites by IP. Which service is MOST likely misconfigured?","options":["Domain Name System (DNS)","NTP","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)","SMTP"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Domain Name System (DNS) resolves hostnames to IP addresses.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — DNS resolves hostnames to IP addresses, so a failure here explains being able to reach sites by IP but not by name.","Wrong — NTP synchronizes time and has no role in hostname resolution.","Wrong — SNMP is used for device monitoring and management, unrelated to name resolution.","Wrong — SMTP handles email transport, unrelated to hostname resolution for browsing."]},{"id":425,"question":"A wireless survey reveals that clients frequently roam between access points (APs) even when stationary. Which configuration is MOST likely incorrect?","options":["Transmit power levels","service set identifier (SSID) naming","WPA version","Channel width"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Excessive power overlap causes unnecessary roaming.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — excessive transmit power causes overlapping coverage cells, leading clients to roam unnecessarily even while stationary.","Wrong — SSID naming is cosmetic and does not cause roaming behavior.","Wrong — the WPA version affects security negotiation, not roaming decisions based on signal strength.","Wrong — channel width affects throughput and interference, not the roaming trigger itself."]},{"id":426,"question":"A technician needs to connect two switches over a long-distance fiber link using a connector with a square body and push-pull design. Which connector should be used?","options":["subscriber connector (SC)","LC","ST","MT-RJ"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"subscriber connector (SC) connectors use a square form factor and push-pull locking.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — the SC (subscriber connector) uses a square body with a push-pull locking mechanism.","Wrong — the LC connector is smaller with a latch clip, not a square push-pull body.","Wrong — the ST connector uses a round bayonet twist-lock design, not push-pull.","Wrong — the MT-RJ connector is a small-form-factor duplex connector, not the square push-pull design described."]},{"id":427,"question":"A network administrator wants to segment broadcast domains while maintaining a single physical switch. Which technology should be implemented?","options":["virtual local area networks (VLANs)","Quality of Service (QoS)","Network Address Translation (NAT)","Port mirroring"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"virtual local area networks (VLANs) logically segment networks on a single switch.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — VLANs logically separate broadcast domains on a single physical switch.","Wrong — QoS prioritizes traffic types; it does not create separate broadcast domains.","Wrong — NAT translates addresses between networks; it doesn't segment broadcast domains on one switch.","Wrong — port mirroring copies traffic for monitoring; it has no effect on broadcast domain segmentation."]},{"id":428,"question":"A technician suspects a duplex mismatch between a switch and a server. Which symptom is MOST likely observed?","options":["Late collisions","High CPU usage","Incorrect virtual local area network (VLAN) assignment","Domain Name System (DNS) failures"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Duplex mismatches commonly cause collisions and poor throughput.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.2","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — a duplex mismatch classically produces late collisions on the full-duplex side of the link.","Wrong — high CPU usage is a device performance symptom, not the classic sign of a duplex mismatch.","Wrong — VLAN assignment issues are a configuration problem unrelated to duplex settings.","Wrong — DNS failures relate to name resolution, not physical-layer duplex negotiation."]},{"id":429,"question":"A cloud architect needs a model where the customer manages applications but not the underlying OS. Which service model applies?","options":["Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Software as a Service (SaaS)","Desktop as a Service (DaaS)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Platform as a Service (PaaS) abstracts OS management while allowing application control.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — PaaS gives customers control over applications and data while the provider manages the underlying OS and infrastructure.","Wrong — IaaS requires the customer to manage the OS themselves, unlike PaaS.","Wrong — SaaS gives the customer only the application itself, with no platform-level control at all.","Wrong — DaaS delivers virtual desktops, not an application platform abstracted from OS management."]},{"id":430,"question":"A user reports slow file transfers to a network-attached storage (NAS) device during routine operations. The technician notes the network-attached storage (NAS) is connected via a 100 megabits per second (Mbps) interface while the rest of the network operates at 1 gigabits per second (Gbps). Which corrective action would MOST improve throughput?","options":["Upgrade the network-attached storage (NAS) link to 1 gigabits per second (Gbps)","Change the network-attached storage (NAS) IP address","Disable jumbo frames","Move the network-attached storage (NAS) to a different virtual local area network (VLAN)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A 100 megabits per second (Mbps) bottleneck limits transfer speeds; upgrading the link removes the constraint.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — the 100 Mbps NAS interface is the bottleneck; upgrading it to 1 Gbps removes the throughput ceiling.","Wrong — changing the IP address has no effect on link speed or throughput.","Wrong — disabling jumbo frames would not resolve a fundamental link-speed bottleneck and could reduce efficiency further.","Wrong — moving the NAS to a different VLAN changes logical segmentation, not the physical link speed limiting throughput."]},{"id":431,"question":"A technician must enable secure remote command-line administration of a router across an untrusted network. Which protocol BEST satisfies this requirement?","options":["Secure Shell (SSH)","Telnet","Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP)","Virtual Network Computing (VNC)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Secure Shell (SSH) encrypts terminal sessions, unlike Telnet.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — SSH encrypts the entire terminal session, protecting credentials and commands over an untrusted network.","Wrong — Telnet sends all session data, including credentials, in plaintext.","Wrong — RDP is designed for graphical remote desktop access, not command-line router administration.","Wrong — VNC provides graphical remote control, not the command-line access needed here."]},{"id":432,"question":"A network engineer is configuring a protocol that manages multicast group membership for streaming applications. Which protocol is required?","options":["Internet Group Management Protocol (IGMP)","Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP)","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)","Session Initiation Protocol (SIP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Internet Group Management Protocol (IGMP) handles multicast group join/leave operations.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — IGMP manages multicast group membership, letting hosts join or leave multicast streams.","Wrong — ICMP handles diagnostic messaging like ping, not multicast group membership.","Wrong — SNMP is used for device monitoring and management, not multicast membership.","Wrong — SIP handles session setup for voice/video calls, not multicast group management."]},{"id":433,"question":"A technician needs to determine the path packets take to reach a remote server experiencing latency. Which diagnostic tool should be used?","options":["traceroute","ping","nslookup","dig"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Traceroute reveals each hop and its response time.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — traceroute shows each hop to the destination along with per-hop response time, isolating where latency builds up.","Wrong — ping tests overall reachability and round-trip time but doesn't show the individual hops.","Wrong — nslookup queries DNS records, unrelated to the path packets take.","Wrong — dig also queries DNS, providing no hop-by-hop path information."]},{"id":434,"question":"A user reports choppy Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) audio during peak network utilization. Which configuration is MOST likely missing?","options":["Quality of Service (QoS)","Port mirroring","Network Address Translation (NAT)","virtual local area network (VLAN) trunking"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Quality of Service (QoS) prioritizes latency-sensitive traffic such as Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP).","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.4","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — QoS prioritizes latency-sensitive traffic like VoIP so it isn't degraded during periods of congestion.","Wrong — port mirroring copies traffic for monitoring; it does not prioritize traffic.","Wrong — NAT translates addresses; it has no effect on voice call quality under congestion.","Wrong — VLAN trunking carries multiple VLANs over one link but does not by itself prioritize voice traffic."]},{"id":435,"question":"A network administrator wants to prevent unauthorized devices from connecting to switch ports in a wiring closet. Which feature should be implemented?","options":["Port security","Port mirroring","Quality of Service (QoS)","Network Address Translation (NAT)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Port security restricts allowed media access control (MAC) addresses.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — port security restricts which MAC addresses may connect to a switch port, blocking unauthorized devices.","Wrong — port mirroring copies traffic for analysis; it does not restrict device connections.","Wrong — QoS prioritizes traffic types; it has no role in restricting which devices can connect.","Wrong — NAT translates IP addresses; it does not control physical port access."]},{"id":436,"question":"A technician needs to connect a workstation to a switch using twisted-pair copper cabling. Which cable type is appropriate?","options":["Straight-through","Crossover","Rollover","Console"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Straight-through cables connect unlike devices.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — a straight-through cable connects unlike devices, such as a workstation to a switch.","Wrong — a crossover cable connects like devices, such as switch to switch or NIC to NIC directly.","Wrong — a rollover cable is used for console management connections, not standard data connections.","Wrong — a console cable is used to connect to a device's management port, not for a workstation-to-switch data link."]},{"id":437,"question":"A router must translate multiple internal private IP addresses to a single public IP for outbound traffic. Which technology enables this?","options":["Port Address Translation (PAT)","Static Network Address Translation (NAT)","Domain Name System (DNS)","Proxy Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Port Address Translation (PAT) maps many internal hosts to one public IP using port numbers.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — PAT maps many internal private addresses to one public IP by tracking unique source port numbers.","Wrong — static NAT maps one private address to one public address on a one-to-one basis, not many to one.","Wrong — DNS resolves names to addresses; it does not translate or share a single public IP among hosts.","Wrong — Proxy ARP answers ARP requests on behalf of another host; it does not translate addresses for outbound traffic."]},{"id":438,"question":"A network engineer needs to ensure routing updates between Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) neighbors are authenticated. Which feature should be configured?","options":["Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) authentication","Routing Information Protocol (RIP) authentication","Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) communities","Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP) variance"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) supports Message Digest 5 (MD5)/Secure Hash Algorithm (SHA) authentication to secure routing exchanges.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — OSPF authentication verifies that routing updates between OSPF neighbors are legitimate before they are accepted.","Wrong — RIP authentication would apply only if RIP were in use; it is unrelated to OSPF neighbor security.","Wrong — BGP communities are used for route tagging and policy, not for authenticating OSPF exchanges.","Wrong — EIGRP variance controls unequal-cost load balancing in EIGRP, unrelated to OSPF authentication."]},{"id":439,"question":"A technician must identify which switch port a rogue device is connected to. Which tool is MOST helpful?","options":["Switch port mapping","Protocol analyzer","Tone generator","Loopback plug"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Port mapping correlates media access control (MAC) addresses to switch interfaces.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — switch port mapping correlates a device's MAC address to the specific switch interface it's connected to.","Wrong — a protocol analyzer captures packet content, not the physical port location of a device.","Wrong — a tone generator traces cable paths but doesn't identify a device's switch port by MAC address.","Wrong — a loopback plug tests NIC transmit/receive function, unrelated to locating a rogue device."]},{"id":440,"question":"A user reports frequent VPN disconnects. Logs show fragmentation due to encapsulation overhead. Which adjustment is MOST appropriate?","options":["Lower the maximum transmission unit (MTU)","Increase the TTL","Change the subnet mask","Disable Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"VPN encapsulation reduces effective maximum transmission unit (MTU); lowering it prevents fragmentation.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — lowering the MTU compensates for the overhead added by VPN encapsulation, preventing fragmentation-related disconnects.","Wrong — increasing the TTL only affects how many hops a packet can traverse, not fragmentation from encapsulation overhead.","Wrong — changing the subnet mask affects local addressing, not encapsulation-caused fragmentation.","Wrong — disabling DHCP affects address assignment, unrelated to VPN packet fragmentation."]},{"id":441,"question":"A technician suspects a copper cable has split pairs. Which tool should be used to confirm this?","options":["Cable certifier","Tone generator and probe","Loopback plug","Punchdown tool"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Certifiers detect wiring faults including split pairs.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — a cable certifier tests for wiring faults such as split pairs against category standards.","Wrong — a tone generator and probe trace cable paths; they do not detect split-pair wiring faults.","Wrong — a loopback plug tests NIC transmit/receive function, not cable wiring faults.","Wrong — a punchdown tool terminates cable into a jack or patch panel; it does not test for split pairs."]},{"id":442,"question":"A network engineer needs a routing protocol that converges quickly and uses cost as its primary metric. Which protocol fits this requirement?","options":["Open Shortest Path First (OSPF)","Routing Information Protocol (RIP)","Border Gateway Protocol (BGP)","IS-IS"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) uses cost and converges faster than distance-vector protocols.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — OSPF uses cost as its metric and converges faster than distance-vector protocols like RIP.","Wrong — RIP uses simple hop count and converges more slowly due to periodic updates.","Wrong — BGP is a path-vector protocol designed for inter-domain routing, not fast intra-domain convergence based on cost.","Wrong — IS-IS is a link-state protocol similar to OSPF but is not the protocol most commonly cited for this requirement in this context."]},{"id":443,"question":"A technician needs to isolate a suspected broadcast storm on a switch. Which metric is MOST useful?","options":["Interface utilization","CPU temperature","Domain Name System (DNS) query count","NTP offset"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Broadcast storms cause abnormally high interface usage.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — a broadcast storm drives interface utilization abnormally high, making it the most direct indicator.","Wrong — CPU temperature reflects thermal conditions, not traffic volume from a broadcast storm.","Wrong — DNS query count reflects name-resolution activity, unrelated to broadcast traffic levels.","Wrong — NTP offset reflects clock drift, unrelated to broadcast storm detection."]},{"id":444,"question":"A wireless engineer must support high-density client environments using multi-user, multiple input, multiple output (MU-MIMO). Which wireless standard is required?","options":["802.11ac Wave 2","802.11a","802.11b","802.11g"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"multi-user, multiple input, multiple output (MU-MIMO) was introduced in 802.11ac Wave 2.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — MU-MIMO was introduced with 802.11ac Wave 2, enabling simultaneous multi-client streams.","Wrong — 802.11a predates MU-MIMO and lacks the necessary spatial stream support.","Wrong — 802.11b is an older, low-throughput standard without MU-MIMO capability.","Wrong — 802.11g also predates MU-MIMO and does not support it."]},{"id":445,"question":"A technician must ensure that only encrypted management traffic is permitted when administering a switch. Which protocol should be disabled to meet this requirement?","options":["Telnet","Secure Shell (SSH)","Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure (HTTPS)","Secure Shell (SSH) File Transfer Protocol (SFTP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Telnet transmits credentials in plaintext; disabling it enforces encrypted management.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — disabling Telnet removes the unencrypted management path, leaving only encrypted protocols available.","Wrong — SSH is the encrypted protocol that should remain enabled, not be disabled.","Wrong — HTTPS is already encrypted and should stay enabled for secure web-based management.","Wrong — SFTP is an encrypted file-transfer protocol and should remain enabled, not disabled."]},{"id":446,"question":"A network administrator needs to identify the physical distance to a suspected fiber break. Which tool is MOST appropriate?","options":["optical time-domain reflectometer (OTDR)","time-domain reflectometer (TDR)","Cable stripper","Crimper"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"optical time-domain reflectometer (OTDR) measures reflections to determine fault distance on fiber.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — an OTDR sends light pulses and measures reflections to pinpoint the distance to a fiber fault.","Wrong — a TDR performs a similar function for copper cabling, not fiber.","Wrong — a cable stripper prepares cable ends for termination; it does not measure fault distance.","Wrong — a crimper attaches connectors to cable; it provides no fault-distance measurement."]},{"id":447,"question":"A technician needs to verify whether a server is actively listening on Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 443. Which tool is MOST appropriate?","options":["netstat","ping","tracert","ipconfig"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Netstat displays active listening ports and connections.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — netstat lists listening ports and active connections, confirming whether port 443 is open.","Wrong — ping only tests ICMP reachability and cannot confirm whether a specific TCP port is listening.","Wrong — tracert maps the path to a destination; it does not show local or remote listening ports.","Wrong — ipconfig shows local IP configuration, not port-listening status."]},{"id":448,"question":"A network engineer must deploy a WAN technology that forwards packets based on labels rather than IP lookups. Which technology applies?","options":["Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS)","Frame Relay","Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM)","Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) uses label switching for efficient forwarding.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — MPLS forwards packets using labels rather than full IP lookups at each hop, improving forwarding efficiency.","Wrong — Frame Relay is an older packet-switching WAN technology that does not use MPLS-style label switching.","Wrong — ATM uses fixed-size cells and its own switching method, not IP-label-based forwarding.","Wrong — PPP is a point-to-point link protocol, not a label-switching WAN forwarding technology."]},{"id":449,"question":"A wireless administrator must enforce certificate-based authentication for all wireless clients. Which method should be implemented?","options":["Extensible Authentication Protocol-Transport Layer Security (EAP-TLS)","Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP), an outdated encryption standard with well-known cryptographic weaknesses","Wi-Fi Protected Access 2 Pre-Shared Key (WPA2-PSK), which uses a single shared passphrase rather than per-user certificates","MAC address filtering, which restricts association by hardware address rather than verifying identity"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Extensible Authentication Protocol-Transport Layer Security (EAP-TLS) requires client certificates for authentication.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — EAP-TLS requires clients to present a valid digital certificate, enforcing strong certificate-based authentication.","Wrong — WEP is a legacy encryption method with serious flaws and does not provide certificate-based authentication.","Wrong — WPA2-PSK authenticates with a shared passphrase known to all clients, not individual certificates.","Wrong — MAC filtering only checks a device's hardware address, which is easily spoofed and not certificate-based."]},{"id":450,"question":"A user reports that their workstation cannot reach the default gateway. Which command BEST verifies local IP configuration?","options":["ipconfig","ping 127.0.0.1","nslookup","route print"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Ipconfig displays IP address, gateway, and subnet mask.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — ipconfig shows the assigned IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway, confirming local configuration first.","Wrong — pinging the loopback address (127.0.0.1) only tests the local TCP/IP stack, not the actual configured gateway.","Wrong — nslookup queries DNS servers and does not display local IP configuration.","Wrong — route print shows the routing table, which is a secondary step after confirming basic IP configuration."]},{"id":451,"question":"A technician needs to prevent switching loops when connecting redundant links between switches. Which protocol should be enabled?","options":["Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)","Link Layer Discovery Protocol (LLDP)","Cisco Discovery Protocol (CDP)","LACP"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) prevents loops by blocking redundant paths.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — STP detects redundant links between switches and blocks the ones that would otherwise create a loop.","Wrong — LLDP is a discovery protocol for advertising device information; it does not prevent switching loops.","Wrong — CDP is Cisco's proprietary discovery protocol, similarly used for information exchange, not loop prevention.","Wrong — LACP bundles multiple links into a single logical link but does not itself prevent loops across separate redundant links."]},{"id":452,"question":"A network engineer needs to aggregate Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) traps and logs from multiple devices into a centralized system. Which solution is MOST appropriate?","options":["security information and event management (SIEM)","Proxy server","Web server","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) server"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"security information and event management (SIEM) platforms collect and correlate logs and alerts.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — a SIEM platform is built to aggregate, correlate, and analyze logs and alerts such as SNMP traps from many devices.","Wrong — a proxy server forwards client requests; it does not aggregate logs or traps from network devices.","Wrong — a web server hosts content; it has no role in collecting SNMP traps or logs.","Wrong — a DHCP server assigns IP addresses; it does not aggregate logging or trap data."]},{"id":453,"question":"A technician needs Domain Name System (DNS) records to automatically update when Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) leases change. Which feature is required?","options":["Dynamic Domain Name System (DNS)","Static Domain Name System (DNS)","Reverse Domain Name System (DNS) only","Split-horizon Domain Name System (DNS)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Dynamic Domain Name System (DDNS) updates Domain Name System (DNS) entries automatically.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — Dynamic DNS automatically updates DNS records when a client's DHCP-assigned address changes.","Wrong — static DNS requires manual updates and would not reflect DHCP lease changes automatically.","Wrong — reverse DNS only maps addresses back to names; it doesn't provide automatic forward-record updates on lease changes.","Wrong — split-horizon DNS serves different answers based on the requester's location, which is unrelated to automatic updates on lease changes."]},{"id":454,"question":"A network administrator must block traffic from a specific IP range at the router. Which tool is MOST appropriate?","options":["access control list (ACL)","Quality of Service (QoS)","Network Address Translation (NAT)","Port mirroring"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"ACLs filter traffic based on IP criteria.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.3","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — an ACL can filter and block traffic from a specific IP range at the router.","Wrong — QoS prioritizes traffic; it does not block traffic based on IP range.","Wrong — NAT translates addresses; it does not filter or block traffic by IP range.","Wrong — port mirroring copies traffic for monitoring; it does not block any traffic."]},{"id":455,"question":"A technician needs to verify that a fiber link supports multiple simultaneous wavelengths. Which technology enables this?","options":["dense wavelength-division multiplexing (DWDM)","coarse wavelength-division multiplexing (CWDM)","Power over Ethernet (PoE)","Data Over Cable Service Interface Specification (DOCSIS)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"dense wavelength-division multiplexing (DWDM) multiplexes many wavelengths over a single fiber.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — DWDM multiplexes many distinct wavelengths onto a single fiber, enabling simultaneous multi-channel transmission.","Wrong — CWDM multiplexes fewer wavelengths with wider spacing, offering less channel density than DWDM.","Wrong — PoE delivers electrical power over Ethernet cabling and has nothing to do with wavelength multiplexing.","Wrong — DOCSIS is a cable modem standard, unrelated to fiber wavelength multiplexing."]},{"id":456,"question":"A network engineer must deploy a protocol that securely encapsulates traffic for site-to-site VPN tunnels. Which protocol applies?","options":["Internet Protocol Security (IPSec)","FTP, a protocol for transferring files that does not provide encryption or tunneling for VPN traffic","TFTP, a simple unauthenticated file transfer protocol unsuitable for secure VPN tunneling","SMTP, a mail transport protocol with no support for encapsulating VPN tunnel traffic"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Internet Protocol Security (IPSec) provides encrypted tunneling for VPNs.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — IPSec provides authenticated, encrypted tunneling used to secure site-to-site VPN traffic.","Wrong — FTP transfers files in the clear and provides no VPN tunneling or encryption capability.","Wrong — TFTP is an even simpler, unauthenticated file-transfer protocol with no VPN function.","Wrong — SMTP transports email between mail servers and has no VPN tunneling capability."]},{"id":457,"question":"A technician needs to determine whether a copper cable run exceeds the maximum supported distance. Which standard defines these limits?","options":["Telecommunications Industry Association/Electronic Industries Alliance (TIA/EIA)","Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) 802.3af, which defines Power over Ethernet delivery, not cable distance limits","Request for Comments 1918 (RFC 1918), which defines private IP address ranges, not cabling distance standards","International Organization for Standardization 27001 (ISO 27001), an information security management standard unrelated to cable distances"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Telecommunications Industry Association/Electronic Industries Alliance (TIA/EIA) standards define cable categories and distance limits.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.1","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — TIA/EIA standards define copper cable categories and their maximum supported distances.","Wrong — IEEE 802.3af defines Power over Ethernet delivery, not cable distance limits.","Wrong — RFC 1918 defines private IP address ranges, unrelated to physical cable distance limits.","Wrong — ISO 27001 is an information security management standard, unrelated to cabling distance specifications."]},{"id":458,"question":"A user cannot join the wireless network after a password change. Which setting is MOST likely incorrect?","options":["pre-shared key (PSK)","Channel","service set identifier (SSID) broadcast","media access control (MAC) address"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An incorrect pre-shared key prevents association.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — an incorrect pre-shared key prevents successful authentication and association after a password change.","Wrong — the wireless channel does not depend on the client's password and wouldn't change due to a password update.","Wrong — SSID broadcast visibility is unrelated to whether the correct password is entered.","Wrong — MAC address filtering is based on hardware address, not affected by a password change."]},{"id":459,"question":"A technician needs to confirm that a switch is learning media access control (MAC) addresses dynamically. Which table stores this information?","options":["content-addressable memory (CAM) table","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) table","Routing table","Domain Name System (DNS) cache"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"content-addressable memory (CAM) tables map media access control (MAC) addresses to switch ports.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — the CAM table stores the dynamically learned MAC-address-to-port mappings on a switch.","Wrong — the ARP table maps IP addresses to MAC addresses, a Layer 3-to-Layer 2 mapping, not switch port learning.","Wrong — a routing table stores network-to-next-hop information, not switch MAC learning.","Wrong — the DNS cache stores resolved hostname-to-IP mappings, unrelated to switch MAC learning."]},{"id":460,"question":"A network engineer must deploy a protocol that tunnels Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) traffic across an Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) infrastructure. Which protocol applies?","options":["6to4","Network Address Translation 64 (NAT64)","Routing Information Protocol next generation (RIPng)","Extended Unique Identifier-64 (EUI-64)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"6to4 encapsulates Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) packets inside Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4).","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — 6to4 encapsulates IPv6 packets within IPv4 headers to tunnel IPv6 traffic across an IPv4 network.","Wrong — NAT64 translates between IPv6 and IPv4 addressing rather than tunneling IPv6 inside IPv4.","Wrong — RIPng is an IPv6 version of RIP for routing, not a tunneling mechanism.","Wrong — EUI-64 is an address-generation method for IPv6 interface identifiers, not a tunneling protocol."]},{"id":461,"question":"A technician needs to verify whether a server responds to Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) echo requests. Which tool should be used?","options":["ping","netstat","tracert","ipconfig"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Ping tests Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) reachability.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — ping sends ICMP echo requests and reports whether the server responds, confirming basic reachability.","Wrong — netstat shows local connections and listening ports, not ICMP echo responses.","Wrong — tracert shows the hop path to a destination, which is more detail than simply confirming an echo reply.","Wrong — ipconfig shows local IP configuration, not remote host reachability."]},{"id":462,"question":"A network administrator must prevent unauthorized Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) servers from assigning IP addresses. Which feature should be enabled?","options":["Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) snooping","Port mirroring, which copies traffic for monitoring but does not block rogue DHCP responses","Quality of Service (QoS), which prioritizes traffic types but does not filter DHCP server messages","Network Address Translation (NAT), which translates addresses but has no role in validating DHCP servers"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) snooping blocks untrusted Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) responses.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — DHCP snooping filters DHCP messages at the switch, blocking responses from untrusted, unauthorized DHCP servers.","Wrong — port mirroring copies traffic for monitoring; it does not block rogue DHCP server responses.","Wrong — QoS prioritizes traffic types; it has no role in filtering DHCP messages.","Wrong — NAT translates addresses; it does not validate or block DHCP server responses."]},{"id":463,"question":"A technician needs to identify which virtual local area network (VLAN) a specific switch port belongs to. Which command is MOST useful?","options":["show vlan","show ip route","show mac address-table","show interfaces status"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"This command displays virtual local area network (VLAN) assignments on the switch.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.5","objective":"Troubleshooting Tools & Commands","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — show vlan lists VLAN definitions and the ports assigned to each VLAN.","Wrong — show ip route displays the routing table, not VLAN port assignments.","Wrong — show mac address-table shows MAC-to-port mappings, not which VLAN a port belongs to.","Wrong — show interfaces status shows link state and speed/duplex, not detailed VLAN membership."]},{"id":464,"question":"A network engineer must ensure that wireless clients use the strongest available encryption. Which protocol should be enforced?","options":["WPA3","Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP)","WPA","Wi‑Fi Protected Access 2-Pre-Shared Key (WPA2-PSK) (TKIP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"WPA3 is the most secure Wi-Fi encryption standard currently available.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Review 2.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — WPA3 is the current strongest Wi-Fi security standard and should be enforced for the best available encryption.","Wrong — WEP is an outdated, broken encryption standard and far weaker than WPA3.","Wrong — WPA is an older standard superseded by WPA2 and WPA3, offering weaker protection.","Wrong — WPA2-PSK with TKIP uses an aging cipher that is weaker than WPA3's encryption."]},{"id":465,"question":"At which Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) layer does a switch primarily operate when forwarding Ethernet frames within a local area network (LAN)?","options":["Layer 1 – Physical","Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 4 – Transport"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Switches forward frames based on media access control (MAC) addresses at the Data Link layer (Layer 2).","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — Layer 1 handles raw bit transmission over physical media, not frame forwarding decisions.","Correct — switches forward Ethernet frames based on MAC addresses, which is a Data Link layer (Layer 2) function.","Wrong — Layer 3 handles logical addressing and routing between networks, which is the router's job, not the switch's basic frame forwarding.","Wrong — Layer 4 handles end-to-end transport functions like segmentation, unrelated to frame forwarding."]},{"id":466,"question":"Which Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) layer is responsible for end-to-end logical addressing and routing between networks?","options":["Layer 2 – Data Link","Layer 3 – Network","Layer 4 – Transport","Layer 7 – Application"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"The Network layer (Layer 3) handles logical addressing (Internet Protocol (IP)) and routing between networks.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.1","objective":"OSI Model & Networking Concepts","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — Layer 2 handles frame forwarding using MAC addresses within a single network segment, not routing between networks.","Correct — Layer 3, the Network layer, handles logical IP addressing and routing packets between different networks.","Wrong — Layer 4 manages end-to-end communication and reliability, not logical addressing and routing.","Wrong — Layer 7 is the Application layer, dealing with user-facing services, not routing."]},{"id":467,"question":"Which port is used by Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure (HTTPS) to securely access websites over Transport Layer Security (TLS)?","options":["Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) 80","Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) 21","Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) 443","User Datagram Protocol (UDP) 53"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure (HTTPS) uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 443 for secure web traffic over Transport Layer Security (TLS)/Secure Sockets Layer (SSL).","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — TCP port 80 is used for unencrypted HTTP traffic, not HTTPS.","Wrong — TCP port 21 is used by FTP for control connections, unrelated to HTTPS.","Correct — HTTPS uses TCP port 443 to secure web traffic with TLS/SSL encryption.","Wrong — UDP port 53 is used for DNS queries, not secure web traffic."]},{"id":468,"question":"Which protocol and port combination is most appropriate for secure remote command-line access to a Linux server?","options":["Telnet on Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) 23","Secure Shell (SSH) on Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) 22","Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) on Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) 3389","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) on User Datagram Protocol (UDP) 161"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Secure Shell (SSH) on Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) 22 provides encrypted remote command-line access.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.4","objective":"Ports, Protocols, Services & Traffic Types","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — Telnet on TCP 23 transmits data in plaintext and is not secure.","Correct — SSH on TCP port 22 provides encrypted remote command-line access, ideal for Linux server administration.","Wrong — RDP on TCP 3389 provides graphical remote desktop access, typically for Windows systems, not command-line Linux access.","Wrong — SNMP on UDP 161 is used for device monitoring, not remote command-line access."]},{"id":469,"question":"Which twisted-pair cable category is rated for 10 gigabits per second (Gbps) at up to 100 meters?","options":["Category 5e (CAT 5e)","Category 6 (CAT 6)","Category 6A (CAT 6A)","CAT 3"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Category 6A (CAT 6A) supports 10 gigabits per second (Gbps) up to 100 meters and is designed to reduce alien crosstalk.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — CAT 5e is rated for up to 1 Gbps, not the 10 Gbps required here.","Wrong — CAT 6 can reach 10 Gbps only over shorter distances (about 55 meters), not the full 100 meters.","Correct — CAT 6A is rated for 10 Gbps at the full 100-meter distance, with improved alien crosstalk protection.","Wrong — CAT 3 supports only very low data rates and is far below the 10 Gbps requirement."]},{"id":470,"question":"Which connector type is most commonly used for Ethernet over twisted-pair cabling?","options":["registered jack 11 (RJ-11)","registered jack 45 (RJ-45)","Lucent Connector (LC)","Bayonet Neill–Concelman (BNC)"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"registered jack 45 (RJ-45) connectors are used for Ethernet over twisted-pair cabling.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — RJ-11 is used for telephone connections, not Ethernet.","Correct — RJ-45 is the standard connector used for Ethernet over twisted-pair cabling.","Wrong — LC is a fiber-optic connector, not used for twisted-pair Ethernet.","Wrong — BNC is used with coaxial cable, not twisted-pair Ethernet."]},{"id":471,"question":"Which Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) standard defines 5 gigahertz (GHz)-only Wi-Fi with maximum theoretical speeds up to 6.9 gigabits per second (Gbps) (with later amendments)?","options":["802.11n","802.11ac","802.11g","802.11b"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"802.11ac operates in the 5 gigahertz (GHz) band and supports very high throughput with multiple spatial streams.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — 802.11n operates in both 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz bands with lower maximum theoretical speeds than 802.11ac.","Correct — 802.11ac is a 5 GHz-only standard with maximum theoretical speeds up to 6.9 Gbps in later amendments.","Wrong — 802.11g operates only in the 2.4 GHz band with much lower maximum speeds.","Wrong — 802.11b is an older 2.4 GHz standard with far lower maximum speeds."]},{"id":472,"question":"Which security protocol is currently recommended for securing Wi-Fi networks in modern environments?","options":["Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP), a legacy encryption standard broken by well-known cryptographic attacks","Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA), an early replacement for WEP that still relies on the weaker RC4 cipher","Wi‑Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) or Wi‑Fi Protected Access 3 (WPA3)","Open network with no encryption at all, leaving all wireless traffic unprotected"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Wi‑Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) and Wi‑Fi Protected Access 3 (WPA3) are the recommended Wi-Fi security standards; Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) and early Wi‑Fi Protected Access (WPA) are considered insecure.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — WEP's encryption has been broken for years and is no longer considered secure.","Wrong — early WPA still depends on the weaker RC4 cipher and is considered outdated.","Correct — WPA2 and WPA3 are the currently recommended standards for securing Wi-Fi networks.","Wrong — an open network provides no encryption, leaving traffic completely exposed."]},{"id":473,"question":"Which of the following is a valid private Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) address?","options":["8.8.8.8","172.16.10.5","192.0.2.10","11.0.0.1"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"172.16.0.0–172.31.255.255 is a private Class B range; 172.16.10.5 is valid private addressing.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — 8.8.8.8 is a public IP address, not part of any private range.","Correct — 172.16.10.5 falls within the private Class B range of 172.16.0.0–172.31.255.255.","Wrong — 192.0.2.10 is part of the TEST-NET-1 documentation range, not a private range.","Wrong — 11.0.0.1 is a public IP address, not within any of the reserved private ranges."]},{"id":474,"question":"Which protocol automatically assigns Internet Protocol (IP) addresses, subnet masks, and default gateways to hosts on a network?","options":["Domain Name System (DNS)","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP)","Network Time Protocol (NTP)","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) dynamically assigns Internet Protocol (IP) configuration information to clients.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — DNS resolves hostnames to IP addresses; it does not assign IP configuration.","Correct — DHCP automatically assigns IP addresses, subnet masks, and default gateways to hosts.","Wrong — NTP synchronizes time between devices and has no role in IP address assignment.","Wrong — SNMP is used for monitoring and managing devices, not assigning IP configuration."]},{"id":475,"question":"Which routing protocol is a distance-vector protocol that uses hop count as its metric and has a maximum of 15 hops?","options":["Open Shortest Path First (OSPF)","Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP)","Routing Information Protocol (RIP)","Border Gateway Protocol (BGP)"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Routing Information Protocol (RIP) is a distance-vector protocol with hop count as its metric and a maximum of 15 hops.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — OSPF is a link-state protocol using cost as its metric, not hop count.","Wrong — EIGRP is an advanced distance-vector protocol using a composite bandwidth/delay metric, not simple hop count with a 15-hop limit.","Correct — RIP is a distance-vector protocol that uses hop count as its metric and limits routes to 15 hops.","Wrong — BGP is a path-vector protocol used for routing between autonomous systems, not a simple hop-count protocol."]},{"id":476,"question":"Which routing protocol is link-state and uses areas and link-state advertisements (LSAs) to build a complete topology of the network?","options":["Routing Information Protocol (RIP)","Open Shortest Path First (OSPF)","Border Gateway Protocol (BGP)","Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP)"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) is a link-state protocol that uses link-state advertisements (LSAs) and areas to build a topology map.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.1","objective":"Routing Technologies","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — RIP is a distance-vector protocol using hop count, not a link-state protocol with areas and LSAs.","Correct — OSPF is a link-state protocol that uses areas and LSAs to build a full topology map of the network.","Wrong — BGP is a path-vector protocol for routing between autonomous systems, not an area-based link-state protocol.","Wrong — EIGRP is an advanced distance-vector protocol and does not use areas and LSAs the way OSPF does."]},{"id":477,"question":"Which technology allows multiple virtual local area networks (VLANs) to be carried over a single physical switch-to-switch link?","options":["Port mirroring, which copies traffic to a monitoring port and has no role in carrying multiple VLANs over a link","Trunking (Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) 802.1Q)","Port security, which restricts which MAC addresses may connect to a port, unrelated to carrying multiple VLANs","Spanning Tree, which prevents Layer 2 loops but does not itself allow multiple VLANs across one link"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) 802.1Q trunking tags frames so multiple virtual local area networks (VLANs) can traverse a single physical link.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — port mirroring duplicates traffic for monitoring and has no role in carrying VLANs across a link.","Correct — 802.1Q trunking tags Ethernet frames so multiple VLANs can be carried over a single physical link.","Wrong — port security restricts which MAC addresses may use a port; it doesn't carry multiple VLANs.","Wrong — Spanning Tree prevents Layer 2 loops but does not itself enable multiple VLANs on one link."]},{"id":478,"question":"Which protocol prevents switching loops by placing redundant links into a blocking state?","options":["VLAN Trunking Protocol (VTP)","Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)","Link Layer Discovery Protocol (LLDP)","Cisco Discovery Protocol (CDP)"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) prevents loops by blocking redundant paths.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — VTP synchronizes VLAN database information across switches; it does not prevent switching loops.","Correct — STP prevents switching loops by placing redundant links into a blocking state.","Wrong — LLDP advertises device information for discovery purposes, not loop prevention.","Wrong — CDP is Cisco's proprietary discovery protocol, also unrelated to loop prevention."]},{"id":479,"question":"Which wide area network (WAN) technology uses labels to make forwarding decisions and is often used by service providers?","options":["Frame Relay","Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS)","Integrated Services Digital Network (ISDN)","Dial-up"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) uses labels instead of traditional Internet Protocol (IP) routing lookups to forward traffic efficiently.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.2","objective":"Switching Technologies","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — Frame Relay is an older packet-switching technology that does not use label-based forwarding.","Correct — MPLS uses labels rather than traditional IP lookups to make fast forwarding decisions, common among service providers.","Wrong — ISDN is a circuit-switched digital telephony technology, not a label-switching WAN technology.","Wrong — Dial-up uses analog phone lines for low-speed connections, unrelated to label switching."]},{"id":480,"question":"Which broadband technology uses existing telephone lines and supports different upstream and downstream speeds?","options":["Cable","Fiber-to-the-home","Digital Subscriber Line (DSL)","Satellite"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Digital Subscriber Line (DSL) uses copper telephone lines and often provides asymmetric speeds (Asymmetric Digital Subscriber Line (ADSL)).","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — cable broadband uses coaxial cable infrastructure, not telephone lines.","Wrong — fiber-to-the-home uses fiber-optic cabling, not existing copper telephone lines.","Correct — DSL uses existing telephone lines and commonly offers asymmetric upstream/downstream speeds.","Wrong — satellite uses a wireless link to an orbiting satellite, not telephone lines."]},{"id":481,"question":"Which Domain Name System (DNS) record type maps a hostname to an Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) address?","options":["quad-A (AAAA) record","mail exchange (MX) record","canonical name (CNAME) record","address (A) record"],"correctIndex":3,"explanation":"An address (A) record maps a hostname to an Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) address.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — an AAAA record maps a hostname to an IPv6 address, not IPv4.","Wrong — an MX record identifies mail servers for a domain, not a host's IP address.","Wrong — a CNAME record is an alias pointing to another hostname, not directly to an IP address.","Correct — an A record maps a hostname directly to an IPv4 address."]},{"id":482,"question":"Which protocol is used to synchronize time across network devices?","options":["Network Time Protocol (NTP)","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)","SMTP","IMAP"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Network Time Protocol (NTP) synchronizes clocks across network devices.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — NTP synchronizes clocks across network devices for accurate timekeeping.","Wrong — SNMP is used for monitoring and managing devices, not time synchronization.","Wrong — SMTP transports email between mail servers, unrelated to time synchronization.","Wrong — IMAP retrieves email from a mail server, unrelated to time synchronization."]},{"id":483,"question":"Which security concept ensures that users are granted only the permissions they need to perform their job functions?","options":["Defense in depth","Least privilege","Separation of duties","Implicit deny"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Least privilege restricts users to only the access necessary for their roles.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.1","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — defense in depth layers multiple security controls; it isn't specifically about limiting individual permissions.","Correct — least privilege restricts each user to only the access needed to perform their job.","Wrong — separation of duties divides tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud, a related but distinct concept.","Wrong — implicit deny blocks anything not explicitly allowed; it's a default-policy stance, not a permission-scoping principle."]},{"id":484,"question":"Which device is primarily used to inspect traffic at Layers 3 and 4 and enforce security policies between networks?","options":["Switch","Firewall","Hub","Repeater"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Firewalls inspect traffic and enforce security policies, typically at Layers 3 and 4.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.1","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a switch primarily forwards frames at Layer 2 based on MAC addresses, not Layer 3/4 policy enforcement.","Correct — a firewall inspects traffic and enforces security policy, typically at Layers 3 and 4.","Wrong — a hub simply repeats signals to all ports with no traffic inspection at all.","Wrong — a repeater regenerates signals at Layer 1 and performs no traffic inspection."]},{"id":485,"question":"Which protocol is commonly used for centralized authentication, authorization, and accounting for remote access and network devices?","options":["Domain Name System (DNS), which resolves hostnames to addresses and has no authentication or accounting function","Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS)","TFTP, a simple unauthenticated file-transfer protocol used for tasks like device firmware transfers","HTTP, a web transfer protocol with no built-in centralized authentication, authorization, or accounting capability"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) provides centralized authentication, authorization, and accounting (AAA) services for network access.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.1","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — DNS resolves names to IP addresses and provides no authentication, authorization, or accounting services.","Correct — RADIUS provides centralized authentication, authorization, and accounting for network and remote access.","Wrong — TFTP is a simple, unauthenticated file-transfer protocol with no AAA function.","Wrong — HTTP transfers web content and has no built-in centralized AAA capability."]},{"id":486,"question":"Which type of attack floods a target with traffic from many distributed sources to exhaust its resources?","options":["Phishing","Man-in-the-middle","Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS)","Structured Query Language (SQL) injection"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"A Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attack uses many sources to overwhelm a target.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.1","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — phishing tricks users into revealing information; it does not flood a target with traffic.","Wrong — a man-in-the-middle attack intercepts communications; it does not overwhelm a target with traffic volume.","Correct — a DDoS attack uses many distributed sources to flood a target and exhaust its resources.","Wrong — SQL injection manipulates database queries; it is unrelated to flooding a target with traffic."]},{"id":487,"question":"Which virtual private network (VPN) type connects entire networks to each other, such as a branch office to headquarters?","options":["Remote-access virtual private network (VPN)","Clientless Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) virtual private network (VPN)","Site-to-site virtual private network (VPN)","Host-to-host virtual private network (VPN)"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Site-to-site VPNs connect entire networks, typically using Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) tunnel mode between gateways.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a remote-access VPN connects individual users to a network, not two entire networks together.","Wrong — a clientless SSL VPN provides browser-based access to specific applications, not a full network-to-network connection.","Correct — a site-to-site VPN connects entire networks together, such as a branch office to headquarters.","Wrong — 'host-to-host VPN' is not the standard term for connecting two full networks together."]},{"id":488,"question":"Which Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) mode encrypts the entire original Internet Protocol (IP) packet and encapsulates it within a new Internet Protocol (IP) header?","options":["Transport mode","Tunnel mode","Promiscuous mode","Monitor mode"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) tunnel mode encrypts the entire original packet and adds a new outer Internet Protocol (IP) header.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — transport mode encrypts only the payload of the original packet, keeping the original IP header intact.","Correct — tunnel mode encrypts the entire original IP packet and wraps it in a new outer IP header.","Wrong — promiscuous mode allows a NIC to process all traffic it sees, unrelated to IPsec encapsulation.","Wrong — monitor mode allows a wireless NIC to capture all nearby wireless traffic, unrelated to IPsec modes."]},{"id":489,"question":"Which cloud service model provides virtual machines, storage, and networking while leaving OS and applications under customer control?","options":["Software as a Service (SaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Function as a Service (FaaS)"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) provides virtualized infrastructure; the customer manages OS, apps, and data.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — SaaS delivers a complete application, with the provider managing everything underneath it.","Wrong — PaaS provides a platform for building applications while the provider manages the underlying OS.","Correct — IaaS provides virtualized infrastructure such as VMs, storage, and networking, while the customer manages the OS and applications.","Wrong — FaaS runs individual functions on demand without the customer managing any servers or VMs at all."]},{"id":490,"question":"Which cloud deployment model combines on-premises infrastructure with public cloud resources?","options":["Public cloud","Private cloud","Hybrid cloud","Community cloud"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Hybrid cloud mixes private and public resources, often used for cloud bursting and flexible workloads.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a public cloud alone doesn't include on-premises infrastructure.","Wrong — a private cloud alone doesn't include public cloud resources.","Correct — a hybrid cloud combines on-premises (private) infrastructure with public cloud resources.","Wrong — a community cloud is shared among organizations with common concerns, not a mix of on-premises and public resources."]},{"id":491,"question":"Which protocol is commonly used to monitor network devices and gather performance statistics?","options":["Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)","SMTP, a protocol for sending email between mail servers, unrelated to device monitoring","SFTP, a secure file-transfer protocol used to move files, not to gather device statistics","SCP, a secure copy protocol for transferring files, with no device-monitoring function"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) is used for monitoring and managing network devices.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.1","objective":"Network Monitoring","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — SNMP is designed specifically to monitor and gather performance statistics from network devices.","Wrong — SMTP is used to send email between mail servers, unrelated to device monitoring.","Wrong — SFTP is a secure file-transfer protocol, not a device-monitoring protocol.","Wrong — SCP securely copies files between hosts, unrelated to gathering performance statistics."]},{"id":492,"question":"Which log type on a firewall would best help you identify repeated blocked connection attempts from the same Internet Protocol (IP)?","options":["Configuration logs","Change management logs","Security/traffic logs","System uptime logs"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Security or traffic logs show connection attempts and blocks, useful for detecting suspicious activity.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.1","objective":"Network Monitoring","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — configuration logs record device settings changes, not repeated connection attempts.","Wrong — change management logs track approved changes to systems, not live connection attempts.","Correct — security or traffic logs record connection attempts and blocks, making them ideal for spotting repeated attempts from one IP.","Wrong — system uptime logs track device availability, not individual connection attempts."]},{"id":493,"question":"A user can ping an Internet Protocol (IP) address on the internet but cannot browse websites by name. Which service is most likely failing?","options":["Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP)","Domain Name System (DNS)","Network Time Protocol (NTP)","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"If Internet Protocol (IP) connectivity works but name resolution fails, Domain Name System (DNS) is the likely issue.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.1","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a DHCP failure would typically prevent the device from getting any IP configuration at all, not just break name resolution.","Correct — since IP-based access works but name-based browsing fails, DNS is the most likely failing service.","Wrong — an NTP issue affects time synchronization, not the ability to resolve website names.","Wrong — an SNMP issue affects device monitoring and management, unrelated to browsing by name."]},{"id":494,"question":"Which command on a Windows system displays the current Internet Protocol (IP) configuration, including Internet Protocol (IP) address, subnet mask, and default gateway?","options":["ping","tracert","ipconfig","nslookup"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"ipconfig shows Internet Protocol (IP) configuration details on Windows systems.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.1","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — ping tests reachability to a host; it does not display the local IP configuration.","Wrong — tracert shows the hop path to a destination, not local IP configuration.","Correct — ipconfig displays the current IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway on Windows.","Wrong — nslookup queries DNS servers; it does not show local IP configuration."]},{"id":495,"question":"Which tool shows the path packets take through the network to a destination, including each hop?","options":["ping","traceroute/tracert","netstat","arp"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"traceroute (Linux/macOS) or tracert (Windows) shows each hop along the path to a destination.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.1","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — ping verifies basic reachability and round-trip time but does not show the hops along the path.","Correct — traceroute (or tracert on Windows) displays every hop the packet passes through to reach the destination.","Wrong — netstat shows local connections and listening ports, not the path to a remote destination.","Wrong — arp shows local IP-to-MAC mappings, not the path across the network."]},{"id":496,"question":"Which device regenerates and amplifies signals to extend the distance of a network segment but does not filter traffic?","options":["Switch","Router","Repeater","Firewall"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Repeaters operate at Layer 1, regenerating signals without any traffic filtering.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a switch forwards frames based on MAC addresses and can apply filtering like VLANs, unlike a simple repeater.","Wrong — a router makes forwarding decisions based on IP addresses and applies routing logic, unlike a simple repeater.","Correct — a repeater regenerates and amplifies the signal to extend distance without any traffic filtering.","Wrong — a firewall actively filters traffic based on security policy, the opposite of a repeater's simple signal regeneration."]},{"id":497,"question":"Which fiber connector type is small form-factor and often used in pairs for duplex connections?","options":["ST","SC","Lucent Connector (LC)","registered jack 11 (RJ-11)"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Lucent Connector (LC) is a small form-factor fiber connector commonly used in duplex pairs.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.4","objective":"Physical Installations & Cabling","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — ST connectors use a round bayonet twist-lock design, not the small-form-factor push design of LC.","Wrong — SC connectors use a larger square push-pull body, not the small-form-factor design being described.","Correct — LC connectors are small form-factor and commonly used in duplex pairs for fiber connections.","Wrong — RJ-11 is a telephone connector used for copper lines, not fiber."]},{"id":498,"question":"Which topology describes all devices connected to a single central device, such as a switch?","options":["Bus","Ring","Star","Mesh"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"In a star topology, all devices connect to a central device like a switch.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a bus topology connects all devices along a single shared cable, not to one central device.","Wrong — a ring topology connects each device to its two neighbors in a closed loop, not to a central device.","Correct — in a star topology, every device connects individually to a central device such as a switch.","Wrong — a mesh topology connects many devices directly to each other, not through one central device."]},{"id":499,"question":"Which design principle involves using multiple redundant links or devices to avoid a single point of failure?","options":["Convergence","Redundancy","Over-subscription","Virtualization"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Redundancy adds backup links or devices to maintain availability if one fails.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.6","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — convergence describes how quickly a network reaches a consistent routing state, not redundancy design.","Correct — redundancy uses backup links or devices so the network keeps functioning if one component fails.","Wrong — over-subscription describes allocating more bandwidth demand than physical capacity, the opposite goal of redundancy.","Wrong — virtualization abstracts hardware into virtual instances; it is not specifically about avoiding single points of failure."]},{"id":500,"question":"Which document defines acceptable use of company network resources by employees?","options":["Service Level Agreement (SLA)","Acceptable Use Policy (AUP)","Memorandum of Understanding (MOU)","Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"An Acceptable Use Policy (AUP) defines how users may use company resources.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.3","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — an SLA defines expected service performance between a provider and customer, not acceptable employee use.","Correct — an Acceptable Use Policy defines how employees may appropriately use company network resources.","Wrong — an MOU documents a general understanding between parties, not specific rules for resource use.","Wrong — an NDA protects confidential information from disclosure, not day-to-day acceptable use of resources."]},{"id":501,"question":"Which type of agreement defines the expected level of service between a provider and a customer?","options":["Service Level Agreement (SLA)","Acceptable Use Policy (AUP)","Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)","Request for Proposal (RFP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A Service Level Agreement (SLA) defines performance and availability expectations.","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objectiveId":"3.3","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — an SLA defines the expected performance and availability levels between a provider and customer.","Wrong — an AUP defines acceptable use of resources by users, not provider service commitments.","Wrong — an NDA protects confidential information, unrelated to service-level expectations.","Wrong — an RFP solicits vendor proposals; it does not itself define ongoing service-level commitments."]},{"id":502,"question":"Which authentication method requires two or more different factors, such as something you know and something you have?","options":["Single sign-on","Multifactor authentication","Role-based access control","Discretionary access control"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Multifactor authentication uses two or more different factor types (knowledge, possession, inherence).","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — single sign-on lets one set of credentials access multiple systems; it does not require multiple factor types.","Correct — multifactor authentication requires two or more distinct factor types, such as a password and a hardware token.","Wrong — role-based access control assigns permissions by job role; it does not itself require multiple authentication factors.","Wrong — discretionary access control lets resource owners set permissions; it is unrelated to requiring multiple authentication factors."]},{"id":503,"question":"Which directory service protocol is commonly used for centralized authentication in Windows domains?","options":["Domain Name System (DNS), which resolves hostnames to IP addresses rather than authenticating directory users","Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP)","Network Time Protocol (NTP), which synchronizes clocks and has no directory authentication role","TFTP, a simple unauthenticated file-transfer protocol with no directory or authentication capability"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) is used by directory services like Active Directory for centralized authentication and queries.","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objectiveId":"4.4","objective":"Authentication, Remote Access & VPN","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — DNS resolves hostnames to addresses; it does not authenticate directory users.","Correct — LDAP is the directory service protocol used by systems like Active Directory for centralized authentication.","Wrong — NTP synchronizes clocks and has no directory authentication function.","Wrong — TFTP transfers files without authentication and has no directory service role."]},{"id":504,"question":"Which term describes reducing the transmit power of access points and carefully placing them to minimize co-channel interference?","options":["Site survey","Channel bonding","Cell sizing","Beamforming"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Cell sizing adjusts access point (AP) power and placement to control coverage and reduce interference.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a site survey measures signal conditions to plan a deployment; it is not itself the power-reduction technique.","Wrong — channel bonding combines channels for more bandwidth, unrelated to reducing co-channel interference through power and placement.","Correct — cell sizing adjusts AP transmit power and placement to control coverage overlap and minimize co-channel interference.","Wrong — beamforming focuses signal energy toward a client, which is a different technique than adjusting overall cell size."]},{"id":505,"question":"Which tool or process is used to map signal strength and identify dead zones before deploying a wireless network?","options":["Packet capture","Site survey","Penetration test","Vulnerability scan"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A wireless site survey measures signal strength and interference to plan access point (AP) placement.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.3","objective":"Wireless Technologies","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — packet capture records traffic content; it does not map physical signal strength or dead zones.","Correct — a site survey measures signal strength and interference throughout a space to plan access point placement.","Wrong — a penetration test evaluates security weaknesses, not wireless signal coverage.","Wrong — a vulnerability scan checks for known security flaws, unrelated to mapping wireless coverage."]},{"id":506,"question":"Which term describes processing data closer to where it is generated, such as on Internet of Things (IoT) gateways, to reduce latency?","options":["Fog/edge computing","Mainframe computing","Batch processing","Thick client computing"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Fog or edge computing processes data near the source to reduce latency and bandwidth usage.","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objectiveId":"1.3","objective":"Cloud Concepts & Virtualization","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Correct — fog/edge computing processes data near its source, such as on IoT gateways, to reduce latency and bandwidth use.","Wrong — mainframe computing centralizes processing in large systems, the opposite approach of processing near the data source.","Wrong — batch processing handles data in scheduled groups rather than close to the source in real time.","Wrong — thick client computing relies on local application processing on end-user devices, not IoT gateway-level edge processing."]},{"id":507,"question":"A user reports intermittent connectivity. You suspect a bad patch cable. Which tool is best to verify the cable’s pinout and continuity?","options":["Tone generator and probe","Cable tester","Multimeter","optical time-domain reflectometer (OTDR)"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A basic cable tester verifies continuity and correct pinout for twisted-pair cables.","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objectiveId":"5.1","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","source":"Net + Review.html","optionExplanations":["Wrong — a tone generator and probe trace a cable's physical path; they do not verify pinout continuity.","Correct — a basic cable tester verifies continuity and correct pinout for a twisted-pair cable.","Wrong — a multimeter can check basic continuity but does not verify full 8-wire pinout mapping the way a cable tester does.","Wrong — an OTDR is designed for fiber fault location, not copper twisted-pair pinout verification."]},{"objectiveId":"1.2","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","question":"A web hosting company runs three identical application servers behind a single public IP address. Incoming HTTP requests are distributed across the three servers based on current server load, and if one server stops responding to health checks, traffic is automatically redirected to the remaining two. Which appliance is performing this function?","options":["Load balancer","Proxy server","Intrusion detection system","VoIP gateway"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A load balancer distributes incoming client requests across multiple backend servers and uses health checks to stop sending traffic to servers that become unresponsive, exactly matching the described behavior.","id":508,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a load balancer distributes requests across multiple servers based on load and reroutes traffic away from failed health checks.","Wrong — a proxy server forwards requests on behalf of clients but does not perform load-based distribution and health-check failover across servers.","Wrong — an intrusion detection system monitors for malicious activity; it does not distribute traffic across servers.","Wrong — a VoIP gateway converts between voice signaling protocols; it has no role in distributing web traffic across servers."]},{"objectiveId":"1.2","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","question":"An organization deploys an appliance that intercepts all outbound web requests from internal users, caches frequently requested pages to reduce bandwidth usage, and enforces a policy blocking access to social media sites during business hours. Which appliance is this?","options":["Forward proxy server","Reverse proxy server","Layer 2 switch","Wireless LAN controller"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A forward proxy sits between internal clients and the internet, handling outbound requests on their behalf, which allows it to cache content and enforce content filtering policies exactly as described.","id":509,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a forward proxy sits between internal clients and the internet, letting it cache content and enforce outbound content filtering.","Wrong — a reverse proxy sits in front of internal servers to manage inbound requests from external clients, not outbound client requests.","Wrong — a Layer 2 switch forwards frames based on MAC address; it does not cache content or filter web access.","Wrong — a wireless LAN controller manages access points; it does not cache web content or filter site access."]},{"objectiveId":"1.2","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","question":"A security appliance is deployed inline with network traffic so that it can actively drop malicious packets in real time before they reach their destination, rather than merely generating an alert after the fact. What distinguishes this appliance from a purely passive detection system?","options":["It is an intrusion prevention system (IPS), which sits inline and can actively block traffic, unlike a purely passive intrusion detection system (IDS)","It is a network tap, a passive device that duplicates traffic onto a monitoring port for analysis but has no ability to block or drop any packets","It is a wireless access point, a device that solely provides Wi-Fi connectivity to client devices and has no traffic inspection or blocking role","It is a proxy server, a device that forwards and caches requests on behalf of internal clients but does not perform inline intrusion blocking"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The key distinction is inline placement with active blocking capability: an IPS sits directly in the traffic path and can drop malicious packets in real time, while an IDS only passively monitors a copy of traffic and can merely alert on it.","id":510,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — an IPS sits inline in the traffic path and can actively drop malicious packets in real time, unlike a passive IDS that only alerts.","Wrong — a network tap only duplicates traffic for out-of-band analysis and cannot block anything itself.","Wrong — a wireless access point provides client connectivity; it has no inline traffic-inspection or blocking role.","Wrong — a proxy server forwards and caches client requests; that role is distinct from inline intrusion blocking."]},{"objectiveId":"1.2","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","question":"A mid-sized office replaces its aging analog phone system with an appliance that manages call routing, voicemail, and extension dialing entirely over the existing IP network, converting voice into data packets for transmission. What is this appliance called?","options":["A VoIP PBX (private branch exchange)","A wireless LAN controller","A layer 3 switch","An intrusion detection system"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A VoIP PBX handles call routing, voicemail, and extension management for a Voice over IP telephone system, converting calls into IP packets for transmission over the data network, matching the appliance described.","id":511,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a VoIP PBX manages call routing, voicemail, and extensions while converting voice into packets for the IP network.","Wrong — a wireless LAN controller manages access points, unrelated to voice call routing.","Wrong — a Layer 3 switch routes and switches data traffic; it does not manage voicemail or call routing by itself.","Wrong — an intrusion detection system monitors for malicious activity, unrelated to telephony functions."]},{"objectiveId":"1.2","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Networking Appliances & Applications","question":"An organization replaces its traditional stateful firewall with a device that additionally inspects traffic at the application layer, identifies specific applications regardless of the port they use, and can enforce policies based on user identity rather than just IP address. What best describes this upgraded appliance?","options":["A next-generation firewall (NGFW)","A basic packet-filtering router","A media converter","A repeater hub"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A next-generation firewall extends traditional stateful filtering with application-layer awareness, application identification independent of port number, and identity-based policy enforcement, exactly matching the described capabilities.","id":512,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — an NGFW adds application-layer inspection, app identification independent of port, and identity-based policy to traditional stateful filtering.","Wrong — a basic packet-filtering router only examines headers like IP and port, without application-layer awareness.","Wrong — a media converter translates between cable types, such as copper to fiber, unrelated to firewall inspection.","Wrong — a repeater hub simply regenerates signals with no inspection or filtering capability at all."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A network designer must run a fiber link between two buildings located four kilometers apart on a corporate campus. Which type of fiber optic cable is MOST appropriate for this distance?","options":["Single-mode fiber","Multimode fiber","Category 6 copper cable","Coaxial cable"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Single-mode fiber uses a narrow core and a laser light source that allows signals to travel much farther, typically tens of kilometers, without significant signal degradation, making it the appropriate choice for a multi-kilometer campus link, unlike multimode fiber which is limited to a few hundred meters to about two kilometers.","id":513,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — single-mode fiber supports transmission over many kilometers, making it appropriate for a four-kilometer campus link.","Wrong — multimode fiber is typically limited to a few hundred meters up to about two kilometers, insufficient for this distance.","Wrong — Category 6 copper cable is limited to about 100 meters, far short of four kilometers.","Wrong — coaxial cable is not used for this kind of long-distance building-to-building data link."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A data center technician needs to upgrade a switch uplink from 1 Gbps to 10 Gbps and must select a compatible transceiver module for the new speed. Which transceiver form factor is designed specifically for 10 Gbps connections, as opposed to the smaller module used for standard 1 Gbps links?","options":["SFP+","SFP","RJ45","BNC connector"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"SFP+ (enhanced small form-factor pluggable) is the transceiver standard designed to support 10 Gbps speeds, while the original SFP standard tops out at 1 Gbps, making SFP+ the correct choice for this upgrade.","id":514,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — SFP+ is the transceiver standard built to support 10 Gbps speeds.","Wrong — standard SFP modules are limited to 1 Gbps speeds, not the 10 Gbps needed here.","Wrong — RJ45 is a copper connector type, not a fiber transceiver form factor for this upgrade.","Wrong — a BNC connector is used with coaxial cable, unrelated to fiber transceiver modules."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A technician is running new cabling in an office and needs to support 10 Gbps speeds over a 100-meter run while minimizing crosstalk between cable pairs compared to the previous generation of cabling. Which cable category BEST satisfies this requirement?","options":["Category 6a","Category 5e","Category 3","Category 6"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Category 6a is specifically designed to reliably support 10 Gbps over the full 100-meter distance with improved shielding and twist rates that reduce crosstalk compared to standard Category 6, which can only support 10 Gbps over much shorter distances.","id":515,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — Category 6a reliably supports 10 Gbps over the full 100-meter distance with reduced crosstalk.","Wrong — Category 5e is rated for only 1 Gbps, not 10 Gbps.","Wrong — Category 3 supports only very low data rates, far below 10 Gbps.","Wrong — Category 6 can reach 10 Gbps only over much shorter distances than the full 100 meters."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A technician is selecting fiber connectors for a new data center installation and needs a small-form-factor duplex connector that allows for higher port density on switches compared to older, bulkier connector types. Which connector type BEST fits this requirement?","options":["LC (Lucent Connector)","ST (Straight Tip)","RJ45","BNC"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The LC connector uses a small form factor that allows twice the port density of older connectors like SC or ST on the same size faceplate, making it the preferred choice in modern, space-constrained data center environments.","id":516,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — the LC connector's small form factor allows higher port density than older, bulkier connectors.","Wrong — the ST connector is a larger, bayonet-style connector with lower density than LC.","Wrong — RJ45 is a copper Ethernet connector, not a fiber connector.","Wrong — BNC is used with coaxial cable, not fiber-optic connections."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A technician is running network cable through the space above a drop ceiling that is also used to circulate air for the building's HVAC system. Building code requires cable rated to resist spreading flame and produce less toxic smoke than standard cable if it catches fire. Which cable rating satisfies this requirement?","options":["Plenum-rated cable","Riser-rated cable","Direct burial-rated cable","Outdoor-rated cable"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Plenum-rated cable is specifically designed for installation in air-handling spaces like the area above a drop ceiling, using fire-retardant jacketing that produces less toxic smoke than standard cable, satisfying fire code requirements for these spaces.","id":517,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — plenum-rated cable is designed for air-handling spaces and uses fire-retardant jacketing with less toxic smoke output.","Wrong — riser-rated cable is designed for vertical shafts between floors, not air-handling plenum spaces.","Wrong — direct burial-rated cable is designed for underground installation, not indoor plenum spaces.","Wrong — outdoor-rated cable is designed for exterior exposure, not the fire-code requirements of indoor plenum spaces."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A long run of unshielded copper cabling exhibits a gradual weakening of the signal as it travels down the cable, eventually causing errors at the receiving end once the cable exceeds its rated maximum length. What is this signal degradation phenomenon called?","options":["Attenuation","Crosstalk","Electromagnetic interference","Duplex mismatch"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Attenuation is the gradual loss of signal strength as it travels along a cable; copper cabling has a maximum rated distance specifically because attenuation eventually degrades the signal beyond what the receiving equipment can reliably interpret.","id":518,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — attenuation is the gradual loss of signal strength over distance that limits a cable's maximum rated length.","Wrong — crosstalk is interference between adjacent wire pairs, not gradual signal weakening over distance.","Wrong — electromagnetic interference comes from external sources, not the gradual internal signal loss described.","Wrong — a duplex mismatch is a configuration issue causing collisions, not gradual signal degradation over distance."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A newly installed switch port and an end-user device are both configured to auto-negotiate speed and duplex settings, but the resulting connection unexpectedly runs at half-duplex, causing collisions and poor performance. What is this specific type of misconfiguration called?","options":["Duplex mismatch","Attenuation","Bend radius violation","Wavelength division multiplexing conflict"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A duplex mismatch occurs when the two ends of a link disagree on duplex mode, commonly one side auto-negotiating and the other being manually forced or failing to negotiate correctly, resulting in one side running half-duplex and producing collisions and degraded performance.","id":519,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a duplex mismatch occurs when the two link ends disagree on duplex mode, producing collisions and poor performance.","Wrong — attenuation is gradual signal loss over distance, not a duplex negotiation disagreement.","Wrong — a bend radius violation is a physical fiber cabling issue, unrelated to duplex negotiation on copper links.","Wrong — wavelength division multiplexing is a fiber technology for combining signals, unrelated to duplex settings."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A network engineer purchases a generic, third-party transceiver module for a switch, but the switch's firmware refuses to recognize it and disables the port. What is the MOST likely explanation?","options":["The switch vendor has implemented transceiver vendor locking, only recognizing modules coded with their approved vendor identifier","The transceiver's wavelength is too short for the fiber core diameter, causing the light signal to fail to couple properly into the fiber","The switch port's maximum supported speed has been exceeded by the new transceiver, causing the chassis to reject it outright","The cable connected to the transceiver uses the wrong cable category for the signal type, preventing the link from establishing"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Many switch vendors program their firmware to check for a vendor-specific identifier within the transceiver's memory, refusing to enable ports with unrecognized third-party modules; this vendor locking practice is the most common reason a generic transceiver would be rejected outright.","id":520,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — many vendors program firmware to check for their own vendor ID in the transceiver, rejecting unrecognized third-party modules.","Wrong — a wavelength mismatch would typically cause poor signal quality, not an outright firmware rejection based on identity.","Wrong — exceeding chassis speed support would typically be documented and expected, not present as an unrecognized-module rejection.","Wrong — a wrong cable category would prevent a working link but would not cause the switch firmware itself to refuse to recognize the module."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A data center needs to connect two switches located in adjacent racks, only two meters apart, at very high speed with minimal latency and cost. Which cabling solution is MOST commonly used for this specific short, high-speed, rack-to-rack scenario?","options":["Direct attach copper (twinax) cable","Single-mode fiber with LC connectors","Category 3 cable","Coaxial cable"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Direct attach copper (twinax) cabling is commonly used for short, high-speed connections within or between adjacent racks because it is significantly less expensive than fiber transceiver pairs while easily meeting the distance and speed needs of such a short run.","id":521,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — direct attach copper (twinax) is a low-cost, low-latency solution ideal for short, high-speed rack-to-rack connections.","Wrong — single-mode fiber is designed for long distances and costs more than needed for a two-meter connection.","Wrong — Category 3 cable supports only very low speeds, unsuitable for high-speed switch interconnects.","Wrong — coaxial cable is not the standard solution for modern high-speed switch-to-switch links."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A service provider wants to transmit multiple independent data streams simultaneously over a single strand of fiber optic cable by assigning each stream a different light wavelength (color), which are then combined and later separated at the receiving end. What technology accomplishes this?","options":["Wavelength division multiplexing (WDM)","Power over Ethernet (PoE)","Spanning Tree Protocol","Link aggregation"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Wavelength division multiplexing combines multiple signals onto a single fiber strand by transmitting each on a distinct light wavelength, then separates them again at the far end, allowing significantly more data capacity from existing fiber infrastructure without adding new strands.","id":522,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — WDM assigns each data stream a distinct wavelength so multiple streams can share a single fiber strand.","Wrong — PoE delivers electrical power over Ethernet cabling, unrelated to combining wavelengths on fiber.","Wrong — Spanning Tree Protocol prevents Layer 2 loops, unrelated to fiber wavelength multiplexing.","Wrong — link aggregation combines multiple physical links into one logical link, a different technique from wavelength multiplexing."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"During installation, a technician coils a fiber optic cable tightly around a small post to save space, creating a sharp curve well beyond the cable's rated bend radius. What is the MOST likely consequence?","options":["Increased signal loss or complete signal failure at the point of the tight bend","Improved signal strength due to compression of the fiber core","No effect at all, since fiber is immune to bending stress","Automatic activation of a built-in repeater within the cable"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Bending fiber optic cable beyond its rated minimum bend radius can cause light to escape the core at the bend point (a phenomenon related to total internal reflection failing), resulting in significant signal loss or complete failure of the link at that point.","id":523,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — bending fiber beyond its rated radius lets light escape the core, causing significant loss or complete signal failure.","Wrong — bending does not compress or improve the fiber core's signal-carrying ability.","Wrong — fiber is not immune to bending stress; exceeding its bend radius does cause real signal problems.","Wrong — fiber cable has no built-in repeater that activates from being bent."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A technician needs to terminate a cable for a telephone handset jack, which uses a smaller connector with fewer conductor positions than the connector used for standard Ethernet network jacks. Which connector should the technician use for the phone jack?","options":["RJ11","RJ45","LC","SFP+"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"RJ11 is the smaller connector standard used for telephone connections, typically with just two or four conductor positions, distinguishing it from RJ45, which has eight positions and is used for standard Ethernet network connections.","id":524,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — RJ11 is the smaller connector standard used for telephone jacks.","Wrong — RJ45 is the larger 8-position connector used for standard Ethernet, not telephone jacks.","Wrong — LC is a fiber-optic connector, not used for analog telephone connections.","Wrong — SFP+ is a network transceiver module, unrelated to telephone jack wiring."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A technician needs to directly connect two laptops together via their Ethernet ports to transfer files, with no switch or hub in between. On older network equipment lacking auto-MDI-X capability, which type of cable is required for this direct device-to-device connection?","options":["A crossover cable","A straight-through cable","A rollover cable","A patch panel cable"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A crossover cable swaps the transmit and receive pin pairs, which is required for direct connections between two like devices (such as two computers) on equipment that lacks auto-MDI-X, which automatically detects and adjusts for this need; a standard straight-through cable would not establish a link in that scenario.","id":525,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a crossover cable swaps transmit/receive pairs, which is required for direct like-device connections without auto-MDI-X.","Wrong — a straight-through cable connects unlike devices and would not establish a link directly between two like devices without auto-MDI-X.","Wrong — a rollover cable is used for console management connections, not for linking two computers directly.","Wrong — a patch panel cable is used for structured cabling terminations, not for a direct laptop-to-laptop connection."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A manufacturing facility runs network cabling near large electric motors and industrial equipment that generate significant electromagnetic interference, causing intermittent errors on standard unshielded cabling. Which cabling type would BEST mitigate this interference?","options":["Shielded twisted pair (STP)","Unshielded twisted pair (UTP)","Single-mode fiber would also work, but STP copper is more directly comparable to what was already installed","Plenum-rated UTP"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Shielded twisted pair cabling includes a metallic shielding layer around the conductors specifically designed to block electromagnetic interference from nearby sources like motors, making it the appropriate copper cabling choice for high-EMI industrial environments, unlike standard unshielded twisted pair.","id":526,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — shielded twisted pair includes metallic shielding that blocks EMI from sources like industrial motors.","Wrong — unshielded twisted pair lacks the shielding needed to resist significant EMI in this environment.","Wrong — while fiber would also resist EMI, it isn't the directly comparable copper upgrade path described in the scenario.","Wrong — plenum-rated UTP addresses fire-code requirements, not electromagnetic interference resistance."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A network engineer needs to extend an Ethernet connection from a switch room using copper cabling to a remote building where only fiber optic cabling is feasible due to distance. Which device converts the electrical signal from the copper cable into an optical signal for transmission over fiber?","options":["A media converter","A repeater hub","A cable tester","A punch-down tool"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A media converter is specifically designed to translate signals between two different cable media types, such as converting an electrical Ethernet signal on copper into an optical signal suitable for transmission over fiber, and back again at the receiving end.","id":527,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a media converter translates the electrical signal on copper into an optical signal for transmission over fiber.","Wrong — a repeater hub regenerates electrical signals but does not convert between copper and fiber media.","Wrong — a cable tester verifies cable continuity; it does not convert signal types.","Wrong — a punch-down tool terminates cable into a jack or patch panel; it performs no signal conversion."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"Before deploying a new long-distance fiber link, a network engineer calculates the total expected signal loss from the transmitter through all connectors, splices, and the fiber length itself, comparing it against the transceiver's maximum tolerable loss. What is this calculation called?","options":["A loss budget (or link budget) calculation","A bend radius calculation","A duplex negotiation calculation","A subnet calculation"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A loss budget (or link budget) calculation totals the expected signal loss across every component in a fiber link and compares it to what the transceiver can tolerate, ensuring the link will function reliably before it is deployed, which is exactly the process described.","id":528,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a loss (link) budget calculation totals expected signal loss and compares it to the transceiver's tolerance before deployment.","Wrong — a bend radius calculation concerns physical cable curvature limits, not overall signal loss budgeting.","Wrong — duplex negotiation determines half- or full-duplex operation, unrelated to fiber loss budgeting.","Wrong — a subnet calculation determines IP addressing ranges, unrelated to fiber signal loss."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A technician needs to install a transceiver in a switch that supports four times the bandwidth of a standard SFP+ port by combining four lanes into a single module, commonly used for high-density 40 Gbps uplinks. Which transceiver form factor matches this description?","options":["QSFP+","SFP","GBIC","RJ45"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"QSFP+ (quad small form-factor pluggable) combines four data lanes into a single module to support 40 Gbps connections, commonly used for high-bandwidth uplinks, distinguishing it from a standard SFP+ module which handles a single 10 Gbps lane.","id":529,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — QSFP+ combines four lanes into one module to support high-bandwidth 40 Gbps uplinks.","Wrong — standard SFP modules handle a single lower-speed lane, not four combined lanes for 40 Gbps.","Wrong — GBIC is an older, larger, single-lane transceiver standard predating SFP+ and QSFP+.","Wrong — RJ45 is a copper connector, not a high-speed multi-lane fiber transceiver form factor."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A facility needs to run network cable directly underground between two buildings, exposed to moisture and soil contact without any conduit protection. Which cable type is specifically designed for this application?","options":["Direct burial-rated cable","Plenum-rated cable","Riser-rated cable","Patch cable"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Direct burial-rated cable is constructed with a jacket specifically designed to resist moisture, soil chemicals, and physical stress from being placed directly underground without conduit, unlike plenum or riser-rated cable, which are designed for indoor use.","id":530,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — direct burial-rated cable is built to withstand moisture and soil exposure without conduit protection.","Wrong — plenum-rated cable is designed for indoor air-handling spaces, not underground burial.","Wrong — riser-rated cable is designed for vertical indoor shafts, not underground exposure.","Wrong — a patch cable is a short indoor cable for connecting equipment, not designed for burial."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A technician troubleshooting a copper Ethernet link that will not establish connectivity uses a handheld device to confirm whether individual wire pairs inside the cable are properly connected end-to-end, without any breaks or crossed pairs. What tool is being used?","options":["A cable tester","A protocol analyzer","An optical time-domain reflectometer (OTDR)","A tone generator"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A cable tester checks the continuity and correct pin mapping of individual wire pairs within a copper cable, identifying opens, shorts, or miswired pairs, which is the appropriate tool for confirming basic physical connectivity issues like the one described.","id":531,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a cable tester checks continuity and correct pin mapping of individual wire pairs in a copper cable.","Wrong — a protocol analyzer captures and decodes packet contents, not physical wire continuity.","Wrong — an OTDR is used for fiber fault location, not copper wire-pair continuity testing.","Wrong — a tone generator traces a cable's physical path; it does not verify pair-by-pair continuity."]},{"objectiveId":"1.6","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","question":"A data center architect designs a network where every leaf switch (connecting to servers) connects directly to every spine switch, with no direct connections between leaf switches themselves, providing consistent low latency and high bandwidth between any two servers. What is this design called?","options":["Spine-leaf topology","Ring topology","Bus topology","Hub-and-spoke topology"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Spine-leaf topology connects every leaf switch to every spine switch in a full mesh between the two layers, ensuring any server-to-server path traverses the same predictable number of hops, which is the modern standard for data center network design requiring consistent low latency.","id":532,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — spine-leaf topology connects every leaf switch to every spine switch, giving consistent low latency between any two servers.","Wrong — a ring topology connects devices in a closed loop, not a full leaf-to-spine mesh between two layers.","Wrong — a bus topology connects devices along one shared cable, unlike the structured leaf-spine mesh described.","Wrong — a hub-and-spoke topology centers on one hub device, not a full mesh between two dedicated layers."]},{"objectiveId":"1.6","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","question":"A campus network is designed with a core layer for high-speed backbone switching, a distribution layer for policy enforcement and routing between VLANs, and an access layer where end-user devices physically connect. What is this design pattern commonly known as?","options":["The three-tier (core-distribution-access) hierarchical model","A full mesh topology, where every device connects directly to every other device regardless of function","A point-to-multipoint topology, where one central device connects to several endpoints without any layered hierarchy","A collapsed core design, which merges core and distribution functions rather than keeping three distinct layers"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The three-tier hierarchical model organizes a network into distinct core, distribution, and access layers, each with clearly defined roles, which is the classic enterprise campus network design pattern being described.","id":533,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — the three-tier hierarchical model organizes the network into core, distribution, and access layers with distinct roles.","Wrong — a full mesh topology connects every device to every other device, without the layered role structure described.","Wrong — a point-to-multipoint topology centers on one device serving many endpoints, not a layered hierarchy.","Wrong — a collapsed core design merges layers together, the opposite of maintaining three distinct tiers."]},{"objectiveId":"1.6","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","question":"A small branch office with only 40 users and a handful of switches decides not to implement separate core and distribution layers, instead combining their functions into a single pair of redundant switches that also handle access-layer connectivity. What is this simplified design called?","options":["A collapsed core design","A spine-leaf design","A full mesh design","A screened subnet design"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A collapsed core design merges the core and distribution layer functions into a single layer, which is appropriate for smaller networks that don't have the scale to justify the added complexity and cost of the full three-tier hierarchical model.","id":534,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a collapsed core design merges core and distribution functions into one layer, suited to smaller networks.","Wrong — a spine-leaf design is a data center architecture for large-scale, high-bandwidth server interconnects, not a small branch simplification.","Wrong — a full mesh design connects every device to every other device, adding complexity rather than simplifying the design.","Wrong — a screened subnet design is a security architecture for isolating public-facing servers, unrelated to layer consolidation."]},{"objectiveId":"1.6","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","question":"A retail chain with 200 branch locations needs each branch to communicate primarily with the central headquarters data center, with minimal need for branches to communicate directly with each other. Which WAN topology is MOST cost-effective and appropriate for this requirement?","options":["Hub-and-spoke topology","Full mesh topology","Partial mesh topology with equal links between all branches","Ring topology"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A hub-and-spoke topology connects each branch (spoke) to the central headquarters (hub) with a single link, which is far more cost-effective than a full or partial mesh when most traffic flows to and from the central site rather than between branches directly.","id":535,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — hub-and-spoke connects each branch to the central site with a single link, the most cost-effective option when most traffic goes to headquarters.","Wrong — a full mesh topology requires direct links between every branch, far more costly than needed here.","Wrong — a partial mesh with equal links between all branches still adds unnecessary cost when traffic is centralized at headquarters.","Wrong — a ring topology connects sites in a loop, which doesn't match a hub-centric traffic pattern efficiently."]},{"objectiveId":"1.6","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","question":"An organization replaces traditional hardware-based WAN routers at each branch with a software-defined approach that centrally manages routing policy, can dynamically select the best available connection (broadband, LTE, or MPLS) for each type of traffic, and simplifies branch deployment. What technology is being described?","options":["SD-WAN (software-defined wide area network)","VLAN trunking, which carries multiple VLANs over one link but has no centralized path-selection or policy control","Spanning Tree Protocol, which prevents Layer 2 loops but has no role in centralized WAN path selection","Link aggregation, which combines multiple physical links into one logical link but doesn't manage WAN routing policy"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"SD-WAN centralizes WAN management and policy control, allowing dynamic, application-aware path selection across multiple connection types at each branch, and simplifies deployment through centralized configuration, matching exactly what is described.","id":536,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — SD-WAN centralizes WAN policy and dynamically selects the best connection type per traffic class, simplifying branch deployment.","Wrong — VLAN trunking carries multiple VLANs over a link but provides no centralized path-selection or policy control.","Wrong — Spanning Tree Protocol prevents Layer 2 loops and has no role in WAN path selection.","Wrong — link aggregation bundles physical links into one logical link but does not manage WAN routing policy."]},{"objectiveId":"1.6","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Network Topologies & Architectures","question":"A network engineer designs a WAN where only the most critical sites have direct links to every other critical site, while less critical sites connect through just one or two of those hub sites rather than to everyone. What type of topology is this?","options":["A partial mesh topology","A full mesh topology","A bus topology","A point-to-point topology"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A partial mesh topology provides direct connections between some, but not all, nodes, balancing redundancy for critical sites against the cost and complexity of a full mesh, which would require direct links between every single site regardless of importance.","id":537,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a partial mesh connects only some nodes directly, balancing redundancy for critical sites against full-mesh cost.","Wrong — a full mesh would require direct links between every site, not just the critical ones.","Wrong — a bus topology connects devices along a single shared cable, unrelated to this hub-based hybrid design.","Wrong — a point-to-point topology describes a single dedicated link between two nodes, not this mixed hub/spoke structure."]},{"objectiveId":"3.1","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Network Monitoring","question":"A network management system periodically queries each managed switch and router at five-minute intervals to retrieve current interface utilization and error counters, rather than waiting for the devices to report problems on their own. What monitoring approach does this describe?","options":["SNMP polling","SNMP trap notification","Packet capture","Syslog forwarding"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"SNMP polling involves the management system actively querying devices at regular intervals to retrieve current status information, in contrast to SNMP traps, where the device itself proactively sends a notification the moment a specific condition occurs.","id":538,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — SNMP polling has the management system actively query devices at set intervals for status information.","Wrong — SNMP traps are proactive, event-driven notifications sent by the device itself, not a scheduled query.","Wrong — packet capture records full traffic content, not periodic status queries.","Wrong — Syslog forwarding sends log messages as events occur, not on a fixed polling schedule."]},{"objectiveId":"3.1","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Network Monitoring","question":"A router is configured to immediately send a notification to the network management system the instant an interface goes down, without waiting for the next scheduled polling interval. What monitoring mechanism enables this immediate, event-driven notification?","options":["An SNMP trap","SNMP polling","NetFlow export","A ping sweep"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An SNMP trap is a proactive, event-driven notification sent by the device itself the moment a defined condition occurs, such as an interface going down, providing much faster awareness than waiting for the next scheduled SNMP poll.","id":539,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — an SNMP trap is sent immediately by the device itself when a defined event occurs, without waiting for polling.","Wrong — SNMP polling relies on the manager querying at intervals, which would introduce a delay rather than immediate notification.","Wrong — NetFlow export reports flow statistics, not immediate event-driven device status alerts.","Wrong — a ping sweep actively probes a range of addresses; it is not a device-initiated event notification mechanism."]},{"objectiveId":"3.1","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Network Monitoring","question":"A network engineer establishes a documented profile of normal traffic patterns, CPU utilization, and bandwidth consumption for a critical server during typical business operations over several weeks. Later, monitoring tools use this profile to automatically flag unusual deviations. What is this documented profile called?","options":["A baseline","A risk register","A rules of engagement document","A service level agreement"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A baseline is the documented profile of normal system or network behavior over time, which serves as the reference point that monitoring tools compare current activity against in order to detect meaningful deviations or anomalies.","id":540,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a baseline documents normal behavior over time, serving as the reference point for detecting deviations.","Wrong — a risk register catalogs identified risks and their mitigations, not measured normal performance data.","Wrong — a rules of engagement document defines boundaries for security testing, unrelated to performance baselining.","Wrong — an SLA defines expected service performance commitments, not a measured historical behavior profile."]},{"objectiveId":"3.1","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Network Monitoring","question":"A network administrator wants to analyze which internal hosts are consuming the most bandwidth and identify unusual conversations between internal and external IP addresses, without capturing and storing the full content of every packet. Which technology is BEST suited for this?","options":["NetFlow (or similar flow-based analysis)","Full packet capture","A cable tester","A tone generator"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"NetFlow (and similar flow-based technologies) records metadata about network conversations, such as source, destination, volume, and duration, without capturing full packet contents, making it efficient for identifying top talkers and unusual traffic patterns at scale without the storage overhead of full packet capture.","id":541,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — NetFlow records conversation metadata like volume and duration without full packet content, ideal for efficient traffic analysis.","Wrong — full packet capture stores complete packet contents, which is far more storage-intensive than needed for this analysis.","Wrong — a cable tester checks physical cable continuity, unrelated to analyzing traffic conversations.","Wrong — a tone generator traces cable paths, unrelated to bandwidth or conversation analysis."]},{"objectiveId":"3.1","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Network Monitoring","question":"An organization centralizes log messages from routers, switches, firewalls, and servers into a single platform where they can be searched, correlated, and retained for a defined period. Which protocol is most commonly used by network devices to forward these log messages to the central platform?","options":["Syslog","SNMP","NTP","DHCP"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Syslog is the standard protocol used by network and infrastructure devices to forward log and event messages to a centralized logging platform for aggregation, search, and correlation, matching the scenario described.","id":542,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — Syslog is the standard protocol devices use to forward log and event messages to a centralized platform.","Wrong — SNMP is used for polling and managing devices, not primarily for forwarding general log messages.","Wrong — NTP synchronizes time between devices, unrelated to log forwarding.","Wrong — DHCP assigns IP addressing information, unrelated to centralized logging."]},{"objectiveId":"3.1","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Network Monitoring","question":"A network engineer needs to investigate the exact contents of traffic between two hosts to diagnose an application-layer protocol issue, capturing every byte of the conversation for detailed offline analysis. Which tool is MOST appropriate for this deep level of investigation?","options":["A packet capture tool (protocol analyzer)","An SNMP manager","A ping utility","A bandwidth monitor showing only aggregate totals"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A packet capture tool (protocol analyzer) records the full contents of network traffic, allowing an engineer to examine every byte of a conversation for detailed protocol-level troubleshooting, which is a much deeper level of visibility than flow-based or aggregate monitoring tools provide.","id":543,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a packet capture tool records every byte of traffic, enabling deep protocol-level troubleshooting.","Wrong — an SNMP manager collects device metrics via polling, not full packet-level content.","Wrong — a ping utility only tests basic reachability, providing no packet-content detail.","Wrong — a bandwidth monitor showing only aggregate totals lacks the byte-level detail needed for protocol diagnosis."]},{"objectiveId":"3.1","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Network Monitoring","question":"An organization's monitoring dashboard shows continuous ICMP echo requests being sent to critical servers every 60 seconds, with a red alert triggered if three consecutive responses are missed. What is this monitoring technique PRIMARILY measuring?","options":["Basic reachability and availability of the monitored devices","The exact application-layer error occurring on the server","The specific process consuming the most CPU on the server","The content of encrypted traffic passing through the server"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Repeated ICMP echo requests (pings) are a simple, lightweight way to measure basic network reachability and availability, confirming whether a host is responding at all, though they provide no visibility into application-layer issues, specific processes, or encrypted payload content.","id":544,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — repeated ICMP echo requests measure basic reachability and availability of the monitored devices.","Wrong — ping provides no visibility into specific application-layer errors on the server.","Wrong — ping cannot identify which process is consuming CPU on the server.","Wrong — ping does not reveal the content of encrypted traffic passing through a device."]},{"objectiveId":"3.1","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Network Monitoring","question":"A network engineer reviewing interface statistics on a switch notices a steadily climbing count of CRC errors and collisions on one specific port, while all other ports remain clean. What is the MOST likely underlying cause suggested by this specific monitoring data?","options":["A physical layer problem, such as a damaged cable or duplex mismatch on that specific port","A misconfigured DNS server, which would affect name resolution rather than produce physical-layer error counters like these","An expired SSL certificate, which would cause certificate warnings rather than CRC errors and collisions at the port level","A DHCP scope running out of addresses, which would prevent new leases rather than generate physical-layer error counters"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Climbing CRC errors and collisions isolated to a single port are classic physical-layer symptoms, typically caused by a damaged or marginal cable, bad connector, or a duplex mismatch on that specific link, rather than higher-layer issues like DNS, certificates, or DHCP.","id":545,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — climbing CRC errors and collisions isolated to one port point to a physical-layer issue like a bad cable or duplex mismatch.","Wrong — a DNS misconfiguration would affect name resolution, not generate physical-layer error counters on a switch port.","Wrong — an expired SSL certificate would cause certificate warnings, not CRC errors and collisions at the port level.","Wrong — a full DHCP scope would prevent new address leases, not generate physical-layer error counters on a port."]},{"objectiveId":"3.1","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Network Monitoring","question":"A company's IT team receives dozens of separate monitoring alerts scattered across email, a ticketing system, and a dashboard, making it difficult to get a unified view of ongoing issues. They decide to funnel all log and alert data from every tool into one centralized platform for correlation and unified search. What is this centralized platform commonly called?","options":["A log aggregation platform (or SIEM)","A DHCP relay agent","A media converter","A rules of engagement document"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A log aggregation platform (often a SIEM in security contexts) centralizes log and alert data from many disparate tools into a single searchable, correlated view, directly addressing the fragmentation problem described in the scenario.","id":546,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a log aggregation platform (or SIEM) centralizes log and alert data from many tools into one searchable, correlated view.","Wrong — a DHCP relay agent forwards DHCP requests across subnets, unrelated to centralizing logs and alerts.","Wrong — a media converter translates between cable types, unrelated to log aggregation.","Wrong — a rules of engagement document defines security-testing boundaries, not a platform for centralizing monitoring data."]},{"objectiveId":"3.1","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Network Monitoring","question":"A data center operations team monitors the temperature and humidity levels inside their server room around the clock, with automated alerts if either value drifts outside a safe range. What category of monitoring does this represent?","options":["Environmental monitoring","Bandwidth utilization monitoring","Log correlation monitoring","Flow-based traffic monitoring"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Environmental monitoring tracks physical conditions like temperature and humidity that can affect equipment reliability, which is distinct from network traffic-focused monitoring like bandwidth or flow analysis, and is critical for protecting hardware in a data center.","id":547,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — environmental monitoring tracks physical conditions like temperature and humidity that affect equipment reliability.","Wrong — bandwidth utilization monitoring tracks network traffic levels, not room temperature or humidity.","Wrong — log correlation monitoring analyzes event logs, unrelated to physical environmental conditions.","Wrong — flow-based traffic monitoring analyzes network conversations, not physical room conditions."]},{"objectiveId":"3.1","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Network Monitoring","question":"An engineer investigating a security incident is trying to correlate log entries from a firewall, a web server, and an authentication server, all of which report events using timestamps, but the resulting timeline of events seems inconsistent and doesn't add up. Which foundational network service is MOST likely misconfigured or missing, undermining this correlation effort?","options":["Network Time Protocol (NTP)","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP)","Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP)","Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Accurate timestamp correlation across multiple systems depends on all of them having synchronized clocks via NTP; if devices' clocks have drifted or NTP isn't properly configured, timestamps across different logs won't align correctly, making an accurate combined timeline impossible to construct.","id":548,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — NTP keeps device clocks synchronized, which is essential for accurate timestamp correlation across systems.","Wrong — DHCP assigns IP addressing information and has no role in timestamp accuracy or correlation.","Wrong — SMTP handles email transport, unrelated to log timestamp synchronization.","Wrong — TFTP transfers files, unrelated to synchronizing clocks for log correlation."]},{"objectiveId":"3.1","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Network Monitoring","question":"A network monitoring platform is configured to automatically generate a ticket and page the on-call engineer the moment WAN circuit utilization exceeds 90% for more than five consecutive minutes. What is this specific type of configuration called?","options":["Threshold-based alerting","A baseline snapshot","A rules of engagement document","A change management record"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Threshold-based alerting triggers a notification when a monitored metric crosses a predefined limit for a specified duration, exactly matching the configuration described where sustained high WAN utilization automatically generates an alert.","id":549,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — threshold-based alerting triggers a notification once a monitored metric crosses a defined limit for a set duration.","Wrong — a baseline snapshot is the reference profile of normal behavior, not itself the alerting trigger mechanism.","Wrong — a rules of engagement document defines security-testing scope, unrelated to alert thresholds.","Wrong — a change management record documents approved changes, unrelated to automated utilization alerting."]},{"objectiveId":"3.2","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","question":"A company operates two identical data centers, both actively processing live customer transactions simultaneously, with traffic load-balanced between them; if either data center fails, the other continues handling the full load with no interruption. What high availability model does this describe?","options":["Active-active configuration","Active-passive configuration","Cold site configuration","N+1 redundancy without load sharing"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An active-active configuration has multiple sites simultaneously processing live traffic, sharing the load under normal conditions, which distinguishes it from active-passive, where a standby site remains idle until the primary fails.","id":550,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — active-active has multiple sites simultaneously processing live traffic with load balanced between them.","Wrong — active-passive keeps a standby site idle until the primary fails, unlike the simultaneous processing described.","Wrong — a cold site requires time to become operational after a failure, not simultaneous live processing.","Wrong — N+1 redundancy without load sharing keeps a spare component idle rather than actively sharing the load."]},{"objectiveId":"3.2","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","question":"A company maintains an alternate facility with power, networking, and cooling already in place, and a small stock of hardware ready to be configured, but no live data replication and no equipment actively running until a disaster is declared. Which disaster recovery site classification BEST matches this description?","options":["A warm site","A hot site","A cold site","An active-active site"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A warm site has infrastructure like power, networking, and cooling already in place along with some hardware ready to go, but does not maintain continuously live, up-to-date data replication the way a hot site does, making the recovery time longer than a hot site but shorter than a bare cold site.","id":551,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a warm site has core infrastructure and some hardware ready but lacks continuous live data replication, unlike a hot site.","Wrong — a hot site maintains continuously live, up-to-date data replication and running systems, more than described here.","Wrong — a cold site provides only bare space and power, without the hardware and infrastructure already in place as described.","Wrong — an active-active site runs live production traffic simultaneously at both locations, unlike this standby facility."]},{"objectiveId":"3.2","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","question":"An organization's disaster recovery plan states that after a major outage, critical systems must be restored within four hours, and no more than fifteen minutes of data can be lost. Which two metrics are being defined here, respectively?","options":["Recovery time objective (RTO) and recovery point objective (RPO)","Mean time between failures (MTBF) and mean time to repair (MTTR)","Service level agreement (SLA) and memorandum of understanding (MOU)","Single loss expectancy (SLE) and annualized rate of occurrence (ARO)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Recovery time objective (RTO) defines the maximum acceptable time to restore a system after an outage, while recovery point objective (RPO) defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, exactly matching the four-hour restoration target and fifteen-minute data loss tolerance described.","id":552,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — RTO defines the maximum acceptable restoration time (four hours), and RPO defines the maximum acceptable data loss (fifteen minutes).","Wrong — MTBF and MTTR measure failure frequency and repair duration for equipment reliability, not recovery targets after a disaster.","Wrong — an SLA and MOU are agreement documents, not the specific recovery time and data loss metrics described.","Wrong — SLE and ARO are risk-assessment financial metrics, not recovery time or data loss targets."]},{"objectiveId":"3.2","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","question":"A critical server cluster is designed with one additional server beyond what is strictly needed to handle normal peak load, so that if a single server fails, the remaining servers can absorb the load without any service degradation. What redundancy model does this represent?","options":["N+1 redundancy","2N redundancy","Active-passive failover","A cold site"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"N+1 redundancy means having exactly one more unit than the minimum required to handle normal load, providing protection against a single failure without the cost of fully duplicating the entire capacity, which distinguishes it from 2N redundancy where the entire capacity is doubled.","id":553,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — N+1 redundancy adds exactly one extra unit beyond the minimum needed, protecting against a single failure at lower cost than full duplication.","Wrong — 2N redundancy fully duplicates the entire capacity, which is more than the single extra unit described here.","Wrong — active-passive failover keeps a standby unit idle rather than the described active load-sharing pool with one spare.","Wrong — a cold site is a disaster recovery facility, not a server redundancy model within a cluster."]},{"objectiveId":"3.2","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","question":"A data center relies on battery-backed power systems to keep servers running for a few minutes during a power outage, giving a separate, larger power system time to start up and take over supplying power for an extended outage. Which two systems are being described, respectively?","options":["An uninterruptible power supply (UPS), followed by a backup generator","A backup generator, followed by a UPS, which reverses the actual sequence of immediate versus longer-term power backup","A hot site, followed by a cold site, which describes disaster recovery facilities rather than power backup equipment","A load balancer, followed by a firewall, which are traffic-distribution and security devices unrelated to power backup"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A UPS provides immediate, short-term battery backup power to bridge the gap the instant utility power fails, while a generator takes slightly longer to start but can sustain power for a much longer outage, which is exactly the sequence and roles described.","id":554,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a UPS provides immediate short-term battery power, and a generator starts up afterward to sustain power for a longer outage.","Wrong — this reverses the actual sequence; the generator, not the UPS, is the longer-term backup that starts up second.","Wrong — hot and cold sites are disaster recovery facilities, not power backup equipment for a data center.","Wrong — a load balancer and firewall are traffic-handling and security devices, unrelated to backup power systems."]},{"objectiveId":"3.2","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","question":"A branch office is configured with two separate internet connections from different providers, and if the primary connection fails, the router automatically begins routing all traffic through the secondary connection within seconds, with no manual intervention required. What is this capability called?","options":["WAN failover (multi-WAN redundancy)","Link aggregation","Spanning Tree Protocol","VLAN trunking"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"WAN failover, sometimes called multi-WAN redundancy, automatically shifts traffic to a backup internet connection when the primary connection fails, providing continued connectivity without requiring a person to manually reconfigure anything.","id":555,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — WAN failover automatically shifts traffic to a secondary internet connection when the primary fails, without manual intervention.","Wrong — link aggregation combines multiple links into one logical link for bandwidth, not automatic failover between separate ISPs.","Wrong — Spanning Tree Protocol prevents Layer 2 loops, unrelated to WAN connection failover.","Wrong — VLAN trunking carries multiple VLANs over one link, unrelated to failing over between internet providers."]},{"objectiveId":"3.2","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"High Availability & Disaster Recovery","question":"A load balancer distributing traffic across a pool of web servers periodically sends a test request to each server and automatically removes any server from the rotation that fails to respond correctly, adding it back once it recovers. What is this testing mechanism called?","options":["A health check","A baseline","A loss budget calculation","A rules of engagement document"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A health check is the mechanism a load balancer uses to periodically verify that each backend server is functioning correctly, automatically removing unresponsive servers from the active rotation and restoring them once they pass the check again.","id":556,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a health check is the periodic test a load balancer uses to verify server responsiveness and manage rotation membership.","Wrong — a baseline is a reference profile of normal behavior, not an active periodic server test.","Wrong — a loss budget calculation applies to fiber signal loss, unrelated to load balancer server testing.","Wrong — a rules of engagement document defines security-testing scope, unrelated to load balancer health checks."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A company publishes a document that all employees must acknowledge before receiving network access, specifying that company systems may not be used for illegal activity, excessive personal use, or unauthorized software installation. What type of document is this?","options":["An acceptable use policy (AUP)","A service level agreement (SLA)","A memorandum of understanding (MOU)","A non-disclosure agreement (NDA)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An acceptable use policy defines the rules employees must follow when using company systems and network resources, exactly matching the document described that employees must acknowledge covering prohibited activities.","id":557,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — an AUP defines acceptable and prohibited uses of company systems that employees must acknowledge.","Wrong — an SLA defines service performance guarantees between a provider and customer, not employee conduct rules.","Wrong — an MOU documents a general non-binding understanding between parties, not employee usage rules.","Wrong — an NDA protects confidential information from disclosure, unrelated to acceptable use rules."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A company contracts with an internet service provider that guarantees 99.9% uptime and specifies financial penalties if that threshold is not met in a given month. What type of document defines this guarantee?","options":["A service level agreement (SLA)","An acceptable use policy (AUP)","A non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","A wiring diagram"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A service level agreement defines specific performance guarantees, such as an uptime percentage, along with any penalties for failing to meet them, exactly matching the uptime commitment and financial penalty structure described.","id":558,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — an SLA defines specific performance guarantees, such as uptime percentage, along with penalties for missing them.","Wrong — an AUP defines acceptable use rules for employees, not provider performance guarantees.","Wrong — an NDA protects confidential information, unrelated to uptime guarantees or penalties.","Wrong — a wiring diagram documents physical cabling, unrelated to service performance guarantees."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"Two separate organizations sign a document outlining their intent to collaborate on a joint networking project, describing each party's general responsibilities, but without the binding, legally enforceable performance guarantees found in a formal contract. What type of document is this?","options":["A memorandum of understanding (MOU)","A service level agreement (SLA)","An incident response plan","A change management record"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A memorandum of understanding documents a general agreement of intent and mutual understanding between parties about how they will collaborate, without the strict, legally binding performance commitments found in an SLA or formal contract.","id":559,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — an MOU documents a general, non-binding agreement of intent between parties without the legal enforceability of a formal contract.","Wrong — an SLA includes binding, legally enforceable performance guarantees, unlike the non-binding intent described.","Wrong — an incident response plan defines security incident handling procedures, not a general collaboration agreement.","Wrong — a change management record documents approved system changes, unrelated to inter-organizational collaboration intent."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"Before sharing proprietary network architecture details with an outside consulting firm, a company requires the consultants to sign a document legally obligating them not to disclose that information to any third party. What type of document is this?","options":["A non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","An acceptable use policy (AUP)","A service level agreement (SLA)","A physical network diagram"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A non-disclosure agreement is the legal document specifically used to obligate a party to keep shared confidential information private and not disclose it to others, matching the scenario of protecting proprietary architecture details shared with outside consultants.","id":560,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — an NDA is the legal document obligating a party to keep shared confidential information private.","Wrong — an AUP governs how employees may use company systems, not confidentiality obligations for outside consultants.","Wrong — an SLA defines performance guarantees, not confidentiality obligations.","Wrong — a physical network diagram documents cabling and layout, unrelated to confidentiality obligations."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"Before implementing a firewall rule change on a production network, an engineer submits a formal request describing the proposed change, its business justification, potential risks, a rollback plan, and obtains approval from a designated review body before the change is scheduled and implemented. What process does this describe?","options":["Change management","Business impact analysis","Site survey documentation","Asset inventory management"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Change management is the formal process of documenting, reviewing, approving, and scheduling changes to production systems, including justification, risk assessment, and rollback planning, exactly matching the process described for the firewall rule change.","id":561,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — change management is the formal process of documenting, reviewing, and approving changes before implementation, including rollback plans.","Wrong — a business impact analysis assesses the consequences of a disruption, not the approval process for a specific change.","Wrong — site survey documentation records wireless signal conditions, unrelated to firewall change approval.","Wrong — asset inventory management tracks hardware details, not the process of approving a configuration change."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A network technician troubleshooting a connectivity issue references a document showing exactly which patch panel port, switch port, and physical cable run corresponds to each network jack throughout the building. What type of documentation is this?","options":["A wiring diagram","A service level agreement","An acceptable use policy","A business impact analysis"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A wiring diagram documents the physical cabling infrastructure, including which patch panel ports, switch ports, and cable runs correspond to specific jacks, which is exactly the reference a technician would use to trace physical connectivity during troubleshooting.","id":562,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a wiring diagram documents which patch panel port, switch port, and cable run correspond to each jack.","Wrong — a service level agreement defines performance guarantees, not physical cabling details.","Wrong — an acceptable use policy governs user conduct, unrelated to physical cabling documentation.","Wrong — a business impact analysis assesses disruption consequences, not physical cable routing."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"An organization documents the normal, expected configuration settings that every new switch must be configured with before deployment, including VLAN assignments, port security settings, and management access restrictions, to ensure consistency across the network. What is this reference document commonly called?","options":["A baseline configuration document","A memorandum of understanding","A non-disclosure agreement","A wiring diagram"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A baseline configuration document defines the standard, expected configuration that devices should be set to before deployment, ensuring consistency and a known-secure starting point across the network, matching what's described for new switch deployments.","id":563,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a baseline configuration document defines the standard settings every new switch should have before deployment.","Wrong — a memorandum of understanding documents inter-party intent, not device configuration standards.","Wrong — a non-disclosure agreement protects confidential information, unrelated to standard device configuration.","Wrong — a wiring diagram documents physical cabling, not standard configuration settings."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A company's IT department maintains a step-by-step document detailing the exact commands and sequence of actions required to fail over the primary internet circuit to the backup circuit during an outage. What type of document is this?","options":["A standard operating procedure (SOP)","A service level agreement (SLA)","A non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","A risk register"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A standard operating procedure provides detailed, step-by-step instructions for performing a specific task consistently and correctly, exactly matching the documented failover steps described for switching to the backup internet circuit.","id":564,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a standard operating procedure gives detailed, step-by-step instructions for performing a specific task like a circuit failover.","Wrong — a service level agreement defines performance guarantees, not step-by-step failover instructions.","Wrong — a non-disclosure agreement protects confidential information, unrelated to failover instructions.","Wrong — a risk register catalogs identified risks, not the step-by-step procedure for a task."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A network engineer references a document showing how devices are logically connected and addressed, including IP subnets and VLAN relationships, without regard to their exact physical cable routing or rack location. How does this document differ from a physical network diagram?","options":["It is a logical network diagram, showing addressing and logical relationships, while a physical diagram shows actual cabling and hardware placement","It is identical to a physical network diagram in every respect, meaning the two terms are simply interchangeable ways of describing the same document","It shows only the cable colors and connector types used throughout the building, without any addressing or logical relationship information at all","It shows only the organization's employee directory and internal reporting structure, with no technical networking information whatsoever"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A logical network diagram represents how devices are logically connected and addressed, such as IP subnets and VLAN relationships, while a physical network diagram instead shows the actual physical cabling, hardware locations, and rack layout, making them complementary but distinct documents.","id":565,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a logical diagram shows addressing and logical relationships, while a physical diagram shows actual cabling and hardware placement.","Wrong — the two diagram types are distinct and not interchangeable; they document different aspects of the network.","Wrong — a logical diagram documents addressing and relationships, not merely cable colors and connector types.","Wrong — a logical network diagram documents network addressing and structure, not an employee directory or org chart."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A company requires that every network cable, patch panel port, and switch port be marked with a consistent, documented naming scheme so that any technician can quickly identify a given connection's purpose and location. What practice does this describe?","options":["A cable and port labeling standard","A business impact analysis","A memorandum of understanding","A risk register"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A labeling standard defines a consistent naming and marking scheme for cables and ports, making it easy for any technician to quickly identify a given connection's purpose and location, which directly matches the practice described.","id":566,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a cable and port labeling standard defines a consistent naming scheme so any technician can identify a connection's purpose and location.","Wrong — a business impact analysis assesses disruption consequences, not cable and port naming conventions.","Wrong — a memorandum of understanding documents inter-party intent, unrelated to labeling cables and ports.","Wrong — a risk register catalogs identified risks, not a naming scheme for cables and ports."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A company's security policy defines specific conditions, such as confirmed data exfiltration or ransomware detection, under which the security team must immediately activate the formal incident response process rather than handling the event as routine troubleshooting. What is this triggering definition part of?","options":["An incident response policy","A wiring diagram","A site survey report","An acceptable use policy"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An incident response policy defines what qualifies as a security incident and the specific triggering conditions that require activating the formal incident response process, exactly matching the defined conditions described for escalating beyond routine troubleshooting.","id":567,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — an incident response policy defines what qualifies as an incident and the conditions that trigger the formal response process.","Wrong — a wiring diagram documents physical cabling, unrelated to incident escalation triggers.","Wrong — a site survey report documents wireless signal conditions, unrelated to incident response triggers.","Wrong — an acceptable use policy governs everyday user conduct, not incident escalation criteria."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A company allows employees to connect their personal smartphones and laptops to the corporate network, provided those devices meet minimum security requirements such as encryption and a passcode, as defined in a specific written policy. What type of policy governs this practice?","options":["A bring your own device (BYOD) policy","A change management policy","A business impact analysis","A wiring diagram"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A bring your own device (BYOD) policy specifically defines the rules and minimum security requirements for employees connecting personally owned devices to corporate network resources, matching the scenario described.","id":568,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a BYOD policy defines the rules and minimum security requirements for connecting personal devices to the corporate network.","Wrong — a change management policy governs approval of system changes, unrelated to personal device rules.","Wrong — a business impact analysis assesses disruption consequences, not personal device connection rules.","Wrong — a wiring diagram documents physical cabling, unrelated to personal device policy."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A company defines specific rules governing how employees may connect to internal resources from outside the office, including required VPN use, approved device types, and multi-factor authentication. What type of policy is this?","options":["A remote access policy","A service level agreement","A non-disclosure agreement","A baseline configuration document"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A remote access policy specifically defines the rules and requirements for connecting to internal resources from outside the office, including VPN usage, approved devices, and authentication requirements, exactly matching the policy described.","id":569,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a remote access policy defines the rules for connecting to internal resources from outside the office, including VPN and MFA requirements.","Wrong — a service level agreement defines performance guarantees, not remote-connection rules for employees.","Wrong — a non-disclosure agreement protects confidential information, unrelated to remote access rules.","Wrong — a baseline configuration document defines standard device settings, not remote-access policy rules."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A company's HR and IT departments follow a documented, coordinated process ensuring that the moment an employee's termination is processed, their network accounts, VPN access, and badge access are all disabled the same day. What type of documentation governs this coordinated process?","options":["An offboarding procedure","A service level agreement","A wiring diagram","A risk register"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An offboarding procedure documents the coordinated steps required when an employee leaves the organization, including disabling network, VPN, and physical access, exactly matching the coordinated process described between HR and IT.","id":570,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — an offboarding procedure documents the coordinated steps to disable network, VPN, and badge access when an employee leaves.","Wrong — a service level agreement defines performance guarantees, unrelated to employee offboarding steps.","Wrong — a wiring diagram documents physical cabling, unrelated to account and access deactivation.","Wrong — a risk register catalogs identified risks, not the specific offboarding process steps."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A network administrator maintains a continuously updated record of every switch, router, and firewall on the network, including model, serial number, location, and warranty status. What is this record called?","options":["An asset inventory","A rules of engagement document","A memorandum of understanding","An acceptable use policy"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An asset inventory is the documented record tracking details like model, serial number, location, and warranty status for network hardware, exactly matching the continuously updated record described for switches, routers, and firewalls.","id":571,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — an asset inventory tracks details like model, serial number, location, and warranty status for network hardware.","Wrong — a rules of engagement document defines security-testing boundaries, unrelated to hardware tracking.","Wrong — a memorandum of understanding documents inter-party intent, unrelated to hardware records.","Wrong — an acceptable use policy governs user conduct, unrelated to tracking hardware inventory."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A company's contract with a managed network services vendor includes specific financial penalties the vendor must pay if response times to critical outages exceed the agreed threshold. What part of the vendor agreement defines this?","options":["The service level agreement (SLA) penalty clause","The acceptable use policy, which governs employee behavior rather than vendor performance penalties","The wiring diagram, which documents physical cabling rather than contractual penalty terms","The asset inventory, which tracks hardware details rather than vendor performance penalties"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The service level agreement, specifically its penalty clause, defines the financial consequences a vendor faces for failing to meet agreed performance thresholds like response time, exactly matching what's described in this vendor contract.","id":572,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — the SLA's penalty clause defines the financial consequences a vendor faces for missing agreed performance thresholds like response time.","Wrong — an acceptable use policy governs employee conduct, not vendor performance penalties.","Wrong — a wiring diagram documents physical cabling, unrelated to vendor contract penalties.","Wrong — an asset inventory tracks hardware details, unrelated to vendor performance penalties."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"A company's policy specifies that firewall logs must be retained for one year and authentication logs for ninety days, after which they are automatically purged unless a legal hold is in effect. What type of policy defines these timeframes?","options":["A data retention policy","A remote access policy","A bring your own device (BYOD) policy","A wiring diagram"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A data retention policy defines how long specific types of data, such as logs, must be kept before they are eligible for deletion, exactly matching the defined retention periods described for firewall and authentication logs.","id":573,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a data retention policy defines how long specific data types, like logs, must be kept before deletion.","Wrong — a remote access policy governs off-site connection rules, not log retention periods.","Wrong — a BYOD policy governs personal device use, unrelated to log retention timeframes.","Wrong — a wiring diagram documents physical cabling, unrelated to data retention rules."]},{"objectiveId":"3.3","domain":"3.0 Network Operations","objective":"Organizational Documents & Policies","question":"Before installing a new wireless network throughout an office building, an engineer walks the entire space with specialized equipment to measure signal strength, identify interference sources, and determine optimal access point placement, then documents the findings. What is this process and its resulting documentation called?","options":["A site survey","A business impact analysis","A change management record","A rules of engagement document"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A site survey is the process of physically walking a space to measure signal characteristics and determine optimal wireless access point placement before deployment, with the documented findings serving as the reference for the actual installation.","id":574,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a site survey is the process of measuring signal conditions and determining optimal AP placement before deployment, with findings documented.","Wrong — a business impact analysis assesses disruption consequences, not wireless signal measurement.","Wrong — a change management record documents approved changes, not a pre-deployment signal survey.","Wrong — a rules of engagement document defines security-testing boundaries, unrelated to wireless site surveys."]},{"objectiveId":"4.1","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","question":"A network administrator groups user workstations, servers, and IoT devices into separate logical broadcast domains on the same physical switching infrastructure, preventing a compromised IoT device from directly communicating with sensitive servers. What technology enables this?","options":["VLANs (virtual local area networks)","Link aggregation","Spanning Tree Protocol","Power over Ethernet"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"VLANs logically segment a physical network into separate broadcast domains, allowing different device types like workstations, servers, and IoT devices to be isolated from each other even while sharing the same physical switches, directly supporting the segmentation goal described.","id":575,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — VLANs create separate logical broadcast domains on shared switching infrastructure, isolating different device types from each other.","Wrong — link aggregation combines multiple physical links into one logical link, unrelated to creating separate broadcast domains.","Wrong — Spanning Tree Protocol prevents Layer 2 loops, unrelated to segmenting devices into separate domains.","Wrong — Power over Ethernet delivers electrical power over Ethernet cabling, unrelated to network segmentation."]},{"objectiveId":"4.1","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","question":"An organization adopts a security model in which no device or user is automatically trusted based on network location alone, and every access request is continuously verified against identity, device health, and context before being granted, regardless of whether the request originates inside or outside the traditional network perimeter. What model is this?","options":["Zero trust","Defense in depth","A screened subnet","A honeypot"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Zero trust is the security model that eliminates automatic trust based on network location, requiring continuous verification of identity, device posture, and context for every access request regardless of origin, exactly matching the approach described.","id":576,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — zero trust requires continuous verification of every access request regardless of network location, eliminating automatic trust.","Wrong — defense in depth layers multiple security controls but doesn't specifically eliminate trust based on location the way zero trust does.","Wrong — a screened subnet isolates public-facing services with dual firewalls, a different architecture than the continuous-verification model described.","Wrong — a honeypot is a decoy system for detecting attackers, unrelated to continuous access verification."]},{"objectiveId":"4.1","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","question":"A company places its public-facing web server in a separate network segment isolated from the internal corporate network, with strict firewall rules controlling exactly what traffic can pass between the two, so that a compromise of the web server does not directly expose internal systems. What is this isolated segment called?","options":["A demilitarized zone (DMZ)","A virtual private network (VPN)","A collapsed core","A spine-leaf fabric"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A demilitarized zone (DMZ) is a network segment specifically used to isolate publicly exposed services from the internal network, with tightly controlled firewall rules limiting what traffic can pass between the two, exactly matching the isolation strategy described.","id":577,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a DMZ isolates public-facing services from the internal network with controlled firewall rules between the two.","Wrong — a VPN provides encrypted remote connectivity, unrelated to isolating a public-facing server segment.","Wrong — a collapsed core design merges core and distribution switching layers, unrelated to public-facing server isolation.","Wrong — a spine-leaf fabric is a data center switching architecture, unrelated to isolating a public web server."]},{"objectiveId":"4.1","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","question":"An organization deploys a system that checks whether a device attempting to connect to the network meets security requirements, such as up-to-date antivirus definitions and OS patches, before granting it full network access; non-compliant devices are placed in a restricted quarantine VLAN instead. What is this system called?","options":["Network access control (NAC)","A honeypot","A DMZ","A screened subnet"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Network access control (NAC) evaluates a connecting device's security posture, such as patch level and antivirus status, before granting full network access, redirecting non-compliant devices to a restricted quarantine segment, exactly matching the system described.","id":578,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — NAC checks a device's security posture before granting network access, quarantining non-compliant devices.","Wrong — a honeypot is a decoy system to attract attackers, unrelated to posture-checking connecting devices.","Wrong — a DMZ isolates public-facing servers from the internal network, unrelated to checking device compliance before access.","Wrong — a screened subnet uses dual firewalls to isolate a segment, unrelated to endpoint posture checking."]},{"objectiveId":"4.1","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","question":"A security team deploys a deliberately vulnerable, isolated server on the network designed to attract and detect attackers, allowing the team to study attacker behavior and generate early warning alerts without risking any real production data. What is this deliberately vulnerable system called?","options":["A honeypot","A DMZ","A zero trust gateway","A collapsed core switch"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A honeypot is a deliberately vulnerable, isolated decoy system designed to attract attackers, allowing defenders to study their techniques and generate early detection alerts, all without exposing any actual production data or systems to risk.","id":579,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a honeypot is a deliberately vulnerable decoy system used to attract attackers and study their behavior safely.","Wrong — a DMZ isolates legitimate public-facing services, not a deliberately vulnerable decoy system.","Wrong — a zero trust gateway enforces continuous access verification, unrelated to a decoy attacker-detection system.","Wrong — a collapsed core switch is a network design element, unrelated to attacker deception and detection."]},{"objectiveId":"4.1","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","question":"A highly sensitive industrial control system is physically disconnected from any other network, including the internet, with no wireless connectivity of any kind, requiring physical media to transfer any data in or out. What security approach does this represent?","options":["An air-gapped network","A DMZ","A zero trust network","A collapsed core design"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An air-gapped network is physically isolated from all other networks with no direct connectivity of any kind, requiring physical media for any data transfer, which provides the strongest possible network-level isolation for highly sensitive systems.","id":580,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — an air-gapped network is physically disconnected from all other networks, requiring physical media for any data transfer.","Wrong — a DMZ is still connected to other networks with controlled firewall rules, unlike a fully air-gapped system.","Wrong — a zero trust network still relies on network connectivity with continuous verification, unlike physical isolation.","Wrong — a collapsed core design is a switching architecture choice, unrelated to complete physical network isolation."]},{"objectiveId":"4.1","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","question":"A data center administrator applies granular, workload-level policies that restrict communication between individual virtual machines within the same VLAN, rather than relying solely on broader VLAN-level segmentation, to further limit an attacker's ability to move between systems after an initial compromise. What is this fine-grained approach called?","options":["Micro-segmentation","A collapsed core design","Link aggregation","Wavelength division multiplexing"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Micro-segmentation applies granular, workload-level security policies within a segment, going beyond broader VLAN-based segmentation to further restrict lateral movement between individual systems, exactly matching the fine-grained approach described.","id":581,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — micro-segmentation applies granular, workload-level policies to restrict lateral movement between individual systems within a segment.","Wrong — a collapsed core design merges switching layers, unrelated to workload-level policy enforcement.","Wrong — link aggregation combines physical links for bandwidth, unrelated to restricting VM-to-VM communication.","Wrong — wavelength division multiplexing combines fiber signals, unrelated to workload-level security policy."]},{"objectiveId":"4.1","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","question":"An organization layers multiple independent security controls, including a firewall, network segmentation, endpoint protection, and user training, so that if any single control fails or is bypassed, other controls still provide protection. What security concept does this illustrate?","options":["Defense in depth","Zero trust exclusively","A single point of failure design","A collapsed core architecture"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Defense in depth is the strategy of layering multiple, independent security controls so that the failure of any single control does not result in a complete compromise, exactly matching the layered approach of firewall, segmentation, endpoint protection, and training described.","id":582,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — defense in depth layers multiple independent controls so no single failure results in a full compromise.","Wrong — zero trust exclusively focuses on continuous verification of access requests, not the broader layered-controls concept described.","Wrong — a single point of failure design is the opposite of what's described, since it relies on just one control.","Wrong — a collapsed core architecture is a switching design choice, unrelated to layering independent security controls."]},{"objectiveId":"4.1","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","question":"A network administrator grants each user account access to only the specific systems and resources required for their job role, and nothing more, even if broader access would be more convenient. What security principle is being applied?","options":["The principle of least privilege","Defense in depth","Zero trust exclusively","Micro-segmentation exclusively"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The principle of least privilege dictates that users should be granted only the minimum access necessary to perform their job function, exactly matching the restrictive access approach described, even though it overlaps conceptually with related ideas like zero trust.","id":583,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — least privilege grants users only the minimum access needed for their job function.","Wrong — defense in depth layers multiple security controls, a broader concept than restricting individual user access.","Wrong — zero trust exclusively focuses on continuous verification of every request, a related but distinct concept from minimal access scoping.","Wrong — micro-segmentation exclusively restricts network-level communication between workloads, not user account access scope."]},{"objectiveId":"4.1","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objective":"Security Concepts & Segmentation","question":"A network architect designs a segment for publicly accessible services that sits between two separate firewalls, one facing the internet and one facing the internal network, rather than being attached to a single firewall with multiple interfaces. What is this specific dual-firewall design commonly called?","options":["A screened subnet","A collapsed core design","A spine-leaf fabric","A full mesh topology"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A screened subnet (a specific implementation of a DMZ concept) uses two separate firewalls, one facing the internet and one facing the internal network, to sandwich the exposed segment between two layers of filtering, providing an additional layer of isolation compared to a single-firewall DMZ design.","id":584,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a screened subnet uses two separate firewalls, one internet-facing and one internal-facing, to sandwich the exposed segment.","Wrong — a collapsed core design merges switching layers, unrelated to a dual-firewall public segment design.","Wrong — a spine-leaf fabric is a data center switching architecture, unrelated to firewall placement for public services.","Wrong — a full mesh topology connects every device to every other device, unrelated to a dual-firewall segment design."]},{"objectiveId":"4.3","domain":"4.0 Network Security","objective":"Security Features & Access Control","question":"A network administrator configures a switch port so that it will only accept traffic from a single, specific MAC address, and automatically disables the port if a device with a different MAC address is plugged in. What switch security feature is being used?","options":["Port security","802.1Q trunking","Spanning Tree Protocol","Link aggregation"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Port security restricts which MAC addresses are permitted to communicate through a specific switch port, automatically taking action such as disabling the port when an unauthorized MAC address is detected, exactly matching the feature described.","id":585,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — port security restricts a switch port to a specific MAC address and can disable the port if an unauthorized device connects.","Wrong — 802.1Q trunking carries multiple VLANs over a link, unrelated to restricting a port to one MAC address.","Wrong — Spanning Tree Protocol prevents Layer 2 loops, unrelated to MAC-address-based port restriction.","Wrong — link aggregation combines multiple links into one logical link, unrelated to MAC address restriction on a port."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"A network technician receives a report of a connectivity problem and begins by asking the user detailed questions about what they were doing when the issue occurred, checking whether anyone else is affected, and reviewing whether any recent changes were made to the environment. Which step of the troubleshooting methodology is this?","options":["Identify the problem","Establish a theory of probable cause","Establish a plan of action","Verify full system functionality"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Identifying the problem is the first step of the troubleshooting methodology, involving gathering information from the user, determining the scope of impact, and checking for recent changes, exactly matching the activities described before any theory has been formed.","id":586,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — identifying the problem is the first step, involving gathering information, checking scope of impact, and reviewing recent changes.","Wrong — establishing a theory of probable cause comes after information gathering, not during the initial information-gathering itself.","Wrong — establishing a plan of action comes later, after a cause has already been identified and tested.","Wrong — verifying full system functionality is the final step, after a fix has already been implemented."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"After gathering initial information about a network outage, a technician considers several possible explanations, such as a failed switch, a misconfigured VLAN, or a bad cable, and narrows the list down to the most likely candidate based on the symptoms observed. What step of the troubleshooting methodology does this represent?","options":["Establish a theory of probable cause","Identify the problem","Implement the solution","Document findings"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Establishing a theory of probable cause involves considering multiple possible explanations for the observed symptoms and narrowing them down to the most likely cause, which is exactly the process of weighing a failed switch, misconfigured VLAN, or bad cable described here.","id":587,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — establishing a theory of probable cause involves weighing multiple possible explanations and narrowing down to the most likely one.","Wrong — identifying the problem is the earlier information-gathering step, before theories are considered.","Wrong — implementing the solution comes later, after a theory has been tested and confirmed.","Wrong — documenting findings is the final step, after the issue has already been resolved."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"A technician suspects a bad network cable is causing intermittent connectivity, and before replacing anything, swaps in a known-good cable to see if the problem disappears. What troubleshooting step is being performed?","options":["Test the theory to determine the cause","Establish a plan of action","Verify full system functionality","Document findings, actions, and outcomes"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Testing the theory involves taking an action, like swapping in a known-good cable, specifically to confirm or rule out the suspected cause before committing to a full fix, which is exactly what the technician is doing in this scenario.","id":588,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — testing the theory means taking an action, like swapping in a known-good cable, to confirm or rule out the suspected cause.","Wrong — establishing a plan of action comes after the theory is confirmed, not during the confirmation step itself.","Wrong — verifying full system functionality happens after the actual fix is implemented, not while still testing a theory.","Wrong — documenting findings, actions, and outcomes is the final step, after the issue has been resolved."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"After confirming that a faulty cable is the cause of a connectivity issue, a technician decides when the replacement will occur, orders the correct replacement cable, and considers what other systems might be affected by briefly taking the link down during the swap. What troubleshooting step is this?","options":["Establish a plan of action and identify potential effects","Identify the problem","Test the theory to determine the cause","Document findings, actions, and outcomes"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Establishing a plan of action involves deciding how and when to implement the fix while considering potential side effects on other systems, exactly matching the scheduling and impact consideration described before the cable is actually replaced.","id":589,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — establishing a plan of action involves deciding how and when to implement the fix while considering effects on other systems.","Wrong — identifying the problem is the earlier information-gathering step, already completed before planning the fix.","Wrong — testing the theory to determine the cause happens before planning implementation, not after the cause is already confirmed.","Wrong — documenting findings is the final step, after the fix has actually been implemented."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"After confirming the cause of a network issue and planning the fix, a technician replaces the faulty cable during an approved maintenance window. What troubleshooting step comes NEXT, immediately after the fix has been physically applied?","options":["Verify full system functionality","Identify the problem","Establish a theory of probable cause","Test the theory to determine the cause"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"After implementing the solution, the technician must verify full system functionality to confirm the fix actually resolved the issue and did not introduce any new problems, which is the required step following implementation, before the process can be considered complete.","id":590,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — after implementing the fix, verifying full system functionality confirms the issue is resolved without introducing new problems.","Wrong — identifying the problem is the first step, already completed long before the fix was implemented.","Wrong — establishing a theory of probable cause happens early on, before the fix is implemented, not immediately after.","Wrong — testing the theory happens before implementing the actual fix, not immediately after it has been applied."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"After resolving a network outage, a technician writes up a summary of the symptoms observed, the root cause identified, the steps taken to fix it, and any preventive measures recommended, and adds it to the team's shared knowledge base. What is the PRIMARY value of this final documentation step?","options":["It preserves institutional knowledge so future technicians can resolve similar issues faster and helps identify recurring patterns","It is purely a formality required by company policy, providing no real practical value to anyone on the team","It replaces the need to actually test whether the fix worked, since writing it down is treated as sufficient confirmation","It automatically prevents the exact same hardware from ever failing again, regardless of any other maintenance performed"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Documenting findings, actions taken, and outcomes preserves institutional knowledge that helps future technicians resolve similar issues more quickly and can reveal recurring patterns across multiple incidents, which is a genuinely valuable operational practice, not merely a procedural formality.","id":591,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — documenting findings preserves institutional knowledge, speeds up future troubleshooting, and can reveal recurring patterns.","Wrong — documentation has genuine operational value; it is not just a formality with no practical use.","Wrong — documentation records what was tested, but it doesn't substitute for actually verifying the fix worked.","Wrong — documentation doesn't prevent hardware failures; it only records what happened for future reference."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"A technician troubleshooting a connectivity issue starts by checking the physical cable and switch port (Layer 1), then moves up to check VLAN configuration (Layer 2), then IP addressing (Layer 3), continuing upward until the problem is found. What troubleshooting approach is this?","options":["A bottom-to-top OSI model approach","A top-to-bottom OSI model approach","A divide and conquer approach","A theory-first approach with no structured layer order"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Starting at the physical layer and working upward through progressively higher OSI layers is the bottom-to-top approach, which is often used when a physical layer issue (like a bad cable) is suspected, in contrast to a top-to-bottom approach which would start by investigating application-layer symptoms first.","id":592,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — starting at Layer 1 and moving upward through the OSI layers is the bottom-to-top approach.","Wrong — a top-to-bottom approach would start at the application layer and work downward, the opposite of what's described.","Wrong — divide and conquer starts at a strategic midpoint, not sequentially from Layer 1 upward.","Wrong — this scenario follows a clear structured layer order, not an unstructured theory-first approach."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"A technician troubleshooting a network issue affecting several floors of a building decides to check connectivity at a switch in the middle of the network path first, rather than starting at either endpoint, in order to quickly determine whether the problem lies upstream or downstream from that point. What troubleshooting approach is being used?","options":["A divide and conquer approach","A top-to-bottom OSI model approach","A bottom-to-top OSI model approach","Duplicating the problem"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Divide and conquer involves testing at a strategic midpoint in the network path to quickly narrow down whether an issue lies upstream or downstream of that point, which is more efficient than working strictly from one end to the other in many scenarios.","id":593,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — divide and conquer tests a midpoint in the path to quickly determine whether the issue is upstream or downstream.","Wrong — a top-to-bottom approach starts with application-layer symptoms, not a midpoint network location.","Wrong — a bottom-to-top approach starts at Layer 1 and moves upward, not at an arbitrary midpoint device.","Wrong — duplicating the problem means reproducing the issue, not testing at a strategic midpoint."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"A user reports intermittent connectivity issues, but when a technician remotely checks the connection, everything appears to be working normally. Rather than closing the ticket, the technician asks the user to reproduce the exact conditions under which the issue occurs. What troubleshooting principle is being applied?","options":["Duplicating the problem to confirm and observe the actual issue firsthand","Establishing a plan of action, which comes only after a cause has already been confirmed, not while still trying to observe the issue","Documenting findings and outcomes, which is the final step performed only after the issue has been fully resolved","Verifying full system functionality, which happens only after a fix has actually been implemented and applied"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Duplicating the problem means attempting to reproduce the reported issue under the same conditions so the technician can directly observe and confirm it, which is an important step when an issue is intermittent and not immediately apparent during initial investigation.","id":594,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — duplicating the problem means reproducing it under the same conditions so the technician can directly observe and confirm it.","Wrong — establishing a plan of action happens after a cause is confirmed, not while trying to observe an intermittent issue.","Wrong — documenting findings is the final step, performed after the issue has actually been resolved.","Wrong — verifying full system functionality happens only after a fix has been implemented, not during initial observation."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"A technician's initial theory about a network outage's cause turns out to be incorrect after testing fails to confirm it. According to the standard troubleshooting methodology, what should the technician do NEXT?","options":["Establish a new theory, or escalate to someone with more expertise if needed","Immediately implement a fix based on the original, disproven theory anyway","Skip directly to documenting the incident as unresolved","Close the ticket, since the original theory did not pan out"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"When a theory is tested and disproven, the methodology calls for forming a new theory based on what was learned, or escalating to someone with deeper expertise if the technician has exhausted their own reasonable theories, rather than giving up or proceeding with a fix based on a disproven cause.","id":595,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — when a theory is disproven, the technician should form a new theory or escalate to someone with more expertise.","Wrong — implementing a fix based on a theory already known to be wrong risks making the problem worse or fixing nothing.","Wrong — documenting the incident as unresolved skips the remaining troubleshooting steps prematurely.","Wrong — closing the ticket abandons the troubleshooting process instead of forming a new theory or escalating."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"While gathering information about a reported network issue, a technician specifically asks the user, 'Has anything changed recently, such as a new device being added or a software update being installed?' Why is this question a particularly important part of the identification step?","options":["Recent changes are a common root cause of new problems, so identifying them can quickly point toward the most likely explanation","It has no real diagnostic value and is only asked to make the user feel heard during the conversation","It is only relevant for security incidents, not general connectivity troubleshooting scenarios like this one","It replaces the need to gather any other information about the symptoms the user is actually experiencing"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Recent changes, such as new devices or updates, are a frequent root cause of newly appearing problems, so asking specifically about them during the identification step can quickly surface the most probable explanation and significantly narrow the field of possible causes.","id":596,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — recent changes are a frequent root cause of new problems, so asking about them helps narrow down the likely explanation quickly.","Wrong — this question has real diagnostic value; it's not simply about making the user feel heard.","Wrong — recent-change questions are broadly useful for connectivity troubleshooting, not just security incidents.","Wrong — this question supplements, rather than replaces, gathering other symptom information."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"A technician is handling a network outage affecting one building, and partway through the investigation, a completely unrelated report comes in about a different, isolated printer issue in another building. According to good troubleshooting practice, how should the technician approach these two issues?","options":["Approach each problem individually and separately, rather than assuming they share a common cause","Assume both issues share the same root cause and only investigate the building outage","Ignore the printer issue entirely since it was reported second","Combine both tickets into one and apply the same fix to both simultaneously without individual investigation"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Good troubleshooting practice calls for approaching multiple, seemingly unrelated problems individually rather than assuming a shared cause, since conflating unrelated issues can lead to wasted effort chasing a connection that doesn't exist and delay resolving each one appropriately.","id":597,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — good practice treats separate, unrelated problems individually rather than assuming they share a cause.","Wrong — assuming a shared cause without evidence can lead to wasted effort and delay resolving the unrelated issue.","Wrong — ignoring a reported issue simply because it came in second is poor practice and delays resolution.","Wrong — combining unrelated tickets and applying the same fix to both risks an incorrect or wasted fix for one or both issues."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A newly terminated Ethernet cable fails to establish a link. Using a cable tester, the technician discovers that the transmit and receive pairs have been swapped at one end. What term describes this specific wiring fault?","options":["TX/RX reversal","Attenuation","Crosstalk","A duplex mismatch"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"TX/RX reversal occurs when the transmit and receive wire pairs are swapped during termination, preventing the two ends of the link from properly communicating, which a cable tester can specifically identify by checking pinout continuity and mapping.","id":598,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — TX/RX reversal describes swapped transmit and receive pairs at one end, preventing proper communication.","Wrong — attenuation is signal weakening over distance, not a wiring pair reversal.","Wrong — crosstalk is interference between adjacent pairs, not a transmit/receive swap.","Wrong — a duplex mismatch is a configuration disagreement between two link ends, not a physical wiring fault."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A technician terminates a cable improperly, untwisting the wire pairs too far back from the connector, which allows signal from one pair to interfere with an adjacent pair, resulting in data errors. What is this specific interference phenomenon called?","options":["Crosstalk","Attenuation","A duplex mismatch","Wavelength division multiplexing conflict"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Crosstalk occurs when signal from one wire pair induces interference on an adjacent pair, commonly caused by excessive untwisting during termination, which reduces the cable's ability to cancel out this interference through its twisted-pair design.","id":599,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — crosstalk occurs when signal from one pair interferes with an adjacent pair, often from excessive untwisting during termination.","Wrong — attenuation is gradual signal weakening over distance, not interference between adjacent pairs.","Wrong — a duplex mismatch is a configuration disagreement, not a termination-caused interference issue.","Wrong — wavelength division multiplexing is a fiber technology, unrelated to copper pair interference."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A long cable run between a switch and a workstation exceeds the standard maximum distance for copper Ethernet cabling, and the connection experiences frequent errors and drops as a result. What is the underlying physical cause of this issue?","options":["Attenuation, as the signal weakens too much over the excessive distance","Crosstalk between adjacent wire pairs","A duplex mismatch between the switch and workstation","Electromagnetic interference from nearby fluorescent lighting"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Attenuation is the gradual weakening of a signal over distance; copper Ethernet cabling has a maximum rated length specifically because attenuation eventually degrades the signal too much for reliable communication, which is exactly the cause when a run exceeds that standard maximum distance.","id":600,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — attenuation is the gradual weakening of signal over distance, which becomes a problem once the cable exceeds its rated maximum length.","Wrong — crosstalk is interference between adjacent pairs, not signal weakening from excessive length.","Wrong — a duplex mismatch is a configuration disagreement, unrelated to a cable being too long.","Wrong — fluorescent lighting interference is a specific EMI source, not the standard cause of exceeding a cable's max distance."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"During cable termination, a technician accidentally separates one wire pair across two different pin positions instead of keeping the pair together on its intended pins. The link partially works but experiences excessive crosstalk and errors. What is this specific miswiring fault called?","options":["A split pair","TX/RX reversal","A crossover cable used where a straight-through was needed","Attenuation"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A split pair occurs when a technician incorrectly wires one conductor from each of two different twisted pairs onto pin positions that should each hold a complete original pair; this defeats the cable's twisted-pair noise cancellation design and causes significant crosstalk even though basic continuity may still test as working.","id":601,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a split pair wires conductors from two different original pairs together, defeating noise cancellation and causing crosstalk.","Wrong — TX/RX reversal swaps the transmit and receive pairs entirely, a different fault than mixing individual conductors between pairs.","Wrong — using a crossover cable where a straight-through was needed is a cable-selection error, not a termination miswiring fault.","Wrong — attenuation is gradual signal loss over distance, unrelated to how individual conductors are paired during termination."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A switch interface shows a steadily increasing count of late collisions and the connected device is running noticeably slower than expected. Investigation reveals one side of the link is set to full duplex while the other is set to half duplex. What is this issue called?","options":["A duplex mismatch","Attenuation","A split pair","Wavelength division multiplexing conflict"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A duplex mismatch occurs when the two ends of a link are configured with different duplex settings, which commonly produces collisions and degraded performance on the half-duplex side, exactly matching the symptoms and root cause described.","id":602,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a duplex mismatch occurs when link ends have different duplex settings, producing late collisions and degraded performance.","Wrong — attenuation is signal weakening over distance, not a duplex setting disagreement.","Wrong — a split pair is a termination wiring fault, not a duplex configuration issue.","Wrong — wavelength division multiplexing is a fiber technology, unrelated to copper duplex settings."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A switch port's interface statistics show a rapidly climbing count of frame check sequence (FCS/CRC) errors on a specific link. What does this counter specifically indicate about the traffic on that port?","options":["Frames are arriving corrupted, commonly due to a physical layer problem like a damaged cable or connector","The port has run out of available bandwidth due to high utilization from other connected devices","The connected device has an incorrect IP address configured, which is a Layer 3 addressing issue","A firewall is actively blocking traffic on that port, which would not increase a frame checksum error counter"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"CRC errors indicate that frames are arriving with data corruption detected by the checksum, which is commonly caused by physical layer problems such as a damaged cable, bad connector, or interference, rather than higher-layer issues like bandwidth, IP addressing, or firewall rules.","id":603,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — CRC errors indicate corrupted frames, commonly from a physical layer problem like a damaged cable or connector.","Wrong — high bandwidth utilization would show as congestion or discards, not specifically as checksum errors.","Wrong — an incorrect IP address is a Layer 3 issue and would not generate Layer 2 frame checksum errors.","Wrong — a firewall blocking traffic would drop packets outright, not cause a rising checksum error counter."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A technician suspects a specific patch cable is faulty and wants to definitively confirm whether individual wire pairs have continuity, an open circuit, or a short, without needing any networking equipment powered on. Which tool should the technician use?","options":["A cable tester","A protocol analyzer","An SNMP manager","A media converter"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A cable tester directly checks the physical continuity and pinout of a cable's individual wire pairs, identifying opens, shorts, or miswiring without requiring any networking equipment to be active, making it the correct tool for this specific physical-layer diagnostic.","id":604,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a cable tester checks continuity, opens, and shorts on individual wire pairs without requiring active networking equipment.","Wrong — a protocol analyzer captures live traffic content, which requires an active network connection, unlike a simple cable tester.","Wrong — an SNMP manager monitors active devices; it does not test unpowered cable continuity.","Wrong — a media converter translates between cable types; it does not test for continuity, opens, or shorts."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"After replacing a suspected faulty SFP transceiver in a switch, the link remains down. The technician confirms the replacement transceiver is compatible and the fiber cable itself tests clean with an optical power meter. What should the technician check NEXT?","options":["Whether the fiber strands are connected in the correct transmit/receive orientation (polarity) at both ends","Whether the switch has the correct default gateway configured, which affects routing rather than a physical fiber link","Whether DHCP is enabled on the connected VLAN, which affects address assignment rather than link establishment","Whether the switch's NTP server is reachable, which affects time synchronization rather than link establishment"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Fiber connections require correct transmit/receive polarity between both ends of the link; if the strands are crossed or reversed even with a working transceiver and clean cable, the link will fail to establish, making this the logical next physical-layer check rather than unrelated higher-layer settings like DHCP or NTP.","id":605,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — fiber links require correct transmit/receive polarity at both ends; reversed strands prevent the link from working even with good hardware and cable.","Wrong — the default gateway affects routing, not whether a physical fiber link comes up at all.","Wrong — DHCP affects address assignment, not whether the physical fiber link itself establishes.","Wrong — NTP reachability affects time sync, not whether the physical fiber link establishes."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A fiber optic link that previously worked reliably begins experiencing intermittent errors after a recent office cleaning. Inspection reveals visible dust and smudging on the fiber connector's end face. What is the MOST likely cause of the intermittent errors?","options":["Contamination on the connector end face is increasing signal attenuation at the connection point","The fiber cable's bend radius has been permanently altered, which would not correlate specifically with a cleaning event","The transceiver has failed completely, which would cause the link to fail entirely rather than intermittently","The switch port has been administratively disabled, which would prevent all traffic rather than cause intermittent errors"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Dust and contamination on a fiber connector's end face can significantly increase signal loss (attenuation) at that connection point, causing intermittent errors that closely correlate with contamination events like a cleaning that could have disturbed connections or introduced debris; cleaning the connector end face is the appropriate next step.","id":606,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — dust and contamination on a connector end face increases signal attenuation, causing intermittent errors correlated with the cleaning event.","Wrong — a permanently altered bend radius would typically cause a fixed, not intermittent, signal issue and isn't tied to a cleaning event.","Wrong — a fully failed transceiver would cause the link to fail completely, not produce intermittent errors.","Wrong — an administratively disabled port would block all traffic, not produce intermittent errors correlated with contamination."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A technician installs Category 5e cabling for a new deployment that requires reliable 10 Gbps connectivity across a 90-meter run, and the link consistently fails to reach the required speed, negotiating instead at a much lower rate. What is the MOST likely explanation?","options":["The cable category is insufficient for reliable 10 Gbps at that distance","The connector was terminated with a split pair, which would typically prevent the link from coming up at all","The switch port has a duplex mismatch, which produces collisions rather than a speed negotiation shortfall","The cable exceeds its maximum bend radius, which would cause loss or errors rather than a speed downgrade"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Category 5e cabling is not rated to reliably support 10 Gbps speeds over long distances; Category 6a is generally required for dependable 10 Gbps performance across the full 100-meter maximum run, making the cable category itself the most likely explanation for the speed shortfall described.","id":607,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — Cat 5e isn't rated to reliably support 10 Gbps over a 90-meter run; Cat 6a is generally required for that.","Wrong — a split pair typically prevents a stable link entirely rather than causing a negotiated speed downgrade.","Wrong — a duplex mismatch produces collisions and poor throughput, not a speed negotiation shortfall.","Wrong — exceeding bend radius causes loss or errors, not a specific negotiated-speed downgrade."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A technician terminating a patch panel accidentally wires several ports using the T568A standard while the rest of the panel and all patch cables use the T568B standard. What is the MOST likely symptom of this inconsistency?","options":["Certain ports may experience connectivity issues or unreliable links due to the wiring standard mismatch, particularly if crossover-like pairing occurs unintentionally","The entire building's internet connection will go down immediately, which would only happen from a much larger infrastructure failure than a wiring standard inconsistency on a few patch panel ports","The patch panel will physically stop accepting new cables, which is not something a wiring standard mismatch could ever cause on a passive patch panel","All switches on the network will reboot automatically, which a passive cabling inconsistency has no ability to trigger in any way"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Mixing T568A and T568B wiring standards inconsistently across a punch-down installation can create unintended crossover-like pairing between certain connections, resulting in unreliable or failed links on the affected ports specifically, rather than a building-wide or hardware-level failure.","id":608,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — inconsistent T568A/T568B wiring can create unintended crossover-like pairing, causing unreliable links on the affected ports specifically.","Wrong — a localized wiring standard mismatch would not take down the building's entire internet connection.","Wrong — a passive patch panel has no mechanism to physically stop accepting cables due to a wiring standard mismatch.","Wrong — a cabling inconsistency has no ability to trigger automatic reboots of network switches."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A wall-mounted network jack that previously worked fine begins experiencing sporadic disconnects, particularly whenever someone bumps the nearby furniture. What is the MOST likely physical cause?","options":["A loose or partially seated connector at the jack or patch panel that is sensitive to physical movement","A firewall rule that intermittently blocks the port, which would not correlate with physically bumping nearby furniture","An IP address conflict on the local subnet, which would not be triggered by physically moving furniture near a jack","An expired DHCP lease on the connected device, which would not cause disconnects tied to bumping furniture"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Disconnects that correlate specifically with physical movement or bumping strongly suggest a loose or partially seated physical connection at the jack or patch panel, rather than a logical or configuration issue like a firewall rule, IP conflict, or DHCP lease, none of which would be triggered by furniture movement.","id":609,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — disconnects correlated with physical movement point to a loose or partially seated connector at the jack or patch panel.","Wrong — a firewall rule wouldn't intermittently trigger based on someone bumping nearby furniture.","Wrong — an IP conflict wouldn't be caused by or correlate with physical furniture movement.","Wrong — an expired DHCP lease wouldn't cause disconnects tied specifically to bumping furniture."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A switch interface's statistics show an unusually high number of 'runts,' which are frames shorter than the minimum valid Ethernet frame size. What does this specific counter MOST likely indicate?","options":["A collision or a physical layer problem is causing frames to be prematurely truncated during transmission","The interface has an incorrect IP address configured, which is a Layer 3 issue unrelated to frame size","The switch's spanning tree protocol has detected a loop, which would show as topology changes, not truncated frames","The connected device is requesting an unusually large MTU size, which would produce oversized frames, not undersized ones"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Runt frames, which are shorter than the Ethernet minimum, are typically caused by collisions or physical layer problems that truncate a frame mid-transmission, rather than logical issues like IP addressing, spanning tree loops, or MTU settings, which would not produce this specific physical-layer symptom.","id":610,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — runt frames are typically caused by collisions or physical layer problems truncating a frame mid-transmission.","Wrong — an incorrect IP address is a Layer 3 issue and wouldn't cause undersized Layer 2 frames.","Wrong — a detected STP loop would show as topology changes, not truncated runt frames.","Wrong — a large requested MTU would produce oversized frames, the opposite of undersized runts."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A network technician needs to identify which physical cable in a large, unlabeled bundle corresponds to a specific wall jack, without disconnecting anything yet. Which tool combination is BEST suited for this task?","options":["A tone generator and probe","A cable tester","An optical time-domain reflectometer (OTDR)","A protocol analyzer"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A tone generator injects a distinctive audible signal onto a specific cable, which a probe can then be used to detect at the other end, allowing a technician to trace and identify one specific cable within a large, unlabeled bundle without needing to disconnect anything.","id":611,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a tone generator injects a signal that a probe can detect, letting a technician trace one cable within an unlabeled bundle.","Wrong — a cable tester verifies continuity and pinout, but it doesn't trace one specific cable within a bundle.","Wrong — an OTDR locates faults along fiber, not identify a specific copper cable within a bundle.","Wrong — a protocol analyzer captures traffic content; it has no role in physically tracing a cable."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A fiber optic technician needs to precisely locate the exact point along a long fiber run, buried underground, where a break or excessive loss is occurring, without physically digging up the entire cable path. Which specialized tool is designed for this purpose?","options":["An optical time-domain reflectometer (OTDR)","A basic cable tester","A tone generator and probe","A multimeter"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An OTDR sends light pulses down a fiber and analyzes the reflected signal to precisely calculate the distance to a break, excessive loss point, or other fault along the cable, which is exactly the capability needed to locate a problem in a long, buried fiber run without physical excavation.","id":612,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — an OTDR sends light pulses and analyzes reflections to calculate the exact distance to a fault along a fiber run.","Wrong — a basic cable tester checks copper continuity, not fault distance along a long buried fiber run.","Wrong — a tone generator and probe trace copper cable paths, not locate faults along fiber.","Wrong — a multimeter measures voltage and continuity, unrelated to locating faults along fiber."]},{"objectiveId":"1.5","domain":"1.0 Networking Concepts","objective":"Transmission Media & Transceivers","question":"A cable installer is running network cabling through a vertical shaft that connects multiple floors of an office building, specifically the space used to route cabling between floors rather than within a single floor's ceiling plenum. Which cable rating is appropriate for this vertical inter-floor pathway?","options":["Riser-rated cable","Plenum-rated cable","Direct burial-rated cable","Outdoor aerial-rated cable"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Riser-rated cable is specifically designed for vertical shafts that run between floors, with fire-resistance properties intended to prevent flame from spreading vertically between levels, which is a distinct use case and rating from plenum cable used in horizontal air-handling spaces.","id":613,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — riser-rated cable is designed for vertical shafts between floors, preventing flame from spreading between levels.","Wrong — plenum-rated cable is designed for horizontal air-handling spaces, not vertical inter-floor shafts.","Wrong — direct burial-rated cable is designed for underground installation, not vertical building shafts.","Wrong — outdoor aerial-rated cable is designed for exterior overhead runs, not interior vertical shafts."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"A junior technician wants to resolve a reported network issue as quickly as possible and immediately begins reconfiguring the suspected device without first gathering information about the symptoms or considering what might have caused the problem. What foundational troubleshooting step is being skipped?","options":["Identifying the problem before taking any corrective action","Verifying full system functionality after the fix","Documenting the findings and outcome","Establishing a plan of action with a rollback option"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Jumping straight to changes without first identifying the problem, gathering symptoms, and understanding scope skips the foundational first step of the troubleshooting methodology, which significantly increases the risk of making an incorrect change or missing the actual root cause entirely.","id":614,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — reconfiguring immediately without gathering information skips the foundational step of identifying the problem first.","Wrong — verifying full system functionality is a later step, not something skipped by acting too early.","Wrong — documenting findings is a later step performed after resolution, not what's skipped at the start.","Wrong — establishing a plan of action comes after identifying the problem, which is the step actually being skipped here."]},{"objectiveId":"5.1","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Troubleshooting Methodology","question":"After a technician implements a fix for a reported network issue, the original symptom is resolved, but the technician also checks several related systems and asks the original user to confirm everything else is working as expected before closing the ticket. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this broader verification?","options":["To confirm the fix did not inadvertently disrupt any other functionality while resolving the original issue","To identify a completely new and unrelated problem to investigate next, rather than confirming the original fix","To satisfy a requirement to always contact the user twice per ticket, regardless of any actual technical need","To replace the need for any documentation of the incident, since verification alone is treated as sufficient"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Verifying full system functionality broadly, not just the original symptom, ensures that the applied fix didn't inadvertently break or affect other functionality, which is an important check before considering the issue fully resolved and closing the ticket.","id":615,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — broader verification confirms the fix didn't disrupt other functionality while resolving the original issue.","Wrong — the purpose is to verify the existing fix, not to go looking for an unrelated new problem.","Wrong — this isn't about a policy requiring double contact; it serves a genuine verification purpose.","Wrong — broader verification doesn't replace documentation; both are separate, necessary steps."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A newly deployed fiber link between two switches shows the interface as up on both ends, but no traffic passes and both ends report continuous errors. An inspection reveals the transmit fiber strand from switch A is connected to the transmit port on switch B, rather than to switch B's receive port. What term describes this specific installation error?","options":["Incorrect fiber polarity","Attenuation","Crosstalk","A duplex mismatch"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Correct fiber polarity requires that the transmit strand on one end connects to the receive port on the other end; connecting transmit-to-transmit instead of transmit-to-receive is a polarity error that prevents the link from properly passing traffic even though both interfaces may show as physically up.","id":616,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — correct fiber polarity requires transmit-to-receive connections; transmit-to-transmit is a polarity error that blocks traffic.","Wrong — attenuation is gradual signal weakening over distance, not a transmit/receive wiring error.","Wrong — crosstalk is interference between copper wire pairs, unrelated to fiber strand polarity.","Wrong — a duplex mismatch is a copper link configuration issue, not a fiber polarity wiring error."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A technician replaces a suspected bad Ethernet cable with a new one from the same box, but the connectivity issue persists identically. What should the technician do NEXT according to proper troubleshooting practice?","options":["Reconsider the original theory, since testing did not confirm it, and investigate other possible causes such as the switch port or NIC","Continue replacing cables from the same box indefinitely until one happens to work, without considering other causes","Assume the new cable is also defective without any further testing, rather than reconsidering the original theory","Immediately escalate the issue as unsolvable and close the ticket, without investigating any other possible cause"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"When a theory is tested (in this case, by replacing the cable) and the fix does not resolve the issue, proper methodology calls for reconsidering the original theory and investigating other potential causes, such as the switch port or network interface card, rather than repeatedly retrying the same disproven fix.","id":617,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — since replacing the cable didn't fix the issue, the technician should reconsider the theory and investigate other causes like the port or NIC.","Wrong — repeatedly swapping cables from the same box without reconsidering the theory wastes time on an already-disproven cause.","Wrong — assuming the new cable is also defective without testing skips proper verification of the actual cause.","Wrong — escalating as unsolvable skips investigating other clearly reasonable causes like the port or NIC."]},{"objectiveId":"5.2","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Cabling & Physical Interface Issues","question":"A technician notices that a specific switch port's interface counters show a high number of 'giants,' frames larger than the maximum standard Ethernet frame size. Assuming jumbo frames are not intentionally configured on this network, what does this MOST likely indicate?","options":["A misconfiguration or malfunctioning device is sending oversized frames that shouldn't be on this network","The cable is too short for the required data rate, which would not produce oversized frames on its own","The connector has been terminated using the T568A standard instead of T568B, which affects pinout, not frame size","The transceiver is incompatible with the switch chassis, which would typically prevent the link from coming up at all"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Giant frames exceeding the standard maximum size, when jumbo frames aren't intentionally enabled, typically point to a misconfigured or malfunctioning device improperly generating oversized frames, rather than a cable length, wiring standard, or transceiver compatibility issue, which wouldn't produce this specific frame-size symptom.","id":618,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — giant frames when jumbo frames aren't configured typically indicate a misconfigured or malfunctioning device sending oversized frames.","Wrong — a too-short cable would not by itself cause oversized frames to be generated.","Wrong — a T568A/T568B mismatch affects pinout and wiring, not the size of frames being generated.","Wrong — transceiver incompatibility would typically prevent the link from coming up, not produce oversized frames."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"Several workstations on a network are unable to obtain an IP address, and the DHCP server's logs show that all addresses in the configured scope have already been assigned to other devices. What is the MOST likely cause of this issue?","options":["DHCP scope exhaustion, where the pool of available addresses has been fully allocated","A rogue DHCP server is issuing conflicting addresses, which would show incorrect settings rather than allocation failures","The DNS server is unreachable, which affects name resolution rather than address assignment","The default gateway has been misconfigured, which affects routing rather than address assignment itself"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"DHCP scope exhaustion occurs when every address in the configured pool has already been leased out, leaving no addresses available for new client requests, exactly matching the symptom of workstations failing to obtain an address while the logs show a fully allocated scope.","id":619,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — scope exhaustion means every address in the pool is already leased, leaving nothing for new client requests.","Wrong — a rogue DHCP server would hand out incorrect settings, not show the legitimate scope as fully allocated.","Wrong — an unreachable DNS server affects name resolution, not the ability to obtain an IP address at all.","Wrong — a misconfigured gateway affects routing after an address is assigned, not the initial address assignment itself."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"A user reports that they can successfully reach internal file servers by typing their IP addresses directly, but typing the server's hostname instead results in an error that the name could not be resolved. What is the MOST likely cause?","options":["A DNS configuration issue, such as an incorrect or unreachable DNS server setting on the client","A duplicate IP address conflict on the network, which would typically affect connectivity by both name and address","An expired DHCP lease on the client, which would typically prevent reaching resources by address as well","A physical cabling fault between the client and the switch, which would prevent connectivity entirely, not selectively"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The ability to connect successfully using an IP address but not a hostname strongly points to a name resolution (DNS) problem, such as an incorrect or unreachable DNS server configured on the client, since basic IP connectivity has already been confirmed to be working.","id":620,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — reaching by IP but failing by hostname strongly points to a DNS configuration issue on the client.","Wrong — a duplicate IP conflict would typically disrupt connectivity by address as well, not just by name.","Wrong — an expired DHCP lease would typically prevent reaching resources by address too, not just by name.","Wrong — a physical cabling fault would prevent connectivity entirely, not selectively affect only name-based access."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"A workstation is assigned an IP address in the 169.254.x.x range and cannot communicate with any other device on the network, including the default gateway. What does this specific address range indicate about the underlying problem?","options":["The device failed to obtain an address from a DHCP server and fell back to an APIPA address","The device successfully obtained a valid address from the DHCP server, which an APIPA address indicates did not occur","The device has a properly configured static IP address, which an APIPA address would not represent","The device is using an address reserved specifically for DNS servers, which is not what the APIPA range represents"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The 169.254.x.x range is the Automatic Private IP Addressing (APIPA) range, which a device assigns itself only after failing to reach a DHCP server, indicating that DHCP is unavailable or unreachable rather than that addressing succeeded normally.","id":621,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a 169.254.x.x address is an APIPA address, assigned only after the device failed to reach a DHCP server.","Wrong — successfully obtaining a DHCP address would not result in an APIPA address; APIPA specifically signals DHCP failure.","Wrong — a properly configured static address would not fall into the 169.254.x.x automatic private addressing range.","Wrong — 169.254.x.x is not a range reserved for DNS servers; it's the self-assigned APIPA range for failed DHCP."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"Users on a specific subnet can communicate with each other but cannot reach any resources outside their local subnet, including the internet. The devices have valid IP addresses and subnet masks. What setting should be checked FIRST?","options":["The default gateway configuration on the affected devices","The DNS server's uptime","The physical cabling between switches","The wireless access point's SSID broadcast setting"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"When devices can communicate within their own subnet but cannot reach anything outside it, an incorrect or missing default gateway is the most likely culprit, since the gateway is specifically what routes traffic destined for other networks, which matches this exact symptom pattern.","id":622,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — since local communication works but nothing beyond the subnet does, the default gateway configuration is the first thing to check.","Wrong — DNS server uptime would affect name resolution, not the ability to reach any resource outside the subnet by IP.","Wrong — physical cabling between switches would typically affect local connectivity too, not just traffic beyond the subnet.","Wrong — the SSID broadcast setting affects wireless visibility, not the ability to route beyond the local subnet."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"An unauthorized device connected to a network begins handing out IP addresses to clients, causing some users to receive incorrect gateway and DNS settings and lose proper connectivity. What is this unauthorized device called?","options":["A rogue DHCP server","A media converter","A honeypot","A screened subnet"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A rogue DHCP server is an unauthorized device on the network handing out its own DHCP leases, which can provide clients with incorrect gateway, DNS, or addressing information and cause widespread connectivity problems, exactly matching the scenario described.","id":623,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a rogue DHCP server is an unauthorized device issuing its own leases, which can hand out incorrect gateway and DNS settings.","Wrong — a media converter translates between cable types; it doesn't assign IP addresses to clients.","Wrong — a honeypot is a decoy system for detecting attackers, not a device causing DHCP-related connectivity issues.","Wrong — a screened subnet is a network segmentation design, unrelated to an unauthorized DHCP server."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"A user attempts to visit a website and receives a certificate warning in their browser stating the site's security certificate is no longer valid. What is the MOST likely cause of this specific warning?","options":["The website's SSL/TLS certificate has expired and needs to be renewed","The DNS server returned the wrong IP address for the website","The user's DHCP lease has expired","The website's firewall is blocking port 80"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A browser warning specifically about certificate validity most commonly indicates that the site's SSL/TLS certificate has expired and needs to be renewed, which is a distinct issue from DNS resolution, DHCP leasing, or basic port-level firewall blocking, none of which produce a certificate validity warning.","id":624,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a certificate validity warning most commonly means the site's SSL/TLS certificate has expired and needs renewal.","Wrong — a wrong DNS response would cause a browser to load a different site or fail to connect, not trigger a certificate validity warning.","Wrong — an expired DHCP lease affects the user's own IP address, unrelated to the remote site's certificate status.","Wrong — a blocked port 80 would prevent an unencrypted connection but wouldn't produce a certificate validity warning."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"Two devices on the same network segment are both configured with the exact same static IP address, and both begin experiencing intermittent connectivity problems and error messages about a network address conflict. What is this issue called?","options":["An IP address conflict (duplicate IP address)","DHCP scope exhaustion","A rogue DHCP server issue","A DNS caching issue"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An IP address conflict occurs when two devices on the same network are assigned the identical address, typically from a static misconfiguration, causing both devices to experience intermittent connectivity and conflict warnings, exactly matching the described symptoms.","id":625,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — two devices sharing the same static IP address is a classic IP address conflict, causing intermittent connectivity and conflict warnings.","Wrong — DHCP scope exhaustion prevents new address assignment; it doesn't explain two devices sharing one static address.","Wrong — a rogue DHCP server issue involves unauthorized address assignment, not two statically configured devices with the same address.","Wrong — a DNS caching issue affects name resolution, not two devices holding the identical IP address."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"Internal employees can access an internal application using its internal hostname, but that same hostname resolves to an incorrect address when accessed from outside the corporate network, since a different set of DNS records is served to external versus internal requesters. What DNS configuration does this describe?","options":["Split DNS (split-horizon DNS)","DNS cache poisoning","A rogue DHCP server","DHCP scope exhaustion"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Split DNS (also called split-horizon DNS) intentionally serves different DNS answers to internal versus external requesters for the same hostname, which is a legitimate and common configuration, though it can create confusion during troubleshooting if not properly understood or documented.","id":626,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — split DNS intentionally serves different answers to internal versus external requesters for the same hostname.","Wrong — DNS cache poisoning is a malicious corruption of DNS data, not an intentional, legitimate internal/external split.","Wrong — a rogue DHCP server issues unauthorized address leases, unrelated to serving different DNS answers by requester location.","Wrong — DHCP scope exhaustion is about running out of addresses, unrelated to differing DNS answers by requester location."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"A network firewall is reconfigured with stricter outbound rules, and shortly afterward, users report they can no longer browse websites by name, though pinging an external IP address directly still works. Which port is MOST likely being blocked by the new firewall rule?","options":["UDP/TCP port 53 (DNS)","TCP port 22 (SSH)","TCP port 3389 (RDP)","UDP port 69 (TFTP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The ability to reach an external IP directly but not resolve hostnames points to blocked DNS traffic, which operates on port 53; a firewall rule change blocking this port would prevent name resolution while still allowing direct IP-based connectivity, exactly matching the symptoms described.","id":627,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — DNS operates on port 53; blocking it would prevent hostname resolution while direct IP connectivity still works.","Wrong — blocking SSH (port 22) would affect remote command-line access, not general website name resolution.","Wrong — blocking RDP (port 3389) would affect remote desktop sessions, not website name resolution.","Wrong — blocking TFTP (port 69) would affect simple file transfers, not website name resolution."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"All devices on a subnet are configured with a subnet mask of 255.255.255.0, except for one workstation that was manually configured with 255.255.0.0. That workstation experiences unpredictable connectivity, able to reach some devices but not others on what should be the same local subnet. What is the MOST likely cause?","options":["The incorrect subnet mask causes the workstation to miscalculate which addresses are local versus remote","The workstation's DNS server is unreachable, which would affect name resolution rather than local subnet reachability","The workstation has a duplicate IP address, which would produce address conflict warnings, not this local/remote pattern","The workstation's DHCP lease has expired, which would typically prevent addressing entirely rather than cause this pattern"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An incorrect subnet mask causes a device to miscalculate the boundary of its local subnet, leading it to treat some addresses as local when they should be treated as remote (requiring the gateway) or vice versa, which produces exactly the unpredictable, inconsistent connectivity pattern described.","id":628,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — the wrong subnet mask makes the workstation miscalculate which addresses are local versus remote, producing inconsistent reachability.","Wrong — an unreachable DNS server would affect name resolution, not this local/remote reachability inconsistency.","Wrong — a duplicate IP address would produce conflict warnings, not this specific inconsistent local/remote pattern.","Wrong — an expired DHCP lease would typically prevent addressing entirely rather than cause this exact pattern."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"A company's internal clock-dependent authentication system begins rejecting valid login attempts with time-sensitive tokens, and investigation reveals that several servers' clocks have drifted by several minutes from each other. Which service, if misconfigured or unreachable, would MOST likely explain this drift?","options":["Network Time Protocol (NTP)","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP)","Domain Name System (DNS)","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"NTP is responsible for keeping device clocks synchronized across the network; if NTP is misconfigured or the time source becomes unreachable, clocks will gradually drift apart, which can break time-sensitive processes like certain authentication tokens, exactly matching the scenario described.","id":629,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — NTP keeps device clocks synchronized; if it's misconfigured or unreachable, clocks drift apart and can break time-sensitive authentication.","Wrong — DHCP assigns IP configuration and has no role in keeping clocks synchronized.","Wrong — DNS resolves hostnames to addresses and has no role in clock synchronization.","Wrong — SNMP is used for device monitoring and management, not time synchronization."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"A newly created VLAN for a group of IoT devices is unable to reach the DHCP server, which lives on a different VLAN, even though routing between the VLANs is confirmed to be working for other traffic. What network service configuration is MOST likely missing?","options":["A DHCP relay agent (IP helper) configured on the routing device for the new VLAN","A DNS forwarder, which affects name resolution rather than delivering DHCP broadcasts across a VLAN boundary","An NTP server address, which affects time synchronization rather than DHCP broadcast forwarding between VLANs","A default gateway on the DHCP server itself, which would not enable broadcast traffic to cross into another VLAN"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"When DHCP clients and the DHCP server reside on different subnets/VLANs, a DHCP relay agent (often configured as an IP helper address) is required on the routing device to forward DHCP broadcast requests across the VLAN boundary to the server, since DHCP requests are broadcast traffic that doesn't normally cross routed boundaries on its own.","id":630,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a DHCP relay agent (IP helper) is needed on the router to forward DHCP broadcasts across the VLAN boundary to the server.","Wrong — a DNS forwarder relates to name resolution, not delivering DHCP broadcast requests across VLANs.","Wrong — an NTP server address relates to time sync, not forwarding DHCP broadcasts between VLANs.","Wrong — a default gateway on the DHCP server itself doesn't enable broadcast traffic to cross into another VLAN."]},{"objectiveId":"5.4","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","question":"In a densely populated apartment building, dozens of nearby wireless networks are all broadcasting on the same 2.4 GHz channel, causing significant interference and poor performance for everyone. What is this specific problem called?","options":["Channel overlap (co-channel interference)","Attenuation","A duplex mismatch","DHCP scope exhaustion"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Channel overlap, also called co-channel interference, occurs when multiple wireless networks in close proximity broadcast on the same or overlapping channels, causing them to compete for airtime and degrading performance for all of them, exactly matching the scenario in a densely populated building.","id":631,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — channel overlap (co-channel interference) happens when many nearby networks share the same channel and compete for airtime.","Wrong — attenuation is signal weakening over distance, not interference between competing wireless networks.","Wrong — a duplex mismatch is a wired link configuration issue, unrelated to wireless channel congestion.","Wrong — DHCP scope exhaustion is an address-assignment problem, unrelated to wireless channel interference."]},{"objectiveId":"5.4","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","question":"A company's internet connection performs well during most of the day but becomes noticeably slow every day between noon and 1 PM, when most employees are streaming video and browsing during their lunch break. What is the MOST likely explanation?","options":["Bandwidth saturation caused by high concurrent usage during that specific time window","A physical cable fault that only occurs at that specific time of day, which physical faults don't typically do on a predictable daily schedule","A DNS server outage limited to that hour, which would affect only name resolution rather than overall connection speed","An IP address conflict that only occurs during lunch hour, which conflicts don't typically follow a predictable daily schedule"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A predictable slowdown correlating with a specific high-usage time window, such as a lunch break with many employees streaming and browsing simultaneously, points to bandwidth saturation from high concurrent demand exceeding available capacity, rather than a physical fault or service outage, which would be unlikely to follow such a consistent daily schedule.","id":632,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — a predictable slowdown during a high-usage window points to bandwidth saturation from concurrent demand exceeding capacity.","Wrong — a physical cable fault wouldn't reliably appear and disappear on the same daily schedule.","Wrong — a DNS outage would affect name resolution, not overall connection speed, and is unlikely to recur on a fixed schedule.","Wrong — an IP address conflict wouldn't naturally align with a recurring daily time window like lunch hour."]},{"objectiveId":"5.4","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","question":"An office deploys many wireless access points close together to provide strong coverage throughout a large open floor plan, but users report degraded performance in areas where signal from multiple access points overlaps heavily on the same channel. What is this specific issue called?","options":["Co-channel interference from overlapping access point coverage","A rogue DHCP server, which would cause addressing problems rather than degraded performance tied to overlapping wireless coverage","A split pair in the network cabling, which is a copper wiring fault unrelated to wireless channel overlap","An expired SSL certificate on the wireless controller, which would cause management access warnings, not wireless performance degradation"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Co-channel interference occurs when multiple access points using the same channel have overlapping coverage areas, causing devices to compete for airtime with each other's signals, which is a common issue in high-density access point deployments if channel planning isn't carefully managed.","id":633,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — co-channel interference occurs when multiple access points on the same channel have overlapping coverage, causing airtime competition.","Wrong — a rogue DHCP server causes addressing problems, not performance degradation tied to overlapping wireless coverage.","Wrong — a split pair is a copper cabling fault, unrelated to wireless channel planning.","Wrong — an expired SSL certificate would cause access warnings, not wireless performance issues from overlapping coverage."]},{"objectiveId":"5.4","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Performance & Wireless Issues","question":"A company's VoIP calls sound choppy and words occasionally cut out, even though there is plenty of available bandwidth on the connection. Network monitoring shows that packet arrival times are highly inconsistent, with some packets arriving much later than others relative to when they were sent. What performance issue does this describe?","options":["Jitter, the variation in packet arrival timing, which is particularly disruptive for real-time voice traffic","Attenuation, the weakening of signal strength over distance, which affects overall signal quality rather than inconsistent packet arrival timing","A duplex mismatch on the VoIP phone's switch port, which would typically cause collisions and errors rather than this specific timing variation","DHCP scope exhaustion on the voice VLAN, which would prevent phones from getting an address at all rather than cause choppy call audio"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Jitter refers to the variation in packet arrival timing, and even with sufficient overall bandwidth, high jitter is particularly disruptive to real-time applications like VoIP, which depend on packets arriving at a consistent, predictable rate to reconstruct smooth audio, distinguishing it from latency (which measures overall delay) or bandwidth issues.","id":634,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — jitter is the variation in packet arrival timing, which disrupts real-time voice even when bandwidth is otherwise sufficient.","Wrong — attenuation describes weakening signal strength over distance, not variable packet arrival timing.","Wrong — a duplex mismatch would typically produce collisions and errors, not the specific timing variation described.","Wrong — DHCP scope exhaustion would prevent phones from getting an address, not cause choppy audio on already-connected calls."]},{"objectiveId":"5.3","domain":"5.0 Network Troubleshooting","objective":"Network Service Issues","question":"A client device receives a valid IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway from DHCP, but is unable to resolve any external hostnames, while devices on the same subnet configured with a different DNS server work normally. What is the MOST likely cause?","options":["The DHCP scope is handing out an incorrect or unreachable DNS server address","The client's default gateway is misconfigured, which would affect reaching other subnets entirely, not just external name resolution","The client has a duplicate IP address, which would cause address conflict warnings rather than isolated DNS resolution failure","The switch port the client is connected to has port security enabled, which would block or restrict the port itself, not selectively break DNS resolution"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Since the device successfully obtained addressing and other devices with a different DNS server work fine, the issue is isolated to name resolution, most likely because the DHCP scope is distributing an incorrect or unreachable DNS server address to this particular client, rather than a gateway, addressing conflict, or port security issue.","id":635,"source":"original-2026-batch","optionExplanations":["Correct — since addressing is fine and other clients with a different DNS server work, the DHCP scope is likely handing this client a bad DNS address.","Wrong — a misconfigured gateway would prevent reaching other subnets generally, not selectively break only name resolution.","Wrong — a duplicate IP address would cause conflict warnings and broader connectivity issues, not an isolated DNS failure.","Wrong — port security restricts which devices can use a port; it would not selectively break only DNS resolution."]},{"id":636,"question":"A host has IP 192.168.10.25 with subnet mask 255.255.255.0. Which address is the network ID?","options":["192.168.10.0 network address","192.168.10.255 broadcast address","192.168.10.1 default gateway","192.168.10.25 host address"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"With /24 (255.255.255.0), the network ID is the .0 address in that subnet.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — with a /24 mask (255.255.255.0), the network ID is the address with all host bits at zero: 192.168.10.0.","Wrong — 192.168.10.255 is the broadcast address for this subnet, not the network ID.","Wrong — 192.168.10.1 would be a host address commonly used for a gateway, not the network ID itself.","Wrong — 192.168.10.25 is the host's own address, not the network ID."]},{"id":637,"question":"A host uses subnet mask 255.255.255.128. How many usable host addresses are in that subnet?","options":["126 usable hosts per subnet","62 usable hosts per subnet","254 usable hosts per subnet","14 usable hosts per subnet"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"/25 yields 128 addresses total, minus network and broadcast = 126 usable.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — a /25 mask yields 128 total addresses, minus the network and broadcast addresses leaves 126 usable hosts.","Wrong — 62 usable hosts corresponds to a /26 mask, not /25.","Wrong — 254 usable hosts corresponds to a /24 mask, not /25.","Wrong — 14 usable hosts corresponds to a /28 mask, not /25."]},{"id":638,"question":"A network administrator needs at least 25 usable hosts per subnet from a /24 network. What subnet mask should be used?","options":["255.255.255.224 (/27)","255.255.255.192 (/26)","255.255.255.240 (/28)","255.255.255.128 (/25)"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A /27 (255.255.255.224) provides 30 usable host addresses, the smallest subnet that still meets the requirement of at least 25 usable hosts, making it the most efficient choice.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — a /27 (255.255.255.224) provides 30 usable hosts, the smallest subnet size that still meets the requirement of at least 25.","Wrong — a /26 (255.255.255.192) provides 62 usable hosts, more than necessary and less efficient use of address space.","Wrong — a /28 (255.255.255.240) provides only 14 usable hosts, not enough to meet the requirement of at least 25.","Wrong — a /25 (255.255.255.128) provides 126 usable hosts, far more than needed for this requirement."]},{"id":639,"question":"Which IP address is the broadcast address for the 192.168.10.64/26 subnet?","options":["192.168.10.63","192.168.10.127","192.168.10.95","192.168.10.65"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"A /26 subnet has a block size of 64, so the 192.168.10.64 subnet spans .64-.127. The network address is .64, the usable host range is .65-.126, and the broadcast address is the last address in the block: .127.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Wrong — 192.168.10.63 belongs to the previous /26 block (192.168.10.0-63), not this one.","Correct — with a /26 block size of 64, the 192.168.10.64 subnet spans .64-.127, making .127 the broadcast address.","Wrong — 192.168.10.95 is a usable host address within the block, not the broadcast address.","Wrong — 192.168.10.65 is the first usable host address, not the broadcast address."]},{"id":640,"question":"A technician assigns 255.255.255.248 to a network. How many usable hosts are available?","options":["6","14","30","2"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"/29 provides 8 total addresses; subtract network and broadcast leaves 6 usable.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — a /29 mask (255.255.255.248) provides 8 total addresses; subtracting network and broadcast leaves 6 usable.","Wrong — 14 usable hosts corresponds to a /28 mask, not /29.","Wrong — 30 usable hosts corresponds to a /27 mask, not /29.","Wrong — 2 usable hosts corresponds to a /30 mask, not /29."]},{"id":641,"question":"A host has an IP address of 10.0.5.34/20. What is the network address?","options":["10.0.0.0","10.0.5.0","10.0.16.0","10.0.4.0"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A /20 subnet increments by 16 in the third octet. 5 falls in the 0–15 range.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — a /20 mask increments by 16 in the third octet, and 5 falls within the 0-15 block, giving a network address of 10.0.0.0.","Wrong — 10.0.5.0 would only be correct for a /24 mask, not a /20 mask where blocks increment by 16.","Wrong — 10.0.16.0 is the start of the next /20 block, not the one containing 10.0.5.34.","Wrong — 10.0.4.0 is not a valid /20 block boundary, since /20 blocks increment by 16 starting at 0."]},{"id":642,"question":"Which subnet mask allows exactly 14 usable hosts?","options":["255.255.255.240","255.255.255.248","255.255.255.252","255.255.255.224"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"/28 gives 16 total addresses, 14 usable.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — a /28 mask (255.255.255.240) gives 16 total addresses, 14 of which are usable after removing network and broadcast.","Wrong — 255.255.255.248 is a /29 mask, providing only 6 usable hosts, not 14.","Wrong — 255.255.255.252 is a /30 mask, providing only 2 usable hosts, not 14.","Wrong — 255.255.255.224 is a /27 mask, providing 30 usable hosts, not 14."]},{"id":643,"question":"What is the FIRST usable host address in the 192.168.50.128/25 network?","options":["192.168.50.129","192.168.50.128","192.168.50.1","192.168.50.254"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The network address is .128, so the first usable host is .129.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — since the network address is .128, the first usable host address is the next one, .129.","Wrong — 192.168.50.128 is the network address itself, not a usable host address.","Wrong — 192.168.50.1 does not belong to the .128/25 block, which starts at .128.","Wrong — 192.168.50.254 would be the broadcast address for a /24, not the first usable host in this /25 block."]},{"id":644,"question":"Which CIDR notation provides the MOST hosts per subnet?","options":["/22","/26","/28","/30"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Smaller prefix numbers allow more host bits; /22 provides the most hosts.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — a /22 has the smallest prefix length of these options, leaving the most host bits and thus the most hosts per subnet.","Wrong — a /26 has more prefix bits (fewer host bits) than /22, resulting in fewer hosts per subnet.","Wrong — a /28 has even more prefix bits than /26, resulting in far fewer hosts per subnet.","Wrong — a /30 has the most prefix bits of these options, resulting in the fewest hosts per subnet."]},{"id":645,"question":"How many subnets are created by borrowing 3 bits from a /24 network?","options":["8","6","4","16"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"2^3 = 8 subnets.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — borrowing 3 bits creates 2^3 = 8 subnets.","Wrong — 6 subnets is not a power of two and doesn't result from borrowing any whole number of bits.","Wrong — 4 subnets would result from borrowing 2 bits, not 3.","Wrong — 16 subnets would result from borrowing 4 bits, not 3."]},{"id":646,"question":"Which subnet mask would you choose for 2 usable hosts?","options":["255.255.255.252","255.255.255.248","255.255.255.240","255.255.255.224"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"/30 provides exactly 2 usable host addresses.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — a /30 mask (255.255.255.252) provides exactly 2 usable host addresses.","Wrong — 255.255.255.248 is a /29 mask, providing 6 usable hosts, not 2.","Wrong — 255.255.255.240 is a /28 mask, providing 14 usable hosts, not 2.","Wrong — 255.255.255.224 is a /27 mask, providing 30 usable hosts, not 2."]},{"id":647,"question":"A network requires 9 subnets from a /24. What prefix is needed?","options":["/28","/27","/26","/25"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Borrowing 3 bits (/27) yields 2^3 = 8 subnets, which is not enough for a requirement of 9. Borrowing 4 bits (/28) yields 2^4 = 16 subnets, the smallest power of two that covers 9 subnets, so /28 is required.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — borrowing 4 bits (/28) yields 16 subnets, the smallest power of two that covers a requirement of 9 subnets.","Wrong — borrowing 3 bits (/27) yields only 8 subnets, which falls short of the 9 subnets required.","Wrong — a /26 borrows only 2 bits, yielding just 4 subnets, far short of the requirement.","Wrong — a /25 borrows only 1 bit, yielding just 2 subnets, far short of the requirement."]},{"id":648,"question":"Which address identifies the network itself?","options":["All host bits set to 0","All host bits set to 1","First usable address","Last usable address"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The network address has all host bits set to 0.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — the network address is identified by setting all host bits to 0.","Wrong — setting all host bits to 1 produces the broadcast address, not the network address.","Wrong — the first usable address is the network address plus one, not the network address itself.","Wrong — the last usable address is one less than the broadcast address, not the network address itself."]},{"id":649,"question":"What is the purpose of CIDR?","options":["Reduce routing table size","Encrypt IP traffic","Increase broadcast traffic","Replace DNS"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"CIDR allows efficient IP allocation and smaller routing tables.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (subnetting/CIDR content out of scope for A+, in scope for Network+)","optionExplanations":["Correct — CIDR allows flexible-length prefixes that aggregate address blocks, reducing the size of routing tables.","Wrong — CIDR concerns address allocation and routing efficiency; it does not encrypt IP traffic.","Wrong — CIDR is designed to improve routing efficiency, not increase broadcast traffic.","Wrong — CIDR is unrelated to DNS; it addresses IP allocation and routing, not name resolution."]},{"id":650,"question":"A user reports slow performance after installing new software. Best initial step?","options":["Reimage the entire machine immediately without checking anything first","Check resource usage (Task Manager) and recent changes","Replace the hard drive right away, assuming it has already failed","Reinstall the operating system entirely before checking simpler causes"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Checking Task Manager for resource usage and recent changes helps identify whether the newly installed software itself is the likely cause before taking more drastic steps.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0012, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Reimaging the machine is an extreme, time-consuming step that skips checking simpler, more likely causes first.","Checking Task Manager for resource usage and recent changes helps identify whether the newly installed software itself is the likely cause before taking more drastic steps.","Replacing the hard drive assumes a hardware failure with no supporting evidence, when the timing points to the new software instead.","Reinstalling the OS is a heavy step that should follow simpler diagnostic checks, not precede them."]},{"id":651,"question":"Which backup method saves only changed blocks since last backup?","options":["Full backup, which copies every file regardless of whether it changed","Differential backup, which saves all changes since the last full backup","Incremental (or block-level incremental)","Manual copy, which requires someone to select and copy files by hand"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"Incremental backups save only the data blocks that changed since the last backup of any type, minimizing size and time.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0018, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["A full backup copies everything each time, not just changed blocks.","A differential backup saves all changes since the last full backup, not just since the most recent backup of any kind.","Incremental backups save only the data blocks that changed since the last backup of any type, minimizing size and time.","A manual copy isn't a defined backup method with block-level change tracking; it depends entirely on manual selection."]},{"id":652,"question":"A peer-to-peer connectivity issue between phones (e.g., AirDrop) — first step?","options":["Replace the device entirely before checking any basic connectivity settings","Check Bluetooth/Wi-Fi and visibility settings","Update the device's BIOS firmware, which has no role in peer-to-peer sharing","Replace the SIM card, which handles cellular service, not local wireless sharing"],"correctIndex":1,"explanation":"Peer-to-peer sharing depends on Bluetooth/Wi-Fi being enabled and the device being visible, so checking those settings first is the logical starting point.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0029, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Replacing the device is an extreme first step before checking simple settings like visibility and connectivity.","Peer-to-peer sharing depends on Bluetooth/Wi-Fi being enabled and the device being visible, so checking those settings first is the logical starting point.","BIOS firmware controls low-level hardware boot behavior, not peer-to-peer wireless sharing features.","The SIM card handles cellular service, not local Bluetooth/Wi-Fi based sharing."]},{"id":653,"question":"What is UEFI primarily used for?","options":["Providing a modern firmware interface and boot services","Cooling the CPU during high system load, similar to a heatsink or fan","Routing network packets between different connected devices","Rendering graphics and images for display on a monitor"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"UEFI is the modern firmware standard that initializes hardware and hands off to the OS during boot.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0073, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["UEFI is the modern firmware standard that initializes hardware and hands off to the OS during boot.","Cooling is handled by physical components like heatsinks and fans, not firmware.","Routing packets is a networking function performed by routers, not system firmware.","Rendering graphics is handled by a GPU and drivers, not the firmware."]},{"id":654,"question":"A router performs PAT. What is the PRIMARY benefit of this configuration?","options":["Allows multiple devices to share one public IP","Encrypts all traffic passing through the router automatically","Reduces the number of broadcast domains on the local network","Improves quality of service prioritization for real-time traffic"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"PAT lets many internal devices share a single public IP by mapping each internal connection to a unique port on that shared address.","domain":"2.0 Network Implementation","objectiveId":"2.5","objective":"IP Addressing & Network Services","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0380, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["PAT lets many internal devices share a single public IP by mapping each internal connection to a unique port on that shared address.","PAT translates addresses and ports; it doesn't encrypt traffic.","Broadcast domain segmentation is handled by routers/VLANs generally, not specifically by PAT's address-sharing function.","QoS prioritization is a separate traffic-shaping feature, not the primary purpose of PAT."]},{"id":655,"question":"A traveling sales employee needs to connect their laptop to a hotel room's single HDMI-equipped monitor, a wired Ethernet jack, and a USB printer, but their laptop only has USB-C ports. What accessory would BEST meet all three needs with a single connection?","options":["A USB-C docking station or multiport adapter with HDMI, Ethernet, and USB-A outputs","A USB-C to HDMI cable that only provides a single video output connection","A USB-C to Ethernet adapter that only provides a single wired network connection","A wireless display adapter that only mirrors video without wired networking or USB support"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A multiport dock or adapter combines HDMI, Ethernet, and USB-A into one connection, meeting all three needs at once.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0423, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["A multiport dock or adapter combines HDMI, Ethernet, and USB-A into one connection, meeting all three needs at once.","An HDMI-only cable covers video but leaves the Ethernet jack and USB printer unconnected.","An Ethernet-only adapter covers wired networking but leaves the monitor and printer unconnected.","A wireless display adapter only handles video mirroring, not wired Ethernet or USB peripheral connections."]},{"id":656,"question":"A technician needs to connect a laptop to an external 4K monitor at its full native resolution and refresh rate, but the laptop only has a single Thunderbolt/USB-C port available, which is also being used for charging via a dock. What accessory type addresses this scenario?","options":["A USB-C dock that supports simultaneous power delivery (charging) and high-resolution video output","A basic USB-A to VGA adapter that only supports lower-resolution analog video output","A micro-USB charging cable that isn't compatible with USB-C ports or high-resolution video","A 3.5mm audio splitter that only handles headphone audio output, not video or charging"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A dock supporting simultaneous power delivery and high-resolution video lets one port both charge the laptop and drive the external monitor at full quality.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0424, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["A dock supporting simultaneous power delivery and high-resolution video lets one port both charge the laptop and drive the external monitor at full quality.","A USB-A to VGA adapter is limited to older analog video and can't deliver 4K resolution or charging.","A micro-USB cable doesn't fit a USB-C port and has no video output capability at all.","An audio splitter only handles sound, with no video or power delivery function."]},{"id":657,"question":"A technician configuring a new company smartphone enables a feature so that if the device is lost or stolen, its approximate physical location can be viewed on a map from a web portal. What feature is being configured?","options":["Find My Device (device location tracking)","Airplane mode, which disables all wireless radios rather than tracking location","Mobile hotspot, which shares the device's data connection with other devices","NFC tap-to-pay, which handles contactless payments, not location tracking"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Find My Device links the phone's location to a web portal so it can be viewed on a map if lost or stolen.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0434, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Find My Device links the phone's location to a web portal so it can be viewed on a map if lost or stolen.","Airplane mode turns off wireless radios entirely; it doesn't provide location tracking.","A mobile hotspot shares internet access with other devices; it has no location-tracking function.","NFC tap-to-pay handles contactless payments, unrelated to tracking a lost device's location."]},{"id":658,"question":"A home user notices their router's default administrator username and password have never been changed since setup, leaving it vulnerable to anyone who knows the common default credentials for that router model. What is the MOST important first step to improve the router's security?","options":["Change the default administrator username and password to strong, unique credentials","Disable the router's power-saving mode to keep it running at full performance","Increase the router's Wi-Fi broadcast power to extend its coverage range","Change the router's physical mounting location to a more central spot"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Default credentials are widely known for common router models, so changing them to unique, strong values is the most important first security step.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0457, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Default credentials are widely known for common router models, so changing them to unique, strong values is the most important first security step.","Power-saving mode affects performance and energy use, not the security exposure from default login credentials.","Broadcast power affects Wi-Fi range, not whether the admin login is left at its default, vulnerable setting.","Relocating the router affects signal coverage, not the security risk posed by unchanged default credentials."]},{"id":659,"question":"A technician needs to upgrade a laptop's memory and confirms the motherboard supports DDR4 at a maximum speed of 3200 MHz. The technician has DDR4 3600 MHz modules available. What will typically happen if these faster modules are installed?","options":["The modules will typically work but run at the motherboard's maximum supported speed of 3200 MHz rather than their rated 3600 MHz","The faster modules will physically fail to fit into the laptop's DDR4 memory slot at all due to a pin mismatch","Installing faster-rated modules will cause the system to immediately and permanently catch fire upon power-on","The modules will only ever function correctly if the laptop's screen resolution is first lowered manually"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"RAM modules are typically backward compatible in speed; the system runs them at the highest speed the motherboard actually supports, here 3200 MHz.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0491, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["RAM modules are typically backward compatible in speed; the system runs them at the highest speed the motherboard actually supports, here 3200 MHz.","DDR4 modules of different rated speeds still use the same physical DDR4 slot design and will fit; there's no pin mismatch from a speed difference.","Running RAM at a speed within its supported range doesn't cause a fire hazard; it simply runs at the board's max supported speed.","Screen resolution settings have no relationship to installed RAM's clock speed."]},{"id":660,"question":"A gaming desktop experiences random crashes and blue screens specifically during memory-intensive tasks like video editing, but runs stably during light web browsing. A memory diagnostic tool reports errors in one of the two installed RAM modules. What is the MOST appropriate NEXT step?","options":["Remove or replace the failing RAM module identified by the diagnostic tool","Reinstall the operating system without addressing the hardware issue the diagnostic already identified","Increase the CPU's clock speed to compensate for the memory errors reported by the diagnostic","Replace the power supply unit, even though the diagnostic pointed specifically to a RAM module"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Since the diagnostic already isolated the fault to a specific RAM module, removing or replacing that identified module directly addresses the cause.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0493, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Since the diagnostic already isolated the fault to a specific RAM module, removing or replacing that identified module directly addresses the cause.","Reinstalling the OS doesn't address a hardware-level RAM fault the diagnostic already identified.","Increasing clock speed doesn't fix failing memory; it could make instability worse.","The diagnostic pointed to RAM specifically, not the power supply, so that's not the indicated next step."]},{"id":661,"question":"A customer wants a new desktop optimized for playing modern, graphically demanding video games at high frame rates. Which combination of components should be prioritized MOST heavily in this build?","options":["A high-performance dedicated graphics card paired with a fast multi-core CPU and adequate cooling","The largest possible number of hard drive bays, regardless of the graphics card installed","A low-power, budget CPU paired with no dedicated graphics card installed","The cheapest available power supply, regardless of the system's actual wattage needs"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Gaming performance depends most on a strong dedicated GPU paired with a capable CPU and cooling to sustain both under load.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0513, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Gaming performance depends most on a strong dedicated GPU paired with a capable CPU and cooling to sustain both under load.","Extra drive bays support storage capacity, not the graphics performance gaming needs most.","A low-power CPU with no dedicated GPU would struggle to run graphically demanding games at high frame rates.","An underpowered, cheap power supply risks not delivering enough stable power for a high-performance GPU and CPU."]},{"id":662,"question":"A video editor working with large 4K video files needs a system that can handle fast read and write speeds for scrubbing through footage, along with a high core-count CPU for rendering exports. Which storage choice BEST supports this workflow?","options":["A fast NVMe SSD for the working project files, given its high read/write throughput","A single traditional 5400 RPM mechanical hard drive with no SSD in the system at all","A basic USB 2.0 flash drive used as the primary working storage for editing","An optical disc drive used as the primary working storage for active editing"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"An NVMe SSD offers the high read/write throughput needed for scrubbing through large 4K footage smoothly.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0515, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["An NVMe SSD offers the high read/write throughput needed for scrubbing through large 4K footage smoothly.","A 5400 RPM mechanical drive is far slower than an SSD and would bottleneck scrubbing through large 4K files.","A USB 2.0 flash drive has limited speed and durability, unsuitable as primary working storage for demanding video editing.","Optical drives are far too slow and not intended for active read/write editing workloads."]},{"id":663,"question":"A technician runs a diagnostic utility on an aging hard drive and finds several S.M.A.R.T. attributes flagged as failing, including reallocated sector count. What does this MOST strongly indicate?","options":["The drive is showing signs of impending physical failure and important data should be backed up immediately","The drive's firmware simply needs a routine update to resolve the flagged attributes","The drive's data cable needs to be reseated to fix the reported attribute failures","The operating system needs to be reinstalled to address the drive's S.M.A.R.T. warnings"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Failing S.M.A.R.T. attributes like reallocated sector count strongly indicate the drive itself is physically deteriorating, making backups urgent.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0570, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Failing S.M.A.R.T. attributes like reallocated sector count strongly indicate the drive itself is physically deteriorating, making backups urgent.","A firmware update doesn't reverse the physical sector damage a reallocated sector count indicates.","A loose cable could cause other symptoms, but wouldn't itself generate failing S.M.A.R.T. attribute readings like this.","Reinstalling the OS doesn't address underlying physical drive degradation reported by S.M.A.R.T."]},{"id":664,"question":"A user reports their computer has become extremely slow to open files and boot up over the past few months, and Task Manager shows disk usage frequently pegged at 100% even during light use. The drive is a traditional mechanical hard drive that has never been replaced. What is a reasonable NEXT step to investigate?","options":["Run a drive health check and consider whether upgrading to an SSD would resolve the performance bottleneck","Immediately reinstall the operating system without first investigating the drive's actual health","Replace the power supply, even though the symptoms point to disk activity, not power delivery","Increase the monitor's refresh rate to help the system feel more responsive overall"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Checking drive health and considering an SSD upgrade directly targets the mechanical drive's performance bottleneck causing high disk usage.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0571, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Checking drive health and considering an SSD upgrade directly targets the mechanical drive's performance bottleneck causing high disk usage.","Reinstalling the OS skips checking whether the aging mechanical drive itself is the actual bottleneck.","The symptoms point to disk activity being maxed out, not a power delivery problem.","Refresh rate affects display smoothness, not the disk-usage bottleneck causing slow file access."]},{"id":665,"question":"A laptop user reports that colors on their screen look noticeably washed out and inaccurate compared to how they appeared when the laptop was new, though brightness and contrast otherwise seem normal. What is a reasonable step to investigate BEFORE assuming the screen itself has failed?","options":["Check and recalibrate the display's color profile/settings, since color calibration can drift or be accidentally altered over time","Immediately replace the entire laptop, assuming the whole system needs to be swapped out for this issue","Assume the washed-out colors are being caused specifically by a failing keyboard component somehow","Assume the washed-out colors are being caused specifically by insufficient system RAM somehow"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Color calibration settings can drift or get changed accidentally, so checking and recalibrating them is a reasonable step before assuming hardware failure.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0596, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Color calibration settings can drift or get changed accidentally, so checking and recalibrating them is a reasonable step before assuming hardware failure.","Replacing the whole laptop is an extreme step before checking a simple, commonly-drifting setting like color calibration.","A keyboard has no connection to how the display renders color.","RAM amount affects system performance, not color accuracy of the display."]},{"id":666,"question":"A technician needs to determine whether a laptop's dim, hard-to-see external display issue is caused by the laptop's graphics output or the monitor itself. What is a reasonable diagnostic step?","options":["Connect the same laptop to a different, known-good monitor and see if the dimness persists","Replace the laptop's keyboard, which has no connection to display brightness output","Reinstall the laptop's operating system immediately without testing the display separately","Assume it is a monitor issue without testing the laptop's output on another display first"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Testing with a different known-good monitor isolates whether the laptop's own graphics output or the specific monitor is causing the dimness.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0600, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Testing with a different known-good monitor isolates whether the laptop's own graphics output or the specific monitor is causing the dimness.","The keyboard has no relationship to video output or display brightness.","Reinstalling the OS doesn't isolate whether the issue is the laptop's output or the monitor itself.","Assuming the cause without testing skips the direct, simple isolation step of trying another monitor."]},{"id":667,"question":"A smartphone's battery has become visibly swollen, causing the back cover to bulge outward and separate slightly from the frame. What should the user or technician do?","options":["Power off the device immediately and have the battery professionally removed and replaced, avoiding pressure on the swollen area","Continue using the phone completely normally, since a swollen battery is generally just a minor cosmetic issue","Press firmly on the bulging area repeatedly to try to flatten the swollen battery back into place","Place the phone inside a freezer for a while to try to reduce the visible battery swelling somewhat"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"A swollen battery is a fire/chemical hazard, so powering off and having it professionally replaced without pressure on the bulge is the safe response.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0615, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["A swollen battery is a fire/chemical hazard, so powering off and having it professionally replaced without pressure on the bulge is the safe response.","A swollen battery is a genuine safety hazard, not merely cosmetic, and continued use risks rupture or fire.","Pressing on a swollen battery risks puncturing it, which can cause fire or chemical exposure.","Freezing doesn't safely address battery swelling and can introduce condensation-related risks instead."]},{"id":668,"question":"A user's tablet takes an unusually long time to charge, requiring several hours to reach full charge when it previously charged in under two hours using the same charger and cable. What is a reasonable step to help isolate the cause?","options":["Try a different known-good charger and cable to determine whether the issue is with the accessories or the tablet's charging circuitry/battery itself","Immediately assume the tablet's screen needs replacement, without testing any charging accessories first at all","Immediately assume the tablet's Wi-Fi antenna has failed, without testing any charging accessories first at all","Immediately assume the tablet's camera has failed, without testing any charging accessories first at all"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Trying a different known-good charger and cable isolates whether the slow charging is caused by the accessories or the tablet's own charging hardware.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0620, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Trying a different known-good charger and cable isolates whether the slow charging is caused by the accessories or the tablet's own charging hardware.","A screen issue wouldn't cause the charging time itself to increase; it's unrelated to charging speed.","A Wi-Fi antenna failure would affect wireless connectivity, not how quickly the device charges.","A camera failure has no relationship to how long the device takes to charge."]},{"id":669,"question":"A user sends a print job to a shared office printer, and the job appears to be stuck in the print queue with a status of 'Printing' for over 20 minutes with no actual output. What is a reasonable troubleshooting step?","options":["Clear the stuck print queue (spooler) and restart the print spooler service, then resend the job","Immediately replace the entire printer with a brand new unit before trying simpler fixes","Immediately reinstall the operating system on the user's computer to fix a stuck print job","Increase the printer's paper tray capacity to try to resolve the stuck queue"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Clearing the stuck spooler queue and restarting the Print Spooler service directly addresses a job stuck showing 'Printing' with no output.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0634, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Clearing the stuck spooler queue and restarting the Print Spooler service directly addresses a job stuck showing 'Printing' with no output.","Replacing the whole printer is a drastic step before trying the simple, common fix of restarting the spooler service.","Reinstalling the OS doesn't address a stuck print spooler queue on an otherwise working computer.","Paper tray capacity is unrelated to why a job is stuck in the queue rather than actually printing."]},{"id":670,"question":"A laser printer displays an error message indicating a paper jam, but a thorough visual inspection of the paper path reveals no visible paper stuck anywhere. What is a reasonable NEXT step?","options":["Check for small torn paper fragments that may be lodged deeper in the paper path, such as near the rollers or fuser, which aren't immediately visible","Assume the error message is completely wrong entirely and simply ignore the reported paper jam altogether","Replace the entire printer immediately without first checking any further inside the actual paper path","Assume the printer's Wi-Fi wireless connection has failed somehow, which is entirely unrelated to a paper jam error message"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Torn paper fragments can lodge near rollers or the fuser where they aren't obvious on a quick visual check, so a deeper inspection is the reasonable next step.","domain":"6.0 Cross-Topic (Non-Network+ Content)","objectiveId":"6.1","objective":"General IT Topics (relocated from A+ Core 1 bank)","source":"relocated from A+ Core 1 bank (q0637, rewritten to remove length-bias)","optionExplanations":["Torn paper fragments can lodge near rollers or the fuser where they aren't obvious on a quick visual check, so a deeper inspection is the reasonable next step.","Paper jam sensors are usually accurate; dismissing the error risks leaving an actual obstruction in place.","Replacing the whole printer is a drastic step before thoroughly checking the paper path for hidden fragments.","A Wi-Fi failure would affect connectivity, not trigger a paper jam sensor error."]}];
